(13, 1, 43, 17, 5, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>In trinitarian doctrine, &ldquo;God the Son&rdquo; did not give up his divine-nature when he took on human-nature at the incarnation, i.e, when he became &ldquo;fully God and fully man&rdquo;. The human-nature of Jesus did not have divine glory &ldquo;before the world existed&rdquo; so this must be the divine-nature of &ldquo;God the Son&rdquo; speaking in John 17:5. But can &ldquo;God the Son&rdquo; be fully God without His glory? Did &ldquo;God the Son&rdquo; cease to be God by giving up his divine glory, or did he not cease to be God and keep his glory? If he kept his glory and continued to be God, why is he asking for his glory back? If he didn&rsquo;t keep his glory and is asking for it back, he ceased to be God and gave up his divine-nature. The trinitarian interpretation of John 17:5 ends up being a tangled web of contradiction.</p>'),
