(13, 1, 54, 3, 16, 3, null, 99, null, '<p>Great is the Secret of Godliness</p> <p>Paul&rsquo;s writings to Timothy during his imprisonment in Rome are full of exhortations and defense instructions against an onslaught of troubling internal and external influences touching the newly formed Christian assemblies. They are full of coaching about the furthering of the ministry that Paul had been given and theyalso reveal a sense of impending alarms for the Christian community. Paul envisions Timothy&rsquo;s part in the solving of these problems on a practical level and his instructions always point to the Doctrine that had already been established by Paul (&ldquo;my gospel&rdquo;) and the other apostles and prophets of the early community. With this in mind we find in the middle of the first epistle to Timothy a section a strange verse that speaks of church management, but then seems to refer to Jesus. I present a couple of well-known versions and will then comment on them.</p> <p>KJV1 Timothy 3:14-16 14 These things write I unto thee, hoping to come unto thee shortly: 15 But if I tarry long, that thou mayest know how thou oughtest to behave thyself in the house of God, which is the church of the living God, the pillar and ground of the truth. 16 And without controversy great is the mystery of godliness: God was manifest in the flesh, justified in the Spirit, seen of angels, preached unto the Gentiles, believed on in the world, received up into glory.</p> <p>NAU1 Timothy 3:14-16 <a id="_Hlk22372539" name="_Hlk22372539"></a>14 I am writing these things to you, hoping to come to you before long; 15 but in case I am delayed, I write so that you will know how one ought to conduct himself in the household of God, which is the church of the living God, the pillar and support of the truth. 16 By common confession, great is the mystery of godliness: He who was revealed in the flesh, Was vindicated in the Spirit, Seen by angels, Proclaimed among the nations, Believed on in the world, Taken up in glory.</p> <p>When noting the subject matter here, we see that Paul is still focused on &ldquo;the household of God, the church of the living God&rdquo;. This continues the overall theme of chapter 3 which instructs Timothy about how &ldquo;overseers&rdquo; and &ldquo;deacons&rdquo; should conduct themselves not only in their own household, but in this household of God, the church. By the time he summarizes all of this with Timothy it has been noted that deacons (ministrants/ servants) in the church need to &ldquo;keep the secret of the faith with a pure conscience&rdquo;. This sacred trust relates, as we shall see, to the &ldquo;secret of godliness&rdquo; in verse 18. This term secret is the key to the entire context.</p> <p>So, in verses 14 and 15 the subject concludes a diatribe about church government and living, but in almost all translations the next verse is coopted. It begins withthe &ldquo;secret of godliness&rdquo; as either &ldquo;God was manifested in the flesh&rdquo; or &ldquo;he was manifested in the flesh&rdquo;. This verse seems to wrench the subject matter from the context and begin an entire new stream of thought; or does it. Scholars have questioned the underlying Greek text for years (see below), but have remained steadfast in their interpretations that verse 16 is about a personality not a object. Left without critical comment it seems to talk of Jesus who was not the church. Why is there such a problem here?</p> <p>Bad textual critical work on the part of early midlevel compilers (authors of the extus Receptus and others) and the corresponding translations from extant/ errant texts of the time is the issue facing us. Yet it is interpreters even today that further obscure a better translation that are the real problems. Strangely, the Greek syntax and grammar are not necessarily the issue, though a will comment on a relative pronoun and it&rsquo;s modifier. It is really a logical and modality issue. It is readily seen that verse 15 and 16 point to &ldquo;things&rdquo;, not personal subjects. Verse 15 talks of the church and verse 16 the &ldquo;secret of godliness&rdquo;. Why do most translations change this neutral subject matter into Jesus between verses? It has to do with the Greek of the second phrase and what it is describing. The first part of verse 16 (&ldquo;confessedly great is the secret of godliness&rdquo;) is agreed upon universally. What is the sedond phrase?</p> <p>BNT 1 Timothy 3:16b - o]j evfanerw,qh evn sarki,( - &ldquo;Which&rdquo; or &ldquo;who&rdquo; was manifested in the flesh&rdquo;.</p> <p>The first word (ὅς) is at issue; what was the original text and what is the translation? Here are the textual facts as described by text critic Bruce Metzger:</p> <p>&ldquo;The reading which, on the basis of external evidence and transcriptional probability, best explains the rise of the others is ὅς [&ldquo;who,&rdquo; &ldquo;which&rdquo;]. It is supported by the earliest and best uncials (א* A*vid C* Ggr) as well as by 33 365 442 2127 syrhmg, pal goth ethppOrigenlat Epiphanius Jerome Theodore Eutheriusacc. to Theodoret Cyril Cyrilacc. to Ps-Oecumenius Liberatus. Furthermore, since the neuter relative pronoun ὅ must have arisen as a scribal correction of ὅς (to bring the relative into concord with μυστήριον [mystery]), the witnesses that read ὅ (D* itd, g, 61. 86 vg Ambrosiaster Marius Victorinus Hilary Pelagius Augustine) also indirectly presuppose ὅς as the earlier reading. The Textus Receptus reads θεός [God], with אe (this corrector is of the twelfth century) A2 C2 Dc K L P Ψ 81 330 614 1739 Byz Lect Gregory-Nyssa Didymus Chrysostom Theodoret Euthalius and later Fathers. Thus, no uncial (in the first hand) earlier than the eighth or ninth century (Ψ) supports θεός [God]; all ancient versions presuppose ὅς or ὅ and no patristic writer prior to the last third of the fourth century testifies to the reading θεός. The reading θεός arose either (a) accidentally, through the misreading of ΟC as ΘC, or (b) deliberately, either to supply a substantive for the following six verbs, or, with less probability, to provide greater dogmatic precision.&rdquo; (Bruce Metzger, A Textual Commentary on the Greek New Testament).</p> <p>So, the reading &ldquo;God was manifested in the flesh&rdquo; is wrong, but then why substitute &ldquo;He&rdquo;? Why not rather read the relative pronoun as &ldquo;which&rdquo; to bring verse 16 into correspondence and coherence with the context of &ldquo;the secret of godliness&rdquo;? Then the relative pronoun would make more sense. Let me explain. The term &ldquo;mystery&rdquo; (in most translations; from the Greek noun musth,rion (musterion)) is more properly explicated as &ldquo;secret&rdquo; and should always be translated not transliterated. It has nothing to do with a &ldquo;mysterious God&rdquo; or &ldquo;God works in mysterious ways&rdquo; or sacraments, mystery religions of the time or anything our modern minds can concoct. I has deep roots in the Hebrew Scritptrues and in the Second Temple literature. In a great work by Raymond E. Brown, S. S. he proves this conclusively. It was something hidden, a secret; no one knew.</p> <p>And the secret of godliness, a non-personal noun phrase does not necessarily relate to Jesus or about Jesus; so why stick a theology in here? The term &ldquo;manifested in the flesh&rdquo; was too tempting. It sounded too much like &ldquo;And the Word became flesh, and dwelt among us&hellip;&rdquo; of Johns&rsquo; Gospel. A pre-existent Christ now comeinto existence! And the term &ldquo;flesh&rdquo; seemingly used similarly? What a perfect place for the monks to monkey with the text&hellip;and so they did and the last verse in a chapter about church polity is mysteriously changed into a comment about Jesus the God-man. Yes, the &ldquo;idea became real&rdquo;. Well, let&rsquo;s just hold our proverbial horses, shall we?</p> <p>The semantic range of the Greek term &ldquo;flesh&rdquo; is vast in Christian Scripture and certainly holds this type of meaning. Originally it was merely the physical &ldquo;flesh&rdquo; coveromg the skeleton, then metaphorically the carnality that opposes God and spirituality and many, many, many other usages figuratively. Interestingly it had been provided by Paul in his letter to the Ephesians which offers a context that mentions another &ldquo;great secret&rdquo;; the relation of a husband and a wife where they become &ldquo;one flesh&rdquo;. This &ldquo;flesh&rdquo;; this reality of one-life-out-of two-brought-togeterh; not physical, not carnal, not always understood by the world is unique. Yet Paul in Ephesians 5: 32 says,</p> <p>BBE Ephesians 5:32 This is a great secret: but my words are about Christ and the church.</p> <p>Paul is speaking of the church and uses the same phraseology. The same term &ldquo;flesh&rdquo; is used as well in that context (Ephesians 5: 29, 31). How does that help us here in the discussion of the &ldquo;secret of godliness&rdquo;? One takeaway is that Paul uses the term &ldquo;flesh&rdquo; as reality; the husband and wife become one flesh. Not one physical body, not a carnal relationship opposed to God, not somting pointing to a worldly mindset, but something that has come into being from an idea just as John used it as relating to Jesus in his Gospel. This is how I propose to see the &ldquo;manifested in the flesh&rdquo; phrase in 1 Timothy 3: 16. Something that was an idea had become a reality. And it was a secret idea.</p> <p>It is &ldquo;great is the secret of godliness, which was manifest in the flesh&rdquo; (came into being; was evident), not &ldquo;God was manifest in the flesh&rdquo; nor even &ldquo;he was manifest in the flesh&rdquo;; it&rsquo;s much bigger than that. It is about Christ and the church here as it was similarly in Ephesians 5. Let me show you more. The next phrases in the verse reveal more eye-opening details and each refers to the launched subject of Paul&rsquo;s third chapter of 1 Timothy, the church and church polity. I&rsquo;ll repeat the first phrase and continue with those parallel modifiers:</p> <p>1. That which was revealed in the flesh (became a reality)</p> <p>2. (it) was &ldquo;vindicated in the Spirit&rdquo; (&ldquo;was given God&#39;s approval in the spirit&rdquo; &ndash; Bible in Basic English)</p> <p>3. (it was) &ldquo;seen by angels&rdquo;</p> <p>4. (it was) &ldquo;proclaimed among the nations&rdquo;</p> <p>5. (it was) &ldquo;believed on in the world&rdquo;</p> <p>6. (it was) &ldquo;taken up in glory&rdquo;</p> <p>There is a logical progression to observe. Something was revealed in the flesh. This same &ldquo;thing&rdquo;, I believe it was the church, that we know as Christianity in the Christian Scriptures, was &ldquo;vindicated (&ldquo;made such as it ought to be&rdquo; (dikaio,w &ndash;&ldquo;justified&rdquo; or just as it ought to be) is another translation)) in (&ldquo;via&rdquo; or &ldquo;with&rdquo;) the spirit&rdquo;. God gave the &ldquo;promised holy spirit&rdquo; on Pentecost 28 AD and marked his work by even giving some extra special, might I say secret stuff. The Jews that day spoke in tongues as evidence (can you say, &ldquo;in the flesh&rdquo;?) of that vindication.</p> <p>Why, then would Paul say next that this same entity was &ldquo;seen of angels&rdquo;? Because angels were not expecting this; they were unaware of this; they were surprised! How do we know? Paul has told us in 1 Corinthians 2: 6-8 and Peter explains their desire (&ldquo;longing&rdquo; or &ldquo;lust&rdquo;) to know about this &ldquo;thing&rdquo; (in 1 Peter 1: 10-12). The ancillary question to Trinitarians would be why would this relate to Jesus? He as announced to have been coming by angels. His coming; may I say not only coming, but arrival, place of birth, viariaous life, murder, resurrection, ascension and seating by God&rsquo;s throne and even his second coming were all &ldquo;seen of angels&rdquo; from the Scripture. And, of course, his actual arrival was celebrated my a &ldquo;multitude of the heavenly host&rdquo; some nine (9) months after Gabriel himself announced the promise. Being &ldquo;seen of angels&rdquo; is not a statement about Jesus. This seition is about something they hadn&rsquo;t seen, hadn&rsquo;t known about; the secret of godliness!</p> <p>&ldquo;Proclaimed among the nations&rdquo; comes next and why is this important in the linear timetable; because thats what came next in the rise and expansion of the church of God. Messiah, his birth, suffering, murder, resurrection, ascension and seating was only a Jewish thing with a Jewish Messiah expected. The &ldquo;crumbs from the table&ldquo;Gentiles, the &ldquo;dogs&rdquo;, the ungodly &ldquo;uncircumcision&rdquo; were to get holy-hell from Messiah and his host bdfore it was all over. They were to be bringing the wealth of their world to the Jews in Jerusalem in the eschaton; they were to be &ldquo;ruled witih a rod of iron&rdquo; by Messiah; just read that in a million places in the Hebrew Scriptures and don&rsquo;t forget Psalm 2. What is up with this present statement by Paul? This &ldquo;proclamation&rdquo; is different; it was spoken of by Paul in his letter to the Romans.</p> <p>NAU Romans 16:25 Now to Him who is able to establish you according to my gospel and the preaching (proclamation, heralding) of Jesus Christ, according to the revelation of the mystery (Secret) which has been kept secret for long ages past,</p> <p>The ministry of the church of God to the Gentiles is quite a bit different than that of the children of Israel. The Gentiles, who were spoken of as, &ldquo;excluded from the commonwealth of Israel, and strangers to the covenants of promise, having no hope and without God in the world&rdquo; (NASBEphesians 2: 12); arguably a pretty bad national trajectory; are now, by the proclaiming of the church they are:</p> <p>&ldquo;&hellip;are fellow heirs and fellow members of the body, and fellow partakers of the promise in Christ Jesus through the gospel, 7 of which I was made a minister, according to the gift of God&#39;s grace which was given to me according to the working of His power<a id="_Hlk22729122" name="_Hlk22729122"></a>. 8 To me, the very least of all saints, this grace was given, to preach to the Gentiles the unfathomable (&ldquo;unsearchable&rdquo; or &ldquo;untrackable&rdquo;) riches of Christ, (NASBEphesians 3: 6-8)</p> <p>I&rsquo;d say that &ldquo;unsearchable&rdquo; thing alone, which angels desired to see, was exceptionaly different from the prophecies given for the future Gentiles. And yesthose prophecies will be fulfilled once the church leaves the planet and new rules are set for the next stage in God&rsquo;s purposes; all Israel will be saved and Messiah comes back and kicks butt / takes names. God&rsquo;s words will not fall idly to the ground. Jesus Christ has become a minister to the Circumcison to fulfill the promises given to their fathers (Romans 15: 8). Early translations have that Jesus Christ was a minister, obscuring the textual truth of the matter. The conflict between Israel and the other nations is not &ldquo;history&rdquo;; they have a bloody future. There will yet be head-banging (Read: &ldquo;rod of iron&rdquo;) in Jesus&rsquo; future. He&rsquo;s not coming back blowin&rsquo; kisses. But the secret, that Gentiles in the &ldquo;dispensation ofthe Secret&rdquo; would be treated in a much more, shall we say, preeminent way; this was new, and they needed to hear it from preachers. After the cross they got the message. And one more thing before we move on; Jesus was not proclaimed to the Gentiles until after his resurrection, ascension and seating next to God.</p> <p>I&rsquo;ve heard the argument, however, that this preaching was just after is resurrection, before his ascension (those 40+ days between the Feast of Unleavened Bread andPentecost 28 AD) and because of his pronouncements about going to the nations and baptizing them (Matthew 28: 19). His mission and that of his disciples during his pilgrimage on the planet was only to Israel. Jesus would not allow his own preachers of the good news of the Kingdom to come to be to anyone but &ldquo;the lost sheep of the house of Israel&rdquo; (Matt. 10:6; 15:24). As the keen reader will attest, this modifier of the leading noun is out of place chronologically if it were to be about Jesus. But it is perfect chronologically and logically if it were about the Christian church.</p> <p>The final two (2) modifiers of the &ldquo;secret of godliness&rdquo;, the &ldquo;believed on in the world&rdquo; and &ldquo;taken up in glory&rdquo; speak loudly to this point as well. Yes, Jesus was believed on in the world, but it was after he was taken up in glory. Jesus was preached to the Gentiles, but it was after he was taken up in glory. The &ldquo;taken up in glory&rdquo; would have been point #4 not point #7 and it isn&rsquo;t that way in any Greek text.</p> <p>Yet, the trajectory of the church, the subject of this third chapter to Timothy(&ldquo;church of the living God, the pillar and support of the truth&rdquo;) follows the points (modifiers) that Paul uses distinctly, logically and chronologically. And verse 16 says that there is no argument about this &ldquo;secret of godliness&rdquo;; it was a commonconfession (o`mologoume,nwj - homologoumenosas - &ldquo;agreed&rdquo;, &ldquo;by common consent&rdquo;). I believe that better hermeneutic is as follows:</p> <p>&bull; That which (&ldquo;the secret of godliness&rdquo;) was revealed in the flesh - became a reality (in similar fashion to Jesus (the &ldquo;Word&rdquo;) &ldquo;became flesh&rdquo;;; but this time its&rsquo; not Jesus)); both the church and the Messiah were in the mind of God and one was secret.</p> <p>&bull; (it was) &ldquo;given God&#39;s approval in (with) the spirit&rdquo;) &ndash; Pentecost 28 AD; speaking in tongues as evidence so no one would miss it.</p> <p>&bull; (it was) &ldquo;seen by angels&rdquo; &nda