INSERT INTO `myrevdata` (`myrevid`, `testament`, `book`, `chapter`, `verse`, `highlight`, `marginnote`, `sqn`, `lastupdate`, `myrevnotes`) VALUES
(14, 1, 41, 4, 33, 0, null, 99, '2023-01-10 19:48:40', '<p>&ldquo;The parable of the sower has asserted that people&rsquo;s ability to &lsquo;hear&rsquo; is quite varied, and is determined by factors in their own character and situation rather than by the form of teaching. But we have seen that parables, by their very nature, serve to bring out that variety. Because they need to be interpreted and applied, and call for a response which is likely to be more than intellectual, the same parables will leave some cold while others respond with enthusiasm &mdash; and by seeking further enlightenment. It is probably this variety in response that Mark here intends to remind us of. Among the crowds who hear the parables there are some who δύνανται ἀκούειν, and will therefore join those περὶ αὐτόν who seek and receive further explanation, but others will go no further. καθὼς ἠδύναντο ἀκούειν then alerts the reader to the fact that not all have that capacity (καθώς being used in the sense &lsquo;insofar as&rsquo; or &lsquo;to the degree that&rsquo;; see BAGD, 391b, 2); and it is the resultant polarisation which Mark again highlights in v. 34.&rdquo; (R. T. France NIGTC])</p>'),
(14, 1, 41, 6, 31, 4, null, 99, '2022-04-03 14:10:13', null),
(14, 1, 41, 6, 56, 0, null, 99, '2021-10-25 18:51:07', '<p>ἵνα κἂν &ndash; implies a conditional clause (cf. Moule, <em>Idiom Book</em>, 138). See also Acts 5:15.</p>'),
(14, 1, 41, 12, 29, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-08 15:56:52', null),
(14, 1, 41, 12, 30, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-08 15:56:54', null),
(14, 1, 41, 12, 31, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-08 15:56:59', null),
(14, 1, 41, 14, 21, 0, null, 99, '2022-04-25 19:35:33', '<p>&ldquo;While the Son of Man <u>goes to his death</u> in accordance with the divine plan, on the other hand it were better for his betrayer had he never been born.&rdquo; (Lane, NICNT)</p> <p>ὑπάγω, in itself a fairly neutral word for &lsquo;going away&rsquo;,46 is used here as a functional equivalent to the following παραδίδοται, summarising the fate which has been outlined in the earlier passion predictions (and perhaps intended to remind us of Jesus&rsquo; prediction in v. 7, ἐμὲ οὐ πάντοτε ἔχετε). (France, NIGTC)</p> <p>πάγω (LN 23.101) (BAGD 3. p. 837): &lsquo;to die&rsquo; [LN ; CEV, GW, NCV, NLT, TEV], &lsquo;to leave this life&rsquo; [LN], &lsquo;to go&rsquo; [BAGD, BECNT, BNTC, NTC, WBC; ESV, KJV, NASB, NET, NIV, NRSV, REB], &lsquo;to go away&rsquo; [AB2, Lns], &lsquo;to go the way appointed for him&rsquo; [AB1]. This is a figurative extension meaning of the verb &lsquo;to go, to depart&rsquo; and it refers to departing from life [LN]. It is a euphemism for dying [BAGD]. &lsquo;Go&rsquo; obviously refers to death [TH]. (Blight, SIL)</p>'),
(14, 1, 41, 14, 34, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-01 16:49:25', null),
(14, 1, 41, 14, 38, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-01 16:50:06', null),
(14, 1, 41, 15, 2, 0, null, 99, '2022-06-20 19:47:45', '<p>σύ λεγείς &ndash; &ldquo;It is not negative (contra Gundry 1993: 932&ndash;33; cf. also Pesch 1980b: 457) or &ldquo;non-committal&rdquo; (Hooker 1991: 367&ndash;68; cf. also J. Edwards 2002: 459) but positive, for Pilate will crucify him on this charge. Jesus&rsquo;s reply, however, implies that his understanding of the title is not the same as Pilate&rsquo;s.2 Jesus does not see his kingship as being political in nature and involving this world (cf. John 18:36&ndash;37).&rdquo; [Stein, BECNT]</p>'),
(14, 1, 41, 15, 3, 0, null, 99, '2022-06-20 19:46:13', '<p>πολλά and πόσα together suggest several [Mark, p. 629] different accusations rather than merely repetition of the one main charge). Taking πολλά and πόσα as accusative of object (using the classical construction [BAGD 423a, 1.a] of κατηγορέω with the genitive of the person and the accusative of the accusation; cf. Acts 28:19) rather than adverbially, as Gundry, 924&ndash;25, 933, prefers.</p>'),
