(14, 1, 45, 5, 6, 0, null, 99, '2023-01-31 14:51:53', '<p>&ldquo;The words κατὰ καιρόν (kata kairon, at the right time, v. 6) modify not &ldquo;when we were still weak&rdquo; but Χριστὸς &hellip; ὑπὲρ ἀσεβῶν ἀπέθανεν (Christos &hellip; hyper asebōn apethanen, Christ died for the ungodly; Moo 1991: 314&ndash;15). To ascertain the particular meaning of κατὰ καιρόν is more difficult. It could mean that Christ died at the right time in terms of God&rsquo;s plan for the world (cf. Rom. 3:26; 8:18; 13:11; Gal. 4:4), fulfilling the promises made in the Scriptures (Murray 1959: 167; Cranfield 1975: 264). Others think the appropriateness of the time relates to the weakness of the ungodly, in that he died at the right time to rescue them from their peril (K&auml;semann 1980: 137; Dunn 1988a: 255; Moo 1991: 315).&rdquo; [Scheiner [BECNT])</p>'),
