(14, 1, 54, 4, 7, 0, null, 99, '2022-08-24 19:42:55', '<p>τοὺς δὲ βεβήλους καὶ γραώδεις μύθους &ndash; the adjectives βεβήλους and γραώδεις are in first-attributive position thereby modifying μύθους. Therefore, perhaps it is better to translate as a double adjective describing &ldquo;myths.&rdquo;</p>'),
(14, 1, 54, 4, 10, 0, null, 99, '2022-08-24 18:14:58', '<p>μάλιστα &ndash; &ldquo;Many commentators conclude that Paul (or the author) has divided humanity into two groups: &ldquo;all people&rdquo; to whom, through the gospel, salvation is offered, and &ldquo;those who have believed&rdquo; in the gospel and so responded to the offer. Another solution depends on the alternative translation for the term rendered &ldquo;especially,&rdquo; i.e. &ldquo;namely, I mean,&rdquo; which then in effect narrows the meaning of &ldquo;all people&rdquo; to &ldquo;believers&rdquo;: &ldquo;who is savior of all people, I mean of those who believe.&rdquo; [Towner, NICNT]</p>'),
(14, 1, 54, 5, 17, 1, null, 99, '2022-04-19 18:47:37', '<p>&ldquo;The term &ldquo;double honor&rdquo; has produced a good deal of discussion. The backing for the instruction that Paul gives in v. 18 suggests that at least in some cases more than respect in the form of acknowledgement i.e. some form material compensation might be meant.15 Moreover, something on this order for those engaged in ministry was clearly the practice in Pauline churches (1 Cor 9:7&ndash;14; 2 Cor 11:8&ndash;9; Gal 6:6; 1 Thess 2:7). But it is well to recall that Paul himself did not lean on the material implications for himself, though he did expect to be treated with the respect to be accorded to those in the service of the gospel. The precise meaning of the stipulation, &ldquo;double honor,&rdquo; is difficult to determine.16 Of the numerous interpretations offered,17 the Pauline practice just cited and the following OT citation (and adaptation in Paul) and allusion to the Jesus tradition point in the direction of &ldquo;honor&rdquo; that could sometimes be expressed in material terms.18 &ldquo;Double&rdquo; might then have meant [1,2 Tim, Titus, p. 364] literally &ldquo;twice as much as&rdquo; some implied or earlier named group, whether it be other elders who do not teach, deacons, widows,19 or figuratively &ldquo;great, more, most, or additional&rdquo; in a superlative sense.20 Surely elders who were householders and who had &ldquo;led well&rdquo; had no need of double pay; but the appropriateness of urging community acknowledgement of their faithfulness is perfectly sensible in the situation of false teaching&rdquo; (Towner, NICNT)</p>'),
(14, 1, 54, 5, 20, 0, null, 99, '2022-04-19 19:38:21', '<p>&ldquo;The purpose of such public rebuke is ἵνα καὶ οἱ λοιποὶ φόβον ἔχωσιν. καί, &ldquo;also,&rdquo; indicates that the disciplinary action was not only for the individual but &ldquo;also&rdquo; that it might have its result in οἱ λοιποί, &ldquo;the others,&rdquo; or [Pastoral Epistles, p. 237] &ldquo;the rest.&rdquo; It may well be that with the latter Paul has in mind just the other elders (so Bernard, Dibelius-Conzelmann, Hanson, Huther, Kelly, Lock, Ridderbos, and Robertson) rather than the whole congregation (so Brox and Wilson); but if a public rebuke would have that effect on the elders it would have the same effect on other believers, since the discipline would be no different for them than for the elders.<br /> &nbsp; Paul wants that public rebuke to have the result that Christians φόβον ἔχωσιν, &ldquo;may fear.&rdquo; ἔχω is used here in the sense of &ldquo;have as one&rsquo;s own,&rdquo; i.e., so that they have φόβος as an appropriate inner characteristic in the face of sin and discipline (BAGD s.v. 2, especially 2eβ). φόβος is used here in the sense of &ldquo;fear, alarm, fright&rdquo; (BAGD s.v. 2aα) and is generally rendered with the word &ldquo;fear&rdquo; (RSV, NEB), though some versions paraphrase with &ldquo;fearful&rdquo; (NASB), &ldquo;afraid&rdquo; (TEV), or &ldquo;warning&rdquo; (NIV). But what are the believers to have fear about? Some answer that it is a fear &ldquo;of sinning&rdquo; (added by NASB). Certainly this is right as far as it goes, but the larger picture needs to be considered. The public rebuke brings about this fear. Thus the fear of receiving such a public rebuke is as much in view as the fear of sinning (cf. Calvin). Others are to be reminded by the public rebuke of the seriousness, shamefulness, and disciplinary consequences of sin. Since Paul is influenced by Deuteronomy&rsquo;s demand for two or three witnesses, it is likely that in this remark he is also influenced by Dt. 13:11, which indicates the result of an act of discipline: All (LXX πᾶς) Israel will be afraid (LXX φοβηθήσεται, the cognate to φόβος here) of the discipline and thus will withdraw from the sin.&rdquo; (Knight, NIGTC)</p>'),
(14, 1, 54, 5, 22, 0, null, 99, '2022-04-19 19:50:19', '<p>&ldquo;Paul specifies measures to be taken to seek to prevent such a difficult disciplinary situation. An appropriate time span should be allowed (not &ldquo;hastily&rdquo;) before laying hands on individuals to set them apart as elders, since this will go a long way toward eliminating the problem. Furthermore, such a precaution will also keep those who lay on hands from sharing responsibility for the sins of one they might otherwise have prematurely set apart.<br /> &nbsp; The key word is ταχέως, which is used in its unfavorable sense, i.e., &ldquo;too quickly,&rdquo; &ldquo;too easily,&rdquo; or &ldquo;hastily.&rdquo; That which should not be done &ldquo;hastily&rdquo; is χεῖρας ἐπιτίθει. ἐπιτίθεναι χεῖρας (or χεῖρα; the combination in the NT 19x; cf. ἐπίθεσις τῶν χειρῶν) is &ldquo;to lay on hands&rdquo; and is used with reference to several things in the NT. Since this section has been dealing with elders, it is natural to understand Paul to be using the concept here, as he has elsewhere, with reference to elders, i.e., for the public means by which they are set apart for the office of elder (so elsewhere in the PE: 4:14, which see; 2 Tim. 1:6). On &ldquo;no one&rdquo; (μηδενί) should hands be laid &ldquo;hastily&rdquo; to set him apart as an elder. Timothy, who with the other elders lays on hands (again 4:14), is commanded as the apostolic representative to see that the process of selecting an elder (cf. Acts 6:1&ndash;6) does not place himself (and the other elders) in a predicament.<br /> &nbsp; Paul focuses on that consequence in the second part of the verse. μηδέ, &ldquo;nor&rdquo; or &ldquo;and not,&rdquo; continues the preceding negation (μηδενί). κοινωνέω means generally &ldquo;share,&rdquo; and here &ldquo;participate,&rdquo; i.e., in sins (ἁμαρτίαις) in the sense of being responsible for them (see especially 2 Jn. 11; cf. Ezk. 3:18; 33:6, 8). By placing a person in an office that has as one of its qualifications that the person be &ldquo;above reproach&rdquo; (3:2), the one laying on hands will seem to be condoning the sins that that person commits (ἁμαρτίαις referring back to the ἁμαρτάνοντας of v. 20). The sins are those of others (ἀλλοτρίαις), but Timothy and the other elders will become responsible for those sins when they lay hands on too hastily.&rdquo; (Knight, NIGTC)</p>');
