(20, 0, 1, 12, 3, 1, null, 99, '2022-07-03 15:28:05', null),
(20, 0, 1, 12, 4, 0, null, 99, '2022-08-05 05:29:55', '<p>Lot&#39;s father was dead (see Gensis 11:27 and 28), so first his grandfather served as his parent / leader figure, then after his grandfather died, Abram, his uncle had that role.</p> <p>There are no references to Lot in the chonology chart, so there&#39;s no way to gauge his age at any point in the verses that refer to him.</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 12, 6, 0, null, 99, '2022-10-29 02:22:22', '<p>Link to <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/1egphtv0gh29ipg/2.1%20Origins%20of%20Patriarchs.jpg?dl=0" target="_blank">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 2-1</a>.</p> <p>This shows Abram would have left Haran and headed south to the east side of the Jordan, crossed, then continued west to Shechem. If the oak of Moreh points to the hill of Moreh, he would have gone north from Shechem to get there.</p> <p>I wonder why these 2 places would have been called out at this point?</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 12, 8, 0, null, 99, '2022-09-06 00:00:53', '<p>Link to <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/fasejlnb78yqv6s/2.2%20Patriarchs%20Abraham%20copy.jpg?dl=0" target="_blank">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 2-2</a>.</p> <p>Bethel and Ai are near each other South of both Moreh and Shehem -- less than 10 miles north of Jerusalem.</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 12, 9, 0, null, 99, '2022-08-14 15:19:05', '<p>Link to <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/mhwu62e5an4wo6t/1.2%20Regions%20and%20Routes.jpg?dl=0" target="_blank">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 1-2</a> .</p> <p>The Negev is South of the Dead Sea and to the west going towards the Mediterranean sea, spanning most of the distance between the two.</p> <p>It seems like God is marking out the boundaries of the promised land.</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 13, 3, 0, null, 99, '2022-09-05 23:50:17', '<p><a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/btc7hffqmibszuq/2.3%20Jacob%20and%20Joseph%20with%20highlights.jpg?dl=0" target="_blank">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 2-3</a> shows Mamre, Bethel and Ai</p> <p>The Negev is on the south end of the Dead Sea about &frac12; way to the Mediterranean. Beer-Sheba is in the Negev. Bethel and Ai, are mostly north of Jerusalem about 10 miles.</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 13, 7, 0, null, 99, '2022-08-12 18:37:23', '<p>Searching on Perizzites, one thing that came up was a map of where they may have lived. Not sure of the accuracy, but it might provide an idea of where this conflict occurred. Note this is consistent with the description of Joshua 17:14-18.</p> <p>Here is a link to a suggested map <a href="https://images.app.goo.gl/3y5AEvoGR8VxvsSD6" target="_blank">https://images.app.goo.gl/3y5AEvoGR8VxvsSD6</a></p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 13, 10, 0, null, 99, '2022-09-05 23:59:18', '<p>There is a 2013 article online where Steve Collins differs from Bill Schlegal as to the location of Zoar. Both put it near the Dead Sea, however Steve has it more north, and Bill more south. See Locating Zoar - Biblical Archaeology Society at biblicalarchaeology.org.</p> <p>Note that the <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/fasejlnb78yqv6s/2.2%20Patriarchs%20Abraham%20copy.jpg?dl=0" target="_blank">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 2-2</a> shows a land mass on the south end of the Dead Sea, then another body of water- consistent with the article above, and it shows Zoar on the southeast side of that body of water.</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 13, 18, 0, null, 99, '2022-08-07 00:23:20', '<p>Mamre and Hebron are south of Jerusalem about 1/3 up from the bottom of the Dead Sea.</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 1, 0, null, 99, '2022-08-14 15:22:00', '<p>See notes and link to map in My REV Genesis 14:5</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 3, 0, null, 99, '2022-09-05 23:46:47', '<p>See <a href="http://www.dropbox.com/s/fasejlnb78yqv6s/2.2%20Patriarchs%20Abraham%20copy.jpg?dl=0">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 2-2</a>, it suggests this location is beyond a land mass at the south side of the Dead Sea near an additional body of water there. (Sodom and Gomorrah would be on the south side of this 2nd body of water)</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 4, 4, null, 99, '2022-08-10 04:54:57', '<p>Who is &quot;they&quot; that rebelled?</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 5, 4, null, 99, '2022-09-05 23:48:39', '<p>Chedorlaomer and those struck enemies of God.</p> <ul> <li>Raphaim were of the race of Nephalim. According to an internet search, several sources showed Ashteroth Karnaim was in Bashan, east of the Jordan, as far north as Galilee.</li> <li>Does Zuzim in Ham imply they were connected to Noah&rsquo;s son Ham who was cursed?</li> <li>The Emim were of the race of Nephalim. See Deuteronomy 2:10-11 Shaveh Kiriathaim was located east of the Dead Sea, south of Mt Nebo.</li> </ul> <p>The <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/fasejlnb78yqv6s/2.2%20Patriarchs%20Abraham%20copy.jpg?dl=0" target="_blank">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 2-2</a> depicts this portion of scripture</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 6, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-14 15:22:18', null),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 7, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-10 04:58:29', null),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 13, 0, null, 99, '2022-09-05 23:51:00', '<p>Bill Schlegal&rsquo;s <a href="http://www.dropbox.com/s/btc7hffqmibszuq/2.3%20Jacob%20and%20Joseph%20with%20highlights.jpg?dl=0">Satellite Bible Atlas Map 2-3</a> shows the most likely location for Mamre to be just north of Hebron (About mid way between the Dead Sea and the Mediterranean Sea east to west, and about center noth to south of the Dead Sea) , which is consistent with Genesis 13:11-12. Using walking distance based on modern Google Maps, Hebron to Damascus would be 316 km or about 196 miles, and would take about 2d 18h to walk. Since Abram chased them north of Damascus, not sure how far he really went too retrieve Lot.</p>'),
(20, 0, 1, 14, 14, 2, null, 99, '2022-11-13 06:47:46', '<p>Which Dan? Can&#39;t be the land assigned to Dan as he wasn&#39;t born yet. Moses would not have been familiar with where that area was when he penned the Torah. Of couse, God told him what to write and God could know.</p>'),
