(41, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:25:48', '<p>Chapter One is an account of functional origins, not an account of material origins. &ldquo;Creation&rdquo; for them involved assigning functions and bringing order rather than manufacturing material.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 1, 26, 2, null, 99, '2022-10-23 23:14:28', '<p>More evidence that he was speaking to a divine council of angels actually occurs in Psalm 8 and in Hebrews 1. In Psalm 8 it says that humans were made a little lower than the Elohim, which the Septuagint renders as angels. If humans were created lower than angels, then one could easily see how they were made after the image of angels and God.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 2, 7, 1, null, 99, '2021-10-05 18:58:42', '<p>The Enuma Elish and Atrahasis both picture the gods creating humans from the ground (clay) and divine elements (the blood of a demon god and the spit of the gods). This connection is more than a coincidence. Thus, rather than being a literal depiction of how God created the first human (which makes no sense as a literal description anyway), it makes more sense to see Genesis 2:7 a figurative depiction that claims it was Israel&rsquo;s God (not Marduk or some other deity) who created humans, and that humans themselves are not originally corrupt but have a dignified origin.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 2, 19, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:26:33', '<p>Change formed to &ldquo;had formed&rdquo; pluperfect form, so that there are no inconsistencies between Genesis 1 and 2, clarifying that these animals had already been made.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 3, 5, 1, null, 99, '2023-02-01 01:17:03', '<p>This could be argued that we have an innate sense of good and evil in us now&hellip; cf. rom. 2</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 3, 15, 1, null, 99, '2022-10-25 03:00:30', '<p>Arguably the most important verse for understanding the whole bible.</p> <p>There is an allusion to this verse in Galatians 3:16. He references a single seed, stemming back from when it was first used here in gen. 3:15.</p> <p>Any language referring to crushing heads, or ashes under the soles of your feet are referencing this, Gen. 3:15! God will triumph over evil, and evil will be under his feet. HUGE</p> <p>The pronoun used for the &ldquo;seed&rdquo; (zera&lsquo;) of the woman in Gen. 3:15 is, in fact, a singular, subject pronoun (the second type of Hebrew pronoun referred to above). Not only is this type of pronoun, when in the singular, never used with the collective nuance of zera&lsquo;, but conversely, in those verses where zera&lsquo; is the antecedent of a singular, subject pronoun, every one refers to a particular zera&lsquo;, a &ldquo;child&rdquo; (e.g., Gen. 21:13; Lev. 17:12, 21:13, 22:24). Thus, the grammatical/syntactical relationship between the subject, pronoun, and verb in Gen. 3:15 is one that belongs to the so-called counting, rather than collective, sense of zera&lsquo;.</p> <p>It would be akin to saying &ldquo;Jack, he ran up the hill,&rdquo; rather than simply, &ldquo;Jack ran up the hill.&rdquo; In Biblical Hebrew when this phenomenon takes place the desired effect is either emphasis or the removal of potential ambiguity. In this case, because the singular, subject pronoun along with zera&lsquo; is always used to convey the sense of a particular &ldquo;child&rdquo; rather than the collective &ldquo;offspring/descendants,&rdquo; the author is removing ambiguity over how zera&lsquo; should be understood.BIOLA.edu</p> <p>Also worth noting that both of these strikes (a bruising of the heel by a snake-bite and a crushing of the head of the snake) are death blows. Somehow in this exchange the &ldquo;he&rdquo; will kill the serpent and the serpent will kill the &ldquo;he&rdquo;. This happens at the cross!</p> <p>Not only is the &quot;seed&quot; singular but the &quot;he&quot; and &quot;you&quot; directly after are also singular in Hebrew. This is clearly referring to the promised Messiah.</p> <hr /> <p>LXX &ndash; why tηρησει? A standard LXX lexicon suggests that the word is a corruption in transmission of a classical verb τειρήσει which can mean &quot;rub hard&quot; or &ldquo;bruise&quot; (Lust, Eynikel, Hauspie, Greek-English Lexicon of the Septuagint, II, 475).</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 3, 16, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:27:32', '<p>Translation: &quot;And to the woman he said, &quot;I will greatly multiply your sorrow in childbirth, in sorrow you will bear sons, your desire will be for your man, and he will rule over you.&quot;</p> <p>Instead of multiplying and filling the earth as they were commanded (Gen. 1:28), now the only thing Eve will be multiplying is pain and sorrow. Whereas her call to reproduce was supposed to be a blessing (Gen. 1:28), now it will be filled with sorrow.</p> <p>Eve&#39;s job of childbearing (Gen. 1:28) will now be filled with toil (Gen. 3:16) and Adam&#39;s job of working (Gen. 2:15) will now be filled with toil (Gen. 3:17-18).</p> <p>You see, the goal of God&#39;s words in Gen. 3:16-19 to Adam and Eve was not to discuss how God is going to make childbirth more painful (Gen. 3:16a), make marriage more difficult (Gen. 3:16b), and make manual labor harder on Adam. Rather, God is saying in Gen. 3:16-19 that their jobs that they were initially given have now been tainted with sin and now life will be filled with sorrow, and will ultimately end in death. Again, why does God only mention childbirth in Genesis 3:16? Are childbirth and marriage the only things that have been cursed by the fall for women? Is everything else untainted? No. He mentions childbirth specifically because he is detailing how something that was supposed to be a blessing will now be filled with sorrow.</p> <p>Eve&rsquo;s desire will be for her &lsquo;man&rsquo;. Many translators translate this as husband (which is its most common meaning of &quot;ishka&quot;), but the word literally means: your man. It is also worth noting that the vast majority of times that Adam is referred to in Genesis 1-3, the Hebrew word used is &ldquo;Adam&rdquo; not &ldquo;ish&rdquo;. So it is certainly possible, that by this usage God is saying not that her desire will be for Adam, but for a future male.</p> <p>This phrase would make almost no sense if we translated it as, &ldquo;Your desire will be for your husband.&rdquo; Was not Eve&rsquo;s desire already for her husband before the fall, and likely much greater and stronger. If anything, the fall likely weakened her desire for her husband. Why would God say this? Also, the second phrase makes no sense, &quot;he will rule over you.&quot; Was Adam not already the leader and Eve the helper (Gen. 2:20)? And are we really saying that men being rulers over women is a curse, when in the New Testament men are to be the &quot;head&quot; of the marriage and the leaders (Eph. 5:22-23;1 Tim. 3:4; 1 Cor. 11:3; 1 Pet. 3:1)? In the New Testament, the headship of the husband seems to be the way God designed things to flourish, not a punishment for women that they have to submit to an unruly dictator in their husband.</p> <p>However, if the translation was for her &lsquo;man&rsquo;, it would make sense, because she is desiring to bring forth this man who will crush the head of the serpent. One other note to bolster this case is her expression in Genesis 4:1, &ldquo;I have brought forth a man, the Lord.&rdquo; Eve was longing for (v. 16b) a man (v. 16b) who would rule over her (v. 16b). The parallels are remarkable and make sense of why she would make this remark in Gen. 4:1.</p> <p>Parallels: Gen. 3:16 - Eve would long for (v. 16b) a man (ish, v. 16b) who would rule over her (v. 16b).</p> <p>Gen. 4:1 - Eve says I have gotten (presumably she was longing for this) a man (ish, 4:1), and she called him Lord (which means ruler).</p> <p>This understanding is supported by two things. 1. She says look I have brought about a &quot;man&quot; (which aligns with the promise of 3:15), she does not say ,&quot;a child&quot; or &quot;a son&quot; (which we would expect), and 2. she calls Cain &quot;Lord&quot; (which means ruler, among other things).</p> <p><strong>Reasons why I think the Messianic interpretation is better:</strong></p> <p>1. It is perfectly literal</p> <p>2. It fits better with the immediate context of Childbearing v. 3:16a</p> <p>3. The other understanding makes no sense.</p> <p>4. It agrees with how Eve understood these words (it explains her response in 4:1)</p> <p>5. The rest of chapters 4-5 is about the seed of Eve. Cain and Abel turn out not to be part of the seed that will crush the serpent so God blesses her with Seth, and he becomes the new center of the story and continuation of the seed.</p> <p>NEW: In the naming of Cain - YHWH, this hasn&#39;t yet been identified as the name of God (Ex. 3:14) but it does mean &quot;Lord&quot; and is translated as kurios over and over again in the septuagint of Genesis. I think Eve may be calling Cain - Lord, the one who would rule over her (see promise in 3:15).</p> <p>SEE - The statement of the woman, &ldquo;I have born a man, YHWH&rdquo; is important. The literal Hebrew has a marker, ֶאת , in front of YHWH and it reads, &ldquo;I have born a man, &ldquo; ֶאת YHWH.&rdquo; This marker is most frequently used as the direct object of the verb, or in apposition, as in naming. This can be seen in the following context as in &ldquo;she again gave birth to his brother, (ֶאת ) Cain.&rdquo; If one simply follows the use of this marker throughout the chapter it is noticed that it prefaces all of the naming done by Eve (Cain in 4:1, Abel in 4:2, Seth in 4:25, as well as Enosh in 4:26). Thus it appears in the immediate context that there is no evidence for making ֶאת (in front of YHWH) different from naming (apposition) in some sense (cf. also 4:17, 18, 20, and 22 for its use before other names). In fact, one has to leave the immediate context to find any use of this Hebrew marker as anything other than a direct object marker or in apposition for naming. THIS IS FROM Biblicalstory.org</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>The Syriac Peshitta (1st&ndash;2nd cent. CE) offers another important early transla- tion independent of the LXX. It, too, renders תשׁוקה as the equivalent of &ldquo;return&rdquo; in Gen 3:16, 4:7 and Song of Songs.51 Several LXX daughter translations, although less weighty, contain parallel readings that attest to an early and widespread ac- ceptance of the translation &ldquo;return.&rdquo;52 The Old Latin (2nd&ndash;3rd cent.),53 Ethiopic</p> <p>(4th&ndash;5th cent.)54 and Armenian (5th cent.)55 all translate the equivalent of &ldquo;return&rdquo; or &ldquo;turning&rdquo; in Gen 3:16; 4:7 and Song of Songs. The Arabic (9th&ndash;10th cent.) has &ldquo;re- turn&rdquo; in Song of Songs and related words in Gen 3:16 (&ldquo;direction&rdquo;) and 4:7 (&ldquo;mod- eration&rdquo;).56 The Coptic Bohairic version (4th cent.) lacks the Song of Songs text but reads the equivalent of &ldquo;(re)turn&rdquo; in Gen 3:16 and 4:7, and the Coptic Sahidic (4th cent.) lacks Gen 4:7, but reads the equivalent of &ldquo;(re)turn&rdquo; in Gen 3:16 and Song of Songs.57</p> <p>The testimony of these translations corresponds to significant early Jewish writings. In reference to Gen 3:16, the Book of Jubilees (2nd cent. BCE) reads, &ldquo;and to your husband is your return.&rdquo;58 Philo (mid-1st cent. CE) asks, &ldquo;Why does the curse on the woman consist of ... turning (ἐπιστροφή) to her husband ...?&rdquo;59 And Josephus (late 1st cent. CE) plausibly reflects a similar tradition in his use of ἀναστρέφω (&ldquo;overturn, return, associate with someone&rdquo;) in reference to God&rsquo;s confrontation with Cain in Gen 4:6&ndash;7.60</p> <p>The Babylonian Targum Onqelos (1st&ndash;5th cent CE) uses תיובה &ldquo;repentance, reply, return&rdquo;61 in Gen 3:16, and apparently תוב (&ldquo;return,&rdquo; &ldquo;repent&rdquo;) in 4:7.62 The Palestinian Targum Neofiti (1st&ndash;5th cent CE) has &ldquo;to your husband you will turn ,your safety&rdquo;), according to Reuling&ldquo;( רחצונך ,in 3:16.63 The marginal reading &rdquo;)מתב( captures the idea likely implied in the Greek ἀποστροφή.64</p> <p>All of this evidence can be supplemented by the Church Fathers. The writings of Clement of Rome, Irenaeus, Tertullian, Didymus the Blind, Ambrose of Milan,Chrysostom, Augustine, Epiphanius, and Theodoret can be adduced to support Lohr&rsquo;s claim that the Fathers &ldquo;use the equivalent of &lsquo;(re)turn&rsquo; (ἀποστροφή and con- versio) largely without exception.&rdquo;65 The exception in mind is Jerome, whom we will discuss below.</p> <p>CONDREN, JANSON C. &ldquo;Toward a Purge of the Battle of the Sexes and &lsquo;Return&rsquo; for the Original Meaning of Genesis 3:16B.&rdquo; Journal of the Evangelical Theological Society 60, no. 2 (June 2017): 227&ndash;45. https://search-ebscohost-com.dts.idm.oclc.org/login.aspx?direct=true&amp;db=a9h&amp;AN=124217370&amp;site=ehost-live&amp;scope=site.</p> <p>--------------------------------</p> <p>The text would also like to explain, however, that the man and woman will return to their places of origin. Just as the &#39;ādām is said, in his &ldquo;curse,&rdquo; to return (bw#t) to the &#39;ădāmâ from which he was taken, so too is the &#39;iššâ, in her &ldquo;curse,&rdquo; said to return (hqw#t; or be driven to return) to the &#39;îš from which she was taken. The content of these statements is open to question, but the parallelism now appar- ent should not be overlooked.</p> <p>Lohr, Joel N. &ldquo;Sexual Desire? Eve, Genesis 3:16 and TŠWQH [Unpointed Hebrew Characters].&rdquo; Journal of Biblical Literature 130 (2011): 227&ndash;46. https://search-ebscohost-com.dts.idm.oclc.org/login.aspx?direct=true&amp;db=oah&amp;AN=OTA0000055271&amp;site=ehost-live&amp;scope=site.</p> <p>INTERESTING</p> <p>----------------------------------</p> <p>Eve&rsquo;s desire was already for her husband and Adam already ruled over her (she was his helper , Gen. 2:20). So, this is a very strange sentence if that is what God is meaning.</p> <p>Judges 8:15 is an example of the phrase &ldquo;your men&rdquo; although its plural being used of men, not just a husband. ehhhh.</p> <p>Ehhhh. after looking at this a lot, I just don&rsquo;t see it. That it is referring to man and not husband.</p> <ul> <li>That phrase in hebrew (ishka) always refers to husband and it is same in greek when it is in the singular.</li> <li>Also, this occurs under the curses section, so it would be strange to find good news.</li> <li>Probably the biggest thing is the almost exact copy of this phrase in Gen. 4:7 in reference to sin and its desires that we must rule over.</li> </ul>'),
(41, 0, 1, 3, 24, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-27 18:31:13', '<p>When Christ opens the way to eternal life, the barring of the way to life is removed (John 14:6; Heb. 10:19-22; Rev. 22:2).</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 4, 1, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:27:36', '<p>Translation: &quot;I have gotten a man, the Lord.&quot;</p> <ol type="1"> <li>By the time you get here in the narrative, Lord is not a title for God, and hhis is not one time just called Lord. Up to this point he is Lord God or just God.</li> </ol> <ol start="2" type="1"> <li>Combining the above evidence with the fact that the hebraic formula: et - &ldquo;name&rdquo; is used over and over again in this passage just to identify names, not to be translated with something like &ldquo;with the help of&rdquo;.</li> </ol>'),
(41, 0, 1, 4, 4, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>ALL FROM BIBLICALSTORY.ORG.</p> <p>Cain&rsquo;s Sacrifice of Vegetables: Following His Father&rsquo;s Human Wisdom:</p> <p>Until Adam invented clothing to cover sin as a new use for vegetables, they were only used for food for man and animals. Adam, following his sin, using his human wisdom invented leaves for clothing. In attempting to approach God through what seemed &ldquo;reasonable,&rdquo; Adam had covered himself, and hopefully his sin, with greenery.</p> <p>Now Cain similarly offers vegetables to establish a relationship with God. Yet Cain is not responding to any revelation of God. The only trace of source is his father&rsquo;s use of vegetables to attempt to continue a relationship to God. Cain follows the serpent by rejecting the revelation of God in 3:15, 21 as to how the relationship should be maintained. In addition, Cain now represents, not only the serpent, but also his father and mother&rsquo;s error, whose source was the serpent. Cain&rsquo;s act, in short, claims righteousness derived from his own depraved mind, his works, normally called &ldquo;self-righteousness.&rdquo;</p> <p>A Sacrifice of Sheep: Following His Father&rsquo;s Desires in 3:21. The only use of animals up this point is for sacrifice as God did in 3:21. There the point was not to clothe Adam and Eve against the elements (there was no need indicated since the weather had not gotten colder nor more foreboding). The specific sacrifice was to illustrate God&rsquo;s provision of The Seed of 3:15 and His unjust death at the hands of the serpent to substitute for their sins.</p> <p>Thus, Abel is raising sheep. There is no other use in the context except for sacrifice and Abel is doing just that. He is acting in accordance with the revelation of God. Hebrews states that the issue is a response of faith to God&rsquo;s revelation.</p> <p>4 By faith9 Abel offered to God a better sacrifice than Cain . . . (Hebrews 11:4a)</p> <p>The epistle of 1 John declares that Abel&rsquo;s &ldquo;deeds&rdquo; were righteous. Abel did no &ldquo;deeds&rdquo; in Genesis except for his sacrifice. It was his only deed. That deed is declared to be righteous, or to be in accordance with God&rsquo;s revealed character (&ldquo;God saw&rdquo;). Cain&rsquo;s were &ldquo;evil&rdquo; or following the direction of Satan.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 4, 8, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>Cain killing abel shows the enmity that would come about between the seed of the serpent (Cain) and the seed of the woman (Abel) and so a new seed needed to be produced in Seth. This is not just a random story but rather it is showing how Gen. 3:15 is playing out.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 4, 14, 1, null, 99, '2021-10-06 17:17:40', '<p>Who Was Cain Fearful of (Genesis 4:14)?</p> <p>Some claim that there had to be lots of people on the earth other than Adam and Eve&rsquo;s descendants; otherwise Cain wouldn&rsquo;t have been fearful of people wanting to slay him because he killed Abel.</p> <p>First of all, one reason that someone would want to harm Cain for killing Abel is if that person was a close relation of Abel!</p> <p>Secondly, Cain and Abel were born quite some time before the event of Abel&rsquo;s death. Genesis 4:3 states:</p> <p>And in the process of time it came to pass that Cain brought an offering of the fruit of the ground to the Lord.</p> <p>Note the phrase &ldquo;in the process of time.&rdquo; We know Seth was born when Adam was 130 years old (Genesis 5:3), and Eve saw him as a replacement for Abel (Genesis 4:25). Therefore, the time period from Cain&rsquo;s birth to Abel&rsquo;s death may have been 100 years or more&mdash;allowing plenty of time for other children of Adam and Eve to marry and have children. By the time Abel was killed, there may have been a considerable number of descendants of Adam and Eve involving several generations.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 4, 17, 1, null, 99, '2021-10-06 17:28:10', '<p>Cain was married before he went to the land of Nod. He didn&rsquo;t find a wife there but &ldquo;knew&rdquo; (had sexual relations with) his wife.12</p> <p>Ehh^^^ I don&rsquo;t like this explanation, i prefer John&rsquo;s in which Cain found a wife possible a few hundred years later. It&rsquo;s just that in the biblical description of these events it is Cain, Abel (who dies) and then Seth who is the replacement for Abel. If there were tons of other sons and daughters before Seth, why was seth the replacement? It seems better to understand that they continued having sons and daughters after Seth, which also lines up chronologically with how the story is told (i.e. they had sons and daughters after discussing Seth; Gen. 5:4).</p> <p>This makes sense in light of what Nod is, too. Nod means &ldquo;wandering&rdquo; in Hebrew. So when Cain went to the land of Nod, he was literally going to the land of wandering, not a place full of people.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 4, 25, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:29:58', '<p>Translation: &quot;another seed/descendant instead of Abel,&quot; ITS THE EXACT SAME WORD USED IN THE PROMISE OF GEN. 3:15.</p> <p>This is significant because it clarifies again this whole passage. Eve is looking for her seed who would crush the head of the serpent! She thought she found it in Cain, but that was certainly not the case.</p> <p>Eve appears to have thought that the bearing of a physical seed was adequate for her prosperity, but through the story she realizes that physical seed is not enough. It must be obedient. This is the same struggle that is found in the patriarchs, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob as well as the 11 brothers. Thus, Genesis 4 is not just a story of how Cain was not the one, but how Eve came to a understanding of God&rsquo;s promise, that God would provide and appoint and it would be in His own time and through His gracious provision, not hers. BIBLICAL STORY.ORG.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 5, 3, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-22 21:51:55', '<p>This is huge for understanding the image of God. After Adam sinned, he produced a child after his own image, not the image of God exactly anymore. I don&rsquo;t think anybody in the new testament is spoken of as being in the image of God, besides Jesus. Perhaps we were created in the image of God, and we lost that image somewhat because of sin. We now show a distorted image of God. Look at Col. 3:10 tying sanctification in with looking more like the image of God. Also, 2 Cor. 3:18 through the Spirit, we are becoming more like the image of God!! Eph. 4:24, 1 Cor. 15:49 &ndash; We bore the image of the man of dust (in our fallenness) and we will bear the image of the man of heaven (in our glorification) again tying image to righteousness.</p> <p>Don&rsquo;t know what to do with 1 Cor. 11:7.</p>'),
(41, 0, 1, 6, 2, 1, null, 99, '2022-10-31 14:45:31', '<p>Disagree with Commentary. I think they literally had sex with the women. John believes that they modified their DNA?? This language is very normal for having sex with them.</p>');
