(41, 0, 5, 18, 20, 0, null, 99, '2022-07-20 00:18:05', '<p>This whole passage is about the prophet who is to come Deut. 18:15-16. So, here this is not a widespread command that if anyone speaks something that doesn&rsquo;t come to pass, they are to be killed, but that if they speak something that doesn&rsquo;t come to pass, they are pretenders in the place of Moses who will die. Not that they are to be put to death, but that they will die, this is a vague expression, even in the septuagint.</p> <p>Craigie says, &ldquo;It would probably be wrong to take these criteria as rules to be applied rigidly every time a prophet opened his mouth. When a prophet announced God&rsquo;s coming judgment and called for repentance, it would clearly be pointless to wait first to see if the judgment actually came to pass, and then to repent (too late!). Rather the criteria represent the means by which a prophet gained his reputation as a true prophet and spokesman of the Lord.&rdquo; (<em>Deuteronomy</em>, 263).</p> <p>Also, both the Jews and the apostles understood this passage to refer to the Messiah (John 1:21,25; 6:14; 7:40; Acts 3:22-26). <em>Surprised by the Voice of God</em></p>'),
