(41, 0, 23, 7, 14, 2, null, 99, '2022-11-14 20:11:38', '<p>I&rsquo;m think that I agree with our commentary. I don&rsquo;t think the five points below are as convincing as the immediate context, that this was to happen in 65 years.</p> <ol type="1"> <li>The word for virgin παρθενος is used in the Septuagint.</li> <li>Nobody concieved in either the septuagint or OT Hebrew is called Immanuel.</li> <li>The Hebrew says &ldquo;You&rdquo; will call his name Immanuel, but Ahaz did not call any child Immanuel in the book of Isaiah.</li> <li>In the Hebrew, it says that &ldquo;before the child knows to refuse the evil and choose the good, the two kings you abhor will be forsaken.&rdquo; This did not happen, because no child that was born was named Immanuel.</li> <li>Isaiah had sexual intercourse with &ldquo;Prophetess&rdquo; in Isaiah 8:3 but they do not name the child Immanuel.</li> </ol> <p>Other side:</p> <ol type="1"> <li>God says that this defeat of Israel&rsquo;s enemies will happen within 65 years, so it would not make much sense to give them a sign that this is going to pass, about a 1000 years later...</li> </ol> <p>Many of these problems are resolved when using the Septuagint translation:</p> <p>Not really, the problems are still there.</p>'),
