(41, 0, 23, 63, 8, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-01 03:05:41', '<p><br /> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Isaiah 63:8: does not say that God will become our savior but that God became our savior. This is in the past tense and it is Israel/Isaiah speaking. So, it is not referring to a future event (Jesus&rsquo; coming) and not equating Jesus to the Father.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>'),
(41, 0, 23, 63, 9, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-30 05:46:02', '<p>cf. commentary on Num. 20:16 and Ex. 23:20, https://letthetruthcomeoutblog.wordpress.com/2023/01/05/exodus-2320-23-who-is-the-angel/?fbclid=IwAR026OOngKlSghXcBUOLxTpvPb_zZSeGSzPS2yUjkvStGg4QMGYIHaH2ESY</p> <p>Next, we will look at Is. 63:9, which reads:<br /> <br /> &ldquo;In all their affliction he was afflicted, and the angel of his presence saved them; in his love and in his pity he redeemed them; he lifted them up and carried them all the days of old.&rdquo;</p> <p>Here is the third passage which supposedly tells us that a divine agent delivered Israel from Egyptian bondage. The Hebrew reads malak panaw, which literally means a messenger of his face. Because this personage was sent to deliver the people of Israel and not simply bring a message, and because &lsquo;face&rsquo; typically denotes &lsquo;presence&rsquo;, and because there is no definite article in the Hebrew text, we can translate it as an agent of his presence.</p> <p>We have already seen that human agents such as prophets and priests are designated as malak, and that Moses was a prophet and, therefore, can rightly be termed a malak. We have also seen that God commissioned Moses to &ldquo;bring my people out of Egypt&rdquo; {see Ex. 3:10}. Now if someone wants to make the point that there is a difference between &lsquo;bringing&rsquo; the people out of Egypt and &lsquo;delivering&rsquo; them, and that Moses did the former but not the later, then I would turn their attention to Acts 7:35-36:</p> <p>&ldquo;This same Moses&mdash;whom they rejected by saying, &lsquo;Who made you ruler and judge?&rsquo; &mdash;was the man whom God sent to be both their leader and deliverer with the help of the angel who had appeared to him in the bush.&rdquo;</p> <p>The phrase in question is literally &ldquo;an agent of his face.&rdquo; This designation, in all probability, refers to the fact that Moses alone enjoyed a &ldquo;face to face&rdquo; rapport with Yahweh. This is brought out in Ex. 33:7-11, Numbers 7:89, 12:5-8 and Deut. 34:10. Yahweh&rsquo;s presence was associated with the cloud that would appear at the tent of meeting. Moses would go there to speak &lsquo;face to face&rsquo; as it were, with Yahweh. &lsquo;Face to face&rsquo; should not be understood literally but should be taken in the sense of directly, without a dream or vision. Yahweh dispensed with these mediating forms when communicating with Moses and spoke to him directly, with audible voice, from the cloud, which was regarded as his presence. Moses continually stood before the face of Yahweh, i.e. in his presence. This is how Moses can rightly be designated &ldquo;a malak of his presence.&rdquo;</p>'),
(41, 0, 23, 65, 17, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:37:08', '<p>I think this is talking about the New Heavens and earth of Rev. 21 not the millenium.</p> <p>There is a large parallel between the old creation and the new creation spoken of here in Isa. 65.</p> <p>Gen. 1</p> <ol> <li>Gen. 1:1 (old creation)</li> <li>Gen. 2:9; 3:22 (tree of life)</li> <li>asdf</li> <li>asdf</li> <li>asdf</li> </ol> <p>Isa. 65</p> <ol> <li>Isa. 65:17 (new creation)</li> <li>Isa. 65:22 (tree)</li> <li>asdf</li> <li>asdf</li> <li>asdf</li> </ol> <p>^^ All from a chart, not my work</p>'),
(41, 0, 23, 65, 20, 5, null, 99, '2022-03-09 21:31:07', '<p>Not millennium passage.</p> <p>THE USE OF ISAIAH 65 IN REVELATION 21:1&ndash;22:4 POINTS TO ISAIAH 65:20 BEING A DEPICTION OF THE ETERNAL NEW CREATION, NOT THE MILLENIUM.</p> <p>My Septuagint translation: Isa. 65:20c-d - For, the young person will be 100 years old, but the sinner who dies at 100 years old will be cursed (not sure what to do with kai here).</p> <p>SIGNIFICANT CHANGES FROM HEBREW TO SEPTUAGINT &ndash;</p> <ol type="1"> <li>Young person WILL BE not WILL DIE at 100 years old.</li> <li>but the SINNER who dies, not ANYONE who dies.</li> </ol> <p>This means that the text doesn&rsquo;t say that young people will die at 100! It says 100 will be young! this also makes more sense because he just got done saying how there will be no premature death!</p> <p>The only phrase talking about people dying is the last one and its subject is SINNERS not people in the new heavens and earth, therefore, this verse is not saying death will be present in the heavens and earth.</p> <p>------------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Johnny&rsquo;s words - There are quite a few reasons why this verse is not saying that death will be present in the New Heavens and Earth. First, let us look at why the greek does not suggest this. To begin, we must not overlook the &ldquo;for&rdquo; (γαρ) conjunction. This conjunction begins v. 20c and tells the reader that he is expanding on a previous thought. What is this previous thought? Well, the author just finished explaining how there shall not be untimely death, or anyone who does not fill out his days. It would be very strange for the author to say that death will be no more, and then to explain how people will die at 100 (as most translations of the hebrew translate this phrase).</p> <p>The second big key in the greek text is the tense of the participle &ldquo;(sinner) who dies&rdquo; and the tense of the verb &ldquo;will be&rdquo;. For some reason many people read this verse 20d as, &ldquo;the sinner will die at 100 years old and will be cursed.&rdquo; Scholars tend to throw the participle into the future. Yet, in the text it is in the present. Now, if you know Koine Greek, you know that the tense of the participle does not speak as much to the timing of the action as the tense of a verb does. However, the most natural way to understand a present participle is something that is occurring right now, not in the future. In this text, Isaiah is saying that the sinner who dies at 100 years old (in this life, presently), will be cursed in the next. He is contrasting the life that many sinners have graciously received with the life that he will give to his saints. He is saying that many sinners have been blessed (undeservingly) with long life here in this life (100 years) but they will be cursed; they will not be so fortunate in the next life. The way we know that Isaiah is no longer referring to saints is because Isaiah changes the referent to &ldquo;sinner&rdquo;. He is saying there will be no more death (v. 20a) in the New Heaven and Earth (for the saint), BUT for the sinner, they will be cursed. He is not saying that there will be death in the New Heavens and earth, because the referent has changed.</p> <p>In v. 20c, Isaiah is saying, &ldquo;You think that living to 100 years is a long time? 100 years in the next life will be considered young! And those that got to enjoy a long life (100 years) in this life, will not get to enjoy eternal life.&rdquo; He is contrasting the two views of life.</p> <p>----------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Anthony Hoekema in his book The Bible and the Future, believe the language is figurative and should be thought of as saying &ldquo;If someone died at 100 they would be thought a mere youth, and if they failed to reach a 100 they would be considered accursed.&rdquo;</p> <p>the eternal new creation context of Isa 65:17&ndash;19 and 65:21&ndash;25 points to the probability that 65:20 is also about the eternal new creation;</p> <p>That there &ldquo;will no longer be [weeping and crying]&rdquo; at the end of verse 19 is the &ldquo;negative counterpart of &lsquo;for ever&rsquo;&rdquo; in verse 18,15 and the &ldquo;no longer&rdquo; that introduces verse 20 is synonymous with the eternal &ldquo;no longer&rdquo; of verse 19, so that it signals that verse 20a&ndash;b at the least, are about eternal realities!</p> <p>Indeed, verse 19 has said that there will never again be &ldquo;weeping&rdquo; and &ldquo;crying,&rdquo; but if verse 20 is affirming the notion of actual death, then there will be &ldquo;weeping&rdquo; and &ldquo;crying&rdquo; over such death in the eternal state introduced in verses 18&ndash;19 and continued with the &ldquo;no longer&rdquo; (which is synonymous with the eternal &ldquo;no longer&rdquo; of v. 19) at the beginning of verse 20.</p> <p>That a reference to Genesis 3 here is fitting is pointed to by the clearer allusion to Gen 3:14&ndash;15 in Isa 65:25, which narrates the curse on the serpent: &ldquo;on your belly shall you go, and dust shall you eat &hellip; he [the seed of the woman] shall bruise you [the serpent] on the head.&rdquo; Isaiah 65:25 has, &ldquo;dust shall be the serpent&rsquo;s food. They [including the serpent] shall do no evil or harm on all my holy mountain.&rdquo;25 This refers to the serpent being consummately defeated, so that there will be more harm or evil in the new age (which could not be true of the millennial age).</p> <p>death (see &ldquo;not labor in vain&rdquo; in Isa 65:23a; cf. Gen 3:17&ndash;19) and of the woman&rsquo;s cursed labor pains (Gen 3:16)27 being reversed into a &ldquo;blessing&rdquo; for her &ldquo;seed&rdquo; (Isa 65:23).</p> <p>The following verbal and thematic parallels can be observed between the two passages that cumulatively are unique in all of the OT: (a) the new epoch occurs on a holy &ldquo;mountain&rdquo; (Isa 25:7, 10a and 65:25; cf. Isa 27:13); (b) it will be a time of &ldquo;rejoicing&rdquo; and &ldquo;gladness&rdquo; (using the same Hebrew verbs ילג and שׂמח for these expressions39); (c) God &ldquo;will remove the reproach of his people from all the earth&rdquo; (Isa 25:6) and &ldquo;the former troubles are forgotten&rdquo; and &ldquo;are hid from&rdquo; God&rsquo;s &ldquo;sight&rdquo; (Isa 65:16); (d) it will be a time in which there will be no more crying (Isa 25:8 and 65:19); (e) both speak of the condition of this new era lasting either &ldquo;for all time&rdquo; (Isa 25:8, the time &ldquo;death&rdquo; will be abolished) or &ldquo;forever&rdquo; (e.g. Isa 65:18, the time of &ldquo;rejoicing&rdquo;).</p> <p>Though Isa 65:20 is not a specific development of Isaiah 25, the verses around verse 20 are dependent on Isaiah 25 and its eternal new creational idea</p> <p>In other words, if all youths will die at one hundred or less, then there would be no old men to live out their days. So, even the premillennial literalist must take the phrase about &ldquo;the youth&rdquo; figuratively to some degree or paraphrase it in some sense so it would be harmonious with their view: e.g. &ldquo;some youths will die at the age of a hundred&rdquo; or &ldquo;one would be considered a youth who dies at the age of one hundred&rdquo; (v. 20d).</p>'),
