(41, 0, 24, 1, 5, 3, null, 99, '2022-12-04 04:11:46', '<p>This text is about Jeremiah. God, throughout the Bible, chooses people from birth to be advocates for him. King David was convinced about this. Isaiah was convinced of this (Isa 49:1). (MY WORDS &ndash; PAUL WAS ALSO CONVINCED OF THIS ROM. 9 MAYBE) It is a fallacy is to take special people in the Bible and then export their experiences to all of humanity. Not everyone is King David or Jeremiah. This is the logical fallacy of composition.</p> <p>But even God&rsquo;s calling doesn&rsquo;t always go as planned. In Numbers 18, God gives Aaron and his sons the priesthood. But in Leviticus 10:1, Aaron&rsquo;s immediate sons quickly sin and God puts them to death. They have failed their calling and have failed God.</p> <p>In 1 Samuel 22, the same thing happens. The sons of Eli sin. God kills them, revokes his promise to Aaron&rsquo;s lineage, and then promises to raise up a faithful priest instead:</p> <p>1Sa 2:30 Therefore the LORD God of Israel says: &lsquo;I said indeed that your house and the house of your father would walk before Me forever.&rsquo; But now the LORD says: &lsquo;Far be it from Me; for those who honor Me I will honor, and those who despise Me shall be lightly esteemed.</p> <p>Notice the revocation of God&rsquo;s promise. If God has foreseen the revoking of His promise, then His promise was a lie. The more natural reading is that although God raised up Aaron&rsquo;s lineage to be a priest nation, they ignored God&rsquo;s guidance, and God changed His mind based on their actions. God chooses to raise up a new priest:</p> <p>1Sa 2:35 Then I will raise up for Myself a faithful priest who shall do according to what is in My heart and in My mind. I will build him a sure house, and he shall walk before My anointed forever.</p> <p>The very next chapter starts with God calling to the boy, Samuel. Samuel was called as a boy, not from before birth, and only because of the failings of Eli&rsquo;s sons. But Eli was called young, because God raises up people from birth. Sometimes they are a plan B, as with David who receives Saul&rsquo;s kingdom after God wanted to give Saul an eternal kingdom but then Saul failed. Sometimes God&rsquo;s chosen fail God.</p>'),
(41, 0, 24, 17, 27, 4, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:38:43', '<p>Quench dods not mean burning eternally! Just that it finishes what it burns!</p>'),
