(41, 0, 27, 7, 7, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-09 03:12:54', '<p>This is the old Roman Empire. 10 horns are the ten kings of the different provinces. But, Rome was not destroyed with fire, like in v. 11&hellip; so idk.</p> <p>This can&rsquo;t be Jerusalem becuase it was not a mighty power.</p>'),
(41, 0, 27, 7, 13, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:39:02', '<p>as John Calvin and other scholars have noted, Daniel 7 refers not to the Son of Man&rsquo;s descent from heaven but to His entrance into heaven to receive His kingdom.</p>'),
(41, 0, 27, 7, 27, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-09 03:10:19', '<p>Doesn&rsquo;t seem to have happened in 70AD, not all dominions serve and obey Christ.</p>'),
(41, 0, 27, 9, 24, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:39:15', '<p>All of these things did happen through the first advent of Jesus.</p> <p>The &ldquo;sealing up of both vision and prophecy&rdquo; is vital and often misinterpreted. Think about who this was written to, Jews, before Christ, those were the ones for whom prophecy and vision would disappear after the 70 weeks and they did! Many of those gifts were transferred to Christianity, see Joel 2, Acts, 2.</p> <p>Anointing the most holy was done at pentecost. The new temple, Christians, see 2 Cor. 6:16.</p>'),
(41, 0, 27, 11, 31, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>This is talking about Antiochus Epiphanes. Nothing Future.</p>'),
(41, 0, 27, 12, 2, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:41:22', '<p>The key to understanding when Daniel 12:2 occurs is found in 12:13. It says that he shall rest, and shall stand in his allotted place at the end of the days. Now, without bringing in any extra theological baggage, does it seem like the end of the days has occurred? No, clearly days are still going. And this would be quite strange to be referring to a different resurrection than the one in Dan. 12:2, because only one resurrection is mentioned in the entirety of scripture (Acts, John 5, Hebrews 9 or 10), besides in Rev. 20:4-6, which I take to be a spiritual resurrection, because it is a visionary passage.</p> <p>Now addressing the two opposing views, the full preterist view and the premillennial dispensational view. First, the full preterist view, they take this resurrection to happen either in 164 BC after the reign of Antiochus Epiphanes, or in 70 AD after the power of the holy people is shattered as Don Preston puts it. The problem of both of these views, is that they simply didn&rsquo;t happen. No multitude of bodies resurrected with both believers and unbelievers. This event is simply not recorded in history. The only bodily resurrection recorded is in the gospels where some believers are resurrected at the death of Jesus. Also, the reason I keep saying bodily resurrection is because an invisible spirit-body resurrection is not resurrection at all. That is important to understand.</p> <p>Next, the premillennial dispensational view. The reason Daniel 12:2 cannot be understood from this viewpoint is that they believe in a large thousand-year gap between the resurrection of believers prior to the millennium (Rev. 20:4-6), and unbelievers after the millennium (Rev. 20:10). Now, to understand this text to refer to anything of that sort is to slaughter the text. It mentions no thousand year gap in between resurrections, and puts them side by side. One resurrection is mentioned here, of believers and unbelievers, to different fates, it is really not that complicated.</p> <p>So, we are not to slaughter the meaning of the text by saying that the resurrection has already happened and we are also not to slaughter it by saying that there is a mysterious 1,000 year gap implied by the word &ldquo;but&rdquo;. Both are to destroy the plain meaning of the text that one resurrection will occur with two destinies.</p>'),
(41, 0, 29, 2, 32, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:41:36', '<p>Destruction of Jerusalem in AD 70. Pentecost is happening in Joel 2:28-31. This makes much more sense than separating these two thoughts by thousands of years as dispensationalists do. After this we would expect the church age.</p>'),
(41, 0, 29, 3, 18, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:41:56', '<p>Not 100% sure this is the church age like Steve Gregg suggests. Not literal, wine doesn&rsquo;t drip from mountains, and a spring will come forth from the house of Yahweh, it is the living water in Zech. 14:8. This water in Joel 3:18 originates in Jerusalem, passes the Jordan to the Acacias on the other side, but two rivers can&rsquo;t pass eachother. They can merge but one can&rsquo;t go over another, this is a clue that the water is not literal!</p>'),
(41, 0, 29, 3, 20, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:42:08', '<p>The true Jerusalem, the one without walls.</p>'),
(41, 0, 35, 3, 13, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-27 04:52:02', '<p>gen. 3:15</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 4, 7, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:42:25', '<p>See Comm. Zech. 14:4. Not literal.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 9, 1, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-03 03:48:54', '<p>Steve Gregg says 1-8 is about victory over Alexander the great, but then v. 9 is about Jesus, not sure yet, don&rsquo;t know what Hadrach and Damascus are.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 12, 10, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:42:50', '<p>Pentecost</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 13, 8, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:42:56', '<p>AD 70, judgement against Jerusalem. That is what this whole section is about Zech. 12-14.</p> <p>Dispensationalists see a 2,000 year gap between Zech. 13:7 and 13:8. Yet, there is nothing in the text to suggest this.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 13, 9, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:43:00', '<p>These are the remnant that survive through AD 70. Peter talks about Christians as going through a furnace.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:43:07', '<p>We must use the big markers in the text to understand the confusing parts. Use the clear to understand the confusing. This text has told us that it is about a punishment against physical Jerusalem in Zech 12. This is not talking about the end of the world because it is a punishment on Jerusalem (Zech. 14:1). Also, the beginning of Zech. 12, which is the beginning of this section is about a judgement against Jerusalem. The second coming is a worldwide event.</p> <p>Also, Zech. 13:7 gives us a time frame for when this all happens, &ldquo;strike the shepherd&rdquo; we know this happens at the time of Jesus, and then in the very same sentence he says &ldquo;and I will turn my hand against the little ones&rdquo; this seems to happen right after in AD 70, not 2,000 years later. That is an extremely awkward way to read the text.</p> <p>Zech. 13:9 is really important for understanding Zechariah&rsquo;s use of &ldquo;Jerusalem&rdquo;. One Jerusalem is the physical Jerusalem that was destroyed in AD 70 (2/3, Zech. 13:8), and one Jerusalem is the spiritual Jerusalem the 1/3 which survive (Zech. 13:9).</p> <p>Why this passage is not completely literal &ndash;</p> <ol type="1"> <li>Zech. 14:8 &ndash; living water is not literal, Jesus said so himself.</li> <li>Zech. 13:1 &ndash; not a literal spring</li> <li>Zech. 13:9 &ndash; people are not literally refined like gold.</li> </ol> <p>This passage is full of symbolism and metaphor, so we must distinguish the meaning from these things.</p> <p>-------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Reasons this passage is not talking about millennial kingdom &ndash;</p> <ol type="1"> <li>There is no day or night (Zech. 14:6-7) this is exactly what happens in the New Jerusalem (Rev. 22:5) not the millennial kingdom.</li> <li>God is the ruler over all, not Jesus (Zech. 14:9). Yahweh is not Jesus.</li> <li>Rivers of living water flow (Zech. 14:8) this also occurs in the New Jerusalem, not the millennial kingdom (Rev. 22:1).</li> </ol>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 2, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:43:11', '<p>Jerusalem here is the physical Jerusalem of Zech. 13:8 which is destroyed.</p> <p>&ldquo;The message is that the future of the church will involve a time when it will be surrounded by its enemies and seemingly overwhelmed by them&hellip;. Under the metaphor of the pillaging of an ancient city, the church is presented as suffering grievously at the hands of her enemies, and yet there has been a remnant left.&rdquo;</p>');
INSERT INTO `myrevdata` (`myrevid`, `testament`, `book`, `chapter`, `verse`, `highlight`, `marginnote`, `sqn`, `lastupdate`, `myrevnotes`) VALUES
(41, 0, 38, 14, 3, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:20', '<p>The &ldquo;nations&rdquo; here could be referring to the Jews who had gathered into Jerusalem to celebrate the passover. These Jews were from every nation and were persecuting the Christians, the True Jerusalem.</p> <p>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>It is not unreasonable to assume this is talking about the eventual destruction of Rome.</p> <p>Isaiah 19:1 talking about the Assyrians coming to fight against egypt, &ldquo;the Lord will come on a swift cloud&rdquo;. This language is used but God didn&rsquo;t literally come on a cloud.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 4, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:26', '<p>This is not literal because topographical changes like this are common in the OT. Zech. 4:7, &ldquo;who are you oh mountain, before Zerubabbel you will become a plain.&rdquo; Did this happen literally? no. Micah 1:3 is equally non-literal.</p> <p>Yahweh here is the one who is standing on the Mount of Olives, not Jesus! This is not talking about the second coming of Jesus as many premillenialists claim.</p> <p>Ezek. 11:23 During God&rsquo;s judgement against Jerusalem, his Shakaina glory leaves Jerusalem and settles on the mount of olives, symbolizing that God&rsquo;s presence is no longer with them in the Temple. Before the destruction in 586BC.</p> <p>Even while God&rsquo;s presence has left physical Jerusalem/Israel, he still provides a way of escape (Exodus/splitting of mountain) for the remnant. The true and spiritual Israel.</p> <p>&ldquo;Verse 4 pictures the LORD creating an unexpected way of escape for his people; verse 5 pictures them using it&hellip;. Quite intentionally, the imagery used here reminds us of Israel&rsquo;s miraculous deliverance at the Red Sea (Exodus 14:1ff).&rdquo;</p> <p>This happened!! they went to the east to Pella!</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 5, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:28', '<p>The earthquake of Uzziah&rsquo;s time is barely mentioned in scripture. Amos prophesied two years before what was apparently the same earthquake (Amos 1:1). Such an earthquake must have been severe if it was still remembered over two centuries later in post-exilic Judah. It was an unforgettable national disaster which doubtless gripped the imaginations of Zechariah&rsquo;s original audience.[4] That historical event is likened to the Lord&rsquo;s coming, which will shake the entire earth (cf. Hag. 2:6&ndash;7; Heb. 12:26&ndash;27) and bring terror to those caught desecrating his holy dwelling.</p> <p>More likely, much of the description of the earthquake, including the mention of Azel, simply refers to details of the historical earthquake during the reign of Uzziah.[2] It is as if the prophet rehearses the details of that past event to say, &ldquo;It will be like that again when the Lord comes to defend his city. His people will have a way of escape.&rdquo; That is certainly the comparison in verse 5: &ldquo;Yes, you will flee just as you fled before the earthquake in the days of Uzziah king of Judah.&rdquo;</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 6, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:32', '<p>Figure of speech, used often in scripture, their lights will go out. Isa. 13:10 fall of Babylon to Persians, Ezek. 32 &ndash; when I put out your light &ndash; when babylonians conquered Egypt, Joel 2:28 judgement on Jerusalem &ldquo;sun shall</p> <p>Its the destruction of one entity (Zech. 14:6), and the creation of another one (Zech. 14:7).</p> <p>Bryan Gregory also observes, &ldquo;The disruption to the normal cycles of day and night is significant. In God&rsquo;s promise to Noah, he had promised that the normal rhythms of seasons and days would not cease for as long as the earth endures (Gen. 8:22).&rdquo;[2] Thus Zechariah indicates that, although he speaks in terms of the old city of Jerusalem and land of Judah, this holy city and promised land will be part of the new creation. The earth as his readers know it will have passed away.[3]</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 7, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:35', '<p>It shall be day one. this is the hebrew literally. It&rsquo;s the first day of the new creation. This is a day of light at night, even though the day before was dark.</p> <p>Its the destruction of one entity (Zech. 14:6), and the creation of another one (Zech. 14:7).</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 8, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:37', '<p>In John 7 Jesus says, &ldquo;As the scriptures say, out of your hearts will flow rivers of living water&rdquo; well what OT scripture says that? None besides this one. That means two things.</p> <ol type="1"> <li>That the Jerusalem here is the spiritual Jerusalem.</li> <li>The water is spiritual not literal.</li> </ol> <p>-------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>This is not just typical of physical change, but of the spiritual blessings that water represents. It is &lsquo;living&rsquo; water flowing freshly from a spring or fountain, and symbolic of true spiritual life given in salvation (Jer. 2:13; John 4:10; 7:38). This looks back to the river of Paradise, when &lsquo;a river watering the garden flowed from Eden&rsquo; (Gen. 2:10), and it looks forward to Paradise restored&hellip;. Truly &lsquo;there is a river whose streams make glad the city of God, the holy place where the Most High dwells&rsquo; (Ps. 46:4).</p> <p>Unlike Ezekiel&rsquo;s river which flowed only to the east (Ezek. 47:1, an embarrassment for those who take both prophecies to refer to the same literal future event), the water splits half to the eastern sea, that is the Dead Sea, and half to the western sea, that is, the Mediterranean. In this way it is available for all the land. And it is available all the time, in summer and in winter. Many streams in Palestine were only winter torrents which dried up in the heat of summer, when the need for water was at its greatest. Not so this source of supply. It is available all the year round. There is no disruption of the bliss of the new creation &lsquo;for the old order of things has passed away&rsquo; (Rev. 21:4).</p> <p>MacKay, <em>Haggai, Zechariah and Malachi</em>, 308&ndash;309.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 9, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:41', '<p>This is true under the new creation. Jesus and Yahweh are king over the whole earth.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 10, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:44', '<p>The exaltation of Jerusalem in verse 10 reflects a common prophetic theme. Perhaps the clearest parallel appears in Isaiah 2:2&ndash;3:</p> <p>2 Now it will come about that in the last days the mountain of the house of the Lord will be established as the chief of the mountains, and will be raised above the hills; and all the nations will stream to it. 3 And many peoples will come and say, &ldquo;Come, let us go up to the mountain of the Lord, to the house of the God of Jacob; that He may teach us concerning His ways and that we may walk in His paths.&rdquo; For the law will go forth from Zion and the word of the Lord from Jerusalem.</p> <p>Steve Gregg, In the Millennial kingdom, Jerusalem, the spiritual Jerusalem is exalted. These things happen in the NT, Christians have come to the ciy of Zion in Hebrews 12 I think. Through Jesus God taught us concerning his ways, and the Spirit was given so that we may walk in his paths.</p> <p>------------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>&ldquo;Before the exile, Geba and Rimmon denoted the northern and southern boundaries of Judah during the days of Josiah&rsquo;s reform. In other words, the land will be restored to her preexilic, pre-disaster state, and being &lsquo;leveled out,&rsquo; will provide a geological setting for the crown jewel of the new creation, the city of Jerusalem&hellip;.The boundaries are not only a way of tracing the city&rsquo;s limits but are more importantly an allusion to Jeremiah 31 where the Lord had promised that the city would be rebuilt from the Tower of Hananel to the Corner Gate (Jer. 31:38). Part of the promise to Jeremiah was that the whole city would once again become holy, never again to be uprooted or demolished (Jer. 31:39&ndash;40; cf. Zech. 14:20&ndash;21). In other words, the boundaries paint a picture of Jerusalem as a city entirely safe from the threat of violence.&rdquo; Gregory, <em>Longing for God</em>, 208&ndash;209.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 11, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:57', '<p>Rev. 22:3</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 12, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:45:59', '<p>Similar to Rev. 20:9</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 14, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:46:07', '<p>And as was promised them, they will share in the spoils. They will plunder the Egyptians. They will inherit the earth.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 15, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:46:10', '<p>Not only will the people themselves who disobey God be cursed, but their possessions too.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 16, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:46:12', '<p>See 1 Cor. 5:8, Christians are keeping the the feast of unleavened bread, but not literally. Spiritually.</p> <p>Then what is the feast of Tabernacles in the NT? The Gentiles coming into the spiritual Jerusalem and celebrating the spiritual feast of tabernacles. How would this be accomplished? Well the time before Israel entered the promised land was when they lived in booths, now the time we live as Christians here on earth before the entering the New Jerusalem is our dwelling in &ldquo;Tabernacles&rdquo;. The important part of this celebration was remembering that even while the Jews were living in tents, God was with them. And now as we await our entering into the New Jerusalem God is with us through the Holy Spirit.</p> <p>2 Cor. 5:1-2 says that Christians live in tents. We are living in booths, not literally, but spiritually as we await our eternal bodies (1 Cor. 15.).</p> <p>We are currently living the fulfillment of the feast of Tabernacles, we are living in Tabernacles, with God dwelling with us, as we await our eternal home!</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Zech. 14:12-15: dealt with the horrible fate of the nations who attacked Jerusalem. There are those Gentiles, however, who survive the Day of the Lord. Though once strangers and enemies to Israel and her God, this remnant of Gentiles are now fellow worshipers with the Israelites. This picture of a remnant from the Gentile nations which engages in perpetual observance of the Feast of Booths (or &ldquo;Tabernacles&rdquo;) beautifully reveals the deep meaning and eventual fulfillment of this Old Testament feast.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 18, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:46:16', '<p>Rain is a not to be understood literally but as God&rsquo;s blessing. Rain comes down from heaven, so many saw it as the blessing of God (Zech. 10:1). If you do not have &ldquo;rain&rdquo;, you do not have the blessing of God.</p> <p>The nations that are not part of the church will not have the blessing of God, or the &ldquo;rain&rdquo;.</p> <p>--------------------------------------------------</p> <p>What harvest is celebrated by this eschatological Feast of Booths? Barry Webb answers well. &ldquo;It is people &ndash; formerly enemies, but now worshippers &ndash; gathered in from all the nations, to worship, at last, their rightful Lord and King.&rdquo;[2]</p> <p>How fitting that the text now contrasts a harvest celebration with the withholding of rain. &ldquo;&lsquo;Rain&rsquo; here stands for all the blessings that the Lord bestows, particularly in the harvest (10:1). These will be withheld from those who persist in their rebellion.&rdquo;[3] Andrew Hill adds, &ldquo;The lack of rainfall was one of the curses God pronounced against Israel for covenant disobedience (cf. Deut. 28:22&ndash;24). <strong>Here that curse is extended to the nations by virtue of God&rsquo;s rule over all peoples.</strong>&rdquo;[4] T. V. Moore remarks, &ldquo;In this future condition, the present mingled state of reward and punishment shall end. Now God sends rain on the just and the unjust, then he will separate the good and the evil, and render unto every man according to his works.&rdquo;[5]</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 19, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:46:39', '<p>In the future day of which Zechariah speaks, Egypt as well as all the unrepentant nations will suffer the unmitigated plagues of God&rsquo;s wrath.They will be cursed. This might be the punishment of unbelievers before their destruction in the Lake of Fire. Perhaps they live cursed for awhile&hellip; and then suffer in the lake of fire. Not exactly sure what to do with this.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 20, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:46:40', '<p>Why were all of these modes of worship using physical things, if they were talking about future spiritual realities? Because that is all they knew. That is the only type of worship they knew. They did not have the Spirit dwelling in them.</p> <p>In the old order some things were holy, some things weren&rsquo;t. The high priest had inscribed on his head &ldquo;Holy to the Lord&rdquo; now even the most mundane things (bells on horses) will be holy.</p> <p>In the OT some things were offered to God and some were not. Sabbath: 6 days not holy, 7<sup>th</sup> holy. Tithe: 90% not holy, 10% holy to God. Priests were holy, commoners were not. Certain foods were holy, other foods were not.</p> <p>In the NT everything is holy or set apart for God!!!! Sabbath is fulfilled in Jesus (), we are a kingdom of Priests (), All food is declared clean ()</p> <p>Zech. 14:20 here is huge in showing that in this &ldquo;day&rdquo; all things even the bells on horses will be holy!</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Why mention the bells on horses? They are mentioned in order to shock Zechariah&rsquo;s audience. &ldquo;Shocking here is the reference to an item associated with the horse, a ritually unclean animal according to Lev. 11:1&ndash;8. In this new Jerusalem, that which was once treated as unclean is now not merely clean, but holy.&rdquo;[1] The inscription on the bells of the horses is the same as that on the high priest&rsquo;s turban!</p> <p>36 You shall also make a plate of pure gold and shall engrave on it, like the engravings of a seal, &lsquo;Holy to the Lord.&rsquo; 37 You shall fasten it on a blue cord, and it shall be on the turban; it shall be at the front of the turban. 38 It shall be on Aaron&rsquo;s forehead, and Aaron shall take away the iniquity of the holy things which the sons of Israel consecrate, with regard to all their holy gifts; and it shall always be on his forehead, that they may be accepted before the Lord. (Exod. 28:36&ndash;38)</p> <p>Zechariah reinforces his point by also speaking of pots and pans. &ldquo;Similarly, the cooking pots in the temple would be as holy as the basins in front of the altar. Even the most common pot would become holy, so holy that anyone wishing to sacrifice could readily use them.&rdquo; Gregory, Longing for God, 211.</p> <p>&ldquo;All distinction between sacred and secular shall be at an end, because all shall now be alike holy.&rdquo;[3] Kenneth L. Barker, Zechariah, Expositor&rsquo;s Bible Commentary, rev. ed., ed. Tremper Longman III and David E. Garland, vol. 8 (Grand Rapids: Zondervan, 2008), 832. These words flatly contradict the entire notion of a literal millennial temple, but they accurately reflect the thrust of Zechariah&rsquo;s words. As MacKay puts it, &ldquo;Even the smallest and seemingly most trivial details of life are consecrated to the Lord. This, of course, would involve the cessation of the Levitical distinction between sacred and common.&rdquo;MacKay, Haggai, Zechariah and Malachi, 318.</p>'),
(41, 0, 38, 14, 21, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:46:45', '<p>We offer up spiritual sacrifices but they are cast in this physical light, because that is all they knew. There was no such thing as a spiritual sacrifice. But there is in the NT. 1 Pet. 2:5 &ndash; we are a holy priesthood offering spiritual sacrifices. Paul says our bodies are a living sacrifice. Hebrews 13:15 says we offer the sacrifice of the praise of God.</p> <p>-------------------------------------------------</p> <p>MacKay is right to say, &ldquo;The mention of the Canaanite is not to debar any on racial grounds, but on ethical and spiritual. &lsquo;Nothing impure will ever enter it, nor will anyone who does what is shameful or deceitful, but only those whose names are written in the Lamb&rsquo;s book of life&rsquo; (Rev. 21:27).&rdquo;[7] MacKay, Haggai, Zechariah and Malachi, 319.</p>'),
(41, 0, 39, 4, 3, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-27 05:01:16', '<p>Gen. 3:15. Crushing the head, ashes under the soles of your feet.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 2, 2, 0, 'I have commentary to add', 99, '2022-08-02 18:28:08', '<p>They came to Jerusalem, not to Bethlehem!! They go to Bethelehem later, they did not follow a star, see commentary on this verse</p> <p>Comm: Now, as we demonstrated in our commentary on Matthew 2:9 the star that the magi most likely saw was the star of Jupiter (King&rsquo;s star). However, something special must have occured to the star to make the magi come to Jerusalem, its simple rising and setting would not have caused the magi to think a king was going to be born. Although there are a few different theories of what happened, they are almost all out of date with Jesus birth. Yet, there is one that lines up quite nicely with Jesus&rsquo; birth.</p> <p>Three times (in May, September, and December of 7BC) Jupiter and Saturn passed over each other so close together that they appeared as one star, this is known as the &ldquo;Triple Conjunction&rdquo; of the two planets, and it only happens once every 800 years. This phenomenon was discovered by Johannes Kepler because a very similar phenomenon occured during his lifetime.</p> <p>Now, the question still stands, what about this phenomenon made the magi think that a King of the Jews would be born?</p> <p>David Hughes put forth a theory in his 1979 book <em>The Star Of Bethlehem Mystery.</em> He proposed that the magi were inspired by the triple conjunction of Jupiter (the King of the Planets) and Saturn (Planet of Justice) in astronomical region of Pisces (spans 330-360 degrees of celestial longitude): the zodiacal sign of the Jewish nation. So, it was this particular phenomenon which rarely occurs in Pisces that prompted the magi to think that a Jewish king would be born. Now, this is all speculation, as the scriptures do not tell us exactly what happened, but it is a very likely explanation for why the magi went to Jerusalem.</p> <p>It is also very possible that something miraculous occured and a star appeared and that is why the magi went to Jerusalem, the reason this is not likely, is that there is no record of this from Chinese astronomers who started keeping records around 250BC and also, more people likely would have seen it than just the magi.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 3, 1, 0, 'I have commentary to add', 99, '2022-06-02 15:32:32', '<p>Commentary: <strong>&ldquo;in those days&rdquo;</strong> &ndash; This is the literal rendering of the phrase from the Greek, however, the phrase is quite peculiar because Matthew has just finished talking about how Joseph, Mary, and Jesus went to Nazareth and lived there. This happened early on in Jesus&rsquo; life, which means that almost 30 years had passed between Matthew 2:23 and Matthew 3:1. So, why does Matthew say, &ldquo;in those days?&rdquo; As if he is speaking of the same time frame as Matthew 2:23?</p> <p>There are no clear occurances of the phrase &ldquo;in those days&rdquo; being used to introduce a completely new time frame, as it is seemingly used here. Many commentaries suggest that this phrase can introduce a new time frame, but when looking at each of those occurances they put forward such as Genesis 6:4, Deuteronomy 17:9, and Daniel 10:2 there is a defined time frame already within the context. The phrase never introduces a new time frame. So, how are we to understand this phrase?</p> <p>R.T. France, in his commentary on Matthew, suggests that the best way to understand &ldquo;in those days&rdquo; is &ldquo;in those days&rdquo; when Jesus was still living in Nazareth. So, although 30 years has passed, what Matthew mentions in Matthew 2:23, that Jesus is living in Nazareth, still holds true in Matthew 3:1, and so &ldquo;in those days&rdquo; is properly supplied. Therefore, &ldquo;in those days&rdquo; means in the days that Jesus was still living in Nazareth, John the Baptist came on the scene.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 3, 7, 0, 'I have commentary written', 99, '2022-06-06 16:29:05', '<p>Comm: <strong>&ldquo;Who warned you to flee from the wrath&hellip;?&rdquo;</strong> &ndash; This question by John is quite peculiar at first, because it seems to be unrelated, the only thing that has happened is that the Pharisees and Sadducees showed up to where John was baptizing. So, how are they fleeing from wrath?</p> <p>The context is very helpful here. It seems that the Pharisees and Sadducees were coming to be baptized by John, so that they could be forgiven. The only problem was, these Jews felt that they could receive baptism from John solely because they were Jews, Abraham was their Father (Matt. 3:9). Yet, their actions did not line up with someone who has truly repented (Matt. 3:8), this is why John has such a harsh reaction towards them. They were there, to be forgiven, but not to repent. Therefore, it becomes clear that the Pharisees and Sadducees wanted things from God (salvation and forgiveness) without having the proper heart posture (true repentance) which God requires before forgiving.</p> <p>We also see this recurring theme of the Pharisees unrepentance all throughout the gospel (Matt. 12:34; 23:37), this idea gets repeated and expanded throughout. In agreement with the rest of the scriptures, here in Matthew 3:7-12, John the Baptist teaches that forgiveness is conditional upon repentance, not simply doing the right outward action, but a right posture of the heart.</p> <p>Thus, they are &ldquo;fleeing from wrath&rdquo; in the sense that they were wanting to be baptized to avoid the wrath and punishment of God. As Leon Morris puts it, &ldquo;The implication is that they had no real repentance but only a desire to escape divine retribution.&rdquo; (Leon Morris, The Gospel according to Matthew, PNTC, 58)</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 5, 5, 0, 'revisit', 99, '2023-02-08 16:38:03', '<p>&ldquo;will inherit the land.&rdquo; This word can be either land or earth in both the new and old Testaments. Here to make a greater connection with the promise of Abraham that he will live in the &ldquo;land&rdquo; this might be more fitting.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 5, 18, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:47:35', '<p>He&rsquo;s essentially saying &ldquo;Until this impossibility happens (which it won&rsquo;t) the law will not be broken.&rdquo; Jerry used analogy i will lose ten pounds before my gym membership expires. Well if he loses ten pounds does that mean his gym membership expires right at that moment? no. It&rsquo;s just he needed to be at the gym for the first thing to be accomplished.</p> <p>Heaven and earth will remain and not pass away before the law is fulfilled.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 10, 10, 1, null, 99, '2022-08-04 21:01:50', '<p>What is the easiest explanation here? The Lord Jesus allowed them to use one walking staff, just not bring along another (or special) one. In other words, they did not need to go out a buy another staff to prepare for their journeys (thus giving them two or more staves, which Jesus forbade). No, just they just needed to bring along the one staff they already had. They did not need to pack a bag with money or extra clothes, either. Bringing along more supplies was unnecessary.</p> <p>NVM its not plural in greek&hellip; idk where this guy got this from</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 12, 31, 1, null, 99, '2022-09-21 18:23:33', '<p>Why, then, in Mark 3:29 does Jesus seem to exclude one sin and one blasphemy from this promise: the blasphemy against the Holy Spirit? I think the reason is that blasphemy against the Holy Spirit puts you beyond repentance, and therefore beyond forgiveness. John Piper has rightly pointed out that verse 29 is not an exception to verse 28. Jesus is not saying, all blasphemies that you repent of will be forgiven except blasphemy against the Spirit. He is saying, all blasphemies that you repent of will be forgiven, but blasphemy against the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven because by its very nature it puts you beyond repentance. It is the sort of sin that issues from a heart so incorrigibly calloused that a person simply isn&rsquo;t able to repent of it. If a sin makes it impossible for you to repent, then that is an unforgivable sin, because forgiveness is promised only to those sins from which we genuinely repent (cf. 4:12). (Sam Storms)</p> <p>This goes with the idea of free will but not with Calvinism, because it is saying that one goes beyond the possibility of forgiveness, but if God is the one who regenerates hearts, how is their a heart to hard for him to regenerate?&hellip; instead, this is saying that there hearts are so hard that they will not repent. By its very nature, it is unforgivable because people do not repent of it. If one can see such true and powerful work of the Spirit and still deny it, that means that they are too hardened to ever repent, and be forgiven.</p> <p>The immediate result of the Pharisees&rsquo; public rejection of Christ (and God&rsquo;s rejection of them) is seen in the next chapter. Jesus, for the first time, &ldquo;told them many things in parables&rdquo; (Matthew 13:3; cf. Mark 4:2). The disciples were puzzled at Jesus&rsquo; change of teaching method, and Jesus explained His use of parables: &ldquo;Because the knowledge of the secrets of the kingdom of heaven has been given to you, but not to them. . . . Though seeing, they do not see; though hearing, they do not hear or understand&rdquo; (Matthew 13:11, 13).</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 12, 34, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-27 04:35:43', '<p>Vipers, Gen. 3:15.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 13, 40, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:47:52', '<p>I think this is talking about AD 70 not the final judgement, because all of the judgements are only negative!</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 16, 28, 5, null, 99, '2022-03-06 06:35:46', '<p>First, in v. 27 the Lord is said to come &ldquo;in the glory of His Father with his angels.&rdquo; But in v. 28 we read that he is &ldquo;coming in His kingdom.&rdquo; Thus, v. 27 speaks of His Father&rsquo;s glory whereas v. 28 speaks of Christ&rsquo;s royal authority. So the first verse emphasizes the Son&rsquo;s coming in the Father&rsquo;s glory, while the second emphasizes the Son&rsquo;s coming in his own kingdom authority.</p> <p>Second, in v. 27 we see the universal nature of his coming: he &ldquo;will then repay every man.&rdquo; Thus, all men will be involved in his judgment. This must be understood in terms of Matt. 25:31&ndash;46, a powerful pronouncement (distinctive to Matthew) regarding the Final Judgment (I will be demonstrating this in my forthcoming commentary on Matt. 21&ndash;25). This should also be compared to Matt. 13:36&ndash;43.</p> <p>But in v. 28 the focus is drawn more narrowly. There Jesus limits the reference to &ldquo;some of those who are standing here.&rdquo; This does not imply that only the disciples will witness AD 70, of course. Yet it does show an intentional distinction of audience expectation in Jesus&rsquo; instruction. One audience includes all men, the other only the disciples for his present instructional and exhortational purpose.</p> <p>We are seeing subtle evidences that Jesus is distinguishing his AD 70 (spiritual, metaphorical) coming from his (literal, glorious) Second Coming to effect the Final Judgment.</p> <p>In order to come to an understanding of this saying, we must again be reminded that when Jesus speaks of the &ldquo;coming of the Son of Man,&rdquo; he is purposefully alluding to Daniel 7:13&ndash;14. And again we must recall that the coming of the Son of Man in Daniel 7 is set within a judgment scene before the throne of God (cf. Dan. 7:9&ndash;10). Unlike the saying in Matthew 10:23, the saying in 16:28 is found in the immediate context of words regarding judgment (v. 27). The point that Jesus is making when he says that there are some standing here who will not die before they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom is that there are some to whom he is speaking who will not</p> <p>die before the prophecy of Daniel 7 is fulfilled, in other words, before Jesus receives the kingdom from his Father.</p> <p>A comparison of Matthew 16:28 with its parallels in Mark 9:1 and Luke 9:27 lends support to this interpretation. All three sayings are set within the same context immediately before the Transfiguration, yet whereas Matthew speaks of some living long enough to see the coming of the Son of Man, Mark and Luke speak of some living long enough to see the coming of the kingdom of God. The &ldquo;coming of the Son of Man&rdquo; then is simply another way of saying &ldquo;the coming of the kingdom of God.&rdquo; It is the assumption that the words &ldquo;coming of the Son of Man&rdquo; must mean &ldquo;Second Coming&rdquo; that has caused much of the confusion. Once we realize that Jesus is simply using a phrase from Daniel 7 to allude to the whole prophecy, texts such as Matthew 16:28 are much more readily understood. Jesus was not predicting that his Second Coming would occur within the lifetime of some of his hearers. He wasn&rsquo;t speaking of the Second Coming at all.v He was referring to the fulfillment of Daniel 7, his reception of the kingdom from the Father, and this was fulfilled within the lifetime of some of his hearers (cf. Matt. 28:18).vi</p> <p>In several places in the Gospels, Jesus alludes to Dan. 7:13&ndash;14, as he does here. This important Messianic text speaks of the Son of Man&rsquo;s coming to God to receive dominion and a kingdom:</p> <p>I kept looking in the night visions, And behold, with the clouds of heaven One like a Son of Man was coming, And He came up to the Ancient of Days And was presented before Him. And to Him was given dominion, Glory and a kingdom, That all the peoples, nations and men of every language Might serve Him. His dominion is an everlasting dominion Which will not pass away; And His kingdom is one Which will not be destroyed.</p> <p>Therefore, this Danielic passage speaks of Christ&rsquo;s vindication and exaltation by the Father, not of his coming to the earth. This passage is particularly applied to the AD 70 judgment upon Israel in Matt. 24:30. But its initial fulfillment will be at his resurrection, whereupon he declares &ldquo;all authority has been given to Me&rdquo; (Matt. 28:18; cp. Rom. 1:4; Eph. 1:20-22; Phil. 2:8-11). The Great Commission clearly echoes Dan. 7:13&ndash;14, justifying it in terms of Old Testament prophecy.</p>'),
