INSERT INTO `myrevdata` (`myrevid`, `testament`, `book`, `chapter`, `verse`, `highlight`, `marginnote`, `sqn`, `lastupdate`, `myrevnotes`) VALUES
(41, 1, 40, 24, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:48:17', '<p>Our study of the first part of the Olivet Discourse (Matt. 24:1&ndash;35), has endeavored to keep in mind Jesus&rsquo; warning to the leaders of Jerusalem that judgment would fall upon them for rejecting the Son of God (23:29&ndash;39). LIGONIER</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 15, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:48:38', '<p>See Dan. 11. But Jesus is not saying that AD 70 is the specific fulfillment of Daniel, but that, just as the temple was desecrated under Antiochus, something like that will happen again. &ndash; from Reformedonline.com</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 27, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-29 01:44:06', '<p>Something that may be missed by the english reader is that Matthew uses Parousia here, instead of erchomai, so he is talking about the final second coming, the parousia.</p> <p>So, here Jesus is saying, during this time of tribulation before the destruction of the temple in AD 70 people will come saying that they are the Messiah, but do not believe them, because the true second Coming, the Parousia, which he talks about in Matt. 24:36-25:49...(maybe) will be obvious!!</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 29, 5, null, 99, '2022-12-05 04:40:14', '<p>When looking at Isa. 13:10 (where this is quoted from) it becomes clear that it was spoken in reference to judgement and a harsh judgement at that, this is not talking about some magical time when the constellations will literally fall or be darkened. Rather it is speaking of a time of immense judgement for sin. This is not talking about the second coming but about Christ&#39;s coming in judgement (see next verse for further confirmation).</p> <p>There are indeed many references in the OT to the destruction of great cities and nations, which are symbolically described as a darkening of the sun, moon or stars. Isaiah 13 predicts the destruction of Babylon, at that stage still in the distant future. In verse 10 we read: &quot;The stars of heaven and their constellations will not show their light. The rising sun will be darkened and the moon will not give its light.&quot; Verse 13 says: &quot;Therefore I will make the heavens tremble, and the earth will shake from its place at the wrath of the Lord Almighty.&quot; In Isaiah 24:23 we read, regarding a judgment on the city of Tyre: &quot;The moon will be abashed, the sun ashamed; for the Lord Almighty will reign on Mount Zion and in Jerusalem&quot;. And in Ezekiel 32:7, a prophecy against Egypt, we read: &quot;When I snuff you out, I will cover the heavens and darken their stars; I will cover the sun with a cloud, and the moon will not give its light.&quot;</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 30, 5, null, 99, '2022-12-05 04:38:43', '<p>First, when Jesus speaks of &ldquo;the son of man coming on the clouds,&rdquo; he is talking</p> <p>not about the second coming but, in line with the Daniel 7 text he is quoting,</p> <p>about his vindication after suffering. The &ldquo;coming&rdquo; is an upward, not a</p> <p>downward, movement. In context, the key texts mean that though Jesus is going</p> <p>to his death, he will be vindicated by events that will take place afterward. (N.T. Wright, Surprised by Hope (Harper Collins PDF), 125.</p> <p>--------------------------------------</p> <p>Why this is not the second coming:</p> <p>1. They are mourning, but Christ&#39;s second coming is spoken of as hope.</p> <p>2. All of these things are to be fulfilled within that generation (Matt. 24:34).</p> <ol start="3" type="1"> <li>Rev. 1:7 parallel passage, those who peirced him see him, this must have happened before that generation died off.</li> </ol> <p>There are two ways this passage could be understood. Either:</p> <p>1. Christ was coming on the clouds in judgement (dark clouds, not white puffy clouds), clouds a metaphor for judgement (Isa. 19:1; Ezek. 30:1-4)</p> <p>OR</p> <p>2. In reference to Dan. 7:13 in which the son of man is coming on the clouds of heaven TO GOD IN HEAVEN, (not to earth), to inherit his kingdom.</p> <p>The second option is slightly better because this verse is quoting Dan. 7:13. Therefore this means that when the Temple is destroyed (Matt. 24:1-35) the kingdom spoken of in Dan. 7:13 will officially be given to Jesus. As John Calvin and other scholars have noted, Daniel 7 refers not to the Son of Man&rsquo;s descent from heaven but to His entrance into heaven to receive His kingdom.</p> <p>-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>&quot;At that time the sign of the Son of Man will appear in the sky, and all the nations of the earth will mourn&quot; (24:30a). Josephus related that, during the siege of Jerusalem, people saw a strange star as well as a large comet that were both visible for a long time (The Wars of the Jews 6:5:3</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 31, 5, 'check translation', 99, '2022-12-05 04:52:51', '<p>we say chosen ones here, but elect in 2 Thess. 2:1</p> <p>In that case, both are allowed to &quot;grow together until harvest&quot; (v.30). At harvest, the tares are gathered and burned, while the wheat is gathered into the barn.</p> <hr /> <p style="text-align:start">In Leviticus 25 we read about the &quot;Sabbath Year&quot; and the &quot;Year of Jubilee&quot;. The main reason for these institutions was the liberation of Jews who became slaves as a result of debt they could not repay. The poor also received back land their family lost through debts during the previous 50 years. The connection between the &quot;Jubilee&quot; and the trumpet call is explained in Leviticus 25:9,10: &quot;[In the 50th year] you must have the trumpet sounded everywhere ... on the Day of Atonement sound the trumpet throughout your land. Consecrate the 50th year, and proclaim liberty throughout the land to all its inhabitants.&quot;</p> <p style="text-align:start">Jesus is the ultimate and eternal fulfillment of the Day of atonement, so how much more appropriate is a &ldquo;trumpet&rdquo; for this news!</p> <p style="text-align:start"><span style="font-size:13.192px"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-family:verdana, arial"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="font-variant-ligatures:normal"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="white-space:normal"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="text-decoration-thickness:initial"><span style="text-decoration-style:initial"><span style="text-decoration-color:initial"><font size="2"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">The fact that Jesus understood his ministry in terms of the Jubilee (Lk 4:16-21), may be significant for our understanding of the prophetic discourse. It seems clear that his announcement of the arrival of the Jubilee in Luke, and of the presence of the Kingdom in Matthew, were &quot;two sides of the same coin&quot;. As David Bosch (1991:89) observed:</font></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <blockquote><font size="2"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><font style="color:#000000; font-style:normal; font-variant-ligatures:normal; font-weight:400; text-align:start; white-space:normal; background-color:#ffffff; text-decoration-thickness:initial; text-decoration-style:initial; text-decoration-color:initial">Luke himself regards this incident as especially significant ... It stands as a &#39;preface&#39; to Jesus&#39; entire public ministry ... It is a &#39;programmatic discourse&#39; which fulfills the same function in Luke&#39;s gospel as the Sermon on the Mount in Matthew&#39;s.<a href="http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&amp;pid=S1015-87582011000200007#25a"><sup>25</sup></a> Bosch, D.J. 1991. <em>Transforming Mission. Paradigm shifts in Theology of Mission.</em> New York: Orbis Books.</font></font></font></blockquote> <p style="text-align:start"><span style="font-size:13.192px"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-family:verdana, arial"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="font-variant-ligatures:normal"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="white-space:normal"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="text-decoration-thickness:initial"><span style="text-decoration-style:initial"><span style="text-decoration-color:initial"><font size="2"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">From this perspective, it looks as if the &quot;loud trumpet call&quot; should, on the basis of good Biblical precedent, be understood as the preaching of the Gospel. Of course, where Leviticus says that the Jubilee should be proclaimed &quot;throughout the land [of Israel]&quot; (25:10), Jesus said that his messengers must announce the &quot;Gospel Jubilee&quot; to all nations. (</font></font></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>Mt 28:19. Matthew 24:31 may be an &quot;echo&quot; of Isaiah 27:13.) (This is all from: Gideon Thom, <em>Jesus and &quot;the Daniel code&quot;</em>, Acta theol. vol.31 n.2 Bloemfontein Jan. 2011)</p> <p>- From KEN GENTRY</p> <p>The parabolic evidence</p> <p>In Matthew 21:38&ndash;45 the Parable of the Landowner teaches that Israel&rsquo;s religious leaders who condemn Christ will be brought &ldquo;to a wretched end&rdquo; so that the owner of the vineyard can then &ldquo;rent out the vineyard to other vine-growers&rdquo; (Matt 21: 40&ndash;41). Jesus interprets this to Israel&rsquo;s religious authorities: &ldquo;Therefore I say to you, the kingdom of God will be taken away from you, and be given to a nation producing the fruit of it&rdquo; (21:43).</p> <p>In Matthew 22:1&ndash;14 the Parable of the Marriage Feast teaches that the gospel was first offered to Israel but that she refused it (22:2&ndash;4). Then when Israel mistreats the gospel messengers &ldquo;the king was enraged and sent his armies, and destroyed those murderers, and set their city on fire. Then he said to his slaves, &lsquo;The wedding is ready, but those who were invited were not worthy. Go therefore to the main highways, and as many as you find there, invite to the wedding feast&rsquo;&rdquo; (22:7&ndash;9).</p> <p>The &ldquo;heaven&rdquo; statement</p> <p>So then, through gospel preaching by faithful messengers (&ldquo;angels&rdquo;), God gathers the elect into his kingdom from &ldquo;the four winds, from one end of the sky to the other&rdquo; (Matt 24:31b). In some English versions such as the KJV and NRSV the phrase &ldquo;from one end of the sky to the other&rdquo; is translated as &ldquo;from one end of heaven [Gk.: ouranos] to the other&rdquo; (e.g., KJV, NKJV, ESV, NIV, NRSV). This rendering suggests that the elect are being gathered from heaven itself, so that it would seem to require a miraculous, eschatological, supernatural activity.</p> <p>But this use of ouranos does not indicate that the action occurs in heaven above. Note two interpretive clues: (1) This language parallels the preceding phrase: &ldquo;from the four winds&rdquo; (i.e., the four points of the compass). (2) In Scripture such language often signifies simply &ldquo;from horizon to horizon&rdquo; (Deut 30:4; Neh 1:9; cp. Matt 8:11; Luke 13:28&ndash;29).</p> <p>So then, here these two world-encompassing phrases speak of evangelistic success spreading throughout the earth. Consequently, this statement picks up on the theme presented in the parables of the landowner and the marriage feast in Matthew 21 and 22 and anticipates the coming &ldquo;Great Commission&rdquo; (Matt 28:19). These phrases hold forth the promise of the fulfillment of the Old Testament prophecies, such as Psalm 22:27: &ldquo;All the ends of the earth will remember and turn to the Lord, / And all the families of the nations will worship before Thee.&rdquo; And Psalm 2:8: &ldquo;Ask of Me, and I will surely give the nations as Thine inheritance, / And the very ends of the earth as Thy possession&rdquo; (See also: Psa 65:5, 8; 66:4; 67:7; 72:8; 86:9; 98:3; Isa 45:22; 66:23; Mic 5:4; Zeph 9:10).</p> <p>The &ldquo;gathering&rdquo; statement</p> <p>The &ldquo;gathering together&rdquo; is the translation of the Greek episunaxousin which is the future tense of episunago (you will recognize the word &ldquo;synagogue&rdquo; is related to this word). This word only appears three times in Matthew. Besides this use in 24:31 it appears two times in 23:37 where Jesus laments:<br /> O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, who kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to her! How often I wanted to gather [episunagagein] your children together, the way a hen gathers [episunagei] her chicks under her wings, and you were unwilling.</p> <p>Obviously the second usage regarding gathering chicks is intended to illustrate the first. Here Jesus longs to gather disciples to himself from Jerusalem. This gathering of disciples is the same meaning in 24:31.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 34, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:49:09', '<p>Absolutely clear that the things preceding this verse happened in 70AD.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 35, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:49:12', '<p>I think this is not saying heaven and earth will pass away in AD 70, but rather, that heaven and earth will pass away eventually, they are more temporary and fleeting than these words of Jesus, his words will not pass away, but even heaven and earth will pass away.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 24, 36, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:49:23', '<p>Everything up to this point was fulfilled in 70 AD, notice his switch of &quot;but&quot; and he starts using language of uncertainty, there will be no way to tell when his second coming is going to happen.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 27, 11, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-26 14:35:48', '<p>Comm. : There is even more evidence that this phrase is not vague but is an affirmation. During the Last Supper, in Matthew 26:25, Judas asks Jesus if he is the one who will betray Jesus, and Jesus responds with this exact phrase &ldquo;You have said it.&rdquo; But we know that this did come to pass, and that Jesus knew Judas would betray him (John 13:2, 11). Thus this phrase is used as an affirmation.</p> <p>Jesus is explicit here, but not in John 5</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 27, 52, 1, null, 99, '2022-09-15 19:19:28', '<p>Have you ever wondered about how Matthew records (Matt. 27:52-53) that after the resurrection of Jesus the tombs were opened, and many bodies of the saints who had fallen asleep were raised, and were seen by many? This is a sign, a sample that the resurrection from the dead comes through Jesus.</p>'),
(41, 1, 40, 28, 16, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:49:37', '<p>1. An angel rolls away the stone from the tomb before sunrise (Matthew 28:2-4). The guards are seized with fear and eventually flee.</p> <p>2. Women disciples visit the tomb and discover Christ missing (Matthew 28:1; Mark 16:1-4; Luke 24:1-3; John 20:1).</p> <p>3. Mary Magdalene leaves to tell Peter and John (John 20:1-2).</p> <p>4. Other women remain at the tomb; they see two angels who tell them of Christ&#39;s resurrection (Matthew 28:5-7; Mark 16:5-7; Luke 24:4-8).</p> <p>5. Peter and John run to the tomb and then leave (Luke 24:12; John 20:3-10).</p> <p>6. Christ&#39;s First Appearance: Mary Magdalene returns to the tomb; Christ appears to her (Mark 16:9-11; John 20:11-18).</p> <p>7. Christ&#39;s Second Appearance: Jesus appears to the other women (Mary, mother of James, Salome, and Joanna) (Matthew 28:8-10).</p> <p>8. At this time, the guards report the events to the religious leaders and are bribed to lie (Matthew 28:11-15).</p> <p>9. Christ&#39;s Third Appearance: Jesus privately appears to Peter (1 Corinthians 15:5).</p> <p>10. Christ&#39;s Fourth Appearance: Jesus appears to Cleopas and companion (Mark 16:12-13; Luke 24:13-32).</p> <p>11. Christ&#39;s Fifth Appearance: Jesus appears to 10 apostles, with Thomas missing, in the Upper Room (Luke 24:36-43).</p> <p>12. Christ&#39;s Sixth Appearance: Eight days after His appearance to the 10 apostles, Jesus appears to all 11 apostles, including Thomas (John 20:26-28).</p> <p>13. Christ&#39;s Seventh Appearance: Jesus appears to 7 disciples by the Sea of Galilee and performs the miracle of the fish (John 21:1-14).</p> <p>14. Christ&#39;s Eighth Appearance: Jesus appears to 500 on a mountain in Galilee (Matthew 28:16-20; Mark 16:15-18; 1 Corinthians 15:6).</p> <p>15. Christ&#39;s Ninth Appearance: Jesus appears to His half-brother James (1 Corinthians 15:7).</p> <p>16. Christ&#39;s Tenth Appearance: In Jerusalem, Jesus appears again to His disciples (Acts 1:3-8).</p> <p>17. Christ&#39;s Eleventh Appearance: Jesus ascends into Heaven while the disciples look on (Mark 16:19-20; Luke 24:50-53; Acts 1:9-12).</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 1, 13, 1, null, 99, '2021-11-20 21:14:17', '<p>Jesus&rsquo;s peaceful coexistence with the wild animals shows him exercising benevolent dominion over creation, which sinful humanity failed to do (cf. Isa. 11:1&ndash;9).</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 2, 18, 1, null, 99, '2022-12-13 16:09:57', '<p>They could tell that the disciples did not fast because they did it so often, on mondays and thursdays I believe.</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 3, 27, 1, null, 99, '2021-11-20 20:35:59', '<p>Jesus says in Mark 3 that once the strong man is bound, he can plunder all of his goods, well, what are his goods? Lost people! Now that the strong man has been bound, Jesus can save souls, and draw all men to himself (). Jesus says that the one who binds the strong man can plunder the strong man&rsquo;s house (3:27). Then he immediately says &ldquo;all sins&rdquo; and &ldquo;whatever blasphemies&rdquo; will be forgiven (except the blasphemy against the Holy Spirit) (3:28). In other words, the forgiveness explained in 3:28 is a result of Jesus&rsquo;s binding of the strong man recounted in 3:27.</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 6, 8, 1, null, 99, '2022-08-04 20:58:40', '<p>What is the easiest explanation here? The Lord Jesus allowed them to use one walking staff, just not bring along another (or special) one. In other words, they did not need to go out a buy another staff to prepare for their journeys (thus giving them two or more staves, which Jesus forbade). No, just they just needed to bring along the one staff they already had. They did not need to pack a bag with money or extra clothes, either. Bringing along more supplies was unnecessary.</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 8, 31, 0, null, 99, '2022-10-31 19:50:43', '<p><strong>&ldquo;after three days rise from the dead.&rdquo;</strong> This verse, Mark 8:31, along with quite a few others in the New Testament, can be taken by some scholars to mean that Jesus raised himself from the dead. However, that is not the best way to understand this passage for quite a few reasons.</p> <p>First, in the other times the Bible speaks of Jesus getting up from the dead it is the Father, God, who raises Jesus, he does not raise himself. Many verses plainly state that it was God who raised Jesus (cp. Acts 2:32; 4:10; 5:30; Rom. 10:9; 1 Cor. 6:14; Gal. 1:1; 1 Thess. 1:9-10; see commentary on John 10:17).</p> <p>Secondly, since we know Jesus was a man (1 Tim. 2:5) it would be quite strange for him to raise himself from the dead. We would not expect a human to raise themselves from the dead, but God to raise humans from the dead.</p> <p>Thirdly, the word ἀναστῆναι (#450 &ldquo;anastenai&rdquo;) can mean to rise up, raise up, or get up. There is an important disctinction that needs to be made between &ldquo;rise up&rdquo; and &ldquo;raise up.&rdquo; Typically, &ldquo;rise up&rdquo; is used when you (the subject) are rising up, and &ldquo;raise up&rdquo; is used when you (the subject) are raising up something else. Thus, if I am rescued out of a swimming pool my body &ldquo;rose up&rdquo; but I was &ldquo;raised&rdquo; by someone else. Both are true simultaneously, however, &ldquo;rise&rdquo; is from an active perspective and &ldquo;be raised&rdquo; is from a passive perspective. This is important because although this is an active infinitive this does not necessarily mean that Jesus raised himself from the dead (if we were to take the meaning to be &ldquo;raise&rdquo;) but that his body rose (active) from the dead (if we take the meaning to be &ldquo;rise&rdquo;) which is true. Jesus&rsquo; body rose from the dead. Jesus (the subject) rose from the dead. This verse does not tell us the cause, or, who raised Jesus from the dead, but just the result, that Jesus rose.</p> <p>The two parallels, in Matthew 16:21 and Luke 9:22, both use the passive form when talking about Jesus&rsquo; resurrection, &ldquo;be raised up.&rdquo; So, if we know that the parallels speak of Jesus being raised, in other words, someone else is doing the raising, then that should influence how we understand the active infinitive here in Mark 8:31. If both &ldquo;rise up&rdquo; and &ldquo;raise up&rdquo; are perfectly good options, and we know Jesus did not raise himself from the dead, we should understand the phrase to be &ldquo;rise up.&rdquo; Jesus was raised from the dead by the power of God (Acts 2:32, passive sense), and his body did rise (active sense). Both are true.</p> <p>Lastly, the active form of &ldquo;anastemi&rdquo; is used of other humans who certainly do not raise themselves from the dead (Mark 12:23) and carries the meaning of &ldquo;rise&rdquo; instead or &ldquo;raise.&rdquo; Therefore, Mark 8:31 is a remarkable prediction by Jesus that he will rise from the dead three days after he is killed, not that he will raise himself from the dead.</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 8, 34, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:07:15', '<p>What does it mean to take up your cross? Well it is not some huge mystery or up to some pastors interpretation. Just look at the next verse. Jesus says that one must lose his own life! That is what it means to take up your cross, is to go to you death, to lose your life.</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 9, 49, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-27 21:23:48', '<p>If Alford is correct in that the two clauses are parallel, and that πᾶς means everyone absolutely (i.e., righteous and unrighteous), then:</p> <p>πᾶς (&ldquo;everyone&rdquo;) = πᾶσα θυσία (&ldquo;every sacrifice&rdquo;)</p> <p>Both the righteous and the unrighteous are sacrifices.</p> <p>πυρὶ ἁλισθήσεται (&ldquo;shall be salted with fire&rdquo;) = πᾶσα θυσία ἀλὶ ἁλισθήσεται (&ldquo;shall be salted with salt&rdquo;)</p> <p>Alford, Henry. <em>The Greek Testament</em>. Vol. 1. Boston: Lee and Shepard, 1878.</p> <p><strong>Accordingly, in Mark 9:49, the righteous are purified from sin when salted with fire, while the unrighteous are devoured when salted with fire.</strong></p> <p>This is why Jesus says in the very next verse that Salt is good, and that you should be salty. Salt was used for preservation, this phrase then is a metaphor for preservation. If we are salty, we will be preserved through the fire. The things that are not salty will be burned up.</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 9, 50, 0, 'Send this commentary to John', 99, '2022-07-01 18:45:15', '<p>We have to remember the context of this strange statement about salt. Jesus has just finished talking about how we must remove causes to sin because the alternative is to go into the destruction in the fire of Gehenna. So, when Jesus says, after salt has become unsalty, &ldquo;How can you make it salty <em>again</em>?&rdquo; The implied answer is that you cannot. He goes on to say in the parallel in Matthew 5:13 that it is not useful for anything but to be trampled under people&rsquo;s feet. He says this because it is true reality of salt in the real world and it helps communicate a thought that Jesus wanted to communicate about not being able to be restored from the fire of Gehenna.</p> <p>Salt even in modern times in the Middle east, and most likely in ancient times, is obtained from marshes along the sea-shore and is sometimes stored in houses or left on the ground, in both cases it can become ruined, unsalty. William Thomson details a story eerily similar to what we find Jesus describing here in Mark 9:50. &ldquo;These houses have merely earthen floors [i.e., have only dirt floors], and the salt next [to] the ground in a few years [is] entirely spoiled. I saw large quantities of it literally thrown into the street, to be trodden underfoot of men and beasts&rdquo; (W. M. Thompson, The Land and the Book, Baker Book House, Grand Rapids, MI, reprinted 1973. Chap. XXVI, &ldquo;Kersa-Tiberias,&rdquo; Pps. 381-382). This thought is parallel to the idea of Gehenna &ndash; no one can be restored after going through the fire of Gehenna, it is an eternal destruction of the unbeliever (2 Thess. 1:9), the unsalty.</p> <p>Here is the meaning of the metaphor. Everyone will be seasoned with fire (Mark 9:49), some people will be salty (believers) and will be a pleasing sacrifice to God (Lev. 2:13). They have salt in themselves (Mark 9:50). The rest will also be seasoned with fire, yet they are not &ldquo;salty&rdquo; because their salt has lost its taste, they will not be a pleasing sacrifice to God (Lev. 2:13) and will be destroyed in the fire of Gehenna (Mark 9:43; 45).</p>'),
(41, 1, 41, 10, 30, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-07 19:14:53', '<p>You will receive a hundredfold of these things spiritually. Not 100 literal mothers. You leave these things literally and you will receive these things spiritually.</p>'),
