(41, 1, 42, 23, 43, 4, null, 99, '2022-08-05 15:22:46', '<p>The place where Christ&#39;s soul went between His death and resurrection is also called paradise (Luke 23:43). Christ promised the thief on the cross that on that very day that he would be with Him in paradise. It is obvious that the thief on the cross was not with Christ in Joseph&#39;s tomb, but he was with Him in paradise (Sheol/Hades).</p>'),
(41, 1, 42, 24, 9, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>1. An angel rolls away the stone from the tomb before sunrise (Matthew 28:2-4). The guards are seized with fear and eventually flee.</p> <p>2. Women disciples visit the tomb and discover Christ missing (Matthew 28:1; Mark 16:1-4; Luke 24:1-3; John 20:1).</p> <p>3. Mary Magdalene leaves to tell Peter and John (John 20:1-2).</p> <p>4. Other women remain at the tomb; they see two angels who tell them of Christ&#39;s resurrection (Matthew 28:5-7; Mark 16:5-7; Luke 24:4-8).</p> <p>5. Peter and John run to the tomb and then leave (Luke 24:12; John 20:3-10).</p> <p>6. Christ&#39;s First Appearance: Mary Magdalene returns to the tomb; Christ appears to her (Mark 16:9-11; John 20:11-18).</p> <p>7. Christ&#39;s Second Appearance: Jesus appears to the other women (Mary, mother of James, Salome, and Joanna) (Matthew 28:8-10).</p> <p>8. At this time, the guards report the events to the religious leaders and are bribed to lie (Matthew 28:11-15).</p> <p>9. Christ&#39;s Third Appearance: Jesus privately appears to Peter (1 Corinthians 15:5).</p> <p>10. Christ&#39;s Fourth Appearance: Jesus appears to Cleopas and companion (Mark 16:12-13; Luke 24:13-32).</p> <p>11. Christ&#39;s Fifth Appearance: Jesus appears to 10 apostles, with Thomas missing, in the Upper Room (Luke 24:36-43).</p> <p>12. Christ&#39;s Sixth Appearance: Eight days after His appearance to the 10 apostles, Jesus appears to all 11 apostles, including Thomas (John 20:26-28).</p> <p>13. Christ&#39;s Seventh Appearance: Jesus appears to 7 disciples by the Sea of Galilee and performs the miracle of the fish (John 21:1-14).</p> <p>14. Christ&#39;s Eighth Appearance: Jesus appears to 500 on a mountain in Galilee (Matthew 28:16-20; Mark 16:15-18; 1 Corinthians 15:6).</p> <p>15. Christ&#39;s Ninth Appearance: Jesus appears to His half-brother James (1 Corinthians 15:7).</p> <p>16. Christ&#39;s Tenth Appearance: In Jerusalem, Jesus appears again to His disciples (Acts 1:3-8).</p> <p>17. Christ&#39;s Eleventh Appearance: Jesus ascends into Heaven while the disciples look on (Mark 16:19-20; Luke 24:50-53; Acts 1:9-12).</p>'),
(41, 1, 42, 24, 49, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>Bart Ehrman suggests that this sentence presents one of the biggest contradictions in the gospels. Here Jesus tells his disciples to stay in Jerusalem, yet in Matthew he tells his disciples to meet him in Galilee. What is going on here and is this a contradiction?</p> <p>It is worth mentioning that here in verse 49 it says to wait in Jerusalem until they are clothed with power from on high. Yet in John, this very same day, they are breathed on by Jesus to receive the Holy Spirit, is that not being clothed with power from on high? Plus wouldn&rsquo;t that contradict Jesus telling them to wait if the Spirit was going to give them power that very same day? It would be quite strange of Jesus to say.</p> <p>Firstly, it is important to recognize the distinction between what happened this Sunday and what would happen at Pentecost. I believe, along with Hall Harris&rsquo; Commentary on the Gospel John, that here, &ldquo;Jesus at this point breathed into the disciples the breath of eternal life. This was in the form of the Holy Spirit, who was to indwell them.&rdquo; I also agree with Harris that, &ldquo;This was the giving of life itself, which flowed out from within (cf. 7:38-39). The giving of power would occur later, on the Day of Pentecost.&rdquo; Although the Holy Spirit was given here to the apostles, securing eternal life, the power and gifts of the Spirit given in a unique way and poured out on all people, did not come until Pentecost (Acts 1:8; Luke 24:49). -See commentary on John 20:22 for more information-</p> <p>So, this statement actually aligns quite nicely with John 20:22 in which life is given, yet the disciples are to wait in Jerusalem until power is given to them.</p> <p>Now, let us try to understand what Luke 24:49 is saying. The context is vital in understanding what Jesus means by using the word &ldquo;stay&rdquo;. Does he mean that the disciples cannot leave Jerusalem at all, even for a few days, or is he saying not to leave Jerusalem permanently, until the Day of Pentecost? Well, does the context give us any hints? In verse 47 Jesus has just given a command similar to the Great Commision of Matthew 28. He tells his disciples to preach repentance and forgiveness of sins to ALL NATIONS, beginning in Jerusalem. Are they to begin traveling right now? No. This is why Jesus says what he says in v. 49. He is telling his disciples not to go preach in all the nations until the day of Pentecost happens and they are clothed with power from on high. Therefore, contextually, Jesus is not telling them that they cannot leave Jerusalem at all, even for a little while, to go to Galilee, but rather that they should not leave Jerusalem to preach to the nations (which requires extended periods of time) until the day of Pentecost. Because if they leave too soon, they will miss this extraordinary event, and perhaps miss out on the power given by the Spirit. This is the reason for Jesus command here. It is not to forbid his disciples from traveling to Galilee for a few days, because he commands them to do this in the book of Matthew.</p> <p>Therefore, if the disciples went to Galilee for a few days, as Jesus also instructed, and then came back, they are still following Jesus&rsquo; command here in v. 49, because they did not miss Pentecost.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 1, 2, 'need to go through logos and change to italics in my commentary!', 99, '2023-02-01 20:03:44', '<p>Things I added recently in bold (11/19/22)</p> <p>-----------------------------------</p> <ol start="5" type="i"> <li>1</li> </ol> <p>Before we begin our commentary on John 1, we must begin with some reasons why we take this passage to be referring to the New Creation through Christ, and is not referring to the Genesis creation at all, because this will influence our understanding of the whole passage (John 1:1-18). Here are some reasons to understand the prologue as a New Creation passage:</p> <ol type="1"> <li>John 1 uses old creation language but in a different way. Light, darkness, and &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; are all discussed like in Genesis, but we are to believe in the light (John 1:7; clearly not physical light), and life comes through belief (John 1:12-13) not through birth. Not everyone experiences this life, it is eternal life, not the kind of life in Genesis 1.</li> <li>John would be contradicting the rest of scripture in which God the Father alone created the heavens and the earth (Gen. 1:1; Ex. 20:11; Psa. 33:6, 121:2; Job 38:4), if we were to understand John 1 as teaching that Jesus created all things in the Genesis creation.</li> <li>John the Baptist never bore witness about the light of the old creation, the sun and the moon, but he did bear witness about Jesus (John 1:15) the light (John 1:8). Therefore, we should not understand the light of John 1:4-5 to be the light of the old creation.</li> <li>The statement in John 1:4, &ldquo;that which came to be in it was life, and the life was the light of men,&rdquo; has nothing to do with John 1:3 if it is talking about the Genesis creation of land, sea, sun, and moon. How is the Genesis creation the &lsquo;light of men?&rsquo; It is not clear. However, it is clear that Jesus is the light of of the world. Light and life are directly connected in John 8:12, &ldquo;Then Jesus spoke to them again, saying, &ldquo;I am the light of the world. The one who continues to follow me will not ever walk in darkness, but will have the light of life.&rdquo;</li> <li>John feels the need to specify that John the Baptist is not the &ldquo;light&rdquo; (John 1:8). If by &ldquo;light&rdquo; he means the sun and moon (the Genesis creation) this statement is nonsensical, of course he is not the sun or moon. However, if by &ldquo;light&rdquo; John has Jesus in mind, it makes sense why he would seek to distinguish the two, by clarifying that John the Baptist is not the True Light.</li> <li>If John 1:1-5 was about the old creation, then there would have to be a 8,000 year gap between John 1:5 and John 1:6. This is highly unlikely considering he continues his thought about light throughout John 1:4-9.</li> <li>John 1:6-7 is clearly about the New Covenant (belief in this light).</li> <li>John 1:12-13 is clearly about the New Covenant (those who receive the true light/word are born from God).</li> <li>The Word or True Light was already flesh in John 1:10-11 when he &ldquo;came to his own&rdquo;. It did not become flesh in John 1:14. The passage is not chronological. Thus, this idea that Jesus pre-existed as a divine being (in John 1:1-13) and then became flesh and was born in John 1:14 simply does not work. Therefore, it would make the most sense to understand the timing of the whole text (John 1:1-18) to be referring to Jesus&rsquo; earthly ministry, or the New Covenant.</li> <li>In John 1:17 the law was given through Moses, grace and truth came through Jesus. This is even more teaching about the New Covenant, not the Old Covenant or old creation.</li> <li>Since John 1:1 has such close parallels with 1 John 1:1-3, which is talking about the &ldquo;Word of Life&rdquo; that the apostles could touch and feel that was with God &ldquo;from the beginning&rdquo; (1 John 1:1), we should understand the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; that was with God in the beginning of John 1:1 to also be referring to something something that they could touch and feel, a person, Jesus.</li> </ol> <p><strong>&ldquo;In the beginning.&rdquo;</strong> This phrase immediately brings the reader&rsquo;s mind back to Genesis 1:1 in which God created all things &ldquo;In the beginning&rdquo;. Yet, we must ask ourselves is the author, John, trying to give us new insight on Genesis, is he trying to rewrite Genesis and tell us that actually &ldquo;The Word&rdquo; (or Jesus) created the old heavens and earth, as Trinitarians would have us believe? Is this the same &ldquo;beginning&rdquo; as the Genesis 1 creation or is this a different beginning?</p> <p>The Racovian Catechism, one of the great doctrinal works of the Unitarian movement of the 14th and 15th centuries, states that the word &ldquo;beginning&rdquo; in John 1:1 refers to the beginning of the Gospel and thus is similar to Mark 1:1, which starts, &ldquo;The beginning of the Gospel about Jesus Christ.&rdquo; The phrase, &ldquo;in the beginning was the word&rdquo; does not refer to the &ldquo;beginning&rdquo; in Genesis 1:1 (The Racovian Catechism; Reprinted by Spirit &amp; Truth Fellowship, pp. 63 and 64). There is tremendous evidence for understanding &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; to refer to the beginning of the new creation in Christ.</p> <p>In the rest of the Gospel of John &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; never means eternity past or the time of the creation of the universe. In the Gospel of John &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; refers to the life and ministry of Jesus:</p> <ul> <li>&ldquo;For Jesus knew from <strong>the beginning</strong> who those were who did not believe, and who it was who would betray him&rdquo; (John 6:65).</li> <li>&ldquo;So they said to him, &lsquo;Who are you?&rsquo; Jesus said to them, &lsquo;Just what I have been telling you from <strong>the beginning</strong>&rsquo;&rdquo; (John 8:25).</li> <li>&ldquo;I did not say these things to you from <strong>the beginning</strong>, because I was with you&rdquo; (John 16:4).</li> <li>&ldquo;And you also will bear witness, because you have been with me from <strong>the beginning</strong>&rdquo; (John 15:27).</li> </ul> <p>The use of &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; by the same author in the same book to mean the beginning of Jesus&rsquo;s life and ministry is good reason to understand &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; in the first verse of his Gospel as a reference likewise to the beginning of the life and ministry of Jesus. Put another way, to interpret &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; in John 1:1 as a reference to the Genesis creation contradicts how John uses the phrase in all other places in his Gospel.</p> <div class="CxSpFirst" style="text-align:start">&ldquo;The beginning&rdquo; is a phrase used multiple times in the New Testament and most often has the meaning of the beginning of the ministry of Jesus or the beginning of the &ldquo;New Creation.&rdquo; For example, Mark 1:1 says, &ldquo;The beginning of the good news of Jesus Christ&rdquo; (see also Luke 1:1-2). Also, most convincingly, the same author, John, uses the phrase &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; at the start of his epistle 1 John, and he means the beginning of the ministry of Jesus. John and his fellow disciples were able to touch, hear, and see the word of life that was &ldquo;from the beginning&rdquo; (1 John 1:1). They did not touch or hear Jesus&rsquo; in his eternal preexistent state, but Jesus in his human body, which they refer to as being &ldquo;from the beginning.&rdquo;</div> <p>Another helpful question to ask to see if this is referring to the Genesis creation or not is: in John 1 what is being created? Is it plants, animals, and the universe like in Genesis 1, or is it new creation concepts, such as eternal life and light? In the Prologue we find that life (John 1:4), light (John 1:4-5), and birth from God (John 1:13) are coming to be through the Word/True Light. In the book of John, life, light, and birth through God come through Jesus. Jesus is &ldquo;the Life&rdquo; in John 14:6, the &ldquo;Light of the World&rdquo; in John 8:12, and people are born again through faith in him in John 3:3. Likewise, it would be quite strange for John to introduce his gospel with the idea that Jesus created the plants, animals and universe (without explicitly mentioning those things) and then to fail to mention this Genesis creation act again in the rest of the book. Thus, it is much more reasonable to conclude that the &ldquo;all things&rdquo; that were created through the Word, or Jesus, are new creation things, because not only are they mentioned in the prologue (John 1:4-5, 13), but also in the book itself (John 3:3, 8:12, 14:6).</p> <div class="CxSpFirst" style="text-align:start"> <p>Noted Bible commentator F.F. Bruce argues for this interpretation:</p> <p>It is not by accident that the Gospel begins with the same phrase as the book of Genesis. In Genesis 1:1, &lsquo;In the beginning&rsquo; introduces the story of the old creation; here it introduces the story of the new creation. In both works of creation the agent is the Word of God. (F.F. Bruce, <em>The Gospel of John</em>, pp. 28 and 29). Thus, it is evident that the vast weight of evidence leans toward understanding &ldquo;in the beginning&rdquo; to refer to the beginning of the ministry of Jesus, or the beginning of the new creation, because of its usage throughout the gospel of John, the New Testament, and its immediate context.</p> <p>So, the question might arise, &ldquo;Why does John use this Genesis language if he didn&rsquo;t have the Genesis creation in mind?&rdquo; John is using this creation language to help us see that this is a new beginning, a new creation that is happening through Jesus Christ (2 Cor. 5:17; Matt. 19:28), and the image brought out by using the words &ldquo;in the beginning,&rdquo; &ldquo;came to be,&rdquo; &ldquo;light,&rdquo; &ldquo;darkness,&rdquo; and &ldquo;life&rdquo; help bring across this idea. However, there are some very notable differences that John uses when describing these concepts that help tell us that this is not the Genesis creation story, but a new creation story.</p> <p>First, there is a battle between the light and the darkness in John 1:5, but the light is victorious. This represents Jesus being victorious over evil through his death and resurrection. Yet, this is much different from the Genesis creation in which God creates physical light in the form of the sun for the day and the moon for the night in Genesis 1:14-19. Second, John the Baptist bears witness about this light, and certainly no one argues that John the Baptist&rsquo;s ministry was about bearing witness to the Sun, rather it was about bearing witness to Jesus (John 1:15). Third, we are to believe in this light (John 1:7), yet, the bible is not teaching us to believe in the Sun, no, we are to believe in Jesus! Fourth, contrary to Genesis 1, people are born in John 1 not through natural processes, but through belief, through trust in Jesus (John 1:12-13). So, as we see, John uses Genesis creation language, but he uses it very differently than Genesis does, and to try to understand these allusions as referring to the Genesis creation misses the point that John is making.</p> <p>For all of these reasons it becomes clear that John is not discussing the Genesis creation at all, instead he is discussing that there is a new world that came to be through Jesus (John 1:10). He is using old creation language in a new way, to describe the new creation coming to be through Jesus Christ. It truly is a beautiful piece of poetry and teaching.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;the Word.&rdquo;</strong> &ldquo;Word&rdquo; is translated from the Greek word <em>logos</em> (#3056 λόγος). In both Greek literature and Scripture, <em>logos</em> has a very wide range of meanings that fall into two basic categories: one is the mind and products of the mind like &ldquo;reason,&rdquo; (the word &ldquo;logic&rdquo; is ultimately from the root <em>logos</em>), and the other is the expression of that reason in language or life: thus, &ldquo;word,&rdquo; &ldquo;saying,&rdquo; &ldquo;command&rdquo; etc. While it is true that &ldquo;Jesus Christ&rdquo; is not a lexical definition of <em>logos</em>, the &lsquo;new creation&rsquo; perspective is not saying that <em>logos</em> <em>means</em> Jesus, but that it <em>refers</em> to Jesus. &ldquo;The Word&rdquo; is a metaphor being used to represent Jesus Christ because Jesus is the expression (Word) of God, just like the serpent is a metaphor for Satan, but Satan is not a literal snake. Satan does not mean snake, it means adversary, but in the same way, &ldquo;the word&rdquo; does not mean Jesus, but it is being used to refer to Jesus.</p> <p>There are quite a few reasons why &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; here in John 1:1-3 should be understood as referring to Jesus.</p> <ol type="1"> <li>Life (John 14:6), light (John 8:12), and new birth (John 3:3) all happen through Jesus in the gospel of John, in the Prologue of John, life, light and new birth all happen through the Word.</li> <li>Jesus is &lsquo;Word of Life&rsquo; in 1 John 1:1, so it would make the most sense to understand him as &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; that creates life here in John 1. It is the same author beginning his book in both places.</li> <li>Jesus is the True light of John 1:9-13 &ldquo;through whom the world comes to be,&rdquo; and who comes to his own people, so because of the almost identical wording in John 1:1-3, it is best to believe that he is also the Word &ldquo;through whom everything comes to be.&rdquo; The language of the two phrases is almost identical and unmistakable, with πάντα διʼ αὐτοῦ ἐγένετο &ldquo;Everything came to be through it/him&rdquo; (John 1:3) vs. ὁ κόσμος διʼ αὐτοῦ ἐγένετο &ldquo;the world came to be through it/him&rdquo; (John 1:10). Also, in John&rsquo;s flow of thought, that which comes to be through the Word is the light of humankind (John 1:4), and similarly, the true light gives light to every person (John 1:9), so it seems that &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; and the &ldquo;true light&rdquo; are both referring to the same thing, Jesus.</li> <li>A title for Jesus that John uses is &ldquo;the Word of God&rdquo; (Rev. 19:13) so it would not be out of the ordinary at all for John to use &ldquo;the word&rdquo; to refer to Jesus.</li> <li>In John 1:14 we are told that the Word became flesh. This is another reason why it makes sense to view &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; as a reference to Jesus. <ul> <li>This verse does not say, &ldquo;God became flesh,&rdquo; or that &ldquo;Jesus became flesh,&rdquo; nor does it mean that Jesus or God became flesh. Rather, it means that the Word (the expression of God) became flesh, in other words, God was not expressed through spoken word like in the Genesis creation, but through a man of flesh, Jesus. [For more information, see the commentary on John 1:14].</li> </ul> </li> <li>The flow of thought does not work in John 1:1-5 if we take &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; to be a reference to the Genesis creation. This &ldquo;light&rdquo; from the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; is victorious over the darkness and John the Baptist testifies about this &ldquo;light.&rdquo; John the Baptist does not testify about the Sun or Moon, but about Jesus who is the Light of the World (John 8:12).</li> <li>The Word was <em>with</em> God in John 1:1, and in John 1:18, Jesus is in a most intimate relationship with the Father, he was with God.</li> <li>In John 1:18 John says that Jesus &ldquo;explains&rdquo; the father, words are used for explanation, thus, one can see the metaphor John would be making by calling Jesus the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; of John 1:1, the explanation of God.</li> <li><strong>In Col. 1:16 &ldquo;all things&rdquo; (in reference to &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in the new creation) are created through Jesus, here in John 1:3, &ldquo;all things&rdquo; are created through the Word, this is another reason to understand the Word as referring to Jesus.</strong></li> </ol> <p>Therefore, &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; is a metaphor used for Jesus in John 1:1-3.</p> <p>There are two reasons we can derive from the immediate context as to why John would use the particular metaphor of the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; for Jesus instead of something else. Firstly, because Jesus is the perfect word, expression, or message of who God is. It is taught that Jesus expresses God in the Prologue (John 1:18), in the book of John (John 8:19), and in the New Testament (Heb. 1:3). Throughout John&rsquo;s gospel we see Jesus teaching that he himself expresses God to us: &ldquo;If you knew me, you would know my father,&rdquo; and, &ldquo;if you have seen me, you have seen the Father&rdquo; (John 8:19, 14:9). The second reason John likely used the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; as a metaphor for Jesus was to illustrate that Jesus is the means by which God created the new creation (John 1:3, 10), just as God&rsquo;s spoken word was the means by which he created the Genesis creation. Jesus is the perfect expression (<em>logos</em>) of God. God creates through his word in the Old and he is creating through his word (Jesus) in the New. His &ldquo;word&rdquo; just looks much different in the New.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;the Word was with God.&rdquo;</strong> This phrase is absolutely vital and should not be ignored when interpreting John 1. Many Trinitarians gloss over this phrase and focus on John 1:1c supposedly calling &ldquo;the Word,&rdquo; God. However, this runs into many problems.</p> <p>In the phrase &ldquo;the Word was with God,&rdquo; Trinitarians understand &ldquo;God&rdquo; to mean Father; that Jesus was with the Father. However, when they arrive at the third phrase they say, &ldquo;Look, Jesus is called God!&rdquo; Yet, right before, God means the Father, so are we claiming that the Son is the Father? No, clearly this is problematic. Well, the Trinitarian might respond that &ldquo;God&rdquo; means the Trinity in 1:1c, however, that does not work either because this would be the logic: Son = Father, Son and Holy Spirit. Jesus is not the Trinity, in Trinitarian theology, he is part of the Trinity. Therefore, this passage actually does not teach the modern definition of the Trinity at all, and must be interpreted quite strangely in the Trinitarian framework, changing the meaning of &ldquo;God&rdquo; throughout the sentence.</p> <p>What John simply means in this phrase is that Jesus was close with God here on earth in his body. He had intimate fellowship with the God of the universe. John further elaborates upon John 1:1 later in John 1:18. He says, that Jesus &ldquo;is in a most intimate relationship withe the Father.&rdquo; Jesus had the full presence of God&rsquo;s Spirit (Luke 4:1), and he called God his own Father (John 5:18). He was one with (John 10:30, 17:22), or united with God. Thus, the context helps bring to light what John meant by his phrase &ldquo;the Word was with God.&rdquo;</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;what God was the Word was.&rdquo;</strong> The final big question of John 1:1 is, does John 1:1c explictly call &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; God? For this question it is helpful to consult the Greek. In the Greek there is an interesting construction of this phrase that is not apparent in many english translations. In John 1:1b the Greek word for God (<em>theos</em>) has an article in front of it. Yet in John 1:1c &ldquo;and the Word was God,&rdquo; there is no article in front of God. Interestingly, John picks back up the article in verse 2. Now we must ask, why would John drop the article particularly in this usage in John 1:1c?</p> <p>Daniel Wallace, a renowned Greek Scholar admits that John 1:1c is likely a qualitative use of &ldquo;<em>theos</em>.&rdquo; He cites that grammatically, the largest proportion of pre-verbal anarthrous predicate nominatives (PAPN) fall into this category (Wallace, <em>BBG</em>, 269). In other words, in a Greek construction like we have here in John 1:1c, the noun &ldquo;<em>theos</em>&rdquo; is usually qualitative. The most natural meaning of the word would be that it referred to the quality of God, i.e., &ldquo;divine,&rdquo; &ldquo;god-like,&rdquo; or &ldquo;like God.&rdquo; The New English Bible gets the sense of this phrase by translating it, &ldquo;What God was, the Word was.&rdquo; James Moffatt, who was a professor of Greek and New Testament Exegesis at Mansfield College in Oxford, England, and author of the well-known Moffatt Bible, translated the phrase, &ldquo;the <em>logos</em> was divine.&rdquo; There are 53 uses of PAPN&rsquo;s in the book of John similar to what we have here in John 1:1c and Philip Harner in his article <em>Qualitative Anarthrous Predicate Nouns</em>, says, &ldquo;In 40 of these cases the qualitative force of the predicate is more prominent than its definiteness or indefiniteness&rdquo; (p. 83). Thus, we have great reason to conclude that John dropped the article in John 1:1c to communicate that the Word had the qualities of God, he was godly, like-God, or divine, but was not God himself.</p> <p>Now, the problem with the typical Trinitarian translation is quite significant. Even Dan Wallace points this out. If we say that John 1:1c is definite, then it would be a convertible proposition with <em>logos</em> (i.e. the Word = God). The problem with this argument is that &ldquo;<em>theos</em>&rdquo; in John 1:1b is the Father (the Word was with God). Thus to say that &ldquo;<em>theos</em>&rdquo; in 1:1c is the same person is to say that the Word was the Father. This is a form of sabellianism or modalism, (Wallace, 268) both heresies according to most evangelical Trinitarians. So, this verse is actually not clear support for Trinitarianism at all. One would have to change the meaning of God from 1:1b to 1:1c, &ldquo;the Word was with God (the Father), and the Word was God (part of the Trinity)&rdquo;, which is a very unnatural reading of the text.</p> <p>Thus, Jesus is not called &ldquo;God&rdquo; in John 1:1, but Jesus (the Word) has the qualities of God. This is absolutely affirmed throughout the New Testament, as Jesus is perfectly loving, patient, and kind like the Father, and Jesus even goes so far as to say that if you see him you have seen the Father (John 14:9).</p> <hr /> <p><span style="font-size: 1.2em;">Problems with Logos Christology:</span></p> <ol type="1"> <li>You have to figure out how John the Baptist bears witness to the light of the old creation. (If you agree that it is a new creation light, a metaphor, then what part of John 1 is old creation?) You have to figure out how did the old creation light overcome the darkness. How is the old creation life, light?</li> <li>You have to figure out when the Word, the plan or purpose of God, switches from being a concept to a person, because it is certainly a person in v. 10. And since there is such continuity in his whole train of thought in the prologue, this is tough.</li> <li>You have to figure out how to reconcile v. 14 with v. 10. If v. 14 is when the plan becomes flesh, what is happening in v. 10? If the prologue is not chronological, which v. 10 suggests, then the support for a chronological reading (which logos christology relies on) falls apart.</li> <li>You have to figure out how God creating the old heavens and earth through his Word helps introduce us to Jesus of Nazareth. Why spend so much time on this?</li> <li>In v. 10 the world &ldquo;came to be&rdquo; through the &ldquo;light&rdquo;. What does this have to do with Jesus? The light never becomes flesh, only the Word becomes flesh. So, why say this? This seems quite peculiar, unless, it is a metaphor about Jesus.</li> </ol> </div>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 2, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-20 18:50:55', '<p><strong>&ldquo;This <em>Word.</em>&rdquo;</strong> This may seem like a uselessly repetitive phrase at first, however, John uses this phrase to specify that he has a specific, singular Word, or person, in mind. It is a specific &ldquo;word&rdquo; not just the general &ldquo;wisdom&rdquo; of God being referred to here. Interestingly, as is pointed out by Andrew Perry,<strong>[fn]</strong> John also uses ουτος to refer to John the Baptist in v. 7, &ldquo;this <em>one</em>&rdquo; (typically translated &ldquo;this <em>man</em>&rdquo;) came to bear witness about the light (John 1:7), whereas in John 1:2, it says, &ldquo;this <em>one</em>&rdquo; (typically translated &ldquo;this <em>Word</em>&rdquo;) was in the beginning with God. John is likely contrasting the life and ministry of Jesus, with the life and ministry of John the Baptist. Whether or not John is making this contrast between Jesus and John the Baptist here in John 1:2, at the very least, John is specifying that he has one particular &ldquo;Word&rdquo; in mind.</p> <p>John is using &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; as a metaphor for Jesus. In other words, when we read &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; we should think &ldquo;Jesus&rdquo; and that the &ldquo;all things&rdquo; coming to be through &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; are coming to be through Jesus. Jesus uses many metaphors about himself in the gospel of John, he calls himself the light of the world (John 8:12), the door (John 10:9), and so on, so it would not be out of the ordinary for John to use &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; as a metaphor for Jesus.</p> <p>[For more discussion on why &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; is being used as a metaphor for Jesus see the New Creation commentary on John 1:1.]</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;in the beginning.&rdquo;</strong> See the New Creation commentary on John 1:1 for an explanation of why &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; refers to the beginning of the New Creation, not the beginning of the Genesis creation.</p> <p><strong>Footnote &ndash; 1. Andrew Perry, <em>John 1: Jesus, Creator of an old creation or of a new one?</em></strong></p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 3, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-20 18:51:49', '<p><strong>&ldquo;Everything came to be through it.&rdquo;</strong> This verse is teaching a creation, however, we must ask, what is the &ldquo;everything&rdquo; (or <em>panta</em>, παντα) being created? Very often in scripture &ldquo;all&rdquo; is used, and does not mean every possible thing but everything in a category. [See commentary on John 21:17 for how the scriptures use &ldquo;all&rdquo;]</p> <p>So, the question remains, is this talking about how everything came to be through God&rsquo;s spoken Word in Genesis, or how everything in the New Creation came to be through Jesus? Does the passage specify what the &ldquo;all&rdquo; things are? Are they plants, animals, and the ocean? Or is it something else? John tells us, &ldquo;that which came to be through it was &ldquo;life&rdquo; (John 1:4). Yet, in context, this &ldquo;life&rdquo; is not genesis life that comes through birth, but it is life that comes through belief (John 1:12-13).</p> <p>The following are reasons that John 1:3-4 is a new creation passage [For more discussion on this, see commentary on John 1:1]:</p> <ol type="1"> <li>It fits better with the immediate context. The &ldquo;light&rdquo; of John 1:4-9 is one continued thought, of which John the Baptist bears witness. He did not bear witness about the old creation light, but the new creation light (Jesus, the light of the world). John bore witness of Jesus (John 1:15) the light (John 1:8). Therefore, we should not understand the light of John 1:4-5 to be the light of the old creation.</li> <li>The statement in John 1:4, &ldquo;that which came to be in it was life, and the life was the light of men,&rdquo; has nothing to do with John 1:3 if it is talking about the Genesis creation of land, sea, sun, and moon. How is the Genesis creation the &lsquo;light of men?&rsquo; It is not clear. However, it is clear that Jesus is the light of the world, and that he is the light of men. Light and life are directly connected in John 8:12, &ldquo;Then Jesus spoke to them again, saying, &ldquo;I am the light of the world. The one who continues to follow me will not ever walk in darkness, but will have the light of life.&rdquo;</li> <li>John 1 uses old creation language but in a different way. Light, darkness, and the beginning are all discussed like in Genesis, but we are to believe in the light (John 1:7; clearly not physical light), and life comes through belief (John 1:12-13) not through birth. Not everyone experiences this life, it is eternal life, not the kind of life in Genesis 1.</li> <li>John would be contradicting the rest of scripture in which God the Father alone created the heavens and the earth (Gen. 1:1; Ex. 20:11; Psa. 33:6, 121:2; Job 38:4), if we were to understand John 1 as teaching that Jesus created all things in the Genesis creation.</li> <li>John feels the need to specify that John the Baptist is not the &ldquo;light&rdquo; (John 1:8). If by &ldquo;light&rdquo; he means the sun and moon (the Genesis creation) this statement is nonsensical, of course he is not the sun or moon. However, if by &ldquo;light&rdquo; John has Jesus in mind, it makes sense why he would seek to distinguish the two, clarifying that John the Baptist is not the True Light.</li> <li>If John 1:1-5 was about the old creation, then there would have to be a 8,000 year gap between John 1:5 and John 1:6. This is highly unlikely considering he continues his thought about light throughout John 1:4-9.</li> <li>John 1:6-7 is clearly about the New Covenant (belief in this light).</li> <li>John 1:12-13 is clearly about the New Covenant (those who receive the true light/word are born from God).</li> <li>The Word was already flesh in John 1:10-11 when he &ldquo;came to his own&rdquo;. It did not become flesh in John 1:14. So this idea that Jesus pre-existed as a divine being (in John 1:1-13) and then became flesh and was born in John 1:14 is simply not found in the text. Therefore, it would make the most sense to understand the timing of the whole text (John 1:1-18) to be referring to Jesus&rsquo; earthly ministry.</li> <li>In John 1:17 the law was given through Moses, grace and truth came through Jesus. This is even more teaching about the New Covenant, not the Old Covenant or old creation.</li> </ol> <p>This Prologue is an introduction to the book. Therefore, we would expect to see the things that he introduced be explained further in the book. If this is talking about Jesus creating the planet earth, or even &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; creating planet earth, why is this not further discussed in the book of John? However, we see new life, or eternal life, come through Jesus in John 14:6 and many other places in the book (John 3:16, 6:47-48, 10:28, 17:3). This new life coming through Jesus is a theme in John 3, and in the entire book of John. However, the Genesis creation coming through Jesus is absent from the book of John and from the New Testament. In fact Jesus himself says, &ldquo;from the beginning, &lsquo;God made them male and female&rsquo;&rdquo; (Mark 10:6). Therefore, Jesus himself attributes the Genesis creation to someone else other than himself, namely, God.</p> <p>It is also worth noting that &ldquo;all things&rdquo; (<em>panta</em>) is used in reference to &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in the new creation many times in the New Testament (Col. 1:20; 2 Cor. 5:18; Rom. 11:36; Heb. 2:10; Heb. 1:2; Col. 1:16; Matt. 11:27; John 17:7; 3:35; 13:3; 1 Cor. 15:27; Eph. 1:22; 3:9). For instance, &ldquo;through him (Jesus) God was pleased to reconcile to himself all things&rdquo; (Col. 1:20). This cannot mean &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in totality, but all things that are part of the new creation, since unreconciled people are not part of &ldquo;all things&rdquo; reconciled to God. Likewise, when 1 Corinthians 15:27 says, &ldquo;For he has put all things in subjection under his feet,&rdquo; this does not include the enemies that will be destroyed (1 Cor. 15:25-26), but &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in the new creation. Therefore, simply saying &ldquo;everything&rdquo; or &ldquo;all things&rdquo; (<em>panta</em>) without specifying that it is everything in the new creation, is not out of the ordinary, and that is exactly what the author John is doing here in John 1:3.</p> <p>&ldquo;All&rdquo; came to be through the Word (John 1:3). &ldquo;All&rdquo; what? All Life. But not the kind of life in Genesis 1, the kind in John 1:12-13.</p> <hr />'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 4, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-19 20:12:34', '<p><strong>&ldquo;That which came to be in it was life.&rdquo;</strong> The way that almost all Trinitarian translations translate verses 3-4 is, &ldquo;All things were made through him, and without him was not anything made that was made. In him was life, and the life was the light of men.&rdquo;</p> <p>The reason why many Trinitarians translate the verse in this way is so that it makes it seem like Jesus utterly and completely made all things. Yet, there is an odd repetition at the end of verse 3, &ldquo;Without him was not anything made <strong>that was made</strong>.&rdquo; Why this weird repetition? The reader can understand that all things were made through him without repeating the phrase &ldquo;that was made.&rdquo; If nothing was made without him, then that would include things &ldquo;that were made.&rdquo; The point is clear. It seems to be an unneccessary repetition.</p> <p>What if the phrase &ldquo;that was made&rdquo; was not a useless repetition with no meaning. What if it is supposed to be paired with the clause that follows? This would read, &ldquo;That which came to be in it was life.&rdquo;</p> <p>Although many translations differ, the Greek grammar makes more sense to understand the last phrase, &ldquo;That has come into being&rdquo; to go with the next clause beginning John 1:4. In other words, the sentence is split at the wrong place in many translations.</p> <p>The following are reasons why we should split up John 1:3 and John 1:4 the way we have in the REV:</p> <ul> <li>The Nestle Aland 28th edition Greek text, one of the most well respected versions of the Greek New Testament, does so.</li> <li>&ldquo;It is a common Johannine feature to end sentences or clauses with some form of οὐδείς.&rdquo; (John 5:30; 6:63; 8:15, 28; 9:33; 10:41; 11:49; 12:19; 14:30; 15:5; 16:23; 18:9, 20, 31; 21:3) [<strong>The Question of Punctuation in John 1:3&ndash;4: Arguments from Ancient Colometry, Author(s): Dan Nässelqvist, Source: Journal of Biblical Literature , Vol. 137, No. 1 (Spring 2018),</strong> pg. 179.]</li> <li>B. F. Westcott concluded that &ldquo;it would be difficult to find a more complete consent of ancient authorities in favour of any reading, than that which supports the second punctuation: Without Him was not anything made. That which hath been made in Him was life.&rdquo; [<strong>B. F. Westcott, The Gospel according to St. John: The Authorized Version with Introduction and Notes (London: Murray, 1896), 4.]</strong></li> <li>&ldquo;All church fathers from the second century who discuss or quote John 1:3&ndash;4 relate the passage in line with Reading A. This is also true of many fathers from the third to the fifth centuries.&rdquo; [<strong>The Question of Punctuation in John 1:3&ndash;4: Arguments from Ancient Colometry, Author(s): Dan Nässelqvist, Source: Journal of Biblical Literature , Vol. 137, No. 1 (Spring 2018), pp. 177.]</strong> For example, Athanasius (4c.), Irenaeus (2c.), Clement of Alexandria (2c.), Origen (3c.), and Tertullian (2c.), all quote John 1:3 without the phrase &ldquo;that which was made&rdquo; at the end of the verse.</li> <li>&ldquo;p75, arguably the earliest punctuated witness to the Fourth Gospel, has an elevated dot after οὐδὲ ἕν, thus supporting Reading A.&rdquo; [<strong>The Question of Punctuation in John 1:3&ndash;4: Arguments from Ancient Colometry, Author(s): Dan Nässelqvist, Source: Journal of Biblical Literature , Vol. 137, No. 1 (Spring 2018), pp. 175-191.]</strong></li> <li>&ldquo;The examination of Readings A&ndash;D from the perspective of ancient colometry thus indicates that only Reading A fully corresponds to ancient compositional practices and results in balanced cola that meet the threefold requirements of syn- tactical completion, unitary thought, and acceptable length.&rdquo; [pg. 190 <strong>Ibid.]</strong></li> <li>&ldquo;Reading A produces an antithetic parallelism in 1:3, which resembles what we find in other Jewish literature, such as the Dead Sea Scrolls.&rdquo; [<strong>Ibid,</strong> p. 178]</li> <li>The NRSV also puts, &ldquo;That has come into being&rdquo; with John 1:4.</li> </ul> <p>The reason why the positioning of &ldquo;that which came to be through him,&rdquo; is so significant, is because with the proper positioning it becomes clearer that John 1:4 is not a completely new topic concerning life and light, but that those are the very things that came to be through the Word. &ldquo;All&rdquo; came to be through the Word (John 1:3). &ldquo;All&rdquo; what? All Life (John 1:4). But not the kind of life in Genesis 1, the kind in John 1:12-13.</p> <p>An interesting parallel to John&rsquo;s words here occurs in 1 John. In 1 John, Jesus is specifically described as the Word of Life (1 John 1:1). He is not the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; of land and sea, but of life. In other words just as God used his &ldquo;Word&rdquo; (Gen. 1:6) to create land and sea in Genesis, life has come to be through the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; (Jesus) in the new creation. John&rsquo;s metaphor of calling Jesus &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; has a purpose. It communicates the parallel in how God is bringing about his new creation.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;And this life was the light of humankind.&rdquo;</strong> [For more information on the &ldquo;light&rdquo; being spoken of here, see commentary on John 1:5, For more information on why John 1 speaks of the New Creation, not the Genesis creation, see our commentary on John 1:1]</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 5, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-19 20:49:21', '<p><strong>&ldquo;the light shines in the darkness.&rdquo;</strong> The &ldquo;light&rdquo; in John 1:4-13 is another metaphorical reference to Jesus and his ministry because the &ldquo;light&rdquo; came into the world (John 1:10) and people believed in the light (John 1:12), so it is evident that John is not referencing physical light.</p> <p>John&rsquo;s metaphorical use of Jesus as the &ldquo;light&rdquo; is also seen by the fact that the Greek is masculine in verse 10. This means that by verse 10 one must understand the &ldquo;true light&rdquo; to not be referring to a literal light, or else it would be neuter, but instead John uses the masculine without introducing a new subject. Thus, John must have something in mind besides literal light, and since John the Baptist bears witness about this light (John 1:7-8), and in the very same passage he bears witness about Jesus (John 1:15), it follows that Jesus is the true light (John 1:9).</p> <p>Even more evidence that this light is in reference to Jesus is found in verse 12, &ldquo;those who believe in his (the true light&rsquo;s) name&mdash;he gave the right to become children of God,&rdquo; and in the book of John itself, John speaks of belief in Jesus as the way by which new birth happens (John 3:15-16).</p> <p>In John 3:19 we find John clearly using light as a metaphor for Jesus when he says, &ldquo;the light has come into the world, and people loved the darkness rather than the light,&rdquo; when just a few verses prior he says that God sent his Son into the world (John 3:17). This light/darkness metaphor in John 3:19 is referring to the concept of salvation and evil people rejecting Jesus as the Messiah. It is not in reference to men being opposed to the brightness of the Sun. John is clearly making a spiritual point not a physical one. He is doing a very similar thing in John 1:5.</p> <p>Another reason why we should understand &ldquo;light&rdquo; to be a metaphor for Jesus in John 1:5 is because Jesus himself claims to be the &ldquo;light of the world&rdquo; (John 8:12). Therefore, it is evident that in the book of John, &ldquo;light&rdquo; is consistently used in reference to Jesus and his ministry.</p> <p>Lastly, John also uses very similar language in 1 John 2:8 when discussing the New Covenant ministry of Jesus, &ldquo;On the other hand, I am writing a new commandment to you, which is true in him and in you because the darkness is passing away and the true light already shines&rdquo; (1 John 2:8). <strong>[fn][Bernard, J. H. A Critical and Exegetical Commentary on the Gospel according to St. John. Edited by Alan Hugh McNeile. International Critical Commentary. (New York: C. Scribner&rsquo; Sons, 1929), 5.</strong></p> <p>Thus, there are numerous reasons to understand this light/darkness metaphor in reference to Jesus and his ministry. The reason why John uses the metaphor, &ldquo;the light shines in the darkness,&rdquo; is because the righteousness and goodness of Jesus&rsquo; life and ministry in a broken world is comparable to a light shining in the darkness.</p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><strong>&ldquo;but the darkness did not overcome it.&rdquo;</strong> In the commentary above, we have demonstrated that the &ldquo;light&rdquo; is not in reference to the Sun, but a reference to Jesus as the &ldquo;light of the world&rdquo; (John 8:12). If John was referring to the literal Sun, what would he mean by, &ldquo;the darkness did not overcome it?&rdquo; However, this statement would make sense if it was referring to Jesus&rsquo; accomplishment of defeating the Devil, sin, and death, through his atoning sacrifice. Jesus was victorious, he defeated death (1 Cor. 15:55-57; Rom. 6:9; Heb. 2:14; 2 Tim. 1:10), and the powers of sin (John 8:36) through his death and resurrection. In fact, before his resurrection, Jesus speaks of his future victory over sin and death as if it has already been accomplished, saying, &ldquo;Take heart, I have overcome the world&rdquo; (John 16:33). The darkness did not overcome the light, what good news.</p> <p style="line-height:1.38">[For more information on why John 1 speaks of the New Creation, not the Genesis creation, see our commentary on John 1:1]</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 6, 0, null, 99, '2023-01-19 22:32:04', '<p><strong>&ldquo;There came a man sent from God.&rdquo;</strong> The first thing to note concerning this phrase is that John the Baptist is not completely irrelevant to the discussion. In John&rsquo;s mind, he felt it relevant to begin talking about John the Baptist directly after mentioning the light and darkness of some creation. Yet, if John 1:4 is referring to the literal light and darkness created in the Genesis creation, then his mentioning of John the Baptist makes no sense. What does John the Baptist have to do with the Genesis creation? However, if the author John has in mind the New Creation through Christ, the light, then introducing John the Baptist is quite essential, as he is the one who prepares the way for Jesus, and testifies to him (John 1:7-8). It is also noteworthy that all of the gospels mention John the Baptist as preparing the way for Jesus (Matt. 3; Mark 1; Luke 1). Therefore, instead of creating at least a 8,000 year gap between John 1:4 and John 1:5, we should understand both to be referring to the New Creation. In fact, John the Baptist bears witness about the light of John 1:4, so, the author John sees great continuity of thought between John 1:4-9.</p> <p>Secondly, the phrase &ldquo;sent from God&rdquo; is a phrase that is used of Jesus quite often (John 3:16; 5:23; Luke 10:16). Many Trinitarians take this to mean that Jesus pre-existed with God in some unkown state and then became a human in the man Jesus. However, as is seen here, to say that someone is sent from God, does not imply pre-existence, instead, it simply means that God has given them a mission to accomplish. &ldquo;Frequent reference is made in the OT to prophets being sent by God (2 Chr. 24:19; 25:15; Jer. 7:25; 25:4, 5; 28:9; 35:15; 44:4; Baruch 1:21).&rdquo; <strong>[fn][Colin G. Kruse, John: An Introduction and Commentary, vol. 4, Tyndale New Testament Commentaries (Downers Grove, IL: InterVarsity Press, 2003), 65.]</strong> In the same way, disciples are sent by Jesus to preach the gospel into the whole world (Matt. 28:18-19), and to his apostles Jesus said, &ldquo;As the Father has sent me, even so I send you&rdquo; (John 20:21). Therefore, it is evident that this &ldquo;sending&rdquo; language is used very often and does not inherently carry the idea of pre-existence.</p> <p>[For more information on why John 1 speaks of the New Creation, not the Genesis creation, see our commentary on John 1:1]</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 7, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-19 22:36:25', '<p><strong>&ldquo;This man came as a witness to testify about the light.&rdquo;</strong> This phrase provides more evidence that the whole prologue concerns Jesus and the new creation. John the Baptist, the subject here, testified about Jesus and his ministry (John 1:15), never once did he testify about the Sun and Moon of the Genesis creation. Therefore, the &ldquo;light&rdquo; is in reference to Jesus the True light (John 1:9) and the &ldquo;light of the world&rdquo; (John 8:12). [For more discussion on the &ldquo;light&rdquo; see our commentary on John 1:5]</p> <p>The same light that came through the Word &ldquo;in the beginning&rdquo; is the same light that John the Baptist testifies about. Therefore, whatever &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; was in verse 1 is around the same time frame as verse 6. There is no gap of thousands of years between &ldquo;the beginning&rdquo; and John the Baptist. To disconnect the light in verse 4 by thousands of years from the light that John is bearing witness about in verse 5 is unwarranted.</p> <p>Therefore, when reading John 1 through a Trinitarian lens, one misses this beautiful analogy that Jesus is the light of the New Creation. Not the old one. He brings light and life to all those who receive him (John 1:12).</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;so that through him all would believe.&rdquo;</strong> The purpose of John the Baptist&rsquo;s ministry was so that people would believe, not in him, but in the True Light which gives light to every person (John 1:9). The &ldquo;light&rdquo; John is speaking of is not a light one sees, but a light one believes in. If one believes in this light, he is born (John 1:13), yet we know that physical birth does not happen through belief, therefore, this must be a different kind of birth. John is speaking of the New Birth which Jesus further discusses with Nicodemus in Chapter 3. This statement provides even more evidence that the author John is speaking of the New Creation which came to be through Christ [For more information on why John 1 speaks of the New Creation, not the Genesis creation, see our commentary on John 1:1].</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 8, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-19 22:37:40', '<p><strong>&ldquo;That man was not the light.&rdquo;</strong> John feels the need to specify that John the Baptist is not the &ldquo;light&rdquo; (John 1:8). If by &ldquo;light&rdquo; he means the Sun and Moon (the Genesis creation) this statement is nonsensical, of course John the Baptist is not the Sun or Moon. However, if by &ldquo;light&rdquo; John has Jesus in mind, it makes sense why he would seek to distinguish the two, clarifying that John the Baptist is not the True Light.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;but he came to testify about the light.&rdquo;</strong> Again, John is reiterating that John the Baptist&rsquo;s mission was to testify about the light, which is Jesus. John the Baptist did not testify about a literal light, a Word or Plan of God, but a person (John 1:15). [For more information on the &ldquo;light&rdquo; see our commentary on John 1:5, For more information on why John 1 speaks of the New Creation, not the Genesis creation, see our commentary on John 1:1]</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 9, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-19 22:47:43', '<p><strong>&ldquo;The true light, who gives light to every person, was coming into the world.&rdquo;</strong> This verse helps to emphasize that John the Baptist was the precursor to Jesus (John 1:15). He came before Jesus to help testify to him and to spread the message that the Messiah was coming into the world (Mark 1:2-4).</p> <p>[For more information on why the &ldquo;light&rdquo; is Jesus, see our commentary on John 1:5, For more information on why John 1 speaks of the New Creation, not the Genesis creation, see our commentary on John 1:1]</p> <p>We should not make the mistake of thinking that John 1:14 is the moment Jesus came into the world. Instead, the author John specifies that Jesus was in the world in John 1:10. Jesus was flesh while he was in the world, thus, he was in the flesh during the events of John 1:10, and also during the events of John 1:1-3.</p> <p>[For more discussion on the chronology of the Prologue see our commentary on John 1:14]</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 10, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-20 04:53:28', '<p><strong>&ldquo;He was in the world.&rdquo;</strong> The &ldquo;world&rdquo; or <em>kosmos</em> (#2889, κόσμος), in this particular usage means the spatial world, but, the author John uses the word <em>kosmos</em> in multiple ways in this verse (the first &ldquo;world&rdquo; is the spatial world and the third &ldquo;world&rdquo; in this verse is the world of people).</p> <p>The text reads &ldquo;He&rdquo; was in the world, not &ldquo;it.&rdquo; Although the &ldquo;True Light&rdquo; is grammatically neuter, the author John surprisingly uses the masculine pronoun &ldquo;him&rdquo; (<em>auton,</em> αὐτὸν) at the end of the verse. In other words, the last phrase must read, &ldquo;yet the world did not know him,&rdquo; and since, translating the sentence &ldquo;It was in the world, and the world came to be through it, yet the world did not know him,&rdquo; does not make sense contextually (because it would introduce two subjects), we have translated the subject as &ldquo;he&rdquo; consistently throughout the verse. The reason the author John uses a masculine pronoun in this verse is to communicate that he does not just have in mind a concept (the True Light) but a person (Jesus).</p> <p>Also, notice the order of the phrases here in John 1:10. John says that Jesus was &ldquo;in the world,&rdquo; then he says that &ldquo;the world came to be through him.&rdquo; If John had the Genesis creation in mind, this is the opposite order of what you would expect. The Genesis creation happened thousands or millions of years before Jesus was in the world. In this scenario, one would expect John to say something along the lines of, &lsquo;the world came to be through him, and <em>then</em> he came into the world.&rsquo; Perhaps John does not have the Genesis creation in mind, but that the world <em>to come</em> came to be through him, and this happened after Jesus&rsquo; resurrection, after his time &ldquo;in the world.&rdquo;</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;the world came to be through him.&rdquo;</strong> There are a few possible interpretations of what this phrase means. First is the common Trinitarian understanding, that &ldquo;the world&rdquo; is in reference to the Genesis creation and this came to be through Jesus. This view would be understood as, &ldquo;the <em>old</em> world came to be through him.&rdquo; However, this Trinitarian understanding is not as fitting for multiple reasons:</p> <ol type="1"> <li>If John meant here in John 1:10b that Jesus created the material creation, then he is rewriting Genesis 1 and the other places in which God the Father is the only creator of heaven and earth (Gen. 1:1; Psa. 121:2; Job 38:4; Mark 10:6).</li> <li>John never discusses Jesus&rsquo; creation of the universe again in the gospel of John. If a Prologue is meant to introduce the gospel account then John introduces something that never comes up again. What does come up again regularly is the new creation of the world: sinners being &ldquo;born&rdquo; again (John 3), and eternal life, or new life, coming through Jesus (John 3:16; 6:33; 14:6).</li> <li>The immediate context before and after John 1:10 discusses belief and life (John 1:4-8; 11-13) not the creation of Genesis.</li> </ol> <p>Therefore, to understand this as the creation of the old heavens and the earth does not fit with the immediate or broad context.</p> <p>[Please see our New Creation commentary on John 1:1 to see why this perspective is not the best way to understand John&rsquo;s words.]</p> <p>Secondly, one could understand this phrase to mean that &ldquo;the world <em>was born</em> through him.&rdquo; Although &ldquo;was born&rdquo; is a possible way to understand the Greek word <em>egeneto</em> (#1096, ἐγένετο), and the &ldquo;world&rdquo; would keep a more consistent meaning throughout John 1:10 (it would mean the &ldquo;unbelieving&rdquo; world in both John 1:10b and 1:10c), and &ldquo;<em>unbelieving</em> world&rdquo; is a very common way John uses <em>kosmos</em> in his gospel (John 7:7; 12:19; 15:18; etc.), this perspective has a few negatives. Firstly, <em>egeneto</em> more often takes the meaning of something &ldquo;coming to be&rdquo; or &ldquo;happening&rdquo; (<em>BDAG</em>, p. 196), and it is used this way by John predominantly throughout the Prologue (John 1:3, 6, 14, 17). Also, John uses a different Greek word <em>egennēthē</em><em>san</em> (#1080, ἐγεννήθησαν) in John 1:13 to communicate the idea of birth. So, if John had meant to communicate that the &ldquo;<em>old</em> world <em>was born</em>&rdquo; through him, he more likely would have used <em>egennēthē</em><em>san.</em> Moreover, since this phrase has extremely strong syntactic parallels with John 1:3, it is unlikely that <em>egeneto</em> in John 1:3 meant to communicate &ldquo;coming to be&rdquo; whereas <em>egeneto</em> in John 1:10 meant to communicate &ldquo;birth.&rdquo; Therefore, it is unlikely that John meant to communicate that &ldquo;the <em>old</em> world <em>was born</em> (came to new life) through him.&rdquo; Although, the theology is certainly true, this is not likely what John was trying to communicate in John 1:10b.</p> <p>The last way to understand this phrase is that the &ldquo;world <em>to come</em> came to be through him.&rdquo; In other words, the new creation came to be through Jesus. The first reason for understanding this phrase in this way is the strong parallel with John 1:3. In whatever way we interpret John 1:3, this should influence how we interpret John 1:10b because the syntax is almost identical. In John 1:3 we read, &ldquo;Everything came to be through it (the Word),&rdquo; and in John 1:10b we read, &ldquo;the world came to be through him.&rdquo; Since, the &ldquo;everything&rdquo; of John 1:3 is everything in the New Creation (see commentary on John 1:3), it would make sense to understand the &ldquo;world&rdquo; of John 1:10b to be the &ldquo;world <em>to come.</em>&rdquo;</p> <p>Secondly, in the book of John, Jesus uses the term &ldquo;world,&rdquo; or <em>kosmos</em>, in a way that implies his Kingdom is of &ldquo;another&rdquo; world.</p> <ul> <li>&ldquo;Whoever is overly attached to his life loses it, and whoever hates his life in <strong>this world</strong> will keep it, resulting in life in the age to come&rdquo; (John 12:25). Some translations read, &ldquo;will keep it for eternal life&rdquo; (ESV). This verse is especially powerful because Jesus is contrasting &ldquo;this world&rdquo; with &ldquo;life in the age to come,&rdquo; or &ldquo;eternal life,&rdquo; which are in the <em>next</em> world. In other words, whoever hates his life in this world will keep it <em>in the world to come,</em> is the implied ellipsis.</li> <li>&ldquo;My kingdom is <strong>not of this world</strong>. If my kingdom were of this world, then my servants would be fighting to keep me from being handed over to the Jews, but in fact, my kingdom is not from here&rdquo; (John 18:36).</li> <li>&ldquo;You are from beneath, I am from above. You are of this world, I am <strong>not of this world</strong>&rdquo; (John 8:23).</li> <li>&ldquo;They are <strong>not of the world</strong>, just as I am not of the world&rdquo; (John 17:16).</li> </ul> <p>Likewise, in Romans 4:13 Paul says that God made a promise to Abraham that he would inherit the world (<em>kosmos</em>). However, Abraham died without receiving the promise (Heb. 11:13). Therefore, Paul must have in mind that Abraham (and his children by faith) would inherit the world <em>to come</em>. Also, in Hebrews 2:5 we read, &ldquo;For he did not put the inhabited world that is about to come in subjection to angels...&rdquo; Although the Greek word for inhabited world is not <em>kosmos</em>, it is very similar in meaning.</p> <p>From the evidence above, there is a world <em>to come,</em> over which Jesus is the King (Heb. 2:5). In Jesus&rsquo; mind, his kingdom is from another world, it is a heavenly kingdom (Matt. 5:10; 7:21; 10:7; Luke 17:20-21). How does one enter this heavenly kingdom, this new creation? By being born from above (John 3:3, 5). How can one be born from above? By believing in Jesus (John 3:15-16). So, entrance into the new world, the new creation, is through Jesus (2 Cor. 5:17). This aligns perfectly with our understanding of John 1:10 that &ldquo;the world <em>to come</em> came to be through him.&rdquo;</p> <p>Now, one might ask how a future reality has already happened, how it can be said of the &ldquo;world <em>to come</em>&rdquo; that it &ldquo;came to be?&rdquo; The answer deals with understanding the &ldquo;hour now is&hellip; but the hour is coming&rdquo; language of the Kingdom that Jesus uses. In John 5:25 we read, &ldquo;Truly, truly, I say to you, the hour comes, and now is, when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God, and those who heard will live.&rdquo; This refers to the new birth, the spiritual resurrection of believers, that is available right now to those who place their trust in Christ and receive the Holy Spirit (Acts 2:38; Eph. 2:6). Yet just a few verses later we read, &ldquo;For the hour is coming in which all who are in the tombs will hear his voice and will come out; those who have done good, to the resurrection of life, and those who have practiced evil, to the resurrection of condemnation&rdquo; (John 5:28-29). This is referring to our future resurrection and the full reality of the Kingdom. Therefore, in some sense the world <em>to come</em> is a present reality, and we are currently a new creation if we are in Christ (2 Cor. 5:17). This is how Jesus is able to say that &ldquo;the Kingdom of God has come upon you&rdquo; (Matt. 12:28). However, the fullness of the new creation and the world to come will arrive in the future (1 Cor. 15:24-28). Both are true. Thus, it is perfectly reasonable to think that the &ldquo;world <em>to come</em>&rdquo; has already come to be a reality through Jesus.</p> <p>The third reason to understand this phrase as, &ldquo;the world <em>to come</em> came to be through him,&rdquo; is that the scriptures commonly use the word &ldquo;all things&rdquo; (<em>panta</em>) with the intention of meaning &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in the new creation. The scriptures speak of &ldquo;all things&rdquo; coming to be through Christ and Christ reigning over &ldquo;all things&rdquo; (Col. 1:20; 2 Cor. 5:18; Rom. 11:36; Heb. 2:10; Heb. 1:2; Col. 1:16; Matt. 11:27; John 17:7; 3:35; 13:3; 1 Cor. 15:27; Eph. 1:22; 3:9). For instance, &ldquo;through him (Jesus) God was pleased to reconcile to himself all things&rdquo; (Col. 1:20). This cannot mean &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in totality, but all things that are part of the new creation, since unreconciled people are not part of &ldquo;all things&rdquo; reconciled to God. Likewise, when 1 Corinthians 15:27 says, &ldquo;For he has put all things in subjection under his feet,&rdquo; this does not include the enemies that will be destroyed (1 Cor. 15:25-26), but &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in the new creation. Therefore, since &ldquo;all things&rdquo; is a common way for the scriptures to speak of the new creation, and this verse has immensly strong parallels with John 1:3 in which &ldquo;all things&rdquo; refers to all things in the new creation, it would not be out of the ordinary for the author John to use &ldquo;the world&rdquo; in reference to the new creation.</p> <p>Although, none of these views should likely be taken with 100% certainty as this is a highly metaphorical passage, we believe that the best way to understand John&rsquo;s words here is that &ldquo;the world <em>to come</em> came to be through him.&rdquo;</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 11, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-20 15:41:12', '<p><strong>&ldquo;He came to his own.&rdquo;</strong> Although Jesus has not been officially introduced anywhere in this passage so far, this phrase provides more evidence that the author John has had a person in mind, not a concept. A literal light, did not come to people in the book of John. However, Jesus did come to his own people, the Jews, in the book of John (John 1:43; 2:13; etc.).</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;his own did not receive him.&rdquo;</strong> This refers to the rejection of Jesus by the Jews, his own people. Not every single Jew rejected him, (John 1:12) but the People as a whole did, and had him crucified (John 19:14-15). &ldquo;For the writers of the New Testament the rejection of Jesus by the Jews was extremely difficult to comprehend. Not only does John repeatedly detail the surprising unbelief of the Jews (e.g., 5:46&ndash;47; 6:64&ndash;65; 7:47&ndash;52; 9:30&ndash;34, 40&ndash;41) but Paul in Romans 9&ndash;11 tried courageously to work out a rationale for the Jewish rejection of Jesus.&rdquo;<strong>[fn]</strong> It is quite the baffling concept, the King who was to lead Israel into a time of everlasting peace and flourishing (Isa. 9:6; 2 Sam. 7:12-13) was rejected by Israel itself. Yet, even with this rejection, the truth remained that Jesus was the King of the Jews (Matt. 27:11; Luke 23:3; John 19:19), whether he came in the way the Jews thought he would or not.</p> <p><strong>Gerald L. Borchert, John 1&ndash;11, vol. 25A, The New American Commentary (Nashville: Broadman &amp; Holman Publishers, 1996), 114.</strong></p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 12, 0, null, 99, '2023-01-20 15:45:40', '<p><strong>&ldquo;to those who believe in his name.&rdquo;</strong> This phrase provides more evidence that the whole passage is about the New Creation, not the Genesis creation. This is not a true light that we see but a true light that we believe in and receive new life. Likewise, in the gospel of John, people believe in Jesus and receive new life (John 3:16; 5:40; 6:47).</p> <p>[For more information on John 1 as a new creation passage see our commentary on John 1:1].</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;children of God.&rdquo;</strong> Israel, who were the children of God in the Old Testament, (Deut. 14:1; Psa. 82:6) and considered themselves to be God&rsquo;s children in the book of John, (John 8:41) rejected their Messiah (John 1:11). Yet, now, we who believe in Christ, get to become children of God (John 1:12; 8:42). The True Israel, the true children of God, are those who have trust (Rom. 2:28-29), not those born of physical descent from Abraham (Rom. 9:6).</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 13, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-20 15:46:33', '<p><strong>&ldquo;who were not born by blood&hellip; but by God.&rdquo;</strong> This is quite a profound statement. John is saying that there is a birth that happens, but it is not through pregnancy, or through natural means, but &ldquo;by God.&rdquo; John likely gets this idea from Jesus&rsquo; teaching in John 3, saying that one must be born from above to enter the kingdom of Heaven. This new birth happens through trust in Jesus Christ, the light (John 1:12; 3:5).</p> <p>[For more information on John 1 as a new creation passage see our commentary on John 1:1].</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 14, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-20 18:58:02', '<p><strong>&ldquo;The Word became flesh.&rdquo;</strong> There are a few things that are vital to understanding this phrase. First, we must understand that &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; was being used as a metaphor in reference to Jesus in John 1:1-3, but that here in John 1:14, we must reevaluate if &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; is again being used as a metaphor for Jesus. [For more information on this, see our commentary on John 1:1.]</p> <p>Understanding &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; as a metaphor for Jesus would be understood as, &ldquo;Jesus became flesh.&rdquo; This would suggest that Jesus pre-existed and then became a human. Now, we do not have space to do a full rebuttal to the pre-existence of Jesus, but here are a few points in response to arguments for pre-existence.</p> <p>First, the authors of the other gospels seem to believe Jesus&rsquo; birth was his beginning. Matthew 1:1 and 1:18 use the noun <em>genesis</em> (γενεσις #1078) which means birth, or origin. <strong>[fn] [Arndt, William, Frederick W. Danker, Walter Bauer, and F. Wilbur Gingrich. <em>A Greek-English Lexicon of the New Testament and Other Early Christian Literature</em>. Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 2000, 192]</strong> Thus, simply put, the bible describes Jesus as having a beginning in the womb of Mary, yet, nowhere is he described as &ldquo;eternally begotten.&rdquo;</p> <p>Jesus is also called the &ldquo;only begotten&rdquo; son, some people might miss the point of this description of Jesus (John 1:14, 18; 3:16; 3:18) because of its being infused with modern ideas of &ldquo;eternal-begottenness&rdquo; which is not a biblical term but a contradictory term. The word &ldquo;only begotten&rdquo; <em>monogenēs</em> (μονογενὴς #3439) has two primary meanings. First, in contexts with sons or daughters it carries the meaning of only begotten (Heb. 11:17; Luke 8:42), and in other contexts it can mean something that is unique, or one of a kind (in 1 Clement 25:2 it is used of the Phoenix). In John 1:18, and likewise in John 1:14, since &ldquo;son&rdquo; follows directly after <em>monogenē</em><em>s</em>, it makes the most sense to understand the meaning to be &ldquo;only begotten&rdquo; son, or simply &ldquo;only son&rdquo; just as Jairus&rsquo;s daughter was his <em>monogenē</em><em>s</em> daughter, or &ldquo;only&rdquo; daughter (Luke 8:42). Being &ldquo;begotten&rdquo; simply means being born or created, and ideas of eternality should not be read into the meaning of the word, in fact, just the opposite. If something is born or created, it is not eternal, and therefore, the use of <em>monogenē</em><em>s</em> points to the fact that Jesus had a beginning about 2,000 years ago. With this in mind, this means that each of the gospel writers believe that Jesus had a beginning (Matt. 1:18; John 1:14; Luke 2:7). Yet, none of the gospel writers explicitly mention a time when Jesus existed before his birth.</p> <p>A better word to use if Jesus had been existing from eternity past would be something like &ldquo;became&rdquo; or &ldquo;transformed&rdquo; but none of the Gospels, including here in John 1:14, teach that Jesus became human or transformed into a human, but that he was created (John 1:18; Matt. 1:18; Luke 2:7; Col. 1:15) just like every other human (Luke 3:23-38). Remember, John 1:14 does not say, &ldquo;Jesus became flesh,&rdquo; we will talk about this more below.</p> <p>In fact, the silence regarding Jesus&rsquo; pre-existence is deafening. Both Matthew and Luke go to great lengths to demonstrate that Jesus&rsquo; bloodline can be traced back to David and ultimately Adam (Luke 3:31; Matt. 1:6), yet there is not the slightest mention of any sort of pre-existence. The gospel writers are seeking to give accounts of the life and ministry of Jesus, but if Jesus had existed for eternity before his 33 year life, and yet one fails to mention his eternal works, and only discusses his earthly life, is there not an astronomical missing piece to the account?</p> <p>As Peter declared by revelation, &ldquo;For he was foreknown before the foundation of the world, but has appeared in these last times for the sake of you&rdquo; (1 Pet. 1:20 &ndash; NASB). Christ was in God&rsquo;s foreknowledge before the world began, but was not yet a reality.</p> <p>Another unsolvable problem caused by the &ldquo;incarnation&rdquo; is that it destroys the correlation that God established of a first Adam and a last Adam. Romans 5:12-19 clearly defines a critical, logical parallel between Adam and Jesus Christ in the context of the redemption of mankind. A major consequence of the doctrine that God became man is that it destroys this key parallel, for Adam is hardly comparable to an eternally pre-existent being. So, how could Jesus be compared to Adam if he pre-existed as God? He couldn&rsquo;t. On the other hand, what we find biblically is that one man accomplished the Fall of humankind, the other man (1 Tim. 2:5) accomplished the redemption of humankind. Jesus was the Last Adam, not the first God-man.</p> <p>The last point in response to pre-existence in John 1:14 is that we must understand the context. We should not think that Jesus created the Genesis creation in a pre-existent state, and then became flesh in John 1:14 because Jesus was already flesh in John 1:10 when he was &ldquo;in&rdquo; the world, and in John 1:11, 12, and 13 when we are to believe in him, namely, in the human flesh and bone Jesus. Thus, the passage is not chronological. Instead, this is a summary statement teaching us that &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; used to create the New Creation is a person (John 1:3, 10, 14; 2 Cor. 5:17) which is in contrast to &ldquo;the Word&rdquo; used to create the Genesis creation that was spoken (Gen.1:3, 6, 9; etc.). So, when we understand that John 1:14 is not chronological, this means that the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; in John 1:1-3 is referring to Jesus when he was in the flesh, not in a pre-existent state. Simply put the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; became flesh in John 1:1 and was flesh all throughout John 1:1-18. Nowhere in the Prologue of John is it taught that Jesus pre-existed without a human body. Likewise, the text in John 1:14 does not say that Jesus became flesh, but that the Word became flesh.</p> <p>Therefore, with all of the evidence above, it is highly unlikely that John meant to use the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; as a metaphor for Jesus here in John 1:14, meaning, &ldquo;Jesus became flesh&rdquo; but rather, he meant to communicate, &ldquo;the Word became flesh <em>in the person Jesus Christ.</em>&rdquo;</p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff">The <em>logos</em>, that is, the expression of God, &ldquo;became flesh&rdquo; (came into concretion or physical existence) in Jesus Christ. Jesus is the &ldquo;image of the invisible God&rdquo; (Col. 1:15) and His chief emissary, representative and agent. Since Jesus perfectly obeyed the Father, he represents everything that God could communicate about Himself in a human person. As such, Jesus could say, &ldquo;If you have seen me, you have seen the Father&rdquo; (John 14:9).</p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff">It is important to ask why John would say, &ldquo;the Word became flesh,&rdquo; which is a statement that seems so obvious to us. Of course Jesus Christ was flesh. He was born, grew, ate, and slept, and Scripture calls him a man. However, what is clear to us now was not at all clear in the early centuries of the Christian era. The Bible must be understood in the context of the culture in which it was written. At the time John wrote the Gospel of John, the &ldquo;Docetic&rdquo; movement was gaining disciples inside Christianity (&ldquo;Docetic&rdquo; comes from the Greek word for &ldquo;to seem&rdquo; or &ldquo;to appear&rdquo;). Docetic Christians believed Jesus was actually a spirit being, or god, who only &ldquo;appeared&rdquo; to be human. Some Docetics did not believe Jesus even actually ate or drank, but only pretended to do so. Furthermore, some Jews thought that Jesus was an angel. In today&rsquo;s theological literature, theologians refer to this as &ldquo;angel Christology.&rdquo;</p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff">John 1:14 was not written to show that Jesus was somehow preexistent and then became flesh. It was written to show that Jesus was not a spirit, god, or angelic being, but a real flesh-and-blood human being. A very similar thing is said in 1 John 4:2, that if you do not believe Jesus has come &ldquo;in the flesh,&rdquo; you are not of God. Likewise in 2 John 1:7 we read, &ldquo;For many deceivers have gone out into the world, those who do not confess Jesus Christ coming in the flesh.&rdquo; It seems that John was battling against docetists who were denying that Jesus was a real human. John is assuring his readers (John 1:14; 1 John 4:2; 2 John 1:7) that Jesus was truly human and therefore, he could truly be the perfect sacrifice for our sins.</p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><strong>&ldquo;the only begotten Son from the Father.&rdquo;</strong> This phrase settles any doubt. John has been speaking in highly poetic terms, yet, he finally brings some clarity, telling us that this fleshly Word, or this human Word, is Jesus. In John 1:18 John says that Jesus &ldquo;explains&rdquo; the Father, and words are used for explanation. Thus, one can see the metaphor John would be making by calling Jesus the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; that became flesh. Jesus explains or reveals what God is like. So, he can suitably be called the &ldquo;Word of God&rdquo; (Rev. 19:13; John 1:14).</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 17, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:56:26', '<p>Egeneto here, is the same as the egeneto of v. 3. The all things that came through Jesus in v. 3, is further clarified here to be grace and truth. These &ldquo;came into being&rdquo; through Jesus. <strong>I do not think it is an accident that John uses the same words here of &ldquo;egeneto&rdquo; and &ldquo;through&rdquo;. The New Covenant, the New Creation came through Jesus. As the old covenenat came through Moses, the new came through Jesus Christ. He changes the verb from &ldquo;given&rdquo; in regards to Moses, to &ldquo;came&rdquo; through Jesus. This is a New Creation passage!</strong></p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 1, 38, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>This account details Jesus meeting Simon Peter and Andrew, not him calling them to be his disciples which occurs in Luke 5:4. If you notice here Jesus does not ever tell them to follow him, but he does in Luke 5:4. These are two separate, non-contradicting accounts and this account occurs first.</p> <p>This is where they first meet and discover this Rabbi from Nazareth.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 2, 1, 1, null, 99, '2021-10-05 02:16:31', '<p>the apparently trivial miracle of turning water into wine, is really about the resurrection. Common water is placed into stone waterpots (&ldquo;buried in the earth&rdquo;), where Jesus miraculously changes it, and when it is &ldquo;raised out of the earth,&rdquo; Jesus turns it into something far superior: an excellent wine (John 2:6-10).</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 3, 13, 2, null, 99, '2022-11-30 23:43:26', '<p><strong>our commentary is good!!</strong></p> <p><strong>--------------------------------------------------------------------</strong></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">John 14:6 is big for this concept. No one can get to the father except through the son. Also that Jesus was the firstborn among the new creation. It seems that Jesus truly was the first one to enter into the presence of god. Not Enoch or Elijah.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">If Enoch or Elijah could immediately go into Gods presence then they really did not need Jesus to put their sins to death. Good point.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">So when it comes to interpreting john 3:13-15 at first we notice a problem -</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">No one</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26124a" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">a</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">has ascended</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26124b" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">b</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">into heaven except the one who descended from heaven&mdash;the Son of Man.</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26124c" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">c</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:700"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">14</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Just as</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26125d" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">d</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Moses</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:italic"><span style="text-decoration:none">lifted up the serpent</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26125e" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">e</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:italic"><span style="text-decoration:none">in</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:italic"><span style="text-decoration:none">the wilderness</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">,</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26125f" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">f</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">so must the Son of Man be lifted up,</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26125g" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">g</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:700"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">15</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">so that everyone who believes in him may have eternal life.&rdquo;</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26126h" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">h</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Well, I thought Enoch and Elijah (it explicitly says elijah did, Enoch is not so explicit) ascended into heaven? Some explain this by saying well he didn&rsquo;t really mean to ascend to heaven but to be the first one to descend from heaven and then ascend to heaven. However, this isn&rsquo;t the argument that the text is trying to make. The text is arguing that nobody has ascended to heaven. The text is not arguing, no one has ever descended and ascended into heaven.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Others might contend that Jesus is the first immortal man to ascend into heaven, which is true, but that is not what the text is referencing. If John wanted to say this why would he talk about ascending and descending from heaven. Just say that he is the firstborn from the dead (Col. 1), and raised immortal (1 Cor. 15). This condition of being the first &ldquo;immortal&rdquo; man to ascend into heaven is simply not in the verse.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Notice also that the text before verse 13 when Jesus is speaking says WE speak of what we have seen. Not I speak of what I have seen. So this spiritual truth is something recognized by his apostles as well(at least I think he is with his apostles, would need to check context). So Jesus does not seem to be saying I have seen heaven but that we have seen heaven. In other words when you have the spirit you see heaven.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">So what do we make of this? Well, first we must realize, since this cannot be taken literally, there must be something more that we are not grasping.</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">The Key to interpreting john 3:13 is Romans 10:5-9 -&rdquo; For Moses writes that the man who practices the righteousness which is based on law shall live by that righteousness. 6 But the righteousness based on faith speaks as follows: &ldquo;Do not say in your heart, &lsquo;Who will ascend into heaven?&rsquo; (that is, to bring Christ down), 7 or &lsquo;Who will descend into the abyss?&rsquo; (that is, to bring Christ up from the dead).&rdquo; 8 But what does it say? &ldquo;The word is near you, in your mouth and in your heart&rdquo;&mdash;that is, the word of faith which we are preaching, 9 that if you confess with your mouth Jesus as Lord, and believe in your heart that God raised Him from the dead, you will be saved;&rdquo;</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Also, Romans 10:6 uses the same verb as John 3:13,</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">αναβαινω. Therefore this is definitely not a stretch in interpretation.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">So in other words, Paul gives us an insight into what it means to ascend to heaven, and to descend into the abyss. Evidently when this language is used, it is all relative to earth. So, ascending into heaven is not a literal ascending to a higher place, but a bringing of heaven to earth, or as we see in Romans 10:6 - bringing christ down. And descending into the abyss is not a literal going down, but to bring something below (in this case, Christ) to us, to where we are. So these figures of speech are all relative to earth. To ascend to heaven is to bring heaven to earth. In other words to be heavenly, is to ascend to heaven.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">We see this use also in Jam. 1:17 - every good and perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights. These gifts are not literally coming down to earth from above, but are simply &ldquo;heavenly&rdquo; gifts, e.g. they come from above. The word used here is</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">καταβαῖνον which is the opposite of</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">αναβαινω.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">It seems that this word</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">αναβαινω and</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">καταβαῖνω</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">can be used in a metaphorical way, because all of these verses not speaking of a literal ascension or descension use these terms.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">This phrase in Rom. 10 actually gives us more insight as well into the meaning of John 3:13. In this passage in Romans, Paul is equating &ldquo;heaven&rdquo; with Christ. Christ brings heaven along with him. Therefore, we have at least one example where Christ is explicitly called heavenly. Let us take this knowledge of &ldquo;things coming down&rdquo; being heavenly to make sense of John 3:13.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">So when we come to John 3:13- this is how the text should be read, when taking into consideration James 1:17 and Romans 10:6-7. &ldquo;</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">No one</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26124a" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">a</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">has ascended</span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">[</span></span></span></span></span></span><a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=John+3%3A13-15&amp;version=NET#fen-NET-26124b" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#b34b2c"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">b</span></span></span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-size:7.5pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">]</span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">into heaven (been heavenly) except the one who descended from heaven (was heavenly)&mdash;the Son of Man.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">This makes perfect sense solving not only the problems with Elijah and Enoch, but also with the meaning of the text. The text is not arguing that no one has ascended AND descended from heaven, as some like to try to see, but the text is arguing that no one has ascended into heaven, that&rsquo;s it. But what does it mean to ascend to heaven? It means to be heavenly. Which Jesus surely was! No one has been heavenly on earth, except Jesus! He is the only one. This reading also fits the context well. Just two verses later, it says that if we believe in him we have &ldquo;eternal life&rdquo;. That is certainly a heavenly concept, and the ultimate good gift (James 1:17). Jesus is the only one who has ever been heavenly or divine here on earth, who has eternal life. No other man could make this claim.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Luke 24:51 ἀναφέρω &ldquo;to take up&rdquo; or &ldquo;to carry up&rdquo; and Acts 1:9 ἐπαίρω to raise up, the only two verses which refer to Jesus&rsquo; literal ascension into heaven actually don&rsquo;t use the term &lsquo;ascend&rsquo; but rather taken up into heaven. Both of these are in the passive tense meaning that God is the one performing the action.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Also Hebrews 11:5 uses the term &lsquo;taken up&rsquo; to refer to Enoch&rsquo;s ascension into heaven. μετατίθημι</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38"><span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Verdana"><span style="color:#000000"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">John 3:13 uses the term αναβαινω. ἀναβέβηκεν is in the active which would be strange if it was referring to the ascension of Jesus. So, not only is it a completely different word than any of the words used to describe the ascension but it is in a different tense. It is likely that this is not referring to a literal going into and coming down from heaven.</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>');
