(41, 1, 43, 4, 18, 1, null, 99, '2021-10-09 20:16:12', '<p>See note on 1 Cor. 6:16.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 5, 18, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:57:26', '<p>FROM ANGELFIRE -</p> <p>In context, this could be taken two different ways:</p> <p>1. The Jews correctly understood that Jesus was making himself equal with God by calling God his own Father and it was for this reason that the Jews wanted to kill him.<br /> <br /> 2. The Jews incorrectly understood that Jesus was making himself equal with God by calling God his own Father. The Jews simply thought Jesus was making himself equal with God but they were wrong. Indeed, Jesus later says, &quot;the Father is greater than I.&quot; Greater is not equal to. Moreover, to claim the Jews were correct, one must regard both of the reasons they wanted to kill him: (1) breaking the Sabbath, and (2) making himself equal with God. One must also consistently suppose that Jesus also broke the Sabbath.</p> <p>Indeed, Jesus later says, &quot;the Father is greater than I.&quot; Greater is not equal to. Moreover, to claim the Jews were correct, one must regard both of the reasons they wanted to kill him: (1) breaking the Sabbath, and (2) making himself equal with God. One must also consistently suppose that Jesus also broke the Sabbath.</p> <p>But Jesus was a Jew born under the Law and a man who did not commit sin. To break the Sabbath was to sin by breaking his God&#39;s Law. Can we conclude that the Jews were correct to understand that Jesus broke the Sabbath? How then can we conclude they were correct to understand Jesus was making himself equal with God?</p> <p>The Jews were insisting Jesus had broke the Sabbath by healing a man on the Sabbath. But carefully regard the following passages:</p> <p>The man went away, and told the Jews that it was Jesus who had healed him. For this reason the Jews were persecuting Jesus, because he was doing these things on the Sabbath. John 5:15-16.<br /> <br /> And he was teaching in one of the synagogues on the Sabbath. And there was a woman who for eighteen years had had a sickness caused by a spirit and she was bent double, and could not straighten up at all. When Jesus saw her, he called her over and said to her, &quot;Woman, you are freed from your sickness.&quot; And he laid his hands on her; and immediately she was made erect again and began glorifying God. But the synagogue official, indignant because Jesus had healed on the Sabbath, began saying to the crowd in response, &quot;There are six days in which work should be done; so come during them and get healed, and not on the Sabbath day.&quot; But the Lord answered him and said, &quot;You hypocrites, does not each of you on the Sabbath untie his ox or his donkey from the stall and lead him away to water him? And this woman, a daughter of Abraham as she is, whom Satan has bound for eighteen long years, should she not have been released from this bondage on the Sabbath day?&quot; Luke 13:10-16.<br /> <br /> Departing from there, he went into their synagogue. And a man was there whose hand was withered. And they questioned Jesus, asking, &quot;Is it lawful to heal on the Sabbath?&quot; so that they might accuse Him. And he said to them, &quot;What man is there among you who has a sheep, and if it falls into a pit on the Sabbath, will he not take hold of it and lift it out? How much more valuable then is a man than a sheep! So then, it IS lawful to do good on the Sabbath. Then he said to the man, &quot;Stretch out your hand!&quot; He stretched it out, and it was restored to normal, like the other. But the Pharisees went out and conspired against him, as to how they might destroy Him. Matthew 12:9-14.</p> <p>Jesus did not break the Sabbath in John chapter 5. According to Jesus, it was not unlawful to heal a man on the Sabbath and he teaches the Jews that they are wrong about their notions of unlawful healing on the Sabbath. However, even though Jesus did not break the Sabbath they accused him of breaking the Sabbath. The Jews obviously did not agree with Jesus about this matter and sought to destroy him for healing on the Sabbath.</p> <p>Interestingly, Jesus later in John chapter 7 actually comments on the healing incident in John chapter 5:</p> <p>Jesus answered them, &quot;I did one deed, and you all marvel. For this reason Moses has given you circumcision (not because it is from Moses, but from the fathers), and on the Sabbath you circumcise a man. If a man receives circumcision on the Sabbath so that the Law of Moses will not be broken, are you angry with me because I made an entire man well on the Sabbath? Do not judge according to appearance, but judge with righteous judgment.&quot; See Notes below.</p> <p>It is quite clear that the Jews were wrongly accusing Jesus and he did not break the Sabbath.</p> <p>For this reason therefore the Jews were seeking all the more to kill Him, because he not only was breaking the Sabbath, but also was calling God His own Father, making Himself equal with God.</p> <p>In verse 16, we read the Jews were persecuting Jesus for healing a man on the Sabbath. In verse 18, we read that they wanted to kill Jesus for two reason and one of them was breaking the Sabbath. However, the overwhelming weight of the evidence demonstrates that Jesus did not actually break the Sabbath. The Jews were wrongly accusing him. We must then entertain the likelihood they were wrongly accusing him of making himself equal with God.</p> <p>One must make yet another observation. While Jesus WAS NOT breaking the Sabbath, Jesus WAS calling God his own Father. And this the detail which makes this statement confusing to readers. One might be tempted to conclude at this point that the Jews mistakenly accused Jesus of breaking the Sabbath but they were not mistaken about calling God his own Father because Jesus did in fact do so. However, if we are to compare the two reasons the Jews wanted to kill Jesus, the most obvious contrast to make is not:</p> <p>1. Breaking the Sabbath<br /> 2. Calling God his own Father</p> <p>The most obvious contrast to make is:</p> <p>1. Breaking the Sabbath<br /> 2. Calling God his own Father making himself equal with God</p> <p>We cannot conclude that John informs us the Jews were angry simply because he called God his own Father but because they thought that calling God his own Father meant he made himself equal with their God. Notice how Jesus clarifies this for them and explains why they are mistaken:</p> <p>Therefore Jesus answered and said to them, &quot;Truly, truly, I say to you, the Son can do nothing of himself, unless it is something he sees the Father doing; for whatever the Father does, these things the Son also likewise does. For the Father loves the Son, and shows him all things that He Himself is doing; and the Father will show Him greater works than these, so that you will marvel... He who does not honor the Son does not honor the Father who sent him... I have come in the name of my Father, and you do not receive me; if another comes in his own name, you will receive him. How can you believe, when you receive glory from one another and you do not seek the glory that is from the only God?</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 5, 23, 2, null, 99, '2022-07-31 05:09:19', '<p><br /> <span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">John 5:23 - the context is judgement. So honor Jesus just as you honor the father. Jesus will be our judge so we have to honor him as we currently honor the father. Not a worship context!!</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 5, 25, 4, null, 99, '2022-01-06 21:57:32', '<p>&ldquo;Truly, truly, I say to you, an hour is coming and now is, when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God, and those who hear will live.&rdquo;</p> <p>The first resurrection was happening even during Jesus&rsquo; ministry, as the time &ldquo;now is.&rdquo; Obviously, this can&rsquo;t be a physical resurrection, so He must be referring to people becoming spiritually alive.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 5, 44, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-01 16:00:22', '<p>&ldquo;<strong>the glory that <em>comes</em> from the only God?</strong>&rdquo; This verse provides great support for Biblical Unitarianism, as it, along with John 17:3, are two places where Jesus himself calls the Father, the only God. Jesus never once from his own lips claims to be God, but multiple times he claims that God the Father is the only God.</p> <p>A few translations such as the KJV, translate this phrase in John 5:44, &ldquo;seek not the honour that <em>cometh</em> from God only?&rdquo; Perhaps to get around Jesus calling the Father the only God, but that is not the correct way to translate the Greek. Translating like this makes &ldquo;only&rdquo; modify &ldquo;<em>cometh</em>&rdquo; or &ldquo;comes&rdquo; which does not actually exist in the Greek text. To put it more clearly, this is how they are really translating the text, &ldquo;seek not the honour that <em>cometh</em> only from God?&rdquo; However, this is not accurate. The adjective &ldquo;only&rdquo; τοῦ μόνου (#3441 monos) modifies God. This is clearly seen because they are both in the genitive case and &ldquo;only&rdquo; is placed right before &ldquo;God&rdquo; in the sentence. &ldquo;Only&rdquo; is not an adverb modifying &ldquo;comes&rdquo; and should not be translated as it is in the KJV. It is an adjective modifying God (i.e. the only God).</p> <p>Thus, John 5:44 provides great evidence that Jesus did not consider himself to be God, but that the Father is the only true God.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 6, 35, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-21 05:49:34', '<p>Clearly not literal!! See John 6:50</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 6, 38, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-04 20:28:58', '<p>See John 6:50, people take the came down from heaven part literally, but the eating of him figuratively&hellip;.</p> <p>John 8:23!! You are from beneath, I am from above</p> <p>Matt. 21:25</p> <p><br /> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Also, the verse, &ldquo;As you sent me into the world I have sent them into the world.&rdquo; (John 17:28) The apostles didn&rsquo;t come down literally from heaven.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 6, 42, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-04 20:29:18', '<p>Jam. 1:17, Matt. 21:25, and John 6:50</p> <p>John 8:23!!!</p> <p><br /> <span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Also, the verse, &ldquo;As you sent me into the world I have sent them into the world.&rdquo; (John 17:28) The apostles didn&rsquo;t come down literally from heaven.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Matt. 21:25 - where did John&rsquo;s baptism come from, heaven or from man? We understand the metaphor there. Nobody thinks that John baptized with water literally falling from heaven. Why don&rsquo;t we understand the metaphor when it refers to Jesus coming from heaven?</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 6, 46, 2, null, 99, '2022-02-21 06:14:28', '<p>Some problems for the Trinitarian:</p> <p>What about the Holy Spirit (the Third member of the Trinity)?</p> <p>What about the angels? If God can be seen, surely those who surround him have seen him?</p> <p>These two points suggest that he may not mean to literally see God. The difficult part is, if we take &ldquo;see&rdquo; to mean &ldquo;know&rdquo;, what does it mean that no one has known God? Known him intimately? Perhaps Jesus really has known him more intimately than any other member of creation? (John 5:20) The father shows him all he is doing.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 6, 50, 2, null, 99, '2022-02-21 05:47:29', '<p>He is not literally coming down out of heaven, and they are not to literal eat him. This is a clue for John 6:42 that he did not literally come down from heaven.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 8, 23, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-03 19:34:02', '<p>Huge verse for understanding all of the metaphorical statements Jesus makes about being &ldquo;from heaven&rdquo;</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 8, 56, 1, null, 99, '2022-10-24 19:59:30', '<p>Another aspect of what Jesus is saying would be (my paraphrase of John 8) &quot;Abraham saw and rejoiced...but here you are, what is your problem? You claim to be son&#39;s of Abraham but you can&#39;t recognize me as Messiah, nor rejoice!&quot;</p> <p>Hebrews 11 also alludes to this tradition. Speaking of Abraham&#39;s faith:</p> <p>All these people were still living by faith when they died. They did not receive the things promised; they only saw them and welcomed them from a distance (Heb. 11:13).</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 10, 30, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-02 02:05:54', '<p>See, John 17:21</p> <ul> <li aria-level="1" style="list-style-type:disc"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Are all christians the same being? No, we are separate beings, therefore this oneness must not be a oneness in being, but a oneness in unity and harmony.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li> </ul>'),
(41, 1, 43, 12, 32, 0, null, 99, '2022-05-13 02:19:39', '<p><strong>will draw all people to myself.</strong> This passage is notoriously difficult and has been used by Universalists to claim that all people, literally every single human that has ever been born, will be saved regardless of whether they believe in Christ in this life or not. They get this understanding primarily from passages such as this one and passages like 1 Corinthians 15:22, which use the word &ldquo;all&rdquo; to describe the group of people who will be saved.</p> <p>However, as we have looked at in our commentary on John 21:17 and our commentary on 1 Cor. 15:22, oftentimes &ldquo;all&rdquo; does not mean &ldquo;all&rdquo; in an unlimited sense but in a limited sense, often limited by context or common sense. Also, if we take &ldquo;all&rdquo; to mean all in an unlimited sense, that seems to contradict many passages of scripture which teach that many people will experience the second death, eternal destruction (Rev. 21:8; Matt. 10:28; 25:46; Mark 9:43).</p> <p>So, if John 12:32 is not saying that Jesus will draw every single human to himself, what is it saying?</p> <p>Context is very helpful here. John 12:20, which begins this section, specifically mentions that Greeks have come up to Jesus to talk with him. Some scholars propose that &ldquo;Greeks&rdquo; in v. 20 means Jews who are not from Jerusalem, in other words Jews who are culturally Greek. Although this is certainly a possible way to understand the word, we feel that these people mentioned in verse 20 are in fact Gentiles, not Jews. There are two reasons for this. First, if John wanted to communicate that these people were actually Jews, but Jews from other places, he could have called them Diaspora Jews, or used the word &ldquo;dispersion&rdquo; as he did in John 7:35. Secondly, John 12:19 suggests that there were certainly Gentiles present in the crowd following Jesus. This verse which is directly before verse 20 says, &ldquo;Therefore the Pharisees said among themselves, &lsquo;You see that you are not accomplishing anything! Look! The world has gone after him.&rsquo;&rdquo; They say that the &ldquo;world&rdquo; has gone after Jesus. The &ldquo;world&rdquo; means all people, or all types of people, Jews and Gentiles alike and it is used that way throughout the gospel of John (John 1:29; 3:16; 14:17). The Pharisees are upset and almost mocking Jesus because even Gentiles were following him, the &ldquo;world&rdquo; was going after him. The Pharisees are seeing all of these Gentiles follow Christ and concluding with their hard hearts that this must not be the <em>Jewish</em> Messiah. It makes no sense why the Pharisees would be mocking Jesus if it was just other Jews from the Dispersion following him. This group who was seeking out Jesus (John 12:12; 12;20) was called &ldquo;the world&rdquo; and &ldquo;Greeks&rdquo;, thus Gentiles are almost certainly included in this group.</p> <p>Now that we have established that these &ldquo;Greeks&rdquo; who were seeking Jesus were likely Gentiles, let us see how this influences our understanding of John 12:32. In this passage, Jesus is dialoguing with this crowd (John 12:29) likely full of Jews and Gentiles (John 12:20-36). Now, most people in the culture who knew about the Jewish Messiah envisioned him as a political ruler who would reign forever (John 12:34), and particularly reign over the Jews. Yet, Jesus painted a different picture of himself as the Messiah throughout the New Testament and even here in John 12. In the immediate context Jesus repeatedly explained that <em>whoever</em> wants to, can have life in the age to come (John 12:25), that <em>anyone</em> could come to him, and that <em>anyone</em> can be honored by the Father (John 12:26). Anyone could be a part of his kingdom. This was revolutionary for these Greeks who were seeking out Jesus (John 12:20). This was a King, a Messiah whose kingdom was not just for Israel but also for these Greeks who were wanting to see and likely follow Jesus.</p> <p>Therefore, when we arrive at v. 32 which reads, &ldquo;I...will draw all people to myself&rdquo; we should not understand this &ldquo;all&rdquo; to mean every single person who has ever been born, but rather &ldquo;all&rdquo; as in &ldquo;anyone,&rdquo; Jew or Gentile. As D. A. Carson puts it, &ldquo;all&rdquo; means &lsquo;all people without distinction, Jews and Gentiles alike&rsquo;, not all individuals without exception (Carson, PNTC, p. 444). This idea of Jesus&rsquo; kingdom being for Jews and Gentiles is also brought about in John 10:16, &ldquo;And I have other sheep that are not of this fold. I must bring them also, and they will hear my voice. And there will be one flock with one shepherd,&rdquo; and John 11:51-52, &ldquo;(Now he did not say this on his own, but being high priest that year he prophesied that Jesus was going to die for the nation, and not for the nation only, but also to gather together into one the children of God who are scattered abroad).&rdquo; Jesus&rsquo; death and resurrection, his kingdom promises, are not just for the Jews but for <em>anyone</em> who is willing to come to him. This is a prominent theme in John&rsquo;s gospel and is on full display here in John 12:32.</p> <p>In the end, this is a beautiful passage in which Jesus shows his heart for all peoples from every nation, both Jew and Gentile to be saved. He longs for anyone who would be willing to turn from their ways and find forgiveness in Him to do so regardless of what nation or ethnicity (Acts 28:28; Gal. 3:14; 28; Rom. 1:16; Col. 3:11). Therefore, John 12:32 teaches us that salvation is not just for one ethnicity, not just for the Jews, but for &ldquo;all&rdquo; people.</p> <p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 16, 11, 5, null, 99, '2022-02-07 02:49:20', '<p>The devil has been judged!</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 16, 13, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-07 02:51:16', '<p>It will guide THEM into truth, not all people into truth. Also, this could be for scripture as well, The Spirit will guide their scripture writing into truth!</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 16, 28, 0, null, 99, '2022-06-06 20:04:58', '<p><strong>&ldquo;going to the Father.&rdquo;</strong> Interestingly, all of the occurrences in scripture which speak of Jesus going to the Father after his resurrection never speak of Jesus as &ldquo;returning&rdquo; to the Father, as if he had already been there, but instead they refer to Jesus as going to the Father (John 13:1, 3; 14:12, 28; 16:10, 17, 28; 17:13; 20:17). This provides more evidence that Jesus was not pre-existent.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 16, 30, 2, null, 99, '2022-05-17 20:41:03', '<p><strong>&ldquo;Now we know that you know all things, and do not need anyone to question you.&rdquo;</strong> This statement by the disciples is quite interesting and when taken by itself seems to suggest that Jesus is all-knowing. However, as we have shown in our commentary on John 21:17 the phrase &ldquo;knowing all things&rdquo; can and is most often used not to describe someone as omniscient, but &ldquo;all things&rdquo; in a specific context. Also in our commentary on John 21:17 we established that Jesus is not omniscient, he does not know literally every piece of knowledge in the universe (Mark 13:31). So, what are the disciples saying? And why do they follow up this statement with, &ldquo;(you) do not need anyone to question you?&rdquo;</p> <p>Context brings much clarity here. This whole section is part of Jesus&rsquo; teaching at the Last Supper with his disciples. In this section, Jesus has been teaching on his death, resurrection and ascension to the Father, but the beginning of his teaching has been in more veiled terms (John 16:16-18). Then Jesus mysteriously knows exactly what the disciples are questioning (John 16:19) and goes on to tell them more about his ascension using some metaphors (John 16:20-24) and then finally he tells them more plainly (John 16:25-29). This is what leads up to the disciples response here in John 16:30.</p> <p>Now, the confusing thing about the disciples statement, &ldquo;Now we know that you know all things,&rdquo; is that Jesus does not seem to be saying anything vastly profound. Immediately prior Jesus just says that he &ldquo;came from the Father&rdquo; and will &ldquo;go to the Father.&rdquo; In other words, Jesus is predicting his death, resurrection, and ascension. Yet, he predicts his own ascension multiple times before this in the gospel of John (John 13:1; 14:12), so what about Jesus&rsquo; statement here makes the disciples feel compelled to say that Jesus knows &ldquo;all things?&rdquo;</p> <p>Interestingly, the disciples may not be replying specifically to what Jesus says in verse 28, but to what he says all the way back in verse 19. Here, in verse 30, is the first time the disciples get to respond to Jesus&rsquo; teaching. Jesus is speaking from John 16:19-28, and now the disciples get a chance to respond. However, it is what is in their response that suggests that they are responding to Jesus&rsquo; unique knowledge in verse 19.</p> <p>The disciples say, &ldquo;(you) do not need anyone to question you,&rdquo; yet, where is the idea of people questioning Jesus found? In verse 19, we read, &ldquo;Jesus knew that they were wanting to ask him.&rdquo; The disciples were wanting to ask Jesus about his phrase &ldquo;a little while&rdquo; and Jesus knew this. However, he knew this without them directly asking him. This is what makes the disciples say in verse 30 that Jesus &ldquo;knows all things,&rdquo; namely, because Jesus knew what they were talking about without them disclosing that information, Jesus had special knowledge. This also makes sense of why the disciples go on to say in verse 30 that Jesus does not need anyone to question him. In other words, they did not need to question him or to ask him questions (John 16:30) because he already knew what they were going to ask him (John 16:18-19).</p> <p>On the other hand, how would Jesus being omniscient mean that he does not need people to question him? Or how would Jesus knowing that he will go to the Father mean that he does not need people to question him? Both of these understandings fail to properly account for the disciples&rsquo; statement in John 16:30b.</p> <p>The statement by the disciples that Jesus &ldquo;knows all things&rdquo; is not about Jesus&rsquo; omniscience, nor about his knowledge of his death, resurrection, and ascension, but is instead about Jesus&rsquo; knowledge of the disciple&rsquo;s question, before they even asked it (John 16:19). This makes sense of the disciples statement in John 16:30 that Jesus does not need anyone to question him.</p> <p>Thus, Jesus &ldquo;knowing all things&rdquo; means that he knew something they did not expect him to know, that he had <em>access</em> to all knowledge, not that he literally knew all of the trillions of pieces of knowledge in the Universe. For example, if somebody secretly wrote a poem one night, and I walk up to them the next day and say, &lsquo;How is the poem going?&rsquo; They would be shocked and might even say, &lsquo;How did you know that? You must know everything!&rsquo; This special knowledge of Jesus about the disciples, that he seemingly should not have had, prompted the disciples to say, &ldquo;Now, we know that you know all things.&rdquo;</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;This is why we believe that you came from God.&rdquo;</strong> The disciples come to this conclusion rather than concluding that Jesus is God. In other words, they did not make the proclamation, &ldquo;You know all things,&rdquo; with the intention of making Jesus equal with the Father, or making him God. Instead they see this act of Jesus as showing that he came from God, not that he was God.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 17, 5, 2, null, 99, '2022-06-30 21:34:34', '<p>John 17:22 is huge for understanding this verse. Whatever the &ldquo;glory&rdquo; was that Jesus had before the world was, is also given to us. So, if this was God-like glory, then we have God-like glory too. But this makes no sense so, the BU understanding makes more sense of what kind of glory it was.</p> <p>Also, 2 Tim. 1:9, we were given grace before the foundation of the ages, not literally, but in the mind of God.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 18, 1, 1, null, 99, '2022-09-15 19:12:14', '<p>Like the first Adam, the Gospel of John describes how Jesus wrestled with doing God&rsquo;s will in a garden (Gen. 3:1-6, John 18:1, 26). The first Adam failed, but Jesus, the second Adam, obeyed.</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 19, 30, 2, null, 99, '2022-09-15 19:17:19', '<p>The New Creation is finished!</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 20, 1, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>1. An angel rolls away the stone from the tomb before sunrise (Matthew 28:2-4). The guards are seized with fear and eventually flee.</p> <p>2. Women disciples visit the tomb and discover Christ missing (Matthew 28:1; Mark 16:1-4; Luke 24:1-3; John 20:1).</p> <p>3. Mary Magdalene leaves to tell Peter and John (John 20:1-2).</p> <p>4. Other women remain at the tomb; they see two angels who tell them of Christ&#39;s resurrection (Matthew 28:5-7; Mark 16:5-7; Luke 24:4-8).</p> <p>5. Peter and John run to the tomb and then leave (Luke 24:12; John 20:3-10).</p> <p>6. Christ&#39;s First Appearance: Mary Magdalene returns to the tomb; Christ appears to her (Mark 16:9-11; John 20:11-18).</p> <p>7. Christ&#39;s Second Appearance: Jesus appears to the other women (Mary, mother of James, Salome, and Joanna) (Matthew 28:8-10).</p> <p>8. At this time, the guards report the events to the religious leaders and are bribed to lie (Matthew 28:11-15).</p> <p>9. Christ&#39;s Third Appearance: Jesus privately appears to Peter (1 Corinthians 15:5).</p> <p>10. Christ&#39;s Fourth Appearance: Jesus appears to Cleopas and companion (Mark 16:12-13; Luke 24:13-32).</p> <p>11. Christ&#39;s Fifth Appearance: Jesus appears to 10 apostles, with Thomas missing, in the Upper Room (Luke 24:36-43).</p> <p>12. Christ&#39;s Sixth Appearance: Eight days after His appearance to the 10 apostles, Jesus appears to all 11 apostles, including Thomas (John 20:26-28).</p> <p>13. Christ&#39;s Seventh Appearance: Jesus appears to 7 disciples by the Sea of Galilee and performs the miracle of the fish (John 21:1-14).</p> <p>14. Christ&#39;s Eighth Appearance: Jesus appears to 500 on a mountain in Galilee (Matthew 28:16-20; Mark 16:15-18; 1 Corinthians 15:6).</p> <p>15. Christ&#39;s Ninth Appearance: Jesus appears to His half-brother James (1 Corinthians 15:7).</p> <p>16. Christ&#39;s Tenth Appearance: In Jerusalem, Jesus appears again to His disciples (Acts 1:3-8).</p> <p>17. Christ&#39;s Eleventh Appearance: Jesus ascends into Heaven while the disciples look on (Mark 16:19-20; Luke 24:50-53; Acts 1:9-12).</p>'),
(41, 1, 43, 20, 22, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>This is a super powerful passage which exemplifies Jesus as the creator of the New Creation, not the Old Creation of Genesis. Yet, the author uses very similar language as the old creation so that the reader would call to remembrance the old creation, but then changes it to show that he is the creator of the New Creation. John says that Jesus &ldquo;ἐνεφύσησεν&rdquo; breathed on the disciples, which is the exact same verb used in the creation account and breath of life given to Adam in Genesis 2:7.</p> <p>Yet, there are beautiful changes that Jesus makes to the old creation. In the new creation Jesus breathes the Holy Spirit &ldquo;πνεῦμα ἅγιον&rdquo;, yet in the old creation God breathes the breath/spirit of life &ldquo;πνοὴν ζωῆς&rdquo;. Secondly, Jesus is breathing on people who are already living beings, he is not breathing life into them, but rather breathing new life into them through the Holy Spirit. There is truly some remarkable wordplay that Jesus is doing here to show that the new creation is through him, not the old creation.</p> <p>I believe, along with Hall Harris&rsquo; <em>Commentary on the Gospel John</em>, that here, &ldquo;Jesus at this point breathed into the disciples the breath of eternal life. This was in the form of the Holy Spirit, who was to indwell them.&rdquo; I also agree with Harris that, &ldquo;This was the giving of life itself, which flowed out from within (cf. 7:38-39). The giving of power would occur later, on the Day of Pentecost.&rdquo; Although the Holy Spirit was given here to the apostles, securing eternal life, the power and gifts of the Spirit given in a unique way and poured out on all people, did not come until Pentecost (Acts 1:8; Luke 24:49).</p> <p>NOT MINE &ndash; When did the disciples receive the Holy Spirit? Matthew, Mark and Luke are silent. But Acts 2 places it 50 days later (and most Christians believe Luke wrote Acts). John 20:22 has Jesus visiting 10 disciples (minus Thomas and the fallen Judas) and bestowing on them (&ldquo;receive&rdquo;) the Holy Spirit. Acts 2 is a completely different public event, with tongues of fire and speaking in tongues. There is no contradiction present. It&rsquo;s &ldquo;apples and oranges&rdquo; and an apple doesn&rsquo;t &ldquo;contradict&rdquo; an orange. Here they (disciples and any others, too) are described as being &ldquo;filled with the Holy Spirit&rdquo; (2:4). Christians can receive a greater &ldquo;measure&rdquo; or manifestation of the indwelling Holy Spirit as time goes on, according to biblical theology.</p>'),
