(41, 1, 43, 20, 28, 2, null, 99, '2022-11-02 21:22:13', '<ul> <li><strong>I think something is going on here with ο κυριος instead of κυριε which is in every other direct address of Jesus in the NT...</strong></li> <li>We need to Change Translation, Add ! at the end and capitalize G.</li> <li>On the day of his resurrection, in words that John recorded only 11 verses prior to Thomas&rsquo;s &ldquo;my God&rdquo; statement, Jesus said to Mary Magdalene, &ldquo;Go to my brothers and say to them &lsquo;I am ascending to my Father and your Father, to my God and your God&rsquo;&rdquo; (John 20:17). Jesus has a God, who is the same God as the apostles&rsquo; God. Jesus&rsquo;s and Thomas&rsquo;s God is also known as the Father. Jesus said he is Thomas&rsquo;s brother, not Thomas&rsquo;s God.</li> </ul> <p>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>&ldquo;The papyri were seen, then, to be very much in step with the classical authors and the NT. Further, when a writer wanted to distinguish individuals&mdash;and there were scores of instances in which distinct individuals were in view&mdash;he or she invariably used a second article (TSKTS)&mdash;except, of course, when a proper name was involved.&rdquo; (Dan Wallace, Sharp Redivivus? A Reexamination of the Granville Sharp Rule) Since Lord and God are not proper names then we should think that distinct individuals are in view. (Johnny) Wallace does not see God as a proper name (Dan Wallace, Sharp Redivivus? A Reexamination of the Granville Sharp Rule, Α.ΘΕΌΣ AS A PROPER NAME) , and lord certainly is not one.</p> <p>Examples:</p> <ul> <li>Mark 3:34 is very close in syntax to John 20:28 &ndash; &ldquo;Behold, my mother and my brothers!&rdquo;</li> </ul> <p>Now there are exceptions to this rule, see Psa. 34:23, but that this is the most common way this construction is used. Which, means, the most common way to understand this construction, especially if the Thomas understood God and Jesus to be two separate people already, which he did (), is that he is referring to two different people, My Lord (Jesus) and My God (The Father).</p> <p>&ldquo;Theodore of Mopsuestia argued that the words were not addressed directly to Jesus but were uttered in praise of God the Father.&rdquo; (Bart Ehrman, The Orthodox Corruption of Scripture, p. 266)</p> <p>Those who want to claim that &ldquo;Thomas called Jesus God&rdquo; should explain from Scripture why God has a God,</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;He who sees Me sees the One who sent Me.&rdquo; (John 12:45) and John 14:8-9 (NASB) Philip *said to Him, &ldquo;Lord, show us the Father, and it is enough for us.&rdquo; 9 Jesus *said to him, &ldquo;Have I been so long with you, and yet you have not come to know Me, Philip? He who has seen Me has seen the Father; how can you say, &lsquo;Show us the Father&rsquo;? (emphasis added) So when Thomas saw Jesus, he finally believed and also saw the Father. &ldquo;My Lord and My God!&rdquo; Two different people.</strong></p> <p>Jesus questions their failure to understand that to see him is to &ldquo;see&rdquo; the Father especially since he had been revealing the Father to them for so long.</p> <p><strong>Overall, the overwhelming usage of Lord in the gospel of John is in reference to Jesus, and God in reference to the Father, and there is no reason to change that here&hellip; He doesn&rsquo;t say you are my Lord and my God.</strong></p> <ul> <li>What did Thomas believe? That Jesus was equal with the Father and equally God? No. This is not what Jesus taught him (14:9-11). Thomas believed that Jesus really was the Christ and that the Father really worked through him (14:9-10). This is what Jesus taught him and this is what John says directly after Thomas&rsquo;s statement, that we should believe that Jesus is the Christ, not that Jesus is God (20:30-31).</li> </ul> <p>Summary &ndash; Just like Jesus said to Thomas earlier, &ldquo;<strong>Believe</strong> me that I am in the <strong>Father</strong> and the <strong>Father</strong> is in me&hellip;&rdquo; (John 14:11). Thomas finally did.</p> <p>If Thomas did not acknowledge the Father when he saw the resurrected Jesus, Thomas failed to listen to Jesus and failed to acknowledge or give credit to the God who raised Jesus from the dead.</p> <p>------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Essentially Thomas is exclaiming that Jesus Christ is Lord and God really worked through him. To believe in the Son, is to believe in the Father (John 12:44). Thomas doesn&rsquo;t just believe in the Son separate from the Father, but he believes in the Son who is intimately tied with his Father and his Father is seen through the Son (John 14:9-11).</p> <p>Trinitarianism claims that because Thomas saw the once dead, now resurrected, flesh-and-bone Jesus, &ldquo;Thomas called Jesus his God.&rdquo; Be honest with yourself. Put yourself in Thomas&rsquo;s place in first century Jerusalem. If you saw and touched the dead-but-now-resurrected-man Jesus, would you think that Jesus was God, or would you think that God (known as the Father) had raised Jesus from the dead?</p> <p>Some Ancient Near East and Greek religions believed in the death and resurrection of their god. Worshipers of Baal, for instance, claimed Baal was dead and came alive. But unlike pagans, biblical thinking Jews believed that the eternal God does not die, nor does he come back to life.</p> <p><strong><u>Apostles&rsquo; Reaction to the Resurrection of Jesus:</u></strong></p> <p><strong>&ldquo;God raised him from the dead!&rdquo;</strong></p> <p><strong>Not: &ldquo;He is God!&rdquo;</strong></p> <p>In all other places in the Bible where the apostles react to the resurrection of Jesus the Messiah from the dead, they do not react by declaring &ldquo;This proves Jesus is God&rdquo;. Rather, they react by declaring: &ldquo;God (the Father) raised the Lord Jesus from the dead&rdquo; (Acts 2:22-24, 2:36, 4:10, 5:30, 10:40, 13:30-37; Rom. 1:4, 10:9, Gal 1:1, 1 Pet. 1:21, etc.)</p> <p>&ldquo;Lord, show us the Father&rdquo;. We might wonder why Philip didn&rsquo;t ask Jesus to show the apostles &ldquo;God the Son&rdquo;?</p> <p>Jesus replied to Philip, Thomas still listening:</p> <p>&ldquo;Have I been with you so long, and you still do not know me, Philip? Whoever has <strong>seen me</strong> has <strong>seen the Father</strong>. How can you say, <u><strong>&#39;Show</strong> us the <strong>Father</strong>&rsquo;? Do you not believe that I am in the <strong>Father</strong> and the <strong>Father</strong> is in me?</u> The words that I say to you I do not speak on my own authority, but the <strong>Father who remains in me does HIS works</strong>. Believe me that I am in the <strong>Father</strong> and the <strong>Father</strong> is in me, or else believe on account of the works themselves&rdquo; (14:9-11).</p> <p>The father is seen in Jesus! So, when Thomas sees Jesus rise from the dead, and believes it, he also believes that the Father was at work in him. He believes in the Father as well! To believe in the Son, is to believe in the Father (John 12:44).</p> <p><strong><u>Thomas Finally Gets It, when you see Jesus, you see the Father</u></strong></p> <p>Some eight days after Jesus told Thomas and Philip that they would <strong>see the Father</strong> in him (eight days after Jesus was raised from the dead), Thomas <strong>saw</strong> and touched the once dead but now alive flesh-and-bone-human Jesus (Luke 24:39). Thomas finally knew (understood and believed) what Jesus was talking about. The life, death and resurrection of Jesus revealed the <strong>Father</strong>, the only God (John 17:3), the Giver of Life. Thomas saw (i.e., understood, knew) that the resurrection of Jesus was the work of <strong>God</strong> the <strong>Father</strong>, that the <strong>Father</strong> had given life to Jesus, that indeed the <strong>Father</strong> was in Jesus, the <strong>Father</strong> is known by the resurrected Jesus, the <strong>Father</strong> is declared in the resurrected Jesus, the <strong>Father</strong> is represented by the resurrected Jesus. Just like Jesus said, &ldquo;<strong>Believe</strong> me that I am in the <strong>Father</strong> and the <strong>Father</strong> is in me&hellip;&rdquo; (John 14:11). Thomas finally did.</p> <p><strong><u>Is Thomas talking about two different people?</u></strong></p> <p>ὁ κύριός μου καὶ ὁ θεός μου: &ldquo;My Lord and my God&rdquo;</p> <p>Notice how &ldquo;my&rdquo; is repeated, Thomas does not just say, &ldquo;My Lord and God&rdquo; but &ldquo;My Lord and my God.&rdquo; Should this double use of the pronoun and article affect our understanding of Thomas&rsquo;s statement?</p> <p>Gal. 1:4; 1 Thess. 1:3, 3:13: τοῦ θεοῦ καὶ πατρὸς ἡμῶν: &ldquo;Our God and Father&rdquo; clearly referring to one person, thus one pronoun.</p> <p>Tobit 13:4 &ndash; &ldquo;For he is our Lord and God,&rdquo; (only 1 pronoun in the Greek) and clearly referencing only God the Father.</p> <p>Ultimately, no, Thomas&rsquo;s use of two pronouns does not necessarily mean that he has two people in mind, but it also does</p> <p>------------------------</p> <p>REASONS THE TRINITARIAN INTERPRETATION DOESN&rsquo;T WORK</p> <p>On the day of his resurrection, in words that John recorded only 11 verses prior to Thomas&rsquo;s &ldquo;my God&rdquo; statement, Jesus said to Mary Magdalene, &ldquo;Go to my brothers and say to them &lsquo;I am ascending to my Father and your Father, to my God and your God&rsquo;&rdquo; (John 20:17). Jesus has a God, who is the same God as the apostles&rsquo; God. Jesus&rsquo;s and Thomas&rsquo;s God is also known as the Father. Jesus said he is Thomas&rsquo;s brother, not Thomas&rsquo;s God.</p> <p>Those who want to claim that &ldquo;Thomas called Jesus God&rdquo; should explain from Scripture why God has a God,</p> <p>Thomas did not say to Jesus &ldquo;YOU are my Lord and my God&rdquo;. Compare Nathaniel&rsquo;s words to Jesus when Nathaniel expressed that Jesus was both the King of Israel and the Son of God: &ldquo;Nathanael answered Him, &quot;Rabbi, you are the Son of God; you are the King of Israel&rdquo; (John 1:49).</p> <p>----------------------------</p> <ul> <li>The Father is &ldquo;the only true God&rdquo; (John 17:1, 3).</li> <li>Jesus&rsquo;s works are the Father&rsquo;s works. The works were done by the Father (10:32, 10:37, 14:10, cf. Acts 2:22).</li> <li>Jesus&rsquo;s words are the Father&rsquo;s words (8:48, 12:49-50, 14:10, cf. Deut. 18:18).</li> <li>Jesus&rsquo;s glory is from the Father (1:14, 8:54, 17:5).</li> <li>Jesus has declared or made known the Father (1:18, 14:10-11).</li> <li>If people knew Jesus, they would know the Father (8:19, 12:45, 14:7-11).</li> <li>Because Jesus spoke the Father&rsquo;s words, and because of the miraculous works Jesus did from the Father, people could &ldquo;know and understand that the Father is in me and I am in the Father&quot; (10:38, 12:49, 14:10).</li> </ul> <p>Again, there is never any indication of another divine person, a so-called &ldquo;God the Son incarnate&rdquo; at work or &ldquo;in&rdquo; Jesus. In the Gospel of John &ldquo;God the Son incarnate&rdquo; gets no credit for anything because he doesn&rsquo;t exist. The Gospel of John makes it crystal clear that the God who is at work in Jesus is the Father.</p> <p>Those who want to claim that &ldquo;Thomas called Jesus God&rdquo; should explain from Scripture why God has a God, because the &ldquo;deity of Christ&rdquo; interpretation means that &ldquo;God-Jesus&rdquo; has a God. Also, if Thomas is brother to &ldquo;God-Jesus&rdquo;, does this mean that Thomas is (a) God?</p> <p>&ldquo;Now Jesus did many other signs in the presence of the disciples, which are not written in this book; but these are written that you may believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God, and that believing you may have life in his name&rdquo; (John 20:30-31).</p> <p>John does <strong><u>not</u></strong> say that he recorded these signs so that we would believe that Jesus is God. Rather, John recorded the signs so that we might believe that Jesus is the &ldquo;Christ/Messiah, the Son of God&rdquo;. &ldquo;Christ/Messiah&rdquo; in the Bible is never a title for deity.</p> <p><strong><u>Lord and God, two different titles in the Gospel of John</u></strong></p> <p>The New Testament consistently uses the same titles that Thomas used to distinguish between <strong>God</strong> (the Father) and the <strong>Lord</strong> Jesus Christ. <strong>God</strong> is not the <strong>Lord</strong> Jesus Christ. The <strong>Lord</strong> Jesus Christ is not <strong>God</strong>. There are many, many biblical examples where the Lord Jesus Christ is differentiated from God. Here are a few:[3]</p> <ul> <li>&ldquo;that the <strong>God</strong> of our <strong>Lord</strong> Jesus Christ, the <strong>Father</strong> of glory, may give you a spirit of wisdom (Eph. 1:17).</li> <li>&ldquo;Grace to you and peace from <strong>God</strong> our Father and the <strong>Lord</strong> Jesus Christ&rdquo; (1 Cor. 1:3, cf. Ephesians 1:3, Rom. 15:6, 1 Pet. 1:3).</li> <li>&ldquo;Blessed be the <strong>God</strong> and Father <strong>of</strong> our <strong>Lord</strong> Jesus Christ, the <strong>Father</strong> of mercies&rdquo; (2 Cor. 1:3).</li> <li>&ldquo;Let all the house of Israel therefore know assuredly that <strong>God</strong> has made him both <strong>Lord</strong> and <strong>Christ</strong>, this Jesus whom you crucified&quot; (Acts 2:36)</li> </ul>'),
(41, 1, 43, 21, 17, 2, null, 99, '2022-05-16 17:25:25', '<p>There are quite a few reasons why Peter is not claiming that Jesus is omniscient here. First, we know that Jesus did not know &ldquo;all things&rdquo; because he grew in wisdom (Luke 2:52) and did not know the hour of his return (Mark 13:32). If Jesus does not know even one thing, which is true, then he is not omniscient. Secondly, this phrase &ldquo;all knowledge&rdquo; is used in scripture multiple times and often it does not carry the meaning of all knowledge in existence. For example:</p> <ul> <li> <p>Ephesians 6:21 reads, &ldquo;Tychicus, the beloved brother and faithful minister in the Lord, will make <strong>known to you all things</strong> so that you also will know the things about me and how I am doing&rdquo; (Eph. 6:21 REV).</p> <p>Is Tychicus really going to make known to them every single piece of knowledge in the entire universe? No, the &ldquo;all things&rdquo; are things about Tychicus&rsquo; situation.</p> </li> <li> <p>In 1 John 2:20, John says that these faithful Christians &ldquo;<strong>have all knowledge</strong>.&rdquo; Do we really believe that they know all things including the deepest understandings of subatomic reality? The passage goes on to say that the &ldquo;anointing&rdquo; (likely referring to the Holy Spirit) teaches them <strong>all things</strong>. Again, this is not &ldquo;all things&rdquo; such as calculus and biology.</p> </li> <li> <p>In John 14:26, Jesus says that the Spirit will &ldquo;teach you (the disciples) <strong>all things</strong>.&rdquo; Did the disciples become omniscient? No, clearly not.</p> <p>Therefore, we should understand &ldquo;all knowledge&rdquo; in a different way than, &ldquo;all knowledge&rdquo; in the universe when it is applied to people who we know are not omniscient.</p> </li> </ul> <p>Now that we have established what knowing &ldquo;all things&rdquo; does not mean, what does it mean? Why does Peter say it here?</p> <p>Well if we look at these examples above, what word captures the authors&rsquo; meanings well? It seems that in all of these examples, something like &ldquo;many&rdquo; is how we would literally capture it in english. Tychicus will make known &ldquo;many&rdquo; things to the Ephesians so that they will be informed about Paul&rsquo;s situation (Eph. 6:21), the faithful Christians do not have all knowledge but they have &ldquo;much&rdquo; knowledge (1 John 2:20), and the Spirit will teach the disciples &ldquo;many&rdquo; things, many truths about God, not every single truth in the universe.</p> <p>Here are even more examples of &ldquo;all&rdquo; really being closer in meaning to &ldquo;many&rdquo;:</p> <ul> <li>&ldquo;You (the disciples) will be hated by <strong>all</strong> for my name&rsquo;s sake&rdquo; (Matt. 10:22), Does Jesus mean literally every single person will hate them? No, he literally means &ldquo;most&rdquo; people, but &ldquo;all&rdquo; is an exaggeration for effect. There were some people who loved the disciples and followed them.</li> <li>&ldquo;<strong>Everyone</strong> is looking for you&rdquo; (Mark 1:37). Did Simon mean that every single person in the town was looking for Jesus without exception or just that &ldquo;many&rdquo; of people were looking for Jesus? Most likely the latter option was true.</li> </ul> <p>Therefore here, in John 21:17, since we know that the subject who knows &ldquo;all things&rdquo; is a person and not the one true God, and since we know that Jesus is not omniscient (Mark 13:32), then the likely meaning of Peter&rsquo;s words here is that Jesus knew &ldquo;many things.&rdquo; Peter&rsquo;s logic is that Jesus knows &ldquo;many things&rdquo; as the greatest prophet and God&rsquo;s son, so surely he should know something simple: that Peter is his friend.</p> <hr /> <p>More examples could be given but the point is clear. Both &ldquo;all&rdquo; and &ldquo;many/most/a lot&rdquo; are interchangeable at times. We do this in english as well. If 8 out of 10 people in a room are running around screaming and wrestling we could say something like, &ldquo;Everyone in here is crazy!&rdquo; Now, not every single person was, but &ldquo;many&rdquo; were. It seems that the &ldquo;all&rdquo; is used in a very similar way in Greek.</p> <p>By &ldquo;all things&rdquo; Peter likely meant something like our english &ldquo;many things&rdquo;. Now, before this sounds like reading into the text a different meaning, terms &ldquo;all&rdquo; (panta, ) and &ldquo;many&rdquo; () can sometime be interchanged in Koine Greek. In other words, &ldquo;all&rdquo; might really mean something closer to &ldquo;many/much/a lot&rdquo; in english, and vice versa.</p> <p>For example in Romans 5:18-19 Paul says, &ldquo;So then just as one transgression resulted in condemnation for all people...For just as through the one man&rsquo;s disobedience the many were made sinners.&rdquo; Paul makes it clear in verse 18, as well as in many other places of scripture, that all people are condemned, there is not a single person that escapes condemnation, yet, in verse 19 he says the &ldquo;many&rdquo; were made sinners. It seems that Paul is comfortable describing a group that contains &ldquo;all&rdquo; people with the term &ldquo;many&rdquo;.</p>'),
