(41, 1, 44, 13, 48, 3, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:40:11', '<p>&ldquo;and they believed, all of them were <em>at that time</em> appointed to life in the age to come&rdquo;</p> <p>There is a debate about the translation and meaning of Acts 13:48, and at issue in the verse is the way to understand the Greek pluperfect periphrastic participle which is the combination of the imperfect verb ἦσαν &ldquo;esan&rdquo; which is the imperfect form of the Greek verb eimi (#1510 εἰμί) and τεταγμένοι &ldquo;Tetagmenoi&rdquo; which is the perfect participle of the Greek verb tassō (#5021 τάσσω), translated &ldquo;were <em>at that time</em> appointed&rdquo; in the REV. The scholars are divided as to the correct translation and interpretation, a division that is usually based on their theology and the overarching way in which they approach the text.</p> <p>Tetagmenoi which has a large semantic range that includes &ldquo;to put in order, to arrange, to appoint, to ordain (in the sense of appoint to a position). A. T. Robertson writes about tetagmenoi, and says it is the &ldquo;paraphrastic past perfect indicative of tassō, a military term, &lsquo;to place in orderly arrangement.&rsquo; The word &lsquo;ordain&rsquo; is not the best translation here. &ldquo;Appointed,&rdquo; as Hackett shows, is better. The Jews here had voluntarily rejected the word of God. On the other side were those Gentiles who gladly accepted what the Jews had rejected, not all the Gentiles.&rdquo; (A. T. Robertson, Word Pictures in the New Testament, Vol. III, The Acts of the Apostles. Some punctuation and translation of the Latin added for clarity). Some scholars understand this word to best be translated as &ldquo;disposed&rdquo; (or inclined), for example &ldquo;as many as disposed themselves for eternal life, believed&rdquo;. However, disposed is outside of the normal semantic range of the word and is not listed as an interpretive option in the majority of well-respected Greek lexicons (BDAG, M-M, etc.).</p> <p>One point of contention on how to translate this verse occurs with whether to understand Tetagmenoi as middle (appointed themselves) or passive (were appointed) as both are possibilities in the Greek, therefore the decision comes down to context and word meaning. We feel that specifically with the word &ldquo;to appoint&rdquo;, it is less likely that someone appoints themselves and more likely that someone is appointed to something. Also, throughout the rest of the NT when Tasso is in the middle or passive it most often being used as a passive (Luke 7:8; Acts 22:10; Rom 13:1). Although many free-will scholars have used this middle voice to get around this seemingly Calvinistic passage, we believe that there is a better way to understand the phrase in the Greek, which still supports the free-will of humans.</p> <p>This better understanding comes about when we realize that the pluperfect periphrastic participle &ldquo;were appointed&rdquo; almost universally occurs at the same time as the main verb. To be more clear, the &ldquo;appointing&rdquo; happens at the same time as the &ldquo;believing&rdquo;, not millions of years before as the Calvinist would understand this verse. Many scholars see the &ldquo;appointing&rdquo; happening in eternity past, but the &ldquo;believing&rdquo; happening when Paul and Barnabas shared the word of the Lord. However, this is simply not the normal use of the pluperfect periphrastic construction. This construction gives the current background or state of the main verb. Let us look at some examples:</p> <ol> <li>Mark 6:52: οὐ γὰρ συνῆκαν ἐπὶ τοῖς ἄρτοις ἀλλʼ ἦν αὐτῶν ἡ καρδία πεπωρωμένη</li> </ol> <ul> <li>&ldquo;they did not believe, but their hearts were hardened&rdquo; describes the state of their hearts when they disbelieved. The point is not that their hearts were hardened before, and then later they disbelieved, rather, the point is that they disbelieved because their hearts were hardened in that moment.</li> </ul> <ol start="2" type="1"> <li> <p>Acts 9:33: εὗρεν δὲ ἐκεῖ ἄνθρωπόν τινα ὀνόματι Αἰνέαν ἐξ ἐτῶν ὀκτὼ κατακείμενον ἐπὶ</p> <p>κραβάττου ὃς ἦν παραλελυμένος</p> </li> </ol> <ul> <li>&ldquo;he found a man&rdquo; is the aorist verb describing the action, &ldquo;who was paralyzed&rdquo; was the state of that man during the action of the main verb, or when he found him.</li> </ul> <ol start="3" type="1"> <li> <p>Acts 4:31: καὶ δεηθέντων αὐτῶν ἐσαλεύθη ὁ τόπος ἐν ᾧ ἦσαν συνηγμένοι καὶ</p> <p>ἐπλήσθησαν ἅπαντες τοῦ ἁγίου πνεύματος καὶ ἐλάλουν τὸν λόγον τοῦ θεοῦ μετὰ</p> <p>παρρησίας</p> </li> </ol> <ul> <li>&ldquo;was shaken&rdquo; is the aorist verb describing the action, &ldquo;the place in which they were gathered&rdquo; is the periphrastic participle that describes the background/state during which the shaking occured. Their gathering occured during the action of the main verb, not before.</li> </ul> <ol start="4" type="1"> <li>Gal 4:3: οὕτως καὶ ἡμεῖς, ὅτε ἦμεν νήπιοι, ὑπὸ τὰ στοιχεῖα τοῦ κόσμου ἤμεθα δεδουλωμένοι</li> </ol> <ul> <li>&ldquo;when we were children&rdquo; is the action, &ldquo;were enslaved to the elementary principles&rdquo; is the pluperfect periphrastic participle describing their state during that action. It could easily be understood &ldquo;were <em>at that time</em> enslaved to the elementary principles.&rdquo;</li> </ul> <p>The normal use is of the pluperfect periphrastic to denote a state which existed in the past, with implication of a prior occurrence which produced it. (Fanning, Buist M. <em>Verbal Aspect in New Testament Greek</em>. Oxford Theological Monographs. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1990, 320.) Levinsohn agrees saying that these pluperfect periphrastics are usually &ldquo;portrayed as an ongoing state (which results from a completed event).&rdquo; (Levinsohn, Stephen H. &ldquo;Functions of Copula-Participle Combinations (&lsquo;Periphrastics&rsquo;).&rdquo; In The Greek Verb Revisited: A Fresh Approach for Biblical Exegesis. Edited by Steven E. Runge and Schristopher J. Fresch. Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press, 2016, 317.)</p> <p>This is exactly what we find in Acts 13:48. What is the prior instance that produced this past state? Their belief. They believed and then were appointed to eternal life. One might ask, &ldquo;What is the status of these believers?&rdquo; They are now appointed to life in the age to come, because of their belief. The pluperfect periphrastic participle is a specific construction that discusses the current state/background of an action, not a state before the action happened.</p> <p>Thankfully, in this case, we have help in the interpretation of this verse in the immediate context, which is Acts 13:46, the translation of which is quite clear. Paul was sharing about Jesus Christ in the synagogue in Antioch of Pisidia, and the Jews there rejected his message, but the Gentiles believed it. In response to that, Paul said to the Jews, &ldquo;you judge yourselves unworthy of life in the age to come.&rdquo; According to what Paul said, he understood that the Jews had a choice to believe or not believe in Christ, and they chose not to believe and thus he said they judged themselves unworthy of salvation. There is no indication that Paul thought that the Jews did not really have a choice in the matter but were simply following a course of behavior that had been preordained for them in eternity past. It is in that context, then, that the Gentiles are said to have chosen to believe and thus are then appointed to life in the age to come.</p> <p>The Bible has many verses that point to God giving people the choice to believe or not believe. Deuteronomy 30:19 says, &ldquo;Today I call heaven and earth to be witnesses against you, that I have set before you life and death, the blessing and the curse; therefore choose life so that you may live.&rdquo; At the end of his life, Joshua confronted the people of Israel and said, &ldquo;choose this day whom you will serve,&rdquo; either Yahweh or pagan gods (Josh. 24:15). Elijah challenged the people to choose the god they would serve: &ldquo;&ldquo;How long will you leap back and forth between the two sides? If Yahweh is God, follow him, but if Baal, then follow him&rdquo; (1 Kings 18:21). There are dozens of verses in the Bible like these, and Acts 13:46-48 is no different. The Jews chose to reject God, the Gentiles chose to accept Him and believe. God gave His only Son that whoever decided to believe in Him would have everlasting life (John 3:16)</p> <p>Therefore, in conclusion, there is no reason to understand this verse as teaching predestination. It is not concerned with that. The verse is concerned with the new status of believers who are appointed to life in the age to come because of their belief.</p>'),
(41, 1, 44, 16, 16, 3, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:40:57', '<p>So, they could tell the future?</p>'),
(41, 1, 44, 20, 28, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:41:04', '<p>Consider changing translation to &ldquo;church of God&rdquo;, just to stick with NA-28 and it doesn&rsquo;t support trinitarianism because of the below commentary.</p> <p>Add Commentary: This is a big verse used to support Trinitarianism and the last phrase is often translated &ldquo;his own blood&rdquo; in reference to the church of &ldquo;God&rdquo; earlier in the verse. Therefore, they read it as God&rsquo;s own blood, and since we all know this verse is referring to the sacrifice of Jesus, Jesus must be God.</p> <p>However, that translation is not accurate to the greek which is literally translated &ldquo;the blood of his own&rdquo;, and the REV rightly adds &ldquo;son&rdquo;. If Luke wanted to say &ldquo;his own blood&rdquo; he would have used the greek phrase &ldquo;αιματος αυτου&rdquo; or &ldquo;his blood&rdquo; (this verse is rendered this way only in the Latin translation of Irenaeus, 395 AD) this would be the most straightforward and common way to say that it was God&rsquo;s blood. However the construction that Luke uses is &ldquo;the blood of his own (son)&rdquo;, or αἵματος τοῦ ἰδίου (this is the reading in the vast majority of manuscripts of Acts 20:28). The word &ldquo;Son&rdquo; is properly supplied when asking the question: who is God&rsquo;s own who shed his blood to purchase the Church? Clearly the answer is Jesus throughout the entirety of the New Testament.</p>'),
(41, 1, 44, 24, 15, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:41:37', '<p>A resurrection, not multiple resurrections as premillennialists assert</p>'),
(41, 1, 44, 26, 28, 1, null, 99, '2021-11-14 21:55:32', '<p>here are some additional scriptures that use the word Christian(s). Means &ndash; little anointed ones,we are anointed! co-heirs with Christ! little kings below the big king</p> <p>Acts 26:28</p> <p>I Peter 4:16</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 1, 4, 0, null, 99, '2022-07-08 21:27:09', '<p><strong>&ldquo;who was appointed.&rdquo;</strong> There is great debate on this word &ldquo;appointed&rdquo; (#3724 ὁρισθέντος) and some translations use the word &ldquo;declared&rdquo; instead. However, the idea of this verb is to appoint, fix, set, or determine, not to declare something that already exists. In other words, this verb is used to describe a new position or boundary, not to declare a position that already exists, therefore, &ldquo;appointed&rdquo; is the proper translation.</p> <p>There is great similarity going on in this verse, Romans 1:4, with Acts 17:31. In Acts 17:31 we read, &ldquo;He will judge the inhabited world righteously by the man he has appointed, having given proof to all people by raising him out from among the dead.&rdquo; So, God appointed Jesus to be the judge, and he proved this appointment by raising Jesus from the dead. The same idea is being communicated here, even the same word for &ldquo;appointed&rdquo; is used. Here in Romans 1:4, Jesus is appointed as the Son-of-God-with-power which is a new position with new authority, and he proved this new appointment &ldquo;by his resurrection.&rdquo;</p> <p>Jesus was already the Son of God in some sense, he was already the Messiah and God&rsquo;s son (Luke 3:38). However, this verse teaches that there is a new sense in which Jesus becomes the exalted Son of God after his resurrection and given new power and dominion (Matt. 28:18). We also find this teaching in Acts 13:33, &ldquo;that God has fulfilled these promises to us&hellip; by raising up Jesus, just as it is written in the second Psalm, You are my Son; today, I have become your Father.&rdquo; Here, the scriptures are connecting Jesus being called the Son of God with his resurrection, not with his birth.</p> <p>Therefore, Romans 1:4 teaches that Jesus was appointed to a new position and given new power, and this was proved by his resurrection from the dead.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 2, 14, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-04 18:59:43', '<p>Perhaps v. 14 answers our questions, he says &quot;they are a law to themselves&quot; essentially the basis for which he will judge them is their own standard. So, if they would say lying is bad, yet they have lied, they have failed their own standard.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 3, 4, 0, 'I have commentary written', 99, '2022-09-19 14:28:49', '<p><strong>&ldquo;so that you will be declared righteous.&rdquo;</strong> The meaning of this verse, when quoting Psalm 51:4 from the LXX and applying it to his current argument, is hypothetical. In this context Paul is saying, if God were put on trial for his faithfulness and truthfulness (Rom. 3:3), he would be found righteous. In other words, God is always faithful and truthful, although we will never judge God literally.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 5, 14, 1, null, 99, '2021-10-05 20:15:25', '<p>Death reigned where adam was supposed to reign with life and peace. Adam was supposed to be a faithful king, but now death reigns instead.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 8, 28, 3, null, 99, '2022-02-07 02:40:40', '<p>God works all things for our good, not God plans all things for our good. This is a much different promise. He is alive and currently working things for our good.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 8, 29, 3, null, 99, '2023-01-05 21:09:38', '<p>Romans 8:28 is the key to understanding the chain of events, often called the &ldquo;ordo salutis&rdquo; in vv. 29-30, and reading this passage in context leads us to a surprisingly different conclusion to vv. 29-30 than we have been previously taught. Romans 8:28 assures the reader that in all things, God works (present tense) for the good of those who love him. Paul is making a statement about how God (PRESENTLY in the 1st Century) works things together for Christians. This is the context for verses 29 and 30. Yet, one might ask, how do we know that God will work things together for good for those who love him? This is the question I believe Paul answers in vv. 29-30. Paul explains, we know God will work things together for good for Christians BECAUSE he has done so for our forefathers, for Israel, for Old Testament saints. These verses are not referring to Christians of all ages, but to Old Testament saints, we must stop reading ourselves into the bible. The rest of this article will detail reasons why this is the case.</p> <p>Think about the logic of these verses (Rom. 8:28-30) from a typical Arminian or Calvinist perspective: &ldquo;We know that in all things, God works for the good of those who love him&hellip; because he has predestined you and will justify and glorify you.&rdquo; Yet, this logic does not follow. How does a future promise give us assurance that he is currently working for our good? However, in my view the logic is: &ldquo;We know that in all things, God works for the good of those who love him&hellip; because he has done this in the past, for our forefathers.&rdquo;</p> <p>I believe that verses 29-30 are not to be ripped out of context and used to explain the order of salvation, but rather are explaining v. 28. This is seen by the conjunction &ldquo;οτι&rdquo; which is likely an explanatory conjunction here. The two main possibilities for translating &ldquo;οτι&rdquo; are &ldquo;that&rdquo; or &ldquo;for/because&rdquo;, and &ldquo;that&rdquo; simply doesn&rsquo;t work here, introducing v. 29. Paul is answering the question how do we know that all things work together (present tense) for our good? Because (&ldquo;οτι&rdquo;), God has worked all things together for the good of our forefathers. This is what vv. 29-30 are talking about. Please do not skip over the &lsquo;for&rsquo; (in many translations) and take this verse out of context.</p> <p>&ldquo;<strong>Foreknew</strong>&rdquo;. How do we know that this word &ldquo;foreknew&rdquo; is being used to describe people in the past? First, its only other usage in Romans, which occurs in Romans 11:2, is clearly describing old testament saints, the 7,000 who have not bowed to Baal (Rom. 11:4). Yet, there is also another clue in the text that suggests that this passage Romans 8:29-30 is referring to past saints. Namely, that all of the verbs in this section are in the past tense. Those who were &ldquo;foreknown&rdquo; were &ldquo;predestined&rdquo;, and were &ldquo;called&rdquo; and were &ldquo;justified&rdquo; and were &ldquo;glorified&rdquo;. For some reason, modern scholars understand this verse to say that those who were &ldquo;foreknown&rdquo; and &ldquo;predestined&rdquo; (past tense), &ldquo;will be called&rdquo; and &ldquo;will be justified&rdquo; and &ldquo;will be glorified.&rdquo; Modern scholars understand the &ldquo;foreknowing&rdquo; and &ldquo;predestining&rdquo; to be in eternity past but then the calling, justification and glorification applies to the present or future. However, this understanding is highly unwarranted because all of the verbs are in the past tense. It is eisegesis to understand the calling, justifying, and glorifying to apply to Christians from all ages because these verbs occur in the past tense in vv. 29-30. The verbs occurred before Paul wrote Romans. These verbs occur BEFORE the 1st century.</p> <p>The word &ldquo;foreknew&rdquo; has two primary meanings, to &ldquo;know an event/person before they existed&rdquo; or &ldquo;know an event/person in the past&rdquo;. For some reason almost all interpreters understand this term to mean &ldquo;knew (them) before they existed&rdquo;. Yet, I do not think that this word necessarily carries this meaning.</p> <p>When studying all of the uses of this word in the New Testament there seem to be two clear meanings. The first usage is to know something before it occurs or beforehand. This is seen in 1 Pet. 1:20 in which God knows Jesus (or the Messiah) before the foundation of the world, and in 2 Pet. 3:17 in which believers know that people will twist the scriptures beforehand, or before it occurs, so that they would not be carried away into error.</p> <p>However the second kind of usage is seen clearly in Acts 26:5. Paul says that the Jews &ldquo;foreknew&rdquo; that Paul had lived his life as a Pharisee. Yet, it is not that the Jews somehow miraculously knew Paul before he was born and knew that he would grow up to be an educated Jew, but rather, the Jews knew that he had lived as a Pharisee because they witnessed it. However, this witnessing occurred in the past. That is likely why Paul uses &ldquo;foreknew&rdquo; here. So, this is another usage of &ldquo;foreknow&rdquo; , namely, to know something that occurred in the past. <strong>they did not know before he was a pharisee that he would live his life as a pharisee, so the action of &ldquo;knowing&rdquo; occured at the same time as the event, but the event occured before the time of Acts 26:5. They knew this event not before it happened but when it happened, in the past. So it seems that the words can be used to indicated knowing something before the current time (to the speaker), or knowing something before a certain time occured.</strong></p> <p>So, which usage is occurring in Romans 8:29? Here in vv. 29-30 is Paul saying that God knew beforehand certain people and then chose them before they existed? God knew them beforehand, but the question is before they were born, or before the time of Paul&rsquo;s writing of Romans 8? Since the likely referent of this term is Old Testament saints just as in Romans 11:2, this is likely saying that God knew Israel, he chose Israel, he called Israel, he justified Israel and he glorified Israel. And again this is not every single person in physical Israel, but the remnant (Rom. 11:2) who loves God (Rom. 8:28).</p> <p>Now, this &ldquo;knowing&rdquo; of Israel is not simply a knowing of the existence of Israel, because God knows all things and certainly would have known that Israel existed. Rather, this use of &ldquo;knowing&rdquo; refers to an intimate knowledge of Israel, a close relationship, and is even used in scripture in reference to sexual relations (Gen. 4:1). The term &ldquo;foreknew&rdquo; in Romans 8:29 tells us that God was close to Israel, he knew them deeply, it is in reference to those whom God previously knew, not that God &ldquo;knew&rdquo; certain people trillions of years before they were born and selected certain ones to be saved. In fact, the most clear way to translate this term might be to simply say, &ldquo;previously knew&rdquo;.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;conformed to the image of his Son&rdquo;</strong> Let us quickly address what it means to be &ldquo;conformed to the image of his Son, so that he might be the firstborn among many brothers&rdquo;. Well, what does it mean to be like Christ? What is Christ like now? He is in a glorified body, sinless, and enjoying communion with the Father. So, what does it mean to be conformed to his image? It means to be given a glorified body, sinless, and enjoying communion with the Father. Was this ever decided beforehand, or prophesied by God in the Old Testament? Sure! In Daniel 12:2 we have the promise of resurrection to life, in Psalm 49:15 David clarifies that the righteous will be redeemed from the grave and God will take them to himself, in Job 19:25-27 Job is sure that he will resurrect. These verses make it clear that God decided beforehand that Old Testament saints would be conformed to the image of Jesus. That they would be resurrected and live forever.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;glorified.&rdquo;</strong> Now, some will contest, &ldquo;Yes, it is possible that &lsquo;foreknew&rsquo; is referring to Old Testament saints, but what about &lsquo;glorified&rsquo; being used in the past tense?&rdquo; Were Old Testament saints glorified? That has to be referring to something future, right?</p> <p>Not exactly. There are numerous examples of &ldquo;glorified&rdquo; being used of Old Testament Israel - Isa. 43:4; 60:9; Ex. 28:2 (priestly garments brought glory); 34:29; 35 (Moses&rsquo; face was glorified after talking with God); Ps. 86:3; 90:15; Lam. 1:8 (Jerusalem had glory); Yet, the most clear example of glory under the old covenant is found in 2 Cor. 3:7-9. In this passage Paul explains that there was glory under the Old Covenant, but there will be more in the new (v. 10).</p> <p>All of the things spoken of in vv. 29-30 did in fact occur to Old Testament saints. God certainly knew Israel (Rom. 11:2-4; Ex. 33:12; 1 Cor. 8:3; 2 Tim. 2:19), decided beforehand that Israel should be conformed to the image of Jesus (This is seen in God&rsquo;s promise of Resurrection: Dan. 12:2; Psa. 49:15; Job 19:25-27), called Israel (Isa. 41:8-9; ), justified Israel (Rom. 4:3; 16; Gen. 15:6; Hab. 2:4), and glorified Israel (2 Cor. 3:7-9; Lam. 1:8; Isa. 43:4; 60:9).</p> <p><strong>Are Arminianism or Calvinism supported here?</strong></p> <p>The Arminian would say that God looked down the corridors of time and saw who would choose him, and then chose them. This does fit the order of the verse nicely in which foreknowledge comes before predestination, however, it leads to a big problem.</p> <p>Could delete this: &quot;First, the grounding objection. The grounding objection highlights that in this scenario something outside of God is the source for something that exists. If God foresees human actions and then bases his choice off of those actions, then really, it is humans that are giving God information. But wait, God created humans. So how could God be getting information from something that he created before he created it? It is an endless cycle of confusion.&quot;</p> <p>Secondly, in Arminian thought God foreknows every individual, so would not every individual be foreknown, predestined, and glorified? This is universalism. One would have to add something to the text that is simply not there to make sense of it. Something like, &ldquo;those whom he foreknew would choose him, he also predestined.&rdquo; This is dangerous eisegesis. It is also a useless statement and action on behalf of God. If all God did was look down the corridors of time, see who would choose him, and then choose them, he is not really choosing them. They are choosing for themselves.</p> <p>Now for the problems with the Calvinistic understanding of this ordo salutis. The most glaring problem is that the order is wrong. Almost all Calvinist scholars understand God&rsquo;s foreknowledge to be a sort of &ldquo;forelove&rdquo; which is fine, however, in v. 29 this occurs before God&rsquo;s act of predestination. In the Calvinist school of thought, God chose you when you had nothing to offer, he chooses some people in eternity past and then sets his love upon them. He gives grace to them because he chose them. However, this is not what we see at all in v. 29 where the &ldquo;forelove&rdquo;, or the love he has for certain individuals occurs before the &lsquo;choosing&rsquo; or &lsquo;predestination&rsquo;. It is also extremely important to notice that these individuals are not being predestined to heaven or hell, but to be conformed to the image of Jesus. This is vital to notice. So, even if this verse was supporting Calvinism up to that point, it says nowhere in the text that people are predestined to heaven or hell. So, the Calvinist doctrine of predestination remains unwarranted. Overall, this text certainly does not help the Calvinist.</p> <p>But what if in the Calvinist vs. Arminian debate of this verse, we are completely missing the mark? What if there is no good solution to this conundrum because we are looking at it all wrong? This passage is not an overview of the order of salvation, but rather a list of the &ldquo;good&rdquo; that God has worked together for Old Testament saints, and that he will continue to work for New Testament saints (v. 28).</p> <p><strong>Summary:</strong> What if Paul is not outlining the order of salvation, but rather encouraging his 1st century readers that God did all of these amazing things (knowing, calling, justifying, and glorifying) for their forefathers, so they can have confidence that God will work for their good as well.</p> <p>The reasons why this understanding is superior are numerous.</p> <p>1. The immediate context in verse 28, naturally leads to the question, &quot;How do we know that God works all things together for the good of Christians?&quot; Answer: Because he has done it all along (v. 29-30). This understanding fits better than: (v. 28) God works all things together for good, (v. 29-30) here is the order of salvation. This understanding does not mesh well.</p> <p>2. The explanatory conjunction ὅτι at the beginning of v. 29 is introducing an explanation of v. 28. Verses 29-30 are not to be read in isolation.</p> <p>3. The only other use of &quot;those whom he foreknew&quot; as a people group in Romans also refers to Old Testament saints (Romans 11:2).</p> <p>4. There is no reason to understand each verb occurs temporally one after the other (there are no textual clues; no words like &ldquo;then&rdquo; or &ldquo;after&rdquo; in this section, and they are all in the same tense)</p> <p>5. The traditional view disregards the past tense of the verbs &ldquo;called&rdquo;, &ldquo;justified&rdquo; and &ldquo;glorified&rdquo;, our view understands these past tense verbs to have occured in the past.</p> <p>6. The traditional view puts verbs that are used in the past tense &ldquo;justified&rdquo; and &ldquo;glorified&rdquo; into the distant future.</p> <p>7. Paul uses οὓς (who or whom) instead of &quot;us&quot; or &quot;we&quot;. We would expect something like: &quot;we were foreknown&quot; not &quot;those whom he foreknew&quot;. This is another piece of clear evidence that Paul has someone else in his mind besides his fellow Christians.</p> <p>The problems with the person who understands this verse to be explaining the order of salvation for New Testament Christians are numerous. They must:</p> <p>1. separate the verse from its immediate context in v. 28</p> <p>2. ignore the explanatory conjunction &ldquo;οτι&rdquo;</p> <p>3. disregard the clear parallel with Romans 11:2</p> <p>4. understand each verb to occur temporally one after the other (for which there are no textual clues; no words like &ldquo;then&rdquo; or &ldquo;after&rdquo; in this section)</p> <p>5. disregard the past tense of the verbs &ldquo;called&rdquo;, &ldquo;justified&rdquo; and &ldquo;glorified&rdquo;</p> <p>6. put verbs that are used in the past tense &ldquo;justified&rdquo; and &ldquo;glorified&rdquo; into the distant future</p> <p>7. understand predestination to be in reference to heaven or hell (disregarding that predestination is never once used to refer to an unbeliever or to hell).</p> <p>8. disregard the οὓς (who or whom) and undestand it to be referring to &quot;us&quot; or &quot;we&quot;, e.g. &quot;we who were foreknown&quot; is how most modern scholars interpret this.</p> <p>There is more that could be said of the follies of interpreting these verses as an ordo salutis, however, you get the point.</p> <p>There is a simpler, more contextual, and truthful interpretation of Romans 8:29-30. The Romans can have confidence that God will work all things together for the good of those who love him, because he has done so in the past. He has worked so many things for the good of Old Testament saints (Rom. 8:29-30), and will continue to do so for New Testament saints.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 8, 37, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:43:12', '<p>Tie this in with Revelation. This is what it means to be a conquerer, to keep the faith, even in the face of death.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 8, 38, 1, null, 99, '2021-11-19 04:57:12', '<p>The context of this verse is persecution. Paul is saying that nothing, no persecution, no being can separate us from the love and redemption we have in Jesus. This context is not talking about losing your salvation. The verse does not say, that you can&rsquo;t deny Christ, its saying nothing else around you can separate you from the promises in Christ.</p>'),
(41, 1, 45, 9, 6, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:46:02', '<p>Antanaclasis &ndash; Israel means 2 different things here.</p> <p>ALL THE BELOW FROM KEITH MATHISON</p> <p>One of the most common questions asked by students of the Bible concerns the relationship between Israel and the church. We read the Old Testament, and it is evident that most of it concerns the story of Israel. From Jacob to the exile, the people of God is Israel, and Israel is the people of God. Despite the constant sin of king and people leading to the judgment of exile, the prophets look beyond this judgment with hope to a time of restoration for Israel. When we turn to the New Testament, the same story continues, and Israel is still in the picture. Jesus is described as the one who will be given &quot;the throne of his father David&quot; and the one who &quot;will reign over the house of Jacob [Israel] forever&quot; (Luke 1:32&ndash;33). He is presented as the One the prophets foresaw.</p> <p>The first to believe that Jesus is the promised Messiah are Israelites&mdash; Andrew, Peter, James, John. But in the Gospels, we also hear Jesus speak of building His church, and we see growing hostility between the leaders of Israel and Jesus. We hear Jesus speak of destroying the tenants of the vineyard and giving it to others (Luke 20:9&ndash;18). In the book of Acts, the spread of the gospel to the Samaritans and Gentiles leads to even more conflict with the religious leaders of Israel. So, is Israel cast aside and replaced by this new entity known as the &quot;church&quot;?</p> <p>There are those who would say yes, but the answer is not that simple, for we also run across hints that God is not finished with the nation of Israel. At the end of His declaration of woes on the scribes and Pharisees, Jesus says, &quot;You will not see me again, until you say, &#39;Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord&#39;&quot; (Matt. 23:39). In the Olivet Discourse, He speaks of Jerusalem being trampled underfoot &quot;until the times of the Gentiles are fulfilled&quot; (Luke 21:24). In Acts, Peter says to a Jewish audience: &quot;Repent therefore, and turn back, that your sins may be blotted out, that times of refreshing may come from the presence of the Lord, and that he may send the Christ appointed for you, Jesus, whom heaven must receive until the time for restoring all the things about which God spoke by the mouth of his holy prophets long ago&quot; (Acts 3:19&mdash;21). Finally, Paul says things about Israel that seem to preclude total rejection. Speaking of Israel, he writes, &quot;I ask, then, has God rejected his people? By no means!&quot; (Rom. 11:1a).</p> <p>In order to understand the relationship between Israel and the church as described in the New Testament, we will need to look at the question in the context of the different answers Christians have given over the years. The traditional dispensationalist view maintains that God has not replaced Israel with the church but that God has two programs in history, one for the church and one for Israel. Traditional dispensationalism also maintains that the church consists only of believers saved between Pentecost and the rapture. The church as the body of Christ does not include Old Testament believers. Progressive dispensationalism has modified some of these views, but the traditional dispensationalist view remains very popular. Some covenant theologians have adopted a view that many dispensationalists describe as &quot;replacement theology.&quot; This is the idea that the church has completely replaced Israel. Jews may still be saved on an individual basis by coming to Christ, but the nation of Israel and the Jews as a people no longer have any part to play in redemptive history.</p> <p>A careful study of the New Testament reveals that both of these interpretations of the relationship between Israel and the church are wanting. The relationship between the people of God in the Old Testament and the people of God in the New Testament is better described in terms of an organic development rather than either separation or replacement. During most of the Old Testament era, there were essentially three groups of people: the Gentile nations, national Israel, and true Israel (the faithful remnant). Although the nation of Israel was often involved in idolatry, apostasy, and rebellion, God always kept for Himself a faithful remnant&mdash;those who trusted in Him and who would not bow the knee to Baal (1 Kings 19:18). This remnant, this true Israel, included men such as David, Joash, Isaiah, and Daniel, as well as women such as Sarah, Deborah, and Hannah. There were those who were circumcised in the flesh and a smaller number who had their hearts circumcised as well. So, even in the Old Testament, not all were Israel who were descended from Israel (Rom. 9:6).</p> <p>At the time of Jesus&#39; birth, the faithful remnant (true Israel) included believers such as Simeon and Anna (Luke 2:25&ndash;38). During Jesus&#39; adult ministry, true Israel was most visible in those Jewish disciples who believed that Jesus was the Messiah. Those who rejected Jesus were not true Israel, regardless of their race. This included many of the scribes and Pharisees. Though they were physically Jews, they were not true Israel (Rom. 2:28&ndash;29). True Israel became def ined by union with the true Israelite&mdash;Jesus Christ (Gal. 3:16, 29).</p> <p>On the day of Pentecost, the true Israel, Jewish believers in Jesus, was taken by the Holy Spirit and formed into the nucleus of the New Testament church (Acts 2). The Holy Spirit was poured out on the true Israel, and the same men and women who were part of this true Israel were now the true new covenant church. Soon after, Gentiles began to become a part of this small group.</p> <p>This is an extremely important point to grasp because it explains why there is so much confusion regarding the relationship between the church and Israel. The answer depends on whether we are talking about national Israel or true Israel. The church is distinct from national Israel, just as the true Israel in the Old Testament was distinct from national Israel even while being part of national Israel. The remnant group was part of the whole but could also be distinguished from the whole by its faith.</p> <p>However, if we are talking about true Israel, there really is no distinction. The true Israel of the Old Testament became the nucleus of the true church on the day of Pentecost. Here the analogy of the olive tree that Paul uses in Romans 11 is instructive. The tree represents the covenant people of God&mdash;Israel. Paul compares unbelieving Israel to branches that have been broken off from the olive tree (v. 17a). Believing Gentiles are compared to branches from a wild olive tree that have been grafted in to the cultivated olive tree (vv. 17b&ndash;19). The important point to notice is that God does not cut the old tree down and plant a new one (replacement theology). Neither does God plant a second new tree alongside the old tree and then graft branches from the old tree into the new tree (traditional dispensationalism). Instead, the same tree exists across the divide between Old and New Testaments. That which remains after the dead branches are removed is the true Israel. Gentile believers are now grafted into this already existing old tree (true Israel/the true church). There is only one good olive tree, and the same olive tree exists across the covenantal divide.</p> <p>What does this mean for our understanding of the relationship between the church and Israel? It means that when true Israel was baptized by the Spirit on the day of Pentecost, true Israel became the New Testament church. Thus, there is continuity between true Israel and the church. This is why the Reformed confessions can speak of the church as existing from the beginning of the world (for example, Belgic Confession, Art. 27). Yet there is discontinuity between the church and national Israel as well, just as there was discontinuity between the faithful remnant and apostate Israel in the Old Testament.</p> <p>Romans 11 and the Future of Israel</p> <p>So, what does this mean for national Israel, the branches that have been broken off from the true Israel because of unbelief? Is God finished with this people as a covenantal entity? In order to answer this question, we must turn to Paul&#39;s argument in Romans 9&ndash;11.</p> <p>In Romans 1&ndash;8, Paul denied that Jews were guaranteed salvation on the basis of their distinctive privileges as Jews. Faith was the key, not ethnicity or any kind of works. Paul argued that all who believe in Jesus are children of Abraham. He also argued that none of God&#39;s promises would fail. All of this would raise serious questions in the minds of his readers. What about Israel? What has become of God&#39;s promises to her in light of her rejection of the Messiah? Has the faithlessness of Israel negated God&#39;s promises? Has Israel been disinherited? Has the plan of God revealed throughout the Old Testament been derailed or set aside? Paul answers these questions in Romans 9&ndash;11.</p> <p>Paul begins Romans 9 with a lament for Israel&mdash;his &quot;kinsmen according to the flesh&quot; (v. 3). He then recounts all the privileges that still belong to Israel&mdash;including the adoption, the covenants, and the promises (vv. 4&ndash;5). In verses 6&ndash;29, Paul defends the proposition he states in verse 6a, namely, that the promise of God has not failed. In verses 6&ndash;13, he explains that the corporate election of Israel never meant the salvation of every biological descendant of Abraham: &quot;not all who are descended from Israel belong to Israel&quot; (v. 6b). In verses 14&ndash;23, Paul expands on this, explaining that salvation was never a birthright based on biological descent. It has always been a gift based on God&#39;s sovereign election.</p> <p>In Romans 9:30&ndash;10:21, Paul elaborates on the turn that redemptive history has taken, namely, that while Israel has stumbled over Jesus, Gentiles are now streaming into the kingdom. It is important to observe that in Romans 10:1, Paul writes, &quot;Brothers, my heart&#39;s desire and prayer to God for them is that they may be saved.&quot; He&#39;s talking about Israel. The very fact that Paul can continue to pray for the salvation of unbelieving Israel indicates that he believes salvation is possible for them.</p> <p>What Paul has said thus far raises the big question, which he now states: &quot;I ask, then, has God rejected his people? By no means!&quot; (11:1a). This is the basic theme of chapter 11. In verses 1&ndash;10, Paul demonstrates that God has not rejected Israel by distinguishing between the &quot;remnant&quot; and the &quot;hardened.&quot; Building on what he has already said in 9:6&ndash;13 and 9:27, Paul indicates that just as in the days of Elijah, there is also now a believing remnant (11:2&ndash;5). In contrast with the remnant, chosen by grace (v. 5), is &quot;the rest,&quot; the nation of Israel as a whole, which has been &quot;hardened&quot; (v. 7). God has dulled the spiritual senses of Israel (v. 8), and they have stumbled (vv. 9&ndash;10).</p> <p>Paul then asks, &quot;Did they stumble in order that they might fall?&quot; (11:11a). What is his answer? &quot;By no means! Rather through their trespass salvation has come to the Gentiles, so as to make Israel jealous&quot; (v. 11b). What is the present significance of Israel&#39;s stumbling? Paul explains that it has happened as a means to bring a multitude of Gentiles into the kingdom. The hardening of Israel is serving God&#39;s purpose. Their trespass has served as the occasion for the granting of salvation to the Gentiles. Paul states, &quot;Now if their trespass means riches for the world, and if their failure means riches for the Gentiles, how much more will their full inclusion mean!&quot; (v. 12, emphasis mine).</p> <p>In verses 11&ndash;12, Paul mentions three events: the trespass (or &quot;failure&quot;) of Israel, the salvation of the Gentiles, and the full inclusion of Israel. The first of these leads to the second, and the second leads to the third. Israel&#39;s trespass, in other words, started a process that will ultimately lead back to Israel&#39;s restoration. This is the first of five places in this short passage where Paul explains the purpose and future of Israel in terms of three stages. Douglas Moo provides a helpful summary:</p> <p>vv. 11&ndash;12: &quot;trespass of Israel&quot;&mdash; &quot;salvation for the Gentiles&quot;&mdash; &quot;their fullness&quot;</p> <p>v. 15: &quot;their rejection&quot;&mdash; &quot;reconciliation of the world&quot;&mdash; &quot;their acceptance&quot;</p> <p>vv. 17&ndash;23: &quot;natural branches broken off&quot;&mdash;&quot;wild shoots grafted in&quot;&mdash;&quot;natural branches&quot; grafted back in</p> <p>vv. 25&ndash;26: &quot;hardening of Israel&quot;&mdash;&quot;fullness of Gentiles&quot;&mdash; &quot;all Israel will be saved&quot;</p> <p>vv. 30&ndash;31: disobedience of Israel&mdash;mercy for Gentiles&mdash; mercy to Israel</p> <p>The repeated occurrence of this &quot;three-stage&quot; process reinforces the idea that Paul is looking forward to a future restoration of Israel. Israel&#39;s present condition is described as &quot;failure&quot; and as &quot;rejection.&quot; Paul characterizes the future condition of Israel in terms of &quot;full inclusion&quot; and as &quot;acceptance.&quot; Israel is not simultaneously in the condition of &quot;failure&quot; and &quot;full inclusion,&quot; of &quot;rejection&quot; and &quot;acceptance.&quot; The &quot;full inclusion&quot; will follow the &quot;failure.&quot; The &quot;acceptance&quot; will follow the &quot;rejection.&quot;</p> <p>Paul anticipates a potential problem in verses 13&ndash;24. Gentile believers who had been taught that they were now God&#39;s people could be easily misled into thinking that this was cause for boasting against the Jews. In these verses, Paul warns against such arrogance. In 11:16&ndash;24, Paul explains the development of redemptive history and the place of Israel within it by using the olive tree analogy that we discussed above. Here again, Paul points to three stages in redemptive history: &quot;natural branches broken off&quot;&mdash;&quot;wild shoots grafted in&quot;&mdash; &quot;natural branches&quot; grafted back in.</p> <p>Paul&#39;s teaching in verses 25&ndash;27 has been at the center of the debate concerning the proper interpretation of chapter 11. Paul writes in verse 25: &quot;Lest you be wise in your own conceits, I want you to understand this mystery, brothers: a partial hardening has come upon Israel, until the fullness of the Gentiles has come in.&quot; Here Paul is still speaking directly to the Gentiles (see v. 13). He wants them to understand a &quot;mystery.&quot; In this context, the mystery involves the reversal of Jewish expectations concerning the sequence of end-time events. The &quot;mystery&quot; is that the restoration of Israel follows the salvation of the Gentiles.</p> <p>In verse 26, Paul continues the sentence begun in verse 25: &quot;And in this way all Israel will be saved.&quot; The biggest debate here is the meaning of &quot;all Israel.&quot; Charles Cranfield lists the four main views that have been suggested: (1) all the elect, both Jews and Gentiles; (2) all the elect of the nation Israel; (3) the whole nation Israel, including every individual member; and (4) the nation Israel as a whole, but not necessarily including every individual member. Since Paul repeatedly denies the salvation of every single Israelite, we can set aside option (3).</p> <p>John Calvin understood &quot;all Israel&quot; in verse 26 to mean all the elect, both Jews and Gentiles. Paul does use this language in other places in his writings. The problem with understanding &quot;all Israel&quot; in 11:26 in this sense is the context. Throughout verses 11&ndash;25, Paul has consistent ly dist inguished between Jews and Gentiles. We also have to remember that Paul&#39;s concern in these chapters is for his kinsmen according to the flesh (9:1&ndash;5). His prayer in this context is for the salvation of unbelieving Israel (10:1). In Romans 11:26, Paul is revealing that the prayer of 10:1 will be answered once the fullness of the Gentiles has come in.</p> <p>Other Reformed theologians, such as O. Palmer Robertson and Herman Ridderbos, have argued that &quot;all Israel&quot; refers to all the elect of the nation of Israel throughout the present age. As with the view that understands &quot;all Israel&quot; to be the church, there is truth in this interpretation. The Jews who are being saved in the present age are not any different from the Jews who are to be saved in the future. The problem with this interpretation, as with the previous one, is that it conflicts with the immediate context. As John Murray observes, &quot;While it is true that all the elect of Israel, the true Israel, will be saved, this is so necessary and patent a truth that to assert the same here would have no particular relevance to what is the apostle&#39;s governing interest in this section of the epistle.&quot; Paul is not in anguish over the salvation of the remnant. They are already saved. He is in anguish over unbelieving Israel. It is this &quot;Israel&quot; for whose salvation he prays (10:1), and it is this Israel that he says will be saved in verse 26.</p> <p>The interpretation of &quot;all Israel&quot; that best fits the immediate context is that which understands &quot;all Israel&quot; as the nation of Israel as a whole, but not necessarily including every individual member of ethnic Israel. Paul consistently contrasts Gentiles and Israel throughout this chapter, and he continues to do so in the first half of the sentence we are examining (v. 25). There is no contextual reason to assume that Paul changes the meaning of the term Israel in mid-sentence here. The &quot;Israel&quot; that will be saved (v. 26) is the &quot;Israel&quot; that has been partially hardened (v. 25). This partially hardened Israel is distinct from the Gentiles (v. 25) and is also distinct from the present remnant of believing Jews, who are not hardened (v. 7).</p> <p>Conclusion</p> <p>The relationship between Israel and the church in the New Testament is not always easy to discern, but it can be understood if we remember the differences between national Israel and true Israel in both the Old Testament and the New, and if we keep in mind what Paul teaches in Romans 11. Israel&#39;s present hardening has a purpose in God&#39;s plan, but this hardening is not permanent. The future restoration of the nation of Israel will involve their re-grafting into the olive tree, the one people of God. The restoration of Israel will mean their becoming part of the &quot;true Israel&quot; by faith in Jesus Christ the Messiah.</p>'),
