(41, 1, 46, 5, 8, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:46:21', '<p>Talk about with John, changing leaven to yeast universally, nobody our age who has not grown up in the church knows what leaven is.</p> <p>We are keeping the feast, but not in the way the Jews kept it, in a new Spiritual way. Through sincerity and truth.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 6, 16, 1, null, 99, '2021-10-09 20:15:30', '<p>Tying this in with John 4:18 it is clear that biblically, one becomes married to the one you sleep with. It is not about the piece of paper, but the covenant bonded through blood!! It is no coincidence then that a woman sheds blood during her first sexual encounter. This is a sign that that is what seals the covenant.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 2, 1, 'Best note', 99, '2022-02-23 05:52:51', '<p>Ehh idk about below, authority is certainly in the passage explicitly twice. Possibly three times. In v. 9 the woman was created for the man. In v. 10 this is why she should have a symbol of &ldquo;authority&rdquo; over her. And in v. 3, the heiarchy of woman&lt;man&lt;Christ&lt;God works, but not if you take it as &ldquo;source&rdquo; as the egalitarians do, because Christ is not the source of &ldquo;men&rdquo; or &ldquo;humankind&rdquo;...</p> <p>--------------------------------------</p> <p>So when we get to 1 Corinthians, we need to understand that Paul had been already been spreading his message of equality among humans far and wide. The Corinthians had received his message, and had gone about applying it to often extreme degrees. The first letter to the Corinthians is not his first message to them - on the contrary, it&#39;s a response to their response to his message.</p> <p>Paul spends most of his letter correcting the over-zealous and abusive applications of things he had told them. So when we get to chapter 11 we need to keep in mind that what Paul is correcting are his own ideas - taken too far. In fact, that&#39;s how he starts his discourse - praising them for trying to follow his teachings and example, before he sets out to suggest that they&#39;ve taken it in the wrong direction.</p> <p>The Corinthian women had apparently taken to the idea of their equality to heart. Not only were they praying and prophesying, participating openly in public, they had removed their veils, the symbol that they were married.</p> <p>It made sense. They were equal, right? Why should they continue to wear something that might indicate someone else&#39;s influence over them? Male and female didn&#39;t matter, why should they continue to wear a symbol of their femininity?</p> <p>But this was incredibly offensive. It was like simultaneously throwing away your wedding ring, and burning your bra in public.</p> <p>So Paul makes a very delicate argument, trying to give them a rationale for not ticking off everyone around them, while still holding on to their sense of equality. He makes an argument about source.</p> <p>Now, the text says &quot;head&quot;, and it is conventional to take this as some kind of a statement about authority structures and dominance, but that&#39;s not what &quot;head&quot; means. In Greek usage, the word head indicated either your literal head, or metaphorically, the source of something, like a stream or a river. *</p> <p>So Paul brings in the Genesis 2 creation story to try to talk about how some things come from other things, and how it is appropriate to show some kind of respect towards that. This is kind of like arguing that you should respect your grandmother. No one would argue that your grandmother is more important than you, or should have authority over you, and yet most of us would think it&#39;s tasteful to show some kind of deference to the fact that she helped bring you into existence.</p> <p>I don&#39;t know about you, but when I spend time with my grandmother, I try not to embarrass her in public. If we&#39;re in a store, or walking somewhere, I don&#39;t feel the need to constantly point out that I&#39;m a grown man and can do whatever I want. I don&#39;t wear clothes that she&#39;ll find terribly offensive, or do some of the ridiculous things that I might feel comfortable with, but would make her nervous.</p> <p>Paul is making a similar argument here. Why embarrass your husband? Why get him mocked by the rest of the community? Maybe even more importantly, why give other people a reason to think you might be engaged in some kind of orgy?</p> <p>What&#39;s fascinating is the response Paul expects. He anticipates an argument that as christians, they don&#39;t care at all about cultural or external physical markers. He accepts that as legitimate, but tries to prove that in fact, they do care, and are being inconsistent. He suggests that if they really don&#39;t care, they should just shave their heads, traipse around looking like prostitutes, and be done with it.</p> <p>Why is he so concerned? Because this isn&#39;t being done in dark rooms with closed doors. People are watching. The reference to &quot;angels&quot; in verse 10 is not talking about spirit beings (who would have no concern for head-coverings!), it&#39;s talking about &quot;messengers&quot;, people who are gossiping about what they see, spreading it to the whole town. *</p> <p>These early christian get-togethers had to be the subject of great curiosity. They are letting women speak! They are having slaves sit at the table! People were paying attention to every move, and Paul is concerned about sending the wrong message. You can almost hear him whisper it: someone&#39;s at the window!</p> <p>In all of this, as in all other places, Paul walks a thin line. He wants christians to be acting out of a new conception of society, where men and women, Jew and Greek, slaves and slave-holders, all have to live together in real relationship. Nothing can compromise that scandalous message, because it is core to what they are doing. And yet, Paul does not want to stir up trouble for themselves on other issues. Just because it&#39;s okay to break local customs and desecrate sacred cows, doesn&#39;t mean that&#39;s the best choice. Better to pick their fights, so that the core message is clear, and there is nothing else to criticize them for.</p> <p>Nowhere in this does Paul suggest that the women should stop displaying their equality. They are to continue speaking and participating (verse 5), they are to understand that they are all interdependent and that no one is over another (verse 11), and most tellingly, they are ultimately to make up their own minds - because it is the woman&#39;s own choice (verse 10), and no one should argue about the decision they make (verse 16).</p> <p>Paul cares a lot. He makes a strong argument. But when it comes down to it, his ultimate statement is that each individual is free to make their own decision. Unlike every other structure on earth, the kingdom of God is the place where all are equal and free, and where no one can dominate another. Not even an apostle.</p> <p>ALL FROM MICAHREDDING.COM</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 3, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-23 01:54:15', '<p>Immediately after verse 3 Paul starts talking about head coverings. So what does whose head of whom have to do with head coverings? By appealing to the creation order (reminding them they were made distinctly male and female) Paul is telling believers that what is on their literal heads brings honour or shame to their metaphorical head and, therefore, impacts their public witness of the gospel.</p> <p>------------------------------------</p> <p>The issue in this verse, and the meaning of &ldquo;head&rdquo; is that which has greater honor, not that which has greater &ldquo;authority&rdquo;. This is seen by the next verse 1 Cor. 11:4, which directly correlates the head with honor.</p> <p>Christ has greater honor than all men (all humans, men and women, Jesus is not just the head of males), Man has greater honor than women, and the Father has greater honor than Jesus.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 5, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-04 21:49:04', '<hr /> <p>EHH IM NOT SURE I AGREE WITH HEISER BECAUSE THIS WHOLE PASSAGE SEEMS TO BE ABOUT AUTHORITY AND HONOR, NOT SEXUALITY&hellip; IDK. Michael Heiser podcast 86 &ndash; discusses that there is good reason to believe that the ancient Greco-Romans viewed the Woman&rsquo;s hair, after puberty, to essentially be testicles (the word is used as testicles in the scientific literature of Hypocrates (Hypocratic oath of doctors)). Therefore, to have her hair uncovered was essentially the same as having her genitalia exposed. They believed that her hair attracted sperm to go throughout a woman&rsquo;s body, and helped with fertility.</p> <p>The question then is, why does it dishonor her? In a moment of public worship to have your genitalia exposed is shameful. Why is it one and the same as if she were shaved? Because to have no hair would also be shameful in the culture, because that means that you essentially don&rsquo;t have &lsquo;testicles&rsquo; and would likely be infertile.</p> <p>------------------------------------</p> <p>In Greek, Roman and Jewish culture loose hair signified sexual looseness. As Payne notes, &ldquo;In the Dionysiac cult, which had a prominent temple in Corinth, it was customary for women to let down their hair to &ldquo;prophesy&rdquo; and engage in all sorts of sexual debauchery.&rdquo;7 This would certainly be out of order in the church! It would bring shame not only on the woman but on her husband. It would be equivalent to the shame of having her head shaved or hair cut off (a punishment for adultery).8 Indeed, as Payne notes,&ldquo;&hellip;in Hellenistic Roman, and Jewish cultures for centuries preceding and following the time of Paul, virtually all of the portraiture, sculpture, and other graphic evidence depicts respectable women&rsquo;s hair done up, not let down loose.&rdquo;9</p> <ul> <li>Putting a metaphorical meaning on v4-5, Paul is saying that if the woman or man shames their own head in a literal sense, they bring dishonour upon their metaphorical head. This is highly important in a culture that places societal value on a person&rsquo;s honour or shame.</li> </ul>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 6, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-23 02:06:39', '<p>Paul is concerned with women not being seen as sexually provocative as they lead worship. This seems to be why he would recommend they shave their head. (Of course today short or long, hair up or down, hats or no hats, has no such connotations, but worship leaders do need to be mindful that what they wear does not detract from the worship of God).</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 7, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-23 02:11:21', '<p>Again, how you display your literal head has impact on how people view your metaphorical head (Man, Christ, God).</p> <p>Paul probably means that the existence of the one brings honor and praise to the other. By creating man in his own image God set his glory in man. Man, therefore exists to God&rsquo;s praise and honor, and is to live in relationship to God so as to be his &lsquo;glory.&rsquo; What we are not told here is why being God&rsquo;s glory means no covering; v. 4 indicates it had to do with not shaming Christ. But that, too, was left unexplained. As in v. 4, however, this word about man is not the point of the argument; it exists to set up Paul&rsquo;s real concern&mdash;to explain why women should be covered when prophesying. But in coming to that concern, he picks up on the word &lsquo;glory,&rsquo; saying only that &lsquo;the woman, on the other hand, is man&rsquo;s glory.&rsquo; The implication is that by praying and prophesying in a way that (apparently) disregarded distinctions between the sexes (being already as angels), she brings shame on the man whose glory she is intended to be. Paul does not hereby deny that woman was created in God&rsquo;s image or that she, too, is God&rsquo;s glory. His point is singular. She is related to man as his glory, a relationship that somehow appears to be jeopardized by her present actions.&rdquo;</p> <p>Gordon D. Fee, The First Epistle to the Corinthians (Grand Rapids, MI: Eerdmans, 1987), 516.</p> <p>The implication of verse 7 may be that the conduct of a Christian man (in particular, a man praying or prophesying with his hair/head in a certain state) affects the reputation and honour of God (i.e. God&rsquo;s doxa), and Paul here reminds men that they are the image of God to reinforce his point.</p> <p>On the other hand, the conduct of a Christian woman (in particular, a woman praying or prophesying with her hair/head in a certain state) affects the reputation and honour of her husband or father (i.e. the man&rsquo;s doxa). Paul does not bring up the fact that woman is also made in the image of God because it doesn&rsquo;t add anything to the point he is making in verse 7.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 9, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-23 01:20:29', '<p>this fits good with the idea that women are men&rsquo;s glory. They represent their husbands or men to the surrounding culture. This is what happened in the ancient culture&hellip; ehh idk</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 10, 1, 'Consider changing translation', 99, '2022-03-04 21:52:10', '<p>If we take Heiser&rsquo;s stance, because of the angels could mean because we don&rsquo;t want Gen. 6 to happen again where angels come and have sexual relations with women. Having her hair down was exposing her genitals.</p> <p>----------------------------------</p> <p>Because of the &ldquo;Messengers&rdquo; makes more sense because it works. Meaning, the women were to have a symbol of authority over their head BECAUSE people were spreading messages about how they were disrespecting their husbands by not having a head covering. Now, BECAUSE of the angels, makes no sense. Every interpretation I&rsquo;ve heard suggests that these women were blurring the gender lines and becoming like angels who do not have gender or are not given in marriage. Now if this is what Paul meant, this is absolutely the most unclear way to say it.</p> <p>Some argue that this passage shows that a woman&rsquo;s head covering is a symbol of the male authority over her. But, as Gordon Fee points out, this doesn&rsquo;t fit with the Greek construction of the verse (it is the subject, the woman, who has authority &ldquo;over&rdquo; the object of the preposition, the head).11 It also goes against the context of what Paul is trying to instil in previous chapters, that is, restricting the believer&rsquo;s new found freedom for the sake of the gospel: 1 Cor 8:9 Be careful, however, that the exercise of your rights does not become a stumbling block to the weak.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 11, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-31 14:23:53', '<p>Mutuality for those &ldquo;In the Lord&rdquo;</p> <p>In the first half of the chiasm, Paul presents his argument using a hierarchy of status or honour (based on &ldquo;firstness&rdquo;) that the first-century Corinthians could relate to. Paul wanted the Corinthians to heed this dynamic for the sake of outsiders, but he did not want them to take it too far. So, in the second part of the chiasm, he provides correctives beginning with verses 11&ndash;12.</p> <p>&ldquo;In the Lord, however, woman is not independent of man, and man is not independent of woman (cf. 1 Cor. 11:8). For just as woman came from man, so man comes through woman, and all things come from God (cf. 1 Cor. 11:9).&rdquo;</p> <p>Outside of the church, there were hierarchies of status and honour. However, within the community of believers, among those &ldquo;in the Lord,&rdquo; the ideal is that there is equal honour.</p> <p>----------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Fee takes the view they are acting as if they have angelic status, he writes, &ldquo;Being &ldquo;in the Lord&rdquo; does not mean exousia [authority] to be as the angels now, where distinction between male and female are understood to no longer exist; rather it means that in the present age neither man nor woman can exist without the other, and gender distinctions are part of the &ldquo;all things [that] are from God.&rdquo;13</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 11, 14, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-04 21:47:15', '<p>Heiser &ndash; He makes a good point on why Paul says &lsquo;nature&rsquo; teaches this. Because according to the latest science they believed that long hair on a man was bad because it attracted sperm, yet a man&rsquo;s sperm needs to leave and enter into a woman, therefore he should have short hair.</p> <hr /> <p>this could be possible:</p> <p>There is also an argument that what Paul is talking about is hairstyles. This is because of verse 14: Does not the very nature of things teach you that if a man has long hair, it is a disgrace to him&hellip; According to Payne, &ldquo;Greek, Roman and Jewish literature of Paul&rsquo;s day frequently speaks of men wearing long effeminate hair as disgraceful, especially when done up like a woman&rsquo;s hair&hellip;Many desiring homosexual liaisons advertised their sexual availability through display of effeminate hair, particularly in the Dionysiac cult that was influential in Corinth&rdquo;6 Paul did not want their behaviour to be taken in way that goes against who God created them to be.</p> <p>Payne, Man and Woman One in Christ, 142-143.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 13, 1, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 21:07:48', '<p>In all of his 3<sup>rd</sup> class subjunctives here in vv. 1-3 Paul doesn&rsquo;t have these things. He doesn&rsquo;t have all knowledge, or all trust or understand all sacred secrets, or give away all that he has. Therefore why do we think he speaks in the tongues of angels?</p> <p>As matters of fact, Paul does not claim to possess all prophetic insight and knowledge or to have all faith or to have given up all his possessions or to have delivered his body to be burned--obviously not, since he is writing a letter!). These are &quot;suppose-so&quot; statements only partially true of Paul&#39;s experience. By the same token, although Paul claims to speak in tongues, it is not necessary to infer that he claims to speak in the tongues of angels. In fact, the analogy of the following parallel expressions indicates that he does not here claim to do so. Speaking with the tongues of angels corresponds to the unreal &quot;all&#39;s&quot; in the succeeding statements [301].</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 13, 8, 1, null, 99, '2022-09-25 03:42:20', '<p>Each of these is one from each of the three sections in the list in 1 Cor. 12:8. Meaning that mentioning these three likely stands for the whole list. (Fee, <em>The First Epistle to the Corinthians</em>, 591)</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 13, 10, 1, null, 99, '2022-06-13 15:32:01', '<p>We need to change this bad! what is &ldquo;the completeness?&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;but when the <strong>complete <em>things</em> come</strong>, the <strong>partial <em>things</em></strong> will be done away <strong>with</strong>.&rdquo;</p> <p>I think &ldquo;things&rdquo; is properly supplied, especially since &ldquo;the partial&rdquo; is referring to prophecy and knowledge or &ldquo;things&rdquo;. This also makes sense logically, when complete things come, you don&rsquo;t need partial things.</p> <p>To me, the phrase &ldquo;the completeness&rdquo; is quite strange and confusing</p> <p>Notice how Paul only uses partial to refer to prophecy and knowledge, he doesn&rsquo;t mention tongues or the other gifts. Why? Because the complete or perfect prophecy and knowledge would come and do away with the gifts. I can&rsquo;t think of a better way to describe the canon of scipture than the complete prophecy and knowledge. It is not the complete &ldquo;tongues&rdquo;.</p> <p>In context, teleios is contrasted with &ldquo;partial&rdquo;, so in this context, it means &ldquo;complete&rdquo;, not &ldquo;perfect&rdquo;. What was &ldquo;partial&rdquo;? God&rsquo;s revelation to us.</p> <p>Does &ldquo;that which is perfect&rdquo; refer to the future coming of Christ?<br /> The common contention that the revelatory gifts of tongues, prophecy, and knowledge will continue until Christ&rsquo;s return is unsupported by the context. Jesus is not mentioned in 1 Corinthians 13. Neither are His 2nd Coming or heaven directly referenced. Paul is talking about &ldquo;knowing&rdquo; God&rsquo;s Word incompletely (via the &ldquo;childish&rdquo; revelatory gifts of tongues, knowledge, and prophecy) versus the coming time when Christians will know God&rsquo;s Word completely (telios = &ldquo;perfect,&rdquo; which references completion/maturity, not &ldquo;moral perfection&rdquo; or &ldquo;absolute perfection&rdquo;).</p> <p>--------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Interpreting &ldquo;face to face&rdquo; as a reference to Christians seeing the face of God in the eschaton is unwarranted by the context. Again, the phrase is connected to Paul&rsquo;s mirror analogy. Look into a mirror, and what do you see? Your face. Thus will Christians see &ldquo;face to face&rdquo; (i.e., will &ldquo;know&rdquo; much more clearly and comprehensively) when the &ldquo;mature&rdquo; knowledge of God comes. This is why the &ldquo;childish&rdquo; and incomplete knowledge of God that came via the gifts of prophecy, tongues, and knowledge &ldquo;ceased&rdquo; and &ldquo;vanished away.&rdquo;</p> <p>A related passage is Numbers 12:6-8: &ldquo;Then He [God] said, &ldquo;Hear now My words: If there is a prophet among you, I, the Lord, make Myself known to him in a vision. I speak to him in a dream. Not so with My servant Moses. He is faithful in all My house. I speak with him face to face, even plainly, and not in dark sayings. And he sees the form of the Lord. Why then were you not afraid to speak against My servant Moses?&rdquo;</p> <p>If Paul is alluding to these verses from Numbers 12 in 1 Cor. 13:12, then God speaking to the church via the gifts of prophecy, tongues, and knowledge is likened to the dark and obscure revelations given to the prophets in Num. 12:6. Contrasted with these &ldquo;dim&rdquo; revelations is the &ldquo;complete, perfect&rdquo; revelation (likened to the &ldquo;face to face&rdquo; revelations given to Moses) which God was now providing through the apostles, and which Paul insists would eventually supplant the more obscure and &ldquo;childish&rdquo; revelations given via the revelatory gifts.</p> <p>Note that &ldquo;face to face&rdquo; is primarily an analogy for clearer and more complete revelationin both Num. 12 and 1 Cor. 13. It must be so, since Moses didn&rsquo;t literally see God face to face (he only saw His backside and/or &ldquo;the form of the Lord&rdquo;).</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 13, 12, 1, null, 99, '2022-06-13 15:38:26', '<p>This doesn&rsquo;t make any sense if he is talking about the completion of the canon, because he WROTE most of the NT canon. So, how will Paul know the canon more fully in the future? he wrote it. But if it&rsquo;s talking about the future return of Christ, it makes sense why Paul would say &ldquo;I&rdquo; will know fully.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 1, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 22:03:51', '<p>First, there is no reference in the text of 1 Corinthians 14 to the emotional or mental state of the tongue-speaker.</p> <p><strong>Is this heavenly languages or earthly languages?</strong></p> <p><u><em>There is no reference to an angelic language in 1 Cor. 14.</em></u></p> <p>Paul is making assertions that all voices are inherently intelligible, but if we do not understand the voice of another human being, we become &quot;gibberish talkers&quot; to each other.</p> <p>A second problem with the heavenly language view is the reference to &quot;kinds of languages&quot; in 1 Corinthians 12:10. Is this a reference to multiple angelic languages? In the multilingual setting of the city of Corinth multiple human languages and translators would have been much more advantageous than angelic languages.</p> <p>In all of his 3rd class subjunctives here in vv. 1-3 Paul doesn&rsquo;t have these things. He doesn&rsquo;t have all knowledge, or all trust or understand all sacred secrets, or give away all that he has. Therefore why do we think he speaks in the tongues of angels?</p> <p><strong>Native Languages</strong></p> <p>We can now state the nature of the languages problem at Corinth: Corinth was a highly multilingual seaport city in which people would sometimes speak out in the Corinthian church service, worshiping God in the language with which they were most familiar (their native language, first language, language of the heart) without translation.</p> <p>This explanation (1) fits the multilingual setting (which all acknowledge); (2) fits all 35 Scriptural observations listed above; (3) explains why the language-speaker is using a problem language to worship God; (4) explains how the language-speaker can be edified even when the language is not translated; (5) explains why Paul would say: &quot;I want you all to speak in [your] languages&quot; (1 Cor 14:5); &quot;Do not forbid to speak in languages&quot; (1 Cor 14:39). In 1 Corinthians 14 Paul as adyadic personality must reconcile two competing values. On the one hand, everything must be done in such a way that the benefit of the group is maintained (thus he says: &quot;Seek to build up the church that you may abound&quot; (1 Cor 14:12); &quot;Let all things be for building up&quot; (1 Cor 14:26). Yet, on the other hand, Paul wants people whose native languages are not Greek to be able to freely worship God in the language most familiar to them (as long as they translate).</p> <p>It should be noted that in 1 Corinthians 14:5, 13, and 27 Paul tells the language-speakers to translate their own languages (&quot;unless he translates&quot;--14:5; &quot;that he may translate&quot;--14:13; and &quot;let two or at most three and let one [of them] translate&quot;--14:27). In 1 Corinthians 14:28, however, Paul says that in a situation in which there is no &quot;translator&quot; (notice that diermeneueto is a noun), the language speaker should &quot;keep silent in the church and speak to himself and to God.&quot; If speaking in languages and translation were miraculous (as some say) then the situation described in 1 Corinthians 14:28 could never occur. The language-speaker is instructed to &quot;pray that he might translate&quot; (1 Cor 14:13). If translation is a supernatural ability that the language-speaker or others with this supernatural ability could practice, then the situation of 1 Corinthians 14:28 could never arise! Either the language-speaker would translate, or one of the supernaturally gifted translators could translate. But in fact the situation of 14:28 could arise, according to Paul. How do we explain this?</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 2, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 20:52:43', '<p>D. A. Carson says of Behm&#39;s argument:</p> <p>More careful word studies have shown that in none of the texts adduced by Behm or the standard lexica does glossa ever denote non-cognitive utterance. The utterance may be enigmatic and incomprehensible, but not non-cognitive. The ecstatic utterances of the pagan religions prove less suitable a set of parallels than was once thought [80-81].</p> <p>And &ldquo;interpretation&rdquo; means translation 18 out of the 20 times it&rsquo;s used in the septuagint with languages.</p> <p>Therefore, I will use language(s) instead of problem tongue(s),and translation instead of interpretation.</p> <p>----------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Information that is provided by several passages within the chapter reveals that some of the Corinthian saints, who possessed the divine gift of being able to speak in foreign languages [ordinary human tongues] in a supernatural manner, were abusing that gift. If, therefore, a person had the divinely bestowed gift of speaking in a &ldquo;tongue,&rdquo; he was to exercise that gift only in an assembly where the same language was known &mdash; unless there was an interpreter present.</p> <p><strong>For the one who speaks in a tongue [to an audience unfamiliar with his language], is not speaking to men [in any meaningful way], but to God [since only God would be able to know what was being said]; for no one [in this audience] would understand, but in his spirit he [the speaker] would be speaking mysteries [that which could not be understood due to the language barrier] to his alien audience.</strong></p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 4, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-17 19:35:16', '<p>This is saying whoever speaks in a tongue without an interpreter, builds himself up, or puffs himself up. It makes him look good and more &ldquo;spiritual&rdquo;, this is exactly what is happening today!! with private prayer languages</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 5, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 22:46:06', '<p>Ehh, it could still work. &ldquo;I want you to speak in other languages&rdquo; with LANGUAGES</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 14, 1, 'For if I pray in a language, my spirit prays, but my mind is unfruitful.', 99, '2022-12-26 02:54:09', '<p>Nope I disagree with the translation below. I don&rsquo;t think it is a native language because he would just say pray then, he wouldn&rsquo;t say pray in a tongue.</p> <p>Translation: For if I pray in a native language, my spirit prays, but my thoughts do not produce fruit.</p> <p>A decision upon its meaning centers in akarpos (&quot;unfruitful&quot;) whether the adjective is passive in sense, meaning the speaker himself receives no benefit, or active in sense, meaning his nous provides no benefit to others...The view that assigns akarpos a meaning of &quot;produces nothing, contributes nothing to the process&quot;... is not convincing, because akarpos does not mean &quot;inactive.&quot; It is a word for results and does not apply to the process through which the results are obtained. The present discussion does not center on the activity or nonactivity of the tongues speaker&#39;s mind, but rather on potential benefit derived by listeners [Thomas, 214-15].</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 15, 1, null, 99, '2022-06-13 14:51:30', '<p>Paul says that should he speak in one of these non-Greek languages (without translation) his spirit will be praying (i.e., he will be speaking from the &quot;heart&quot;), but his mind will not be producing fruit in others (they will not be edified by speech which is unintelligible to them).</p> <p>Paul begins with the words &quot;What should be done then?&quot; &quot;He answers his own question, replying that all worship activities (which he represents with two examples: &quot;prayer&quot; and &quot;singing&quot;) be done &quot;with the Spirit and with the mind.&quot;</p> <p>Again, modern scholars read in modern psychological categories that were completely foreign to Paul&#39;s dyadic-oriented thinking. Paul is saying in v 15 that all worship activities should be &quot;from the heart&quot; (i.e., &quot;with the spirit&quot;) and also &quot;intelligible&quot; (i.e., &quot;with the mind&quot;). Paul then shifts to another negative example in vv 16-17. If someone praises God from the heart (&quot;with the spirit&quot;) unintelligibly (i.e., &quot;without the mind&quot; [implied]), &quot;the one occupying the place of the unlearned&quot; (i.e., the person not knowing the particular language) cannot even assent to the prayer of the language speaker (&quot;how will he say the &#39;Amen&#39; at your giving of thanks, since he does not know [what you are saying]&quot;). Paul says the language speaker may give thanks well (&quot;For you truly give thanks well&quot;), but because the language is unintelligible to the other person, that individual is not edified (&quot;but the other is not built up&quot;).</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Seventh, NC-NLU&#39;s would involve random, arbitrary sounds or syllables, which would not bear any cognitive content. The text of 1 Corinthians 14 says precisely the opposite. The problem tongue(s) of 1 Corinthians 14 involve the lyrics of songs (1 Cor 14:15) and expressions of prayer, praise, and &quot;giving thanks.&quot; The problem tongue(s) also involve words. In 1 Corinthians 14:19 Paul says that he prefers &quot;five intelligible words&quot; to &quot;myriads, countless words in a tongue.&quot;</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 16, 1, null, 99, '2022-06-13 14:58:46', '<p>There is an assumed &ldquo;you praise with the spirit,&rdquo; but not with understanding.</p> <p>Also, the words clearly have meaning, it&rsquo;s just that the &ldquo;unlearned&rdquo; person doesn&rsquo;t know the language you are speaking. But it is still a language!</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 17, 1, null, 99, '2022-06-13 15:00:42', '<p>Again it&rsquo;s an intelligible language, he is giving thanks, his words have meaning</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 18, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 22:18:16', '<p>Where did Paul use these multiple human languages? Thomas answers: &quot;He instead refers to his public ministry with various linguistic groups encountered in connection with missionary travels&quot; (219). Gerhard F. Hasel concurs: &quot;Paul speaks in tongues more than all the Corinthians, and thus as a missionary to Gentile peoples and nations&quot; (149).</p> <p>While there is no evidence that Paul used multiple languages for private prayer purposes, he did so as missionary to the Gentiles. Even in Jerusalem, Paul switched back and forth between languages. In Acts 21-22 he speaks to a Judean crowd in Aramaic at first; then, when the crowd becomes hostile, he speaks in Greek to a Roman Chiliarch (Acts 21:37). Finally,to establish himself as Judean, he addresses them in the &quot;holy tongue,&quot; Hebrew (Acts 21:40, 22:2).</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 21, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 20:39:09', '<p>when Paul cites Old Testament precedent in 1 Corinthians 14:21-22 he appeals to past experience of the unintelligible human languages of Israel&#39;s conquerors (i.e., &quot;by men of other tongues&quot;). The Old Testament context prophesying in the intelligible human language (i.e., Hebrew) was intended for believers (&quot;prophecy is not for unbelievers but for believers&quot;--1 Cor 14:22b). When this was rejected by Israel&#39;s unbelief, they received unintelligible languages (&quot;and tongues is not a sign for believers but for unbelievers&quot;--1 Cor14:22a) as a sign of God&#39;s judgment.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 27, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 20:51:42', '<p>As W. F. Orr and J. A. Walther observed regarding the interpretation of tongues: &quot;If the reference is to &#39;languages,&#39; this should be rendered &#39;translation&#39;&quot; (280). If the reference is to genuine NC-NLU&#39;s (non-cognitive), then interpretation or translation cannot take place.</p> <p>Gundry notes: &quot;The term interpretation (diermeneuo), used frequently in connexion with glossolalia in 1 Corinthians, normally refers to translating a language when used in such a context&quot; (300). J.G. Davies, discussing interpretation in the Septuagint and the New Testament,writes:</p> <p>Thus of the twenty-one instances of the use of hermeneuein and its cognates in the LXX and the New Testament, apart from the seven occurrences in 1 Cor. 12 and 14, one refers to a satire or figurative saying, two to an explanation or exposition, and eighteen have the primary meaning of translation...the evidence is such as to warrant the assertion that the word used by Paul of interpreting glossolalia carries with it the strong suggestion of translating a foreign language [230].</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 28, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 22:06:52', '<p>Blackwelder notes:</p> <p><strong>This implies that a person needing an interpreter is able to ascertain in advance whether or not an interpreter is present. This could not be done if nonhuman or heavenly languages were involved;</strong> for if that were the case the interpretation would have to come as a special disclosure in each instance, hence a speaker could never be certain that he should present a message [67].</p> <p>------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Since translation involves the factors that Crystal refers to here, wouldn&#39;t it make sense for Paul to tell the language-speaker to ask God for help in translating into Greek--his second language, one that he may not know nearly as well as he knows his own native language?</p> <p>This also helps to explain the relationship between 1 Corinthians 14:13 and 14:28. If the language-speaker is competent to translate his language into Greek, he should do so, or one of the translators (who knows both the language of the language-speaker and Greek) ought to translate. If none of the translators present knows the particular language, however, and if the language-speaker engages in a local language from some distant part of the Roman Empire, and he is not very familiar with Greek (or competent in Greek), he should &quot;keep silent in the church&quot; (i.e., keep that particular language out of the service for the sake of the group).</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 34, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-04 19:07:18', '<p>Jerry has a good perspective on this verse, he is basically saying that women were untrained in being in large groups, so they might have shouted out questions and things, whereas Paul is saying they should not be doing that.</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>These two verses maybe a quote, Paul quoting the letter that the corinthians sent to him. Just like in, &ldquo;It is not good for a man to touch a woman&rdquo; (1 Cor. 7:1), &ldquo;We all possess knowledge&rdquo; (1 Cor. 8:1), &ldquo;There is no resurrection&rdquo; and &ldquo;Christ has not been raised&rdquo; (1 Cor. 15:12, 14).</p> <p>Reasons why for quote:</p> <ol type="1"> <li>v. 39 says do not forbid anyone from speaking in tongues. It is very possible that this is a response to men in the corinthian church trying to silence women v. 34-35.</li> <li>Immediately after 34-35 he says &ldquo;What?&rdquo; This makes no sense if he is teaching truth in 34-35.</li> <li>The masculine &ldquo;monous&rdquo; in v. 36 makes no sense unless this is a quote. The subject in v. 34-35 is the women, so why would Paul then say, did the word of God come to you alone (Masculine)? If the women were claiming that the word of God came to them alone we would expect a feminine here. But, if this is a quotation of false teaching by the men in the Corinthian church it would make sense why Paul would say rhetorically, &ldquo;Did the word of God come to you alone (Masc.)?&rdquo; No, it came to the women also&hellip; this would be Paul&rsquo;s point. The masculine gender of &ldquo;only ones&rdquo; in verse 36 does not seem to follow logically after 14:34-35 and its instructions to women unless verse 36 is a reprimand to a group of men that wants to silence women.</li> </ol> <p>Reasons why for later addition to text:</p> <p>As noted, verses 34-35 sit uncomfortably within 1 Corinthians 14, both grammatically and hermeneutically. In fact, if you skip over verses 33b-35, and go straight from verse 33a to verse 36, the passage flows and makes good sense. Furthermore, because of the existence of textual variations involving verses 34-35 in several early manuscripts of 1 Corinthians, some scholars, notably Gordon D. Fee and Philip B. Payne, suggest verses 34-35 may have been inserted into the text of Paul&rsquo;s letter by an unknown scribe at a very early date.[20]</p> <p>In a few early (mostly Western) texts of 1 Corinthians 14, verses 34-35 are located after verse 40 (e.g., Codex Claromontanus, Codex Augiensis, Codex Boernerianus, Codex Regis, and some Latin manuscripts). Metzger (1994:499) offers an explanation for the different location of these verses: &ldquo;Such scribal alterations represent attempts to find a more appropriate location in the context for Paul&rsquo;s directive concerning women.&rdquo;</p> <hr /> <p>DONT KNOW WHAT TO DO WITH 1 COR. 11:7.</p> <p>Craig Keener takes into consideration the culture of learning in the first century and proposes that the problem being addressed in 1 Corinthians 14:34-35 was women who were interrupting the flow of congregational meetings by asking too many rudimentary questions. He writes, &ldquo;Throughout the first-century Mediterranean world, novices were expected to learn quietly, but more advanced students were expected to interrupt all kinds of public lectures with questions.&rdquo; (Keener 2001:50) Keener suggests the Corinthian women may not have realised that interrupting the meetings with their basic questions was culturally inappropriate, even shameful.</p> <p>A tongues-speaker, male or female, is to be silent (sigaō) and stop speaking in tongues if there is no one to interpret (1 Cor. 14:28 ESV).<br /> ~ A prophet, male or female, is to be silent (sigaō) and stop prophesying if someone else receives a revelation (1 Cor. 14:30).<br /> ~ Women are to be silent (sigaō) and stop asking questions if there is anything they want to learn (manthanō); they should keep their questions for home (1 Cor. 14:34-35). These questions may have been directed to the men and women prophesying: prophecy was so that everyone could learn (manthanō) and be encouraged (1 Cor. 14:31 CSB).</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 14, 35, 1, null, 99, '2022-10-30 00:26:50', '<p>I think this is what it is saying &ndash; &ldquo;The Bible&rsquo;s teaching may be controversial but it&rsquo;s not self-contradictory. Paul doesn&rsquo;t forbid women from praying and prophesying in the assembly. On the contrary, he wishes for them to do it in a way that honors male headship (1 Cor. 11:2&ndash;16). Among other things, that means that women may prophesy but that they may not judge prophesies (1 Cor. 14:34&ndash;36). This teaching reflects Paul&rsquo;s very practical concern for women who minister in churches and how they might do so in a way that honors headship. That very same concern should mark every congregation&mdash;even ours.&rdquo; 9 marks</p> <p>The first problem with John Truitt&rsquo;s, forbidding women to judge prophecy view, is that is says here in v. 35 that the woman wants &ldquo;to learn&rdquo; not &ldquo;to judge&rdquo; she should do it at home.</p> <p>Secondly, where is that spoken of in the law?</p> <p>Thirdly, there is something about there speaking in which they wish to learn something. They are not acting as an authority here but are seeking to learn something, which makes sense why Paul says they should just <strong>ask</strong> at home.</p>');
INSERT INTO `myrevdata` (`myrevid`, `testament`, `book`, `chapter`, `verse`, `highlight`, `marginnote`, `sqn`, `lastupdate`, `myrevnotes`) VALUES
(41, 1, 46, 14, 39, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-22 22:11:04', '<p>He does not say earnestly desire to speak in tongues!! Because it is just speaking in your native language, but he does say to desire to prophecy, because this is a supernatural phenomenon!</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 15, 23, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-28 17:20:47', '<p>This is explicit that the resurrection of the dead occurs at the same time as Christ&rsquo;s second coming!</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 15, 24, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:46:34', '<p>It is only at the end of the thousand years, the end of the reign of Christ that the resurrection occurs and death is defeated (1 Cor. 15:23-28). So it is no surprise that the final judgment and resurrection of the dead happens once the thousand year reign is complete (Rev. 20:11-15).</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 15, 50, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:46:38', '<p>Flesh and blood is not the sinful nature, it is the physical body. He is not saying here that sinners won&rsquo;t inherit the kingdom of God, although true, not what he is saying. Rather it is that this body can&rsquo;t inherit the good that is coming. We must die and rise again. This also answers why Jesus didn&rsquo;t usher in the Kingdom on his 1<sup>st</sup> coming, because a kingdom with our bodies and our current state would not be an everlasting kingdom.</p>'),
(41, 1, 46, 15, 51, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:46:50', '<p>Why &ldquo;we&rdquo; here? See commentary on 1 Thess. 4:15.</p>'),
(41, 1, 47, 5, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:46:58', '<p>See Comm. on Zech. 14:16, this is how we are keeping the feast of booths, we are living in our tent (current bodies) waiting for our eternal dwelling (New Jerusalem, new bodies).</p>'),
(41, 1, 47, 5, 2, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:47:03', '<p>This goes with comm. on Zech. 14:16 and Rev. 20:8-10. This is more evidence that this Church age is our &ldquo;tent&rdquo; dwelling before we enter the promised land/New Jerusalem. This is more evidence that we live in the now and still to come.</p>'),
(41, 1, 47, 5, 4, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:47:11', '<p>This verse is absolutely essential for understanding v. 6. This verse makes it clear that Paul is not saying that when he dies, he becomes an unembodied spirit in v. 6, here he says that he does not want to be unclothed (in other words, not have a body).</p>'),
(41, 1, 47, 5, 8, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:47:15', '<p>Again v. 4 brings clarity. When Paul says he desires to be &ldquo;out of the body&rdquo; or away from the body, he is speaking of his earthly temporal body. But v. 4 makes it clear that he does not want to be unclothed &ndash; a disembodied soul &ndash; but he wants to be in his new body at home with the Lord.</p>'),
(41, 1, 48, 1, 15, 0, 'I have commentary written', 99, '2022-09-12 13:42:43', '<p><strong>&ldquo;who separated me from my mother&rsquo;s womb.&rdquo;</strong> Some translations such as the ESV read, &ldquo;when he who had set me apart before I was born.&rdquo; This makes it sound as if God knew Paul would become a Christian before he was ever born. In other words, that God predestined Paul&rsquo;s salvation. However, this is not what the Greek says, the Greek reads, &ldquo;from my mothers womb&rdquo; not &ldquo;before I was born&rdquo; that concept is simply not in the text. The idea is that from the womb Paul has been set apart to be a powerful man for God&rsquo;s kingdom.</p> <p>Paul was from the tribe of Benjamin and was circumcised on the eighth day (Phil. 3:5), meaning that his parents (from birth) raised him to be a faithful Jew. Jewish training for a boy such as Paul would likely have looked like this: &ldquo;At five years old he comes to the reading of the scripture, at ten to the Mishnah, at thirteen to the practice of the commandments, at fifteen to the Talmud, at eighteen to marriage, at twenty to pursue a calling&rdquo; (Rabbi Judah b. Tema in <em>m. Avot</em> 5.21. Herbert Danby trans. <em>The Mishnah</em>, Oxford University Press, 1933, p. 458). He was trained in the Hillel school of the Jews (John Mcray, <em>Paul: his Life and Teaching</em>, 44-45), and he was a rabbi trained by Gamaliel in Jerusalem (Acts 22:3). Paul was able to do things for God&rsquo;s kingdom that many almost no one else could do, because of his prior training and his being set apart from his mother&rsquo;s womb.</p> <p>In other words, how we might say this expression &ldquo;from my mother&rsquo;s womb&rdquo; in modern-day english would be, &ldquo;my whole life&rdquo; or, &ldquo;from birth.&rdquo; Paul&rsquo;s whole life he was set apart for God&rsquo;s work, and thanks to the grace of God in calling him to Jesus, he was able to have a tremendous impact for the kingdom of God.</p>'),
(41, 1, 48, 3, 10, 0, 'stopped here with Diego', 99, '2022-10-31 23:53:35', null),
(41, 1, 48, 3, 19, 1, null, 99, '2022-09-04 20:32:03', '<p>Gen. 3:15!</p>'),
(41, 1, 49, 1, 11, 3, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:47:24', '<p>God is working all things together according to his will! Not God knows all things according to the plan of his will. This is the power model</p>'),
