(41, 1, 49, 2, 5, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:47:46', '<p>Spiritual resurrection, Rev. 20:4-6.</p>'),
(41, 1, 49, 4, 8, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-10 00:29:05', '<p>I think this is talking about taking Satan, sin and death, the place where people were captured, captive. See Hoehner commentary on eph. 4:8 agree for the most part. THOSE WHO WERE HELD IN BONDAGE have been freed and have obtained the gifts of the Spirit from their victorious Lord and Savior Jesus.</p> <p>I do think the &ldquo;gifts&rdquo; here in context are clearly the gifts of the holy Spirit</p>'),
(41, 1, 49, 4, 10, 0, null, 99, '2022-07-20 16:02:16', '<p><strong>fill all things</strong>, this is metaphorical because in just the next two verses he talks about how all these different literal people make up his figurative body &ndash; the body of christ.</p>'),
(41, 1, 49, 5, 23, 1, null, 99, '2022-03-04 22:49:20', '<p>Women submission to men only applies in marriage, not in the church, because men aren&rsquo;t the head of the Church, Christ is.</p> <p>The contrast is clear here: Women submit to men in marriage, The church (men and women) submits to christ.</p> <p><strong>This is NOT what the verse says</strong>: Women submit to men in marriage, Women in the church submit to men in the church.</p>'),
(41, 1, 49, 5, 33, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-06 21:49:41', null),
(41, 1, 50, 1, 23, 5, null, 99, '2022-02-11 17:18:38', '<p>Alt. Translation: &ldquo;Now I am hard pressed between the two, having the intense desire to depart <em>in death</em> and to be with Christ <em>at the resurrection</em> because that is far better,&rdquo;</p> <p>Reasons for this &ndash;</p> <ul> <li>We would have to supply a subject &ldquo;for the return <em>of Christ</em>&rdquo; (Christ) which isn&rsquo;t in the text, in order to make sense of &ldquo;return&rdquo; as the meaning.</li> <li>It is most natural to see his phrase here as being contrasted with what comes after, not a third option interjected into his two options laid out. &ldquo;for it is far better&rdquo; but &ldquo;it is more necessary&rdquo;</li> <li>Depart is the much more common usage of this word, i.e. set free, luw</li> <li>Causal is good here for the participle. He is explaining why he is hard pressed between the two.</li> </ul> <p>also, I see the mainstream understanding as well, I think I&rsquo;m maybe 70/30 for mainstream understanding.</p> <p>This does not mean that he goes to heaven immediately upon death. In our understanding, when a person dies, he is unconcious and the next moment that he is concious is the resurrection of the dead. So, it absolutely makes sense that Paul would say that when he departs, he will be with Christ. Because in his next waking moment, he is with Christ.</p>'),
(41, 1, 50, 2, 6, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-19 05:28:43', '<p>&ldquo;Who, though he appeared to be a God (or God), considered being equal with God not something to be claimed.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;but <em>instead</em> emptied himself by taking the appearance of a servant, becoming in resemblance like men.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;And in order to be found/seen in outward appearance as a man, he humbled himself, becoming obedient to death-even death on a cross!&rdquo;</p> <p>lit. &ldquo;Who, being in appearance God, or a God&rdquo;</p> <p>Also, why don&rsquo;t we just change this to appearance instead of form? If we have to explain what it means to be in the &ldquo;form&rdquo; of God. Also, this is way better because it makes clear that this &ldquo;form of God&rdquo; was not in eternity past, but on earth when people could see him. They saw Jesus&rsquo; miracles and he seemed like a God.</p> <p>&ldquo;stolen&rdquo; or &ldquo;claimed&rdquo; instead of grasped? The term is a term about a bounty. As if a pirate were stealing a bounty. To me claiming works much better than grasping here. It&rsquo;s claiming something that is not yours, not just grasping something.</p>'),
(41, 1, 50, 2, 7, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-19 05:11:58', '<p>&ldquo;but <em>instead</em> emptied himself by taking the appearance of a servant, becoming in resemblance like men.&rdquo; OR &ldquo;becoming like men in resemblance&rdquo;</p> <p>lit. &ldquo;becoming in the likeness of men&rdquo;</p> <p>I think the phrase &ldquo;being born in the likeness of men&rdquo; needs to go with &ldquo;emptied himself&rdquo; grammatically, but why don&rsquo;t we change &ldquo;being born&rdquo;???? Birth is not the focus here. Being born as a man or like men is not an act of humility (unless we want to teach preexistence here) however, becoming like men when you could be praised as a God is an act of humility.</p>'),
(41, 1, 50, 2, 8, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-19 05:31:47', '<p>Possible purpose use of the participle here: &ldquo;And in order to be found/seen in outward appearance as a man, he humbled himself, becoming obedient to death-even death on a cross!&rdquo;</p> <p>Im not really sure what purpose the phrase &ndash; &ldquo;and being found in fashion as a man, he humbled himself&rdquo; serves? Why add the being found part? Being found as a man he humbled himself just doesn&rsquo;t make sense. But the purpose use of the participle does make sense. No other use of the participle seems to make sense.</p>'),
(41, 1, 50, 2, 10, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:47:50', '<p>In response to Universalist claims, it is important to note that in this phrase Paul specifically uses the term &ldquo;under the earth&rdquo; not &ldquo;in Hell&rdquo;. Perhaps Paul is saying here that those who are currently in heaven (angels), on earth (living humans) and under the earth (dead humans) will worship Jesus, not that Christ&rsquo;s enemies (in hell) will bow to him as Lord (Phil. 2:11) which simply does not make sense.</p> <p>I need to do a word study of the phrase &ldquo;under the earth&rdquo; again. To be sure that the above is true.</p>'),
(41, 1, 51, 1, 16, 2, null, 99, '2023-02-01 20:33:52', '<p><strong>Thrones, Dominions, Rulers, and Authorities:</strong> These are all angelic positions created in the New Creation. They are new creation concepts. See Ephesians 1:21</p> <p>How cool is it that a new set of angelic beings has been created to help serve the new creation, and Christ&rsquo;s current kingdom. Notice the past tense throughout the passage, this creation has already happened, just like in John 1 where all things were created through the Word.</p> <p>θρόνοι are not mentioned elsewhere in the N.T., but in Test. XII. Patr. (Levi 3) they are placed in the highest (seventh) heaven. Probably the name was meant as a designation of spirits who occupied thrones surrounding the throne of God. Comp. Rev. 4:4. Clement of Alex. seems to regard them as so called because supporting or forming the throne of God (Proph. Ecl. 57), as the cherubim are represented in Ezek. 9:3, 10:1, 11:22; Ps. 80:2, 99:1.</p> <p><strong>Thomas Kingsmill Abbott, A Critical and Exegetical Commentary on the Epistles to the Ephesians and to the Colossians, International Critical Commentary (New York: C. Scribner&rsquo;s sons, 1909), 216.</strong></p> <p>Eph. 6:12 &ndash; clearly spiritual beings&hellip;</p> <p>There is a general consensus among scholars that the terms used here refer to spiritual beings.</p> <p><strong>Richard R. Melick, Philippians, Colossians, Philemon, vol. 32, The New American Commentary (Nashville: Broadman &amp; Holman Publishers, 1991), 219.</strong></p> <p>These spirit beings occupy a significant place in the epistle.</p> <p>Indeed, they are the object of much discussion here and in 2:8&ndash;3:4. Paul seems to have felt a need to note that these spirit beings are created by the power of Christ and conquered by the power of the cross (2:15).</p> <p><strong>Richard R. Melick, Philippians, Colossians, Philemon, vol. 32, The New American Commentary (Nashville: Broadman &amp; Holman Publishers, 1991), 220.</strong></p>'),
(41, 1, 51, 1, 17, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:47:57', '<p>The &ldquo;all things&rdquo; that are held together is the Church. V. 17 is not to be disconnected with v. 18. He is the head of the body which holds the whole body together. The Head ; Holds together; first ; preeminent, these are all describing Jesus&rsquo; role with the Church! The Head analogy means that Jesus was First, and preeminent. This passage is not talking about the Supremacy of Jesus in the creating the earth, and then talking about his supremacy in the Church, NO its all the same topic, the Church. What he is head over, is what he is preeminent in. cf. Col. 2:19.</p>'),
(41, 1, 51, 1, 18, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:48:00', '<p>Col. 1:18 is not to be ripped out of its immediate context. Paul does not go from talking about the creation of the land and sea in vv. 16-17 to Christ&rsquo;s rank above the Church. That makes no sense and is out of left field. Rather Col. 1:16-20 is all about the Church, the new creation.</p> <p>There is also an insightful connection Paul makes between συμβιβαζόμενον in 2:19 and συνέστηκεν in 1:17. In both of these passages, the respective words mean to hold together, and Paul also makes another connection between these two passages by referring to Christ as the &ldquo;Head&rdquo; κεφαλὴ. However, this head that holds everything together in 2:19, is holding together the Church, not the mountains and valleys of the old creation. This means that what is being held together in 1:17 is also the Church, not subatomic particles or however one desires to understand Christ &ldquo;holding together&rdquo; the old creation. It is once again affirmed to be a new creation passage.</p>'),
(41, 1, 51, 1, 19, 0, null, 99, '2022-06-29 19:03:17', '<p>Eph. 3:19 we have that fullness too</p>'),
(41, 1, 51, 2, 9, 2, null, 99, '2022-08-02 02:22:49', '<ul> <li aria-level="1" style="list-style-type:disc"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Colossians 2:9 -</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none"><sup style="font-size:0.6em">14</sup></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">But when he comes into an assembly full of righteous men who have a Spirit of deity, and intercession is made from them, that man is emptied, and the earthly spirit fleeth from him in fear, and that man is struck dumb and is altogether broken in pieces, being unable to utter a word</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li> </ul> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Lightfoot, J. B., &amp; Harmer, J. R. (1891).</span></span></span></span></span></span></span> <a href="https://ref.ly/logosres/apfthlfteng?ref=ApostolicFathers.Herm%2c+M+XI%2c+14&amp;off=0&amp;ctx=one+with+the+other.+~14%EF%BB%BFBut+when+he+comes" style="text-decoration:none"><span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#0000ff"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:italic"><span style="text-decoration:underline"><span style="-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none"><span style="text-decoration-skip-ink:none">The Apostolic Fathers</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></a> <span style="font-size:9pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">(pp. 435&ndash;436). London: Macmillan and Co.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">This is a quote from Hermas, in which he uses the word deity, the same word used in Col. 2:9. Now, Hermes says that humans have a Spirit of Deity. Does that mean that we are God?? No, or even part God? No. That just means that we are indwelt by God, and that some of his righteousness and divinity is poured into our hearts.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">So, if Jesus has the &ldquo;fullness of Deity, does that make him fully God, no, he just has the full outpouring of the Spirit. The Fullness of the Spirit of Deity.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">We must understand where this way of understanding Col. 2:9 takes us. If we say that having the fullness of Deity makes one God, then does having the Holy Spirit inside of us, even partly, make us partly God? This would make trinitarians very nervous to say, it almost sounds like Mormonism. Yet, this is consistent logically.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">We must understand that having something dwelling inside of you, does not make you that thing. So because we have the Spirit of God dwelling in us, that does not make us the spirit of God.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:12pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:''Times New Roman''"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Also, we must understand how strange this would be to say that God has deity dwelling in him? Of course he does, he is God. However, it would make sense to say that Jesus, a man, has deity dwelling in him, because men do not normally have that. This is a significant statement.</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>'),
(41, 1, 52, 4, 15, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:48:23', '<p>I think why Paul uses &ldquo;We&rdquo; here instead of &ldquo;they&rdquo; is that he truly did not know the timing of Jesus 2<sup>nd</sup> coming. After all, Jesus didn&rsquo;t even know the timing of his second coming (). To Paul, the second comiong certainly could have come within his lifetime, yet we know that it still has not happened.</p>');
INSERT INTO `myrevdata` (`myrevid`, `testament`, `book`, `chapter`, `verse`, `highlight`, `marginnote`, `sqn`, `lastupdate`, `myrevnotes`) VALUES
(41, 1, 52, 4, 17, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-10 20:48:12', '<p>It doesn&rsquo;t make any sense to make the point repeatedly that we will not precede those who have fallen asleep but then to say that we will resurrect with them at the same time (hama v. 17). Evidence against rapture.</p>'),
(41, 1, 52, 5, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-08 19:55:48', '<p>I know that &ldquo;Now concerning&rdquo; is a phrase that Paul uses to change topics, but it is also a phrase that can be used to further explain a topic (which seems to be the case here), its like he gives this information in the chapter right before, and now he says, well concerning the times and dates (of this EVENT) we know that it will come like a thief in the night.</p>'),
(41, 1, 52, 5, 2, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-08 20:05:33', '<p>Parallels closely with Matt. 24:36-end, which I believe to be about second coming</p>'),
(41, 1, 52, 5, 3, 5, null, 99, '2022-09-05 18:04:58', '<p>&ldquo;The day of the Lord&rdquo; in Scripture is always a time when God would come in judgement upon this world. According to these terms, the second coming cannot be described to the believer as a &ldquo;day of the Lord,&rdquo; for believers have no judgement to fear at the second coming.</p>'),
(41, 1, 52, 5, 4, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-08 20:10:43', '<p>The fact that Paul doesn&rsquo;t want the Thessalonians to be surprised by this event means that this event involves them, which would not be true if it was referring to 70AD.</p>'),
(41, 1, 52, 5, 19, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-26 21:27:08', '<p>&ldquo;extinguish&rdquo; I think quench could be confusing to some people.</p>'),
(41, 1, 52, 5, 23, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-08 19:54:21', '<p>This clearly is not talking about AD 70, but uses Parousia. It would be strange for Paul to use Parousia to refer to two different comings of christ, but never specify that there are two comings.</p>'),
(41, 1, 53, 1, 9, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-08 23:39:28', '<p>Doesn&rsquo;t seem like AD 70 &ndash; everlasting destruction</p> <p>It could be that vv. 5-8 or so are about 70AD, but in the end they will pay everlasting destruction.</p>'),
(41, 1, 53, 1, 10, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-05 20:22:48', '<p>this isn&rsquo;t talking about 70AD because the thessalonians will see him here</p>'),
(41, 1, 53, 2, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-29 02:56:36', '<p><strong>This chapter has nothing about the resurrection, judgement, or rapture, it is about the judgement on the man of lawlessness.</strong></p> <p>-----------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>This chapter seems to switch topics from what he was just previously talking about, the end of the world. Here, he begins talking about the lawless one (AD 70).</p> <p><strong>Gathering together with him: see note on matt. 24:31&hellip; Here it functions the same way. With the coming destruction of Jerusalem and the temple, Christians will henceforth be &ldquo;gathered together&rdquo; in a separate and distinct &ldquo;assembly&rdquo; (episunagoge; the church is called a sunagoge in Jas 2:2). After the temple&rsquo;s destruction God will no longer tolerate going up to the temple to worship (it will be impossible!), as Christians frequently do prior to AD 70.</strong></p> <p><strong>In chapter 1 the second advent brings &ldquo;everlasting destruction from the presence of the Lord&rdquo; (1:9); here this coming results in temporal &ldquo;destruction&rdquo; (2:8). There the second advent includes &ldquo;his mighty angels&rdquo; (1:7); here the temporal judgment mentions nothing about these angels (2:1&ndash;12). Thus, the second advent provides an eternal resolution to their suffering; the AD 70 Day of the Lord affords temporal resolution (cf. Rev 6:10).</strong></p>'),
(41, 1, 53, 2, 8, 5, 'What if this is at the Lawless one&rsquo;s apparent coming?? not Jesus&rsquo;s', 99, '2023-01-24 19:34:44', '<p>What is &ldquo;appearance of his coming&rdquo;? The genitive makes no sense here. Maybe: &ldquo;his apparant coming&rdquo;? Descriptive genitive</p> <p>Also: Spirit from his mouth? Breath I think would be more appropriate</p> <p>In Christ&rsquo;s judgment-coming against Jerusalem, we also discover judgment for the man of lawlessness, Nero. Thus, Christians may take comfort in the promised relief from both Jewish and Neronic opposition (2Th 2:15&ndash;17). Not only does Titus destroy Jerusalem within twenty years, but Nero himself dies a violent death in the midst of the Jewish War (June 9, AD 68).</p> <hr /> <p>What if this is at the Lawless one&rsquo;s apparent coming?? not Jesus&rsquo;s</p> <p>This would mean that the passage is not teaching that the Lawless one would be destroyed at Jesus&rsquo; literal second coming but that the lawless one would be destroyed when he appeared on the scene, which basically happened to Nero. This fits the immediate context MUCH better. Verse 9 begins with lit. &ldquo;of whom the coming (same word as in v.8) is according to the working of Satan&rdquo; The subject doesn&rsquo;t switch, it continues (ου &ldquo;who&rdquo; in v. 8 and 9) and the same word is used in back to back sentences (παρουσια), thus I&rsquo;m not sure why we would think that two different comings are being discussed here. I could talk more about this!</p>'),
(41, 1, 53, 2, 9, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:48:45', '<p>Paul said in verses 9-12 that the coming of the lawless one would be accompanied by power, signs, lying wonders, the working of Satan, and unrighteous deception. God would also send delusion to those who &ldquo;did not believe the truth but had pleasure in unrighteousness.&rdquo;</p> <p>In Antiquities of the Jews and Wars of the Jews, Josephus wrote about a phenomenon taking place in the Jewish world before and during the Jewish-Roman War, especially in Judea and Galilee. During this time, said Josephus, there were &ldquo;a great number of false prophets suborned by the tyrants [Zealots] to impose on the people.&rdquo; Here Josephus described the close working relationship between the Zealots and false prophets. Many of the people, he said, were persuaded &ldquo;by these deceivers,&rdquo; who were &ldquo;such as belied God himself&rdquo; (Wars 6.5.2-3).</p> <p>In Antiquities 20.8.6 Josephus wrote the following about numerous false prophets who deceived the Jews during the time of the Procurators Felix (52-58 AD) and Festus (59-62 AD). He mentioned their lying wonders, and showed that they shared the war agenda of the Zealots:</p> <p>&ldquo;These works, that were done by the robbers, filled the city with all sorts of impiety. And now these impostors and deceivers persuaded the multitude to follow them into the wilderness, and pretended that they would exhibit manifest wonders and signs, that should be performed by the providence of God&hellip; And again the robbers stirred up the people to make war with the Romans, and said they ought not to obey them at all; and when any persons would not comply with them, they set fire to their villages, and plundered them.&rdquo;</p> <p>------------------------</p> <p>I personally lean toward Eleazar ben Simon being the man of lawlessness because [1] he made the temple his central command post for the entire first half of the Jewish-Roman War (3.5 years) [2] he oversaw so many lawless acts in the temple for an extended period of time, and [3] he was killed at the time of the temple&rsquo;s destruction. ALL ADAM MAARSCHALK</p>'),
(41, 1, 53, 2, 14, 2, null, 99, '2022-10-07 13:39:54', '<p>We can obtain the glory of Christ, if he was God, we surely would not obtain that level of glory.</p>'),
(41, 1, 54, 1, 9, 0, null, 99, '2022-02-19 16:21:02', '<p>Rebellious here is the same word as unsubmissive in 1 Tim. 2:11-12. Consider changing translation to bring this out.</p>'),
(41, 1, 54, 2, 12, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-11 15:18:01', '<p>Translation: I do not find this argument that we shouldn&rsquo;t translate &ldquo;or&rdquo; convincing at all: Belleville, &ldquo;Teaching and Usurping Authority,&rdquo; 218, gives as examples Matt. 6:20, &ldquo;where thieves neither break in nor steal&rdquo; (i.e., break in with a view to steal); Acts 17:24, God &ldquo;neither dwells in temples made with human hands nor is served by human hands&rdquo; (i.e., dwells in human temples with a view to being served by human hands). The translation proposed here is similar to Belleville&rsquo;s renderings: &ldquo;I do not permit a woman to teach with a view to dominating a man,&rdquo; or, &ldquo;I do not permit a woman to teach a man in a dominating way,&rdquo; 219. <strong>I need to look at Payne&rsquo;s article on this again though.</strong></p> <p><strong>Egalitarian</strong></p> <p>the logic doesn&rsquo;t flow from the complementarian side. If you think about it this would be Paul&rsquo;s logic &ndash; I do not permit a woman to teach or have authority over a man because men were created first and Eve was deceived once. If thereby Paul is saying that women are more easily deceived and should not be teachers, there are two problems with that. First, that means they should not be teaching anybody at any age level or any gender, they are simply more easily deceived than men. Secondly, that is a very high standard that God is holding women to, if God&rsquo;s reasoning is: women were deceived once therefore, they are more easily deceived, therefore, they can never be teachers, have men not done the same thing, and therefore, would be disqualified? Also, if the problem is that women are more easily deceived, why are they encouraged to teach younger women (Titus 2:3-5)? They should not be teaching anybody.</p> <p>1 Tim. 1:3 is huge! Also, 2 Cor. 11:3 seems to show that Paul believed that men could be deceived just as Eve was deceived? Would that not also disqualify them from ministry?</p> <p>&quot;The opposing arguments of what is falsely called &lsquo;knowledge&rsquo; &rdquo; (mentioned in 1 Timothy 6:20-21) involved the belief in female superiority over men because virgin women experienced special union with God and could share their spiritual power and insights with men. Hence Paul condemns people who forbid marriage in the Ephesian church for spiritual reasons (1 Tim. 4:3a). The virgin status of Artemis explains why virginity and celibacy were highly esteemed virtues among some Ephesians, but Paul saw such asceticism as dangerously entangled with local religion. Contrary to a theory popularized by Kroeger in I Suffer Not a Woman, no evidence exists that people in first-century Asia viewed Artemis as a fertility or sex goddess and therefore practiced temple prostitution (see Sondra Gahn, The Identity of Artemis in First-Century Ephesus). Artemis was actually praised as the divine tomboy who could save (&quot;Artemis the Savior&quot; was a common regional epithet) and protect people without any man&rsquo;s help&mdash;a strength celebrated in her great hunting exploits.</p> <p>Only the Egalitarian view properly accounts for v. 15.</p> <p>Also, we need to discuss</p> <p>The account in On the Origin of the World is as follows:</p> <p>After the day of rest Sophia sent her daughter Zoe, being called Eve, as an instructor in order that she might make Adam, who had no soul, arise so that those whom he should engender might become containers of light. When Eve saw her male counterpart prostrate she had pity upon him, and she said, &lsquo;Adam! Become alive! Arise upon the earth!&rsquo; Immediately her word became accomplished fact. For Adam, having arisen, suddenly opened his eyes. When he saw her he said, &ldquo;You shall be called &lsquo;Mother of the Living.&rsquo; For it is you who have given me life.&rdquo; (Ed. James Robinson, &ldquo;On the Origin of the World&rdquo;, The Nag Hammadi Library in English: Revised Edition (San Francisco: Harper, 1988), 115:31-35, 116:1-7.)</p> <p>Support for the idea that Paul is correcting the Ephesian women is also found in his use of &ldquo;not&rdquo; in 1 Tim. 2:14. Paul does not simply say that Eve was deceived. He says, &ldquo;Adam was not deceived, but the Woman...&rdquo; was deceived. He seems to be correcting false teaching regarding the creation narrative, that Adam was the one who was deceived.</p> <p><strong>Complementarian</strong></p> <ol type="1"> <li>If it was because of a lack of knowledge it doesn&rsquo;t make sense why he would say I do not permit you to teach &ldquo;a man&rdquo;, it should be teach <em>at all.</em></li> <li>I can&rsquo;t get over 1 Cor. 11:3 where there is a clear authority structure girl &lt; man &lt; christ&hellip;.</li> </ol> <p>-----------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Why authority instead of Originator?</p> <p>First, because abuse authority is the much more common usage.</p> <p>Secondly because Paul is contrasting authentew with quietness. It makes sense to contrast abusing authority with being quiet and in submission, it does not make sense to contrast false teaching with being quiet.</p> <hr /> <p>3 reasons why it&rsquo;s a woman, not all women, in 1 Timothy 2:12</p> <p>One reason for my belief that verse 12 is about a couple, is Paul&rsquo;s switch from the plural &ldquo;men&rdquo; and &ldquo;women&rdquo; in 1 Timothy 2:8-10 to the singular &ldquo;man&rdquo; and &ldquo;woman&rdquo; in verses 11-12. There is a reason why Paul switched from plural to singular, and we need to pay attention to the apostle&rsquo;s choice of language.[1]</p> <p>The second reason I believe 1 Timothy 2:12 is about a couple is because of the singular verb sōthēsetai in 1 Timothy 2:15. This verb is correctly translated as &ldquo;she will be saved&rdquo; and refers to a woman, not plural women. The plural verb meinōsin &ldquo;they continue&rdquo; in the same verse probably refers to the couple: &ldquo;she [a woman] will be saved &hellip; if they [the couple] continue &hellip;) [2]</p> <p>The third reason I believe 1 Timothy 2:12 is about particular people, and not referring to all women in general, is because the context of the second half of 1 Timothy 2 is the problem behaviour of certain people in the Ephesian church.</p> <p>In 1 Timothy 2:11-15, Paul uses the rhetorical device of asyndeton[3] and narrows his focus to the problem behaviour of one of these rich women. This woman was not ready to teach&mdash;she needed to learn quietly&mdash;and she was acting in a domineering or controlling manner (Greek: authenteō) towards a man, most likely her husband. Her controlling behaviour may have stemmed from a concern about the effects of sex and procreation on salvation, a not uncommon concern in the early church.[4]</p> <p>Two options for understanding 1 Tim. 2:13-14 &ndash;</p> <p>1. Paul is correcting the false teaching that these women were teaching by correctly telling the Genesis story. This can be seen by Paul saying Adam was not deceived but Eve was, his tone seems to be correcting a false thought that Adam was deceived.</p> <ol start="2" type="1"> <li>1 Tim. 2:13-14 serves as a reminder of what happens when you do not learn but take authority when you are not supposed to. Eve took authority, was deceived and deceived Adam.</li> </ol> <ul> <li>The third reason I believe 1 Timothy 2:12 is about particular people, and not referring to all women in general, is because the context of the second half of 1 Timothy 2 is the problem behaviour of certain people in the Ephesian church.</li> <li>V. 11 is the absolute key. This is not for all women for all time. He is addressing a specific problem of a disruptive woman.</li> <li>I really don&rsquo;t think v. 15 is about Eve bearing Jesus, because at this time Jesus was already born. To say that &ldquo;she will be saved through the birth of the Child&rdquo; is quite strange for a woman who has already died and a child who has already been born. v. 15 is not about eve like I thought because it talks in the future tense about her salvation, yet she is dead and gone, and Paul continues to discuss things &ldquo;she&rdquo; must do. This makes no sense if referring to eve.</li> <li>1 Tim. 2:15 is likely also correcting false understandings we know going on in the church about abstaining from marriage 4:3. &ldquo;Against this background Paul assures Timothy (and through him these erring women) that childbirth does not jeopordize salvation, but is perfectly compatible with it- provided that faith, love, holiness and decency are there as well.&rdquo; Article by Steve Moyter.</li> <li>Authentein should be translated &ldquo;have authority&rdquo; or &ldquo;take authority&rdquo; it doesn&rsquo;t seem to necessarily be a negative word. Authentein &ndash; I have identified some 30 examples of this meaning in the extant Greek liter -ature which predates AD 312.24 It should be pointed out that in none of these cases is &lsquo;master&rsquo; used in the pejorative sense of &lsquo;autocrat&rsquo; or &lsquo;despot&rsquo;. In fact, it is used twice in Christian contexts to refer to the lordship of Jesus Christ. <strong>Article by Albert Wolters lists them.</strong></li> </ul> <p>The ancient travel-writer Pausanias remarked that &ldquo;All cities worship Artemis of Ephesus, and all individuals hold her in honour.&rdquo; Guide to Greece 4.31.8. Pausanias wrote his Guide in the early second century CE, but in this quotation, he was writing about a time before 150 BCE. Quotations from Pausanias&rsquo; Guide are taken from Jerome Murphy-O&rsquo;Connor&rsquo;s St Paul&rsquo;s Ephesus: Texts and Archaeology (Collegeville, MN: Liturgical Press, 2008)</p>'),
(41, 1, 54, 2, 15, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-06 17:34:28', '<p>&ldquo;But She will be saved through childbearing if they (her metaphorical children) continue in trust and love and holiness , with good judgement.&rdquo;</p> <p>Interesting interpretation^^^ allegorical. possible...</p> <p>I think this is also correcting wrong information that this &ldquo;woman&rdquo; was teaching. It doesn&rsquo;t make sense to refer to Eve. Why would he add the next line: if they continue&hellip; it just simply makes no sense. But if he was talking about people in Ephesus alive at that time, it makes sense why he would admonish them to continue in trust and love.</p> <p><strong>The Theme of Virginity in the Acts of Paul and Thecla</strong></p> <p>A couple of weeks ago I read the Acts of Paul and Thecla. This work of fiction dates to around 150 AD and is thought to have been written by a presbyter somewhere in Asia Minor.[1] It was well known in the early church, and several prominent early church fathers refer to it (Tertullian, Ambrose, Jerome, Augustine, Methodius, Gregory of Nazianzus, Gregory of Nyssa, and others) which indicates its widespread influence.[2]</p> <p>The repeated theme of virginity and chastity (not having sex) is striking in the Acts of Paul and Thecla. (This theme is a feature in all the Apocryphal Acts.) In the Acts of Paul and Thecla, this theme is apparent from the beginning where Paul brings the &ldquo;word of God&rdquo; in a house church in Iconium. This &ldquo;word of God&rdquo; is mostly about chastity and sexual self-restraint (egkrateia) which is associated with resurrection. Thirteen beatitudes constitute Paul&rsquo;s message; the following four are specifically about chastity:</p> <p>Blessed are those keeping their flesh chaste, because they will be a temple of God.<br /> Blessed are those with self-control (egkrateia), because God will speak to them.<br /> Blessed are those having wives as though not having them (i.e. being married and celibate), because they will receive an inheritance from God.<br /> Blessed are the bodies of virgins, because their bodies are pleasing to God and they will not lose the reward of their chastity; because the word of the Father will be a work of salvation to them in the day of his Son, and they will have rest forever. (Sections 5-6)</p> <p>The last beatitude links virginity with salvation. Paul&rsquo;s supposed message is that the life of a good Christian is a life of celibacy and that chaste living has a bearing on our salvation and on our resurrection.[3] Thecla, the virgin par excellence, embraces this teaching and resolutely remains a virgin despite bitter opposition and mortal danger. And she later becomes a teacher and preacher endorsed by Paul.[4]</p> <p><strong>The Theme of Not Having Children in the Egyptian Gospel</strong></p> <p>Other early Christian writings also extol the virtue of celibacy, and they explicitly connect it with not having children. In the days before relatively safe and widely available contraceptives, having children was not an unexpected result of the sexual union of husband and wife. Several Christian documents that promoted virginity and celibacy, by extension, also promoted not having children. One of these documents is the Gospel of the Egyptians, dated to between 80-150.[5]</p> <p>The Gospel of the Egyptians does not survive as a whole but several early Christian authors quote from it, giving us glimpses of its content and ethos.</p> <p>Ron Cameron writes,</p> <p>&ldquo;Despite the paucity of the extant fragments, the theology of the Gospel of the Egyptians is clear: each fragment endorses sexual asceticism as the means of breaking the lethal cycle of birth and of overcoming the alleged sinful differences between male and female, enabling all persons to return to what was understood to be their primordial and androgynous state. This theology is reflected in speculative interpretations of the Genesis accounts of the Creation and the Fall (Gen. 1:27; 2:16-17, 24; 3:21), according to which the unity of the first man was disrupted by the creation of woman and sexual division. Salvation was thus thought to be the recapitulation of Adam and Eve&rsquo;s primordial state, the removal of the body and the reunion of the sexes.&rdquo;[6]</p> <p>Clement of Alexandria is one person who quoted selections from the Gospel of the Egyptians and provided commentary on them.[7] In Stromata 3.9.66 (written around 200) he provides this quotation: &ldquo;Salome said, &lsquo;How much longer will people (anthrōpoi) continue to die?&rsquo; . . . The Lord answers: &lsquo;So long as women bear children.&rsquo; Salome answers, &lsquo;I have done well, then, in not bearing children.&rsquo;&rdquo;[8]</p> <p>A saying contained in the Gospel of Thomas gives a different account of an incident recorded in Luke 11:27. Jesus&rsquo; supposed statement in saying 79 in the Gospel of Thomas highlights the perceived ideal of celibacy and not having children:</p> <p>&ldquo;A woman from the crowd said to him, &ldquo;Blessed is the womb which bore you and the breasts which nourished you.&rdquo;<br /> [Jesus] said to her, &ldquo;Blessed are those who have heard the word of the Father and have truly kept it. For there will be days when you will say, &lsquo;Blessed is the womb which has not conceived and the breasts which have not given milk.&#39;&rdquo; (Logos 79, Gospel of Thomas) [9]</p> <p><strong>Asceticism and Gnosticism in 1 Timothy</strong></p> <p>The person, or community, who compiled the sayings in the Gospel of Thomas had Gnostic sympathies which included encouraging asceticism. Tertullian, in his work against Gnostics (written sometime around 200), mentions 1 Timothy in the context of the teaching of the Gnostic teachers Marcion (c. 85-160) and Apelles. Tertullian writes, &ldquo;Instructing Timothy, [Paul] attacks those who forbid marriage. This is the teaching taught by Marcion and his follower Apelles.&rdquo; (Prescription Against Heretics 33) Apparently, Marcion did not allow married converts to be baptised.[10]</p> <p>Irenaeus, in his work opposing Gnostic heresies (written about 180), mentions the school of the Gnostic teacher Saturninus who spoke strongly against marriage and procreation. Irenaeus wrote, &ldquo;They say marriage (gamein) and procreation (gennan) are from Satan. Many of those, too, who belong to his school, abstain from animal food, and draw away multitudes by a feigned temperance of this kind.&rdquo; (Against Heresies 1.24.2 cf. 1 Tim. 4:3) Irenaeus likewise criticises the teachings of Tatian (120-180): &ldquo;. . . like Marcion and Saturninus, he declared that marriage was nothing else than corruption and fornication.&rdquo; (Against Heresies 1.28.1) [I provide Irenaeus&rsquo;s paragraph about Tatian in a postscript below.]</p> <p>C.K. Barrett, writing about the Pastoral Letters of the New Testament (which includes First Timothy), notes an implied attack on Paul and his teaching &ldquo;by those Jewish Gnostic Christians whose heretical kind of Christianity lurks in the background of the Pastorals.&rdquo;[11] Gnosticism was a &ldquo;dualistic transcendent religion of salvation&rdquo; that swept across the Roman Empire and was a real threat to apostolic Christianity.[12] Christian Gnosticism syncretised (or combined) Greek philosophical and pagan religious ideas with Christian and Jewish teaching.[13] Asceticism, including celibacy or chastity, was a major tenet of several strands of Gnosticism.</p> <p>There are several indications in First Timothy that the heresy being addressed in the letter was an early or incipient form of Gnosticism that promoted chastity. One of these indicators is 1 Timothy 4:3 where Paul states that some in the church at Ephesus were forbidding marriage. This heretical teaching is one of the factors behind Paul&rsquo;s advice that idle younger widows remarry (1 Tim. 5:11-15). It is possible that Paul&rsquo;s statements in 1 Timothy 2:13-14 corrected some of the many false ideas circulating about Adam and Eve that would become popular among some Gnostic teachers. Furthermore, Gnostic-like beliefs, especially sexual renunciation, may be squarely behind Paul&rsquo;s corrective teaching on salvation in 1 Timothy 2:15.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;The Childbirth&rdquo; or &ldquo;Having Children&rdquo; in 1 Timothy 2:15?</strong></p> <p>Yet she will be saved through childbearing (tēs teknogonias) if they continue in faith, and love, and holiness with moderation. 1 Timothy 2:15</p> <p>1 Timothy 2:15 is an enigmatic verse and several interpretations have been put forward to explain its meaning. Some scholars suggest that this verse is about physical safety during the childbirth process.[14] A few English translations of 1 Timothy 2:15 convey this idea (e.g., NASB; Darby Translation, Moffat Translation, Weymouth New Testament).</p> <p>Another interpretation of verse 15 is that &ldquo;childbearing&rdquo; should be translated as &ldquo;the childbirth&rdquo; (tēs teknogonias) and that it refers to the birth of Jesus Christ, through whom salvation comes. (The ISV, and footnotes in NEB and NLT, convey this idea.) Those who propose &ldquo;the childbirth&rdquo; interpretation highlight the connection between the birth of Jesus Christ and the seed of the woman promised in Genesis 3:15. However, while two verbs in 1 Timothy 2:13-14 are borrowed directly from the Septuagint&rsquo;s version of Genesis 2:7-8, 15 and 3:13 (plassō: form/ mould and apatatō: deceive), 1 Timothy 2:15 has no clear linguistic connection with Genesis 3:15.</p> <p>The definite article is also highlighted in &ldquo;the childbirth&rdquo; interpretation. Abstract nouns, however, are commonly used with a definite article in Greek and these articles are usually left untranslated in English translations. So the definite article may not be significant. Some also make the argument that we can&rsquo;t be sure of the precise meaning of teknogonia.[15] Yet, the cognate infinitive teknogonein appears a few chapters later in 1 Timothy where it is typically translated as &ldquo;to have children&rdquo; or &ldquo;to bear children&rdquo; (1 Tim. 5:14).</p> <p>The difficulty of &ldquo;the childbirth&rdquo; interpretation of 1 Timothy 2:15 is that elsewhere in 1 Timothy, Jesus and salvation are mentioned together plainly, but Jesus is not mentioned in 2:15. I agree with Margaret Davies when she says, &ldquo;Had Christ&rsquo;s birth been the subject, the name Christ Jesus would have been highlighted, as in 1:15 and 2:5.&rdquo;[16] Nevertheless, I believe that salvation, rather than safety, is the meaning in 2:15.[17] The verb sōthēsetai (&ldquo;s/he will be saved&rdquo;) is usually, but not always, used in the New Testament with the meaning of eschatological salvation. For example, &ldquo;&hellip; the one who endures to the end will be saved&rdquo; (Mark 13:13b).</p> <p>I suspect &ldquo;Gnostic, or semi-Gnostic, ideas&rdquo; are the impetus for Paul&rsquo;s teaching in 1 Timothy 2:15.[18] It is plausible that in this verse Paul was assuring a married woman (or women) in the Ephesian church that if she renounced celibacy, had sex with her husband, and became pregnant, she would not jeopardise or lose her salvation. Rather, &ldquo;she will be saved.&rdquo;[19]</p> <p>I suspect Paul&rsquo;s message in 1 Timothy 2:15 is that salvation is not dependent on celibacy and remaining childless, but involves continuing in faith, and love, and holiness (hagiasmos) which are &ldquo;expressions of a saved life.&rdquo;[20] Holiness is an ascetic ideal, but Paul wants holiness &ldquo;with good sense&rdquo; (meta sōphrosunē), or, in moderation. He doesn&rsquo;t want extreme piety or asceticism. By associating holiness with childbirth, he indicates that marriage, sex, and procreation are not opposed to piety as many Christians, including Jewish Proto-Gnostic Christians, were teaching in Ephesus and in many other parts of the Roman world.[21]</p> <p>Paul&rsquo;s teaching about marriage and having children in 1 Timothy 2:15, 4:3-4 and 5:11-15 (cf. Tit. 2:4-5) is distinctly different from the teaching attributed to him in the Acts of Paul and Thecla.[22] And it is the antithesis of the teaching found in many Christian documents that circulated widely in the second century, documents that strongly promoted virginity and chastity as saving virtues.</p>'),
(41, 1, 54, 3, 2, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-07 04:01:20', '<p>Chrysostom&rsquo;s Homily on 1 Tim 3:2 states, &ldquo;This he does not lay down as a rule, as if he [an overseer] must not be without one [a wife], but as prohibiting his having more than one.&rdquo; NPNF1 13:438.</p> <p>in Homily 11 on 1 Timothy 3 John Chrysostom wrote regarding 1 Timothy 3:12, &ldquo;Deacons must be men of one woman. This is appropriate to say regarding women deacons also.&rdquo; That Chrysostom would say this in spite of his opposition to women in leadership demonstrates that it was natural for Greeks to understand &ldquo;man of one woman&rdquo; as a generic masculine intended to apply to both men and women.</p> <p><br /> In context &ldquo;one woman man&rdquo; clearly excludes polygamy and by logical extension may also exclude sexual infidelity. The closest English expression is &ldquo;monogamous.&rdquo; (Philip Payne&rsquo;s words)</p> <p>The phrase, &ldquo;One woman man&rdquo; is not to be taken as, the only people qualified to serve as elder are those who are and have been only married to one woman, because this would disqualify men who are single, divorced, and remarried. Yet, Paul himself and Jesus were both unmarried, would this mean that they are not qualified to be elders? Paul is also not forbidding remarriage with this phrase. George Knight III in his commentary on the Pastoral Epistles, pp. 157-159 writes, &ldquo;it would be strange for the apostle of liberty, who considered widows and widowers &lsquo;free to be married &hellip;, only in the Lord&rsquo; (1 Cor 7:39) and who used this principle of freedom to illustrate his teaching on the law (Rom. 7:1-3), to deny this freedom to a potential church officer whose spouse has died.</p> <p>&ldquo;The real issue is not so much where he has come from but who he is now by God&rsquo;s grace. If a man is currently faithful to his wife, being above reproach, and has proven himself in that relationship, then it is possible for him to become an elder.&rdquo; (Merkle, 40 Questions about Elders and Deacons, 128)</p>'),
(41, 1, 54, 3, 11, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-07 03:29:22', '<p>For one thing, the author could have made things crystal clear by adding διάκονῶν (&ldquo;of deacons&rdquo;) or ἐπίσκοπῶν (&ldquo;of bishops&rdquo;)&mdash;or both, after the word &ldquo;women,&rdquo; had he intended to refer to wives of either or both groups. Since he did not do so, I take it that this is not what he meant.</p> <p>Furthermore, if wives of deacons were intended, why would he list part of the qualifications for deacons, then qualifications for their wives, then finalize his list of qualifications for deacons? If the women in similar positions were to be held to the same high standards as the male deacons, then this makes perfect sense. (NOT MY WORDS)</p> <p>The fact that the four qualifications Paul lists for women [deacons] in 3:11 are virtualy the same and in the same order as the requirements for deacons in 3:8, and because he goes on to give other requirements for deacons in verse 12 shows that verse 11 must also be about the qualifications of deacons. (Phil Payne)</p>'),
