(41, 1, 56, 2, 3, 1, null, 99, '2022-02-19 16:36:06', '<p>Older women teach! So paul in 1 Tim. 2:12 must not be saying that women should not teach because they are more prone to deception. Then they wouldn&rsquo;t be able to teach younger women either.</p>'),
(41, 1, 56, 2, 13, 2, null, 99, '2022-11-08 15:39:12', '<p>Titus 1:4 same words, clearly two distinct people, God and Jesus, yet in the next chapter is he collapsing the two into one person? Is the author dumb? Clearly not. He would not be teaching that God is the Father in Chapter 1 and then that actually God is the Son in chapter 2.</p> <p>SUMMARY - Norton makes some great points and shows the irrelevance of the Granville Sharp Rule in &ldquo;proving&rdquo; the Trinity. The Granville Sharp rule does not apply if it is clear that the two things being discussed are different, for example, with gold and silver. We non-Trinitarians assert that there was no ambiguity in the minds of the first-century readers between God and Jesus. They were known to be different from each other. Because no ambiguity between Christ and God would arise in the minds of the readers if the second article was omitted, it can be (and was) omitted without a problem. Likewise, there was no need for a second article in Matthew 21:12 in the phrase, &ldquo;all the [ones] selling and buying,&rdquo; or in Ephesians 2:20 in the phrase, &ldquo;the apostles and prophets,&rdquo; because no one would ever think that &ldquo;sold&rdquo; and &ldquo;bought&rdquo; meant the same thing, or that &ldquo;apostles&rdquo; and &ldquo;prophets&rdquo; were referring to the same people. This sort of distinction is apparent in numerous passages throughout the Bible.</p> <p>The limitations and exceptions to the rule stated by him are as follows: In this case, then, it appears that the article is not repeated, because its repetition is not necessary to prevent ambiguity.</p> <p>2. No similar rule applies to proper names. &lsquo;The reason,&rsquo; says Middleton, &lsquo;is evident at once; for it is impossible that John and Thomas, the names of two distinct persons, should be predicated of an individual&rsquo; (p. 68).</p> <p>This remark is not to the purpose [i.e., &lsquo;is not correct&rsquo;], for the same individual may have two names. The true reason for this limitation is, that proper names, when those of the same individual, are not connected by a copulative or copulatives, and therefore that, when they are thus connected, no ambiguity arises from the omission of the article.</p> <p>5. Lastly, &lsquo;we find,&rsquo; he says, &lsquo;in very many instances, not only in the plural, but even in the singular number, that where attributives are in their nature absolutely incompatible, i.e., where the application of the rule would involve a contradiction in terms, there the first attributive only has the article, the perspicuity of the passage not requiring the rule to be accurately observed&rsquo; (p. 92).</p> <p>All from STF commentary</p> <p><br /> <span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Titus 2:13 - appearing of the GLORY of our great God and savior Jesus Christ, not of our great God and Saviour Jesus Christ. Those attributes are describing the glory. Also, God is called savior in verse 10! So it would not be strange to call him savior in verse 13 as well. BIG&mdash;- Matthew 16:27 - son of man will come in the glory of his father! Jesus comes in the glory of the father. The grace of God comes in Jesus&rsquo; first coming v. 11, and the glory of God comes in his second coming v. 13 really coooolll!!!!! (Trinity delusion)</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>'),
(41, 1, 57, 1, 1, 0, null, 99, '2022-12-28 15:39:56', '<p>&ldquo;<strong>a prisoner for the sake of Christ Jesus.</strong>&rdquo; The literal greek is simply &ldquo;a prisoner of Christ Jesus&rdquo; but in Greek the &ldquo;of&rdquo; is just the genitive and can have many possible meanings. Basically, the genitive can be summed up as one thing relating to another in some way. So, for our context here, it is that Paul is a prisoner in some way related to Christ Jesus.</p> <p>When translators (NASB, CSB, NIV) translate it as simply &ldquo;of&rdquo; it makes it sound possessive, in other words, Paul is Christ&rsquo;s prisoner. However, this is not the meaning we think Paul meant here by calling himself a prisoner. We must remember that this is one of Paul&rsquo;s prison epistles and that he is in prison as he is writing this, which he mentions later in Philemon 1:10. For this reason, we believe that Paul is referring to his imprisonment by Rome for the sake of Christ, not that he is Christ&rsquo;s prisoner.</p>');
