(41, 1, 58, 1, 6, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:50:23', '<p>The &ldquo;world&rdquo; here, as various commenters note, is the new era initiated by Christ. It is at his exaltation that the angels are commanded to worship him &ndash; that is the author&rsquo;s thought. And it is at his resurrection or exaltation that he is &ldquo;begotten,&rdquo; fully becoming Son/King. (Romans 1:4) This writer in Hebrews 2:5 says &ldquo;Now God did not subject the coming world, about which we are speaking, to angels&rdquo; &ndash; using the same word, oikoumene. Again, the whole context here is to then-recent events, especially Jesus&rsquo;s exaltation. -TRINITIES.</p>'),
(41, 1, 58, 1, 7, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:50:38', '<p>I really think the author here is arguing that angels are or can be temporary (v. 7), whereas Jesus and his kingdom will last forever (vv. 8-12).</p> <p>The author is taking the LXX translation or mistranslation of Ps 104:4 (ὁ ποιῶν κτλ., a nominative without a verb, as in 1 Co 3:19) to mean that God can reduce angels to the elemental forces of wind and fire, so unstable is their nature, whereas the person and authority of the Son are above all change and decay. The meaning might also be that God makes angels out of wind and fire; but this is less apt. Our author takes the same view as the author of 4 Esdras, who (8:21) writes:</p> <p>&ldquo;Before whom the heavenly host stands in terror,</p> <p>and at thy word change to wind and fire.&rdquo;</p> <p>Rabbinic traditions corroborate this interpretation; e.g. &ldquo;every day ministering angels are created from the fiery stream, and they utter a song and perish&rdquo; (Chagiga, ed. Streane, p. 76), and the confession of the angel to Manoah in Yalkut Shimeoni, ii. 11. 3: &ldquo;God changes us every hour &hellip; sometimes he makes us fire, at other times wind.&rdquo;</p> <p>The interest of rabbinic mysticism in the nature of angels is illustrated by the second century dialogue between Hadrian, that &ldquo;curiositatum omnium explorator,&rdquo; and R. Joshua ben Chananja (cp. W. Bacher, Agada der Tannaiten2, i. 171&ndash;172). The emperor asks the rabbi what becomes of the angels whom God creates daily to sing His praise; the rabbi answers that they return to the stream of fire which flows eternally from the sweat shed by the Beasts supporting the divine throne or chariot (referring to the vision of Ezekiel and the &ldquo;fiery stream&rdquo; of Dn 7:10). From this stream of fire the angels issue, and to it they return. Λειτουργούς of angels as in Ps 103:21 (λειτουργοὶ αὐτοῦ, ποιοῦντες τὸ θέλημα αὐτοῦ).</p> <p>James Moffatt, A Critical and Exegetical Commentary on the Epistle to the Hebrews, International Critical Commentary (Edinburgh: T&amp;T Clark International, 1924), 12.</p>'),
(41, 1, 58, 1, 8, 2, 'Check my note for next time we talk about it with Jerry', 99, '2023-01-27 02:35:55', '<p><strong>Possible:</strong> This is about the one true God:</p> <p>&quot;Your throne, O God, is forever and ever,</p> <p>the scepter of uprightness is the scepter of your kingdom.&quot;</p> <p>This is about the anointed one who is anointed by the one true God:</p> <p>&quot;You have loved righteousness and hated wickedness;</p> <p>therefore God, your God, has anointed you</p> <p>with the oil of gladness beyond your companions.&quot;</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Psa. 7:2 &ndash; Κύριε ὁ θεός μου very common, O lord, my God.</p> <p>Psa. 53:6 &ndash; ὁ κύριος ἀντιλήμπτωρ &ldquo;the lord is the protector,&rdquo; notice no article (same thing in Psa. 58:10)</p> <p>Psa. 61:9 &ndash; ὁ θεὸς βοηθὸς ἡμῶν &ldquo;God is our helper&rdquo; no article</p> <p>So, we don&rsquo;t really have any clear grammatical parallels. Overall, I think I would just stick with what we have because of the context where the God has a God.</p> <p>Need to figure out why UBS thinks if it is autou then we should translate it &ldquo;your throne is God&rdquo;? p. 663, A Textual Commentary on the Greek New Testament, United Bible Societies, 1971. Nevermind, I get it, the &ldquo;his kingdom&rdquo; would be in reference to God&rsquo;s kingdom. Therefore the &ldquo;You&rdquo; the whole time would be in reference to Jesus: &ldquo;God is your throne&rdquo; and &ldquo;God, your God&rdquo; has anointed you. EHHH BUT this whole scheme makes the Septuagint reading very different from the NT?</p> <p>If the last word in Hebrews 1:8 is autou, this actually really changes things. It would mean that &ldquo;the scepter of uprightness is the scepter of his kingdom.&rdquo; This means that there are two characters in view in this verse: God, and someone who is over the Kingdom (i.e. &ldquo;his kingdom&rdquo;). This resolves the tension that the King is being called God.</p> <p>They also noted that later manuscripts which read &ldquo;your (sou) kingdom&rdquo; are now in agreement with the corresponding passage in the Greek OT Septuagint! (Remember that the UBS Committee recognizes, as do most Bible scholars, that the NT manuscript that differs slightly from the Septuagint is more likely to be correct than another one which perfectly agrees because copyists strongly tended to deliberately &ldquo;correct&rdquo; Septuagint quotes they found in the NT .)</p> <p>Reasons from a Trinitarian why it should be &ldquo;your throne is God&rdquo;: Statistically, (ὁ θεὸς) is rendered &ldquo;God&rdquo; hundreds of times in the NT, as opposed to the scant few times (3x) as &ldquo;O God.&rdquo; Going with the odds again, the author of Hebrews (Paul for me) uses (ὁ θεὸς) as &ldquo;God&rdquo; dozens of times and only one other time as a vocative, 10:7. When we look to the context, Hebrews 1:7, it is God speaking to a worshipper about the angels, and so, he is not being addressed. In 1:8, it is God speaking to a worshipper about the Son, and so God again is not being addressed, The following verse, Hebrews 1:9, God is still talking to a worshipper about the Son, saying of the Son, &ldquo;You have loved righteousness and hated wickedness; therefore God, your God, has anointed you &hellip;,&rdquo; meaning here, again, it is not God being addressed. The author of Hebrews is quoting from Psalm 45:6, which was being addressed to a human king, likely King Solomon, who actually sat on God&rsquo;s throne.</p> <p>----------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Both from the immediate context and with the presence of translation problems, there are quite a few reasons why we do not believe that this verse is not calling Jesus &ldquo;God&rdquo; nor should it be translated, &ldquo;Your throne, O God, is forever and ever.&rdquo;</p> <p>First, evidence that the psalm is speaking of a human king is in Psalm 45:7, which says, &ldquo;You have loved righteousness and hated wickedness. Therefore God, your God, has anointed you with the oil of exultation above your peers.&rdquo; That the text calls God, &ldquo;your God,&rdquo; i.e., the king&rsquo;s God, shows that the king is inferior to God. &ldquo;God&rdquo; does not have a God. It would make no sense to be calling the king &ldquo;God&rdquo; here, as the clear biblical teaching is that there is one God (1 Cor. 8:6; John 5:44; 17:3), so if Jesus is the one true God, how could he have a God?</p> <p>Secondly, the context of both Hebrews 1 and Psalm 45 make it clear that this king being referred to is not the supreme God because this king has been blessed by God (Psa. 45:2), has a wife (Psa. 45:9), and simply put, he is a human king (Psa. 45:1, 5, 13, 15), not the supreme God. We also know this passage in Psalm 45 is not originally about Jesus because the king has a wife. The queen is said to be a woman of foreign descent, possibly from Tyre (Ps. 45:12) who was told to forget her own people and father&rsquo;s house (Ps. 45:10), and she and her husband have an ivory house (Ps. 45:8). Those facts have led some commentators to suggest that this psalm is referring to the marriage of the Phoenician princess Jezebel to King Ahab, who had an ivory palace (1 Kings 22:39). But that is untenable since Ahab does not fit the characteristics of a godly king that are so prominent in the psalm. Solomon, who also married foreign women and lived in luxury, is a much more likely candidate.</p> <p>Thus, the original quote in Psalm 45:6 is not actually referring to Jesus, but originally refers to an Old Testament king, but also finds later application in Jesus. If the verse is calling the king &ldquo;God,&rdquo; then that would make both Solomon and Jesus God, which is untenable, and there is no internal reason to apply Psalm 45:6 to the Messiah without verse 7 applying to the same king. That would be eisegesis, reading into the verse to make it fit one&rsquo;s theology. If the psalm is calling the Messiah &ldquo;God,&rdquo; then the Davidic king is also God. So, if a Trinitarian is using this verse to prove Jesus is God, it actually would prove too much and make Solomon God too.</p> <p>Thirdly, the king&rsquo;s God &ldquo;anointed&rdquo; him, setting him above his &ldquo;peers.&rdquo; This is evidence against a Trinitarian interpretation of the verse for a number of reasons. One is that &ldquo;God&rdquo; does not have any peers to be set above, whereas the human king of Israel, including the Messiah, does have peers. The Messiah, Jesus Christ, did have peers because he was completely human and not a God-man as Trinitarian theology asserts. Also, Psalm 45:7 says this king loved righteousness and hated wickedness, and &ldquo;therefore&rdquo; God anointed him. This makes perfect sense if the king is human, but if this king is &ldquo;God,&rdquo; was he really anointed because he loved righteousness? It makes no sense that &ldquo;God&rdquo; needed to be anointed at all.</p> <p><strong>Translation</strong>:</p> <p>Now let us address some reasons why Hebrews 1:8 should not be translated, &ldquo;Your throne, O God, is forever and ever.&rdquo; Although &ldquo;Your throne, O god, is forever and ever&rdquo; is a legitimate translation of Hebrews 1:8, there is evidence that &ldquo;Your throne is God forever and ever&rdquo; is actually a better translation.</p> <p>The renowned Greek scholar and Trinitarian, A. T. Robertson noted that the Greek word <em>theos</em> (God) could be understood as a vocative, &ldquo;O God,&rdquo; or as a nominative, as in the phrase, &ldquo;God is thy throne&rdquo; or &ldquo;Thy throne is God.&rdquo; He wrote: &ldquo;Either [translation] makes good sense.&rdquo; While it is true that from a strictly translational point of view either a vocative or nominative translation is acceptable, all translation is informed by context and scope, and the context strongly argues against the translation &ldquo;Your throne, O God.&rdquo;</p> <ol type="1"> <li>There is a very good reason for believing that the correct translation of Psalm 45:6 is &ldquo;God is your throne,&rdquo; or some other translation (some are given below) that takes &ldquo;God&rdquo; as referring to the Most High God and not a human &ldquo;god.&rdquo; If Psalm 45:6 is translated, &ldquo;Your throne, O God&hellip;,&rdquo; then Psalm 45:6 would be the only verse in the whole Bible in which a human being is directly and personally addressed as &ldquo;god.&rdquo; There are times when humans are referred to as gods (John 10:33-34) or as a god to someone else (Moses over Pharoah in Ex. 7:1), meaning that they act as a god over that person, they rule over them; but nowhere else in the Bible is a human being personally addressed as &ldquo;god.&rdquo; Added to that evidence is the fact that &ldquo;Elohim&rdquo; occurs four times in the psalm (Ps. 45:2, 6, and 45:7 (twice)), and three of them clearly refer to God, so it fits the psalm that the fourth would also refer to God the Father.</li> <li>Robert Alter gives another argument why &ldquo;O God&rdquo; is likely not the correct translation. In <em>The Hebrew Bible: A Translation with Commentary</em> writes &ldquo;Some construe the Hebrew here to mean, &lsquo;Your throne, O God,&rdquo; but it would be anomalous to have an address to God in the middle of the poem because the entire psalm is directed to the king or to his bride.&rdquo;</li> <li>Another argument for the translation, &ldquo;Your throne is God forever and ever,&rdquo; is that it matches the parallelism in the Greek between Hebrews 1:8a and 1:8b. In Hebrews 1:8b we have two nominative nouns and in English we add an &ldquo;is&rdquo; in between. This looks like: &ldquo;the scepter (nominative noun) of uprightness is the scepter (nominative noun) of your kingdom.&rdquo; It is very common in both Greek and Hebrew to add a &ldquo;to be&rdquo; verb to make a sentence understandable in English, and almost every modern translation translates Hebrews 1:8b this way. Interestingly, the first half of the verse has the same construction, a nominative noun and then another nominative noun with no verb. Thus, it is fitting to supply an &ldquo;is&rdquo; in between these two nouns just as most translations do in the second half of the verse. Hebrews 1:8a would read &ldquo;Your throne (nominative noun) is God (nominative noun)&rdquo; and 1:8b reads, &ldquo;the scepter (nominative noun) of uprightness is the scepter (nominative noun) of your kingdom.&rdquo; So, it would make the parallelism flow beautifully, in that there are two metaphors being used of this king and his kingdom. God is metaphorically his throne (or his source of authority) and the scepter of uprightness is metaphorically the scepter of his kingdom. In other words, this king rules with righteousness instead of a physical scepter.</li> </ol> <p>The main argument against the translation &ldquo;Your throne is God,&rdquo; is that the phrase does not make sense to some people. But we must understand that the verse is not using &ldquo;throne&rdquo; as a seat, a chair, but as it is often used in the Bible, as a source of authority. In fact, if &ldquo;throne&rdquo; is understood to be a chair then the verse does not make sense: the &ldquo;throne&rdquo; is the source of authority. In essence, the verse is saying, &ldquo;your source of authority is God.&rdquo; For example, when David chose Solomon to be king, one of David&rsquo;s top men, Benaiah said to David, &ldquo;&hellip;may he [Yahweh] be with Solomon and make his throne greater than the throne of my lord king David&rdquo; (1 Kings 1:37). In speaking of Solomon&rsquo;s &ldquo;throne&rdquo; being greater than David&rsquo;s, Benaiah was saying that Solomon would have more authority and dominion than David did, which came to pass. The use of &ldquo;throne&rdquo; referring to the authority that the throne represents also occurs in the New Testament. When the angel Gabriel appeared to Mary, he told her she would give birth to the Messiah and he said, &ldquo;the Lord God will give to him the throne of his father David&rdquo; (Luke 1:32). In saying that Mary&rsquo;s son would have the &ldquo;throne&rdquo; of David, he meant the authority that the throne represented. That authority went all the way back to God&rsquo;s promise to David that his &ldquo;throne&rdquo; would endure forever, which is why Gabriel then said, &ldquo;...he will reign over the house of Jacob forever, and of his kingdom there will be no end&rdquo; (Luke 1:33).</p> <p>&ldquo;Your throne is God forever&rdquo; means that God is the authority, the &ldquo;throne&rdquo; of the king, and the king reigns with the authority of God. This king, and by extension the Messiah, the true king of Israel, has been specially anointed by God (Psa. 45:7).</p>'),
(41, 1, 58, 1, 10, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-27 03:09:20', '<p>Perhaps, he is just using an old creation passage and applying it to Jesus, through whom the New creation comes, and the reason he quotes through v. 12 is because it emphasizes the eternality of Jesus. NOPE</p> <p>There is one thing that is clear that should influence our interpretation of the passage. The phrase, &ldquo;the heavens are the works of your hands&rdquo; is cleared up by Psalm 8 and Hebrews 2:7, they are the works of the Father&rsquo;s hands, because Jesus is set over the works of the Father&rsquo;s hands (Heb. 2:7 i think) not his own hands. Therefore, however we want to interpret vv. 10-12 it should be in light of this. There is something else we must note that influences the interpretation of this passage. Hebrews 2:5 states &ndash; For he did not put the inhabited world that is about to come (about which we are speaking) in subjection to angels&mdash; and since Hebrews 2:1-4 is not about the new creation, we should be looking for the New Creation in Hebrews chapter 1.</p> <p>Thus, two things should inform our understanding of Hebrews 1:10-12. First, it is the works of the Father&rsquo;s hands, and secondly, he is likely referring to the new creation.</p> <p>Hebrews 1:10-12 is fairly clearly about the new creation when reading it with fresh eyes. It speaks of heaven and earth being rolled up, and &ldquo;changed like a garment&rdquo; (Heb. 1:11). This is exactly what we get from New Testament prophecies concerning the new creation (1 Cor. 15, 2 Pet. 3). You might ask, what does this have to do with Jesus? Well, this new creation is what Jesus is going to reign over at God&rsquo;s right hand (Heb. 1:13). This is the exact connection the author makes in Hebrews 2:7, he says, &ldquo;You crowned him with glory and honor, and set him over the works of your hands. 8You put all things in subjection under his feet.&rdquo; And he goes on to say, &ldquo;Now in putting all things in subjection to him, he left nothing that is not subject to him. But now we do not yet see all things subjected to him.&rdquo; (Heb. 2:8). Notice the present tense of v. 8, &ldquo;he left nothing that <em>is not</em> subject to him.&rdquo; Thus, Jesus is currently reigning over all things in the new creation, but the author clarifies that there is a future time when we will see all things subjected to him. The argument throughout Hebrews 1:10-12 to Hebrews 2:5 to Hebrews 2:7-8 is that there is a new creation that will occur (&ldquo;changed like a garment&rdquo; in Heb. 1:11 and &ldquo;we will see all things&rdquo; in Heb. 2:8), and Jesus has been set over this new creation (Heb. 1:13; 2:8).</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------</p> <p>Is it reasonable to suppose that in a section where the author is trying to establish for his readers the fact of the son&rsquo;s superior status compared to angels, that he would pull a passage out of the OT that speaks of God creating the the heavens and the earth and simply apply it to the son, even though it makes no mention of the son. How would this be convincing to the readers? It seems to me that this would only be effective if the readers already believed that the son was Yahweh, the creator. But if they already believed this then the whole exercise of the author in this chapter is superfluous; you would not have to prove to Jews that the Creator is superior to angels.</p> <ul> <li>If this is about angels it makes sense why the author then goes on in v. 13 to say, &ldquo;BUT to which of his angels has he ever said&rdquo;, this only makes sense if the thing he said right before was about angels!</li> </ul> <p>Structure: 8-9 Jesus</p> <p>10-12 angels</p> <p>13 Jesus</p> <p>14 angels</p> <p>The mention of &lsquo;the heavens&rsquo; would have evoked the thought of angels in the mind of 1st century Jews.</p> <p>Psalm 33:6 is a big one! It directly connects Heavens with hosts or angels</p> <p>Deut. 32:43 (LXX) &ndash; &ldquo;Rejoice you heavens with him, and let all the angels of God worship him.&rdquo;<br /> Here the &lsquo;heavens&rsquo; and the &lsquo;angels&rsquo; are synonymous thoughts, thus the heavens implies the angels.<br /> <br /> Ps. 89:5 &ndash; &ldquo;The heavens praise your wonders, O Yahweh, also your faithfulness in the assembly of the holy ones.&rdquo;<br /> To say that the heavens praise Yahweh is to say that those in the heavens praise Yahweh.</p> <p>Neh. 9:6 &ndash; &ldquo;You alone are Yahweh. You created the heavens, the highest heavens with all their host, the earth and all that is on it, the seas and all that is in them. You give life to all of them, and the heavenly host worships You.&rdquo;</p> <p>Deut. 32:1 &ndash; &ldquo;Listen, O heavens, and I will speak; hear O earth, the words of my mouth.&rdquo;</p> <p>So it is both reasonable to conclude and probable that the author of Hebrews quoted Ps. 102:25-27 specifically because of the clause which states that the heavens will be rolled up like a robe and like a garment be changed, and that his readers would have understood this. His point would be that while the throne of the son will last for ever, whatever function angels presently have is only temporary and will come to an end. In order to get the flow of the author&rsquo;s thought I will combine the two citations but only with the pertinent clauses, according to what I think the author&rsquo;s purpose was in citing each passage.<br /> <br /> But to the son [it says], &ldquo;Your throne, O god, will last for ever and ever . . .<br /> and [it also says] . . . the heavens (and by implication those who rule in the heavens) . . . will wear out like a garment. You will role them up like robe; like a garment they will be changed . . .&rdquo;</p> <p>So then, this view of the passage solves all of the problems that are inherent in the other views, both the trinitarian and BU views. It also maintains the original context of Psalm 102 and the flow of thought of the author&rsquo;s argument. ALL FROM TROY SALLINGER</p> <hr /> <p>There are three predominate BU interpretations: 1.The author does intend that Ps. 102:25-27 refers to the son, but that the creation of the heavens and earth refer to the new creation not the original one. Hence, the son is the creator of the new heavens and earth. 2.The author does not intend the verse to refer to the son but to the Father, and he employs it to show the everlasting nature of God&rsquo;s kingdom in the words, &ldquo;But you remain the same, and your years will never end.&rdquo; 3. Through wisdom Christology, Jesus is the embodiment of wisdom and we know that God created all things through his wisdom, so in this way it could be said of Jesus that he created the heavens and the earth. None of these interpretations is satisfying for the following reasons: #1 is untenable because it would involve the perishing of the new heavens and earth. Attempts have been made to alleviate this problem but they are not convincing. Plus this understanding has the same problem that the trinitarian interpretation has, i.e. the passage does not mention the son at all. #2 doesn&rsquo;t seem right because it breaks the flow of thought of the whole passage, in which the author is switching back and forth between citing verses about the son and verses about angels. Why would the author interrupt this flow to simply show that Yahweh created the heavens and the earth? #3 doesn&rsquo;t work because there are no hints in the passage at all that we are to make this connection. Nothing in all of Hebrews 1 talks about Jesus as wisdom, and certainly nothing in v. 10-12 compares wisdom and Jesus at all. Also, Hebrews 1:2 is not talking about Jesus creating all things, but creating the &ldquo;ages&rdquo;, or the new creation, the new covenant age. This option seems to be totally reading into the text. Widsom is not personified anywhere in this text. MOST IS FROM TROY SALLINGER</p> <p>---------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p><strong>Why this verse does not prove Trinitarianism:</strong></p> <p><strong>Context:</strong></p> <p><strong>1. Jesus is said to be the heir of all things, how could Jesus be heir, if he is God and created all things.</strong></p> <ol start="2" type="1"> <li><strong>Jesus became better than the angels after his sacrifice and resurrection (Heb. 1:4), not before. Before his resurrection he was made a little lower than the angels (Heb. 2:7). How could God be lower than the angels, his own creation?</strong></li> <li><strong>Jesus inherited a name more excellent than the angels (Heb. 1:4), namely &ldquo;Son&rdquo; (Heb. 1:5-6). It would be much more simple to call Jesus, God, then his name would be superior, but rather the scriptures teach that Jesus is the Son of God.</strong></li> </ol> <p><strong>The Verse itself:</strong></p> <ol type="1"> <li><strong>The verse is talking about God not Jesus. (The quotation from Psalm 102 in the LXX! is the psalmist talking about God and to God).</strong></li> <li><strong>Clearly, the &ldquo;works of your hands&rdquo; are the Father&rsquo;s in 2:8, so it makes the most sense to understand the &ldquo;works of your hands&rdquo; in 1:10 to be the Father&rsquo;s as well.</strong></li> <li><strong>Structurally, it makes more sense to understand Hebrews 1:10-12 to go with Hebrews 1:13-14. The &ldquo;de&rdquo; (but) introducing v. 13 typically means that something is being contrasted with the previous thought.</strong></li> <li><strong>The overall argument of the author makes more sense to understand it as the Father&rsquo;s works in vv. 10-12, not Jesus&rsquo; works (see argument analysis below).</strong></li> <li><strong>Jesus cannot be credited with the exact same thing that the Father is credited with, that would be a case of confusing persons. Even with the abomination of Desolation which had multiple people fit that title, the bible speaks of multiple abominations of desolation (Antiochus Epiphanies in Ez. 36 and Nero or Titus in Matt. 24), yet they are desolating TWO DIFFERENT THINGS. They are not credited with desolating the exact same things, in the same way we cannot credit Jesus with the exact same thing as the Father.</strong></li> </ol> <p><strong>Why did the author of Hebrews choose this passage particularly?</strong></p> <p><strong>I think the purpose of this quote is to help explain what exactly Jesus is reigning over at God&rsquo;s right hand. Hebrews 1:10-12 explains that it is not just the old creation (v. 10) but also the new creation (v. 11) which Jesus will be reigning over. So, when we read that Jesus is reigning over the works of God&rsquo;s hands (2:8) and over all things (2:8b), we understand that to be the present heavens and earth and the new heavens and earth. This also aligns nicely with what he goes on to say in Hebrews 2:8. Namely, that all things have been put in subjection to Jesus (2:8b) but we do not yet see all things that are subjected to him (2:8c), because the new heavens and earth will also be subjected to him. Understanding Hebrews 1:10-12 to be in reference to the Father agrees much more nicely with Hebrews 2:5-8 than understanding vv. 10-12 to be in reference to Jesus.</strong></p> <hr /> <p>Argument analysis:</p> <p><strong>Doesn&rsquo;t make sense:</strong></p> <p>1. Jesus created the old heavens and earth.</p> <ol start="2" type="1"> <li>But no angel has been asked to reign over all things with God (v. 13). Rather, they are servants (v. 14).</li> </ol> <p>OR</p> <ol type="1"> <li>Jesus created the New Heavens and Earth.</li> <li>But no angel has been asked to reign over all things with God (v. 13). Rather, they are servants (v. 14).</li> </ol> <p><strong>Does make sense:</strong></p> <p>1. God created all things.</p> <ol start="2" type="1"> <li>But no angel has been asked to reign over all things with God (v. 13). Rather, they are servants (v. 14)</li> </ol> <p>ALSO: I can&rsquo;t imagine &ldquo;the works of your hands in v. 10 to be Jesus&rsquo; works, and the &ldquo;works of your hands&rdquo; in 2:8 to be the Father&rsquo;s works. This would be quite strange.</p> <p>The argument is</p> <p>God created all things (v. 10-12) and he has subjected all things under Christ&#39;s feet (v. 13). This flows perfectly with what follows: For God did not subject to angels the world to come...<br /> You have placed all in subjection under his feet (2:5-8)</p> <p>You have appointed him over the works of Your hands. (in Psa. 8:6, from which this is quoted in Hebrews 2:5-8; Psa. 8:4-5).</p> <p>Observe carefully how the writer is reasserting the same message. In chapter one he refers to the works of God&#39;s hands and then asks to which angel has God ever asked to sit at His right hand. To sit at God&#39;s right hand is to have authority over all heaven and earth (see Matthew 28:18). Now observe how he says the same thing again in chapter 2. God placed all His creation under Jesus&#39; feet, all the works of His hands. BOTH passages are about God giving Jesus authority over all His creation.</p> <p>1:10 You Lord in the beginning laid the foundation of the earth. The heavens are the WORKS OF YOUR HANDS</p> <p>1:13 - God has appointed Jesus over all things.</p> <p><br /> 2:8 You have appointed him (Jesus) over ALL THINGS AND PUT ALL THINGS UNDER HIS FEET.</p> <p>It is abundantly clear who the writer had in mind in verse 10, the Father, and the works of the Father&#39;s hands, the Father who asked Jesus to sit at His right hand (v.13) thereby appointing Jesus over the works of His hands.</p> <p>The Trinitarian claim is based on a wishful assumption that God is saying a second thing to the Son when he sees the word &quot;AND&quot; at the beginning of verse 10. However, the evidence forcefully shows that God is not the speaker at verse 6 or verse 7 or verse 8. The writer uses the Greek verb legei at verses 6 and 7 which must be translated as &quot;IT says&quot; since God did not say these words. The writer&#39;s style is also to use kai (&quot;and&quot;) to introduce a new argument. Hebrews 1:10-12 is not to be read as a unit with Hebrews 1:8-9 but to be read as a unit with verse 13. Moreover, we have several contrasts in this chapter between what God does for Jesus vs. what God does for the angels. In verse 13, we find that HE asks Jesus to sit at his right hand, something he has never asked an angel to do. Who is this HE but the Lord of verse 10? And that is very the point of Hebrews 1:10-12, that is, in all the history of creation, from beginning to end, God the Father has never ever asked, and never will ask, an angel to sit at His right hand. The heavens are the works of the Father&#39;s hands and He has not appointed an angel (see 2:5) but He has appointed a man, the son of man, Jesus, over all the works of His hands by seating Jesus at His right hand crowning him with glory and honor. The writer&#39;s words at verses 2:5-8 leave absolutely no doubt who he had in mind at verse 1:10ff. The Father in the beginning laid the foundation of the earth; the heavens are &quot;the works of His hands&quot; (v. 1:10) and He has now appointed Jesus over these &quot;works of His hands&quot; (2:7).</p> <p>ALL from ANGELFIRE ^^^</p> <p><strong>IF you understand as new creation passage, which I DONT right now:</strong></p> <p>It is common for the writer of Hebrews to apply OT texts that formerly were applicable word for word to people like David and Solomon to Yeshua in separate applications and fulfillments and never because he&#39;s a person of their essences, of course. (2 Sam 7:14, Heb. 1:5, Ps. 45:6, Heb. 1:8) So it shouldn&#39;t be any wonder that he would do the same thing with creation scriptures because there is an old one and a new one. Well, we have, in context, the &quot;inhabited earth to come&quot; (2:9), &quot;the last days&quot; (1:2), and a &quot;kingdom&quot;(1:8), etc. How apropos considering that in the context of Psalm 102 in the LXX (which is what Hebrews is quoting), we have &ldquo;the generation to come&rdquo; and &quot;the people that shall be created&quot; (v. 18) Really, nothing more should have to be said. It&#39;s obvious Yeshua is agent of the new creation. Isaiah 51:16 sheds light. Here Yahweh says prophetically:<br /> <br /> &quot;I have put My words in your mouth and have covered you with the shadow of My hand, to establish the heavens, to found the earth, and to say to Zion, &#39;You are My people.&#39;&quot;</p> <p>HUGE not my writing.</p> <p>If the texts are about a new creation, how could such ever be &quot;changed&quot;? I think this is actually very key for understanding this passage and seeing that it is a new creation passage (Hebrews 2:5; I think this is a summary statement saying that everything up to that point is discussing the new creation). He says this statement for future generations. So, one key thing here is acknowledging the tense of the verbs.</p> <p>There are different verb tenses going on here that help bring clarity to the meaning of the text. It is not an example like Isa. 53 (he WAS despised and rejected) clearly putting a past tense on a prophecy. This is different, all of the verbs in this quotation in Hebrews 1:10-12 are in the future besides those in v. 10 which are past (laid) and present (are the works). Why this shift from past to future? Well, because this act of new creation had already been accomplished by the time of the writing of the book of Hebrews. Jesus has &quot;figuratively&quot; laid the foundation of the earth and the heavens (new creation in Christ, 2 Cor. 5), and even this creation that Jesus has inaugurated will pass away and be replaced by the everlasting kingdom. Some scholars understand Heb. 1:10-12 to be referring to the millenial kingdom that Jesus will lead, and then that kingdom will pass away and be replaced by the eternal kingdom of Rev. 21. However, that reading mistakenly throws all of the verbs into the future. They read &quot;laid&quot; and &quot;are&quot; as future, instead of as accomplished acts. Therefore, that argument does not stand.</p> <p>Ehh^^</p> <p>-------------------------------------</p> <p>Psalm 102 is discussing the everlasting kingdom, so when we arrive at Heb. 1:10-12, we should expect the author to be using Psa. 102 in this way. This is exactly what we observe.</p> <p>The author of Hebrews&rsquo; point in Heb. 1:10 is not to say that Jesus created the heavens and the earth. This becomes clear when looking at the emphasis of the quotation and the context of Psa. 102. When looking at this quotation&rsquo;s emphasis, 2/3 of the quote concerns the temporality of creation and how it will pass away (Heb. 1:11-12) and 1/3 of the quote concerns the creation of the world. In context Psalm 102 is clearly discussing the eternality of God&#39;s future kingdom. Psalm 102:3-11 is discussing David&#39;s temporality, that his days are like a shadow and that he withers away like the grass (Psa. 102:11). Psalm 102:12 contrasts David with God who is enthroned forever. The temporality of David&#39;s days contrasted with the eternality of God&#39;s days is contrasted again in Psalm 102:24. This is the verse directly preceding our text (Psalm 102:25-27). Therefore, it is clear that the context of this quote in Psalm 102:25-27 deals with the eternality of God in opposition to the fading away of all other things.</p> <p>Not only would this be the only place that this is taught (embedded in an OT quotation) but why does the author go on to quote Psalm 102:26-27 along with v. 25? Why wouldn&rsquo;t the author of Hebrews just quote Psalm 102:25 and then stop? Because the creation of the world is not the purpose of this quotation. The purpose is to show the eternality of God&rsquo;s kingdom even over the physical creation which is temporal and will &ldquo;wear out&rdquo;.</p> <p>There is another problem with using Hebrews 1:10 to say that Jesus is the creator of the world. Namely, that by doing so, you are making Jesus = The Father, and Trinitarians do not want to do this. In context, the OT quotation is referring to the Father, because consistently throughout the OT, the Father is the only one credited with the creation of all things (Gen. 1:1; Psa. 121:2). There is no possible way to reasonably believe that Psa. 102:25 was referencing Jesus, and luckily, most scholars would agree that Psa. 102:25 is in reference to the Father. So, therefore, it is poor exegesis to say, &ldquo;Look, in Hebrews, Lord is referring to Jesus, but that exact same Lord in the Psalms is the Father!&rdquo; Let me clarify why.</p> <p>You have to understand, it is not simply calling Jesus God, it is calling Jesus the Father, this is something Trinitarians overlook.</p> <p>Two different people can&rsquo;t be credited with the exact same thing. Even with the case of the abomination of desolation. The bible speaks of two different abomination of desolations (Antiochus epiphanies ez. 36 and Titus Matt. 24) yet they are desolating two different things! They both are not credited with doing the exact same abominations. In the same way, we cannot credit Jesus with the exact same act as the Father. Since the text uses the singular, one being created the world. Our theology cannot lead us to think that both Jesus and God created the world, in that case it should say &ldquo;Lords&rdquo;.</p> <p>This understanding also fits better with the context of Hebrews 1:7. Since we have established that verse 7 is discussing the temporality of angels(see MAKE angels, the verb clarifies this meaning, the verse doesn&rsquo;t say angels are winds, but that God MAKES them winds), this helps clarify the contrast being made in vv 8-12. It makes no sense to say, angels are temporary BUT Jesus created the world! No, this is not a contrasting argument. However it does make sense to say that angels are temporary, but Jesus and his kingdom are eternal. This is what we see in vv 7-12.<br /> In this whole section Jesus is being contrasted as superior to angels.<br /> <br /> It makes no sense to say:<br /> V.7 angels are temporary BUT<br /> V.8-9 Jesus reign is eternal<br /> AND<br /> V.10-12 Jesus created the world.<br /> <br /> Yes that would mean jesus was superior to angels, but it does not fit well at all with the flow of the argument. But it does make sense to say:<br /> <br /> V.7 angels are temporary BUT<br /> V.8-9 Jesus&rsquo; reign is eternal<br /> AND<br /> V.10-12 Jesus&rsquo; kingdom will outlast even the creation</p> <p>How is this in reference to the son? Because the new garment of v. 11 is the new creation, which Jesus has initiated and will reign over.</p> <p>In other words the angels are like a flaming fire (which goes out) and winds (which go away) like the old garment that will be rolled up (v. 11), but Jesus and his Kingdom will remain forever.</p> <p>New Creation argument which i dont buy because it says it will pass away :</p> <ol start="2" type="1"> <li>Note the &ldquo;latter-day&rdquo; context of the whole chapter after 1:1. Because of that, the &ldquo;beginning&rdquo; here and the creation (1:10) are best taken as the beginning of the new era, and Jesus&rsquo;s &ldquo;new creation.&rdquo;</li> <li>it is because of his exaltation that Jesus has become superior to the angels (1:4), this is the context for these quotes in Hebrews 1:5-13.</li> <li>Immediately after the 1:10-12 quote is 1:13 in which Jesus is exalted to the right hand of God, again exaltation is the context.</li> <li>Hebrews 2:5 says that the subject matter is the &ldquo;world to come&rdquo; not the old creation.</li> </ol>'),
