(41, 1, 58, 9, 23, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>NEW:</p> <p>I was looking some more at Heb. 9:23 and reading anything I could find on it. I came across one author who referenced Heb. 3:6 which speaks of Christians as God&#39;s house, or God&#39;s dwelling place, which is also reiterated in other places such as Eph. 2. But I think this is important for our discussion because it shows that Christians are the place where God dwells, Christians are God&#39;s sanctuary, even in the mind of the author of Hebrews. This verse connects a heavenly location (the house of God, 3:6) with people. So, it is not out of the scope of the author of Hebrews, or the context, that the heavenly _____ that needed to be cleansed may in fact be Christians.</p> <p>So, even if in v. 23 the author had in mind the heavenly sanctuary, I would argue that there are likely two heavenly sanctuaries. One is the actual sanctuary that exists in the heavens, and one is Christians here on earth. God dwells in both of these places.</p> <p>The big question here is what heavenly things need sacrifices, and what sacrifices in the bible have atoned for heavenly things?</p> <p>To clarify, the phrase reads in the greek lit. &ldquo;the heavenly __ themselves&rdquo; but we need to supply an object in english, this is the conundrum, what is the referrent here?</p> <p>There are three main possible interpretations for how to understand what the heavenly things/ones are. They could be heavenly objects such as the temple that exists in heaven (Heb. 8:5), they could be heavenly beings such as angels, or they could be humans. All of these options are possible grammatically as it could refer to plural persons or plural objects, however, I believe that this passage is referring to humans because that seems to be the only biblical option.</p> <p>Contextually, this passage makes clear that the better &ldquo;sacrifices&rdquo; being referred to here in v. 23 is likely the sacrifice of Jesus. In Hebrews 9:12-14; 15; 24; 26; 28 the author is discussing the new covenant through Christ&rsquo;s blood. Surrounding all around the passage in question is the atonement of Jesus and its superiority to the old covenant sacrifices. We do not have to guess as to which &ldquo;sacrifices&rdquo; were better, it is littered throughout the context.</p> <p>If Christ&rsquo;s is the better sacrifice being referred to here in v. 23 then this helps illuminate and eliminate some interpretive options. Let&rsquo;s discuss option one, that the &ldquo;heavenly things&rdquo; are objects in heaven. The first glaring problem is that nothing in heaven needs cleansing. God dwells in the temple in heaven (Heb. 9:11; 24; Acts 17:24; Hab. 2:20), and God&rsquo;s temple is repeatedly called holy (Psa. 11:4; Jon. 2:7). Therefore, we should not expect sin to be present there and we should not expect it to need purification or cleansing with sacrifices (Heb. 9:23). This heavenly temple likely welcomes the full presence of God, with no impediments due to sin, so what would need to be sprinkled with blood, or better blood? It simply does not make sense.</p> <p>Now to our second interpretive option. If one wants to assume that somehow angels have sinned and they are the ones who need to be cleansed with sacrifices, this concept would be brand new to scripture. It would be complete opinion, nowhere in scripture is there mention of angels receiving atonement, or Jesus&rsquo; atonement being efficacious for angels. Scripture only speaks of angels being held in chains until judgement for their sin (2 Pet. 2:4), and Jesus&rsquo; atonement is efficacious for humans because he was a human, it was substitutionary. Jesus was not an angel so there is no reason to assume that his atonement is anyway efficacious for angels. None of these conjections are anywhere in scripture so it is safe to rule out this option as being unlikely.</p> <p>As mentioned above, I believe that we are missing the mark by translating this phrase as &ldquo;heavenly things&rdquo;, we are supplying the &ldquo;things&rdquo; here which is not in the greek. However, this could just as easily be referring to persons. I think that what is being referred to here is not heavenly objects, but heavenly people, ultimately, Christians.</p> <p>Christians in the New Testament are referred to as &ldquo;heavenly&rdquo; multiple times. Perhaps the most blatant reference to Christians as heavenly is in 1 Corinthians 15:48 in which Christians are explicitly called heavenly or &ldquo;of heaven&rdquo;. Christians have a heavenly calling (Heb. 3:1), a heavenly gift (Heb. 6:4), and have come to the heavenly Jerusalem (Heb. 12:22). Therefore, it would not be strange for the author of Hebrews to refer to Christians as &ldquo;heavenly ones&rdquo;.</p> <p>If &ldquo;heavenly&rdquo; is referring to Christians then this fits perfectly with the surrounding context which discusses the New Covenant through Christ&rsquo;s sacrifice for sins bringing redemption. In both Hebrews 9:14 and 9:24 the author specifies that Christ&rsquo;s atonement is for &ldquo;our&rdquo; sins. Who is the &ldquo;our&rdquo; referring to? 1<sup>st</sup> Century Christians. Contextually, Christ&rsquo;s atonement was for those who would believe in him, not for angels or for the heavenly temple. So, why should we interpret Hebrews 9:23 any differently?</p> <p>The common way to refer to something in the location of heaven is to say &ldquo;in the heavens&rdquo; (ἐν τοῖς ἐπουρανίοις), or something similar like earlier in verse 23 which says (ἐν τοῖς οὐρανοῖς) however this key preposition ἐν is absent from the second half of Hebrews 9:23, this suggests that the author of Hebrews is not referencing something physically located in the heavens. If the author of Hebrews was attempting to identify something or objects located in heaven we would expect him to keep that exact same phrasing that he used in the first half of the verse. Something like, &ldquo;It was necessary for the copies of the things in heaven to be cleansed with these sacrifices, but the things in heaven themselves with better sacrifices than these.&rdquo; Did you catch the difference? The author removes the &ldquo;in&rdquo; from the second half of the sentence. I think this is done purposefully to show the reader that he is no longer referencing something that exists in heaven but is heavenly, namely, Christians. When paired with the two arguments above, it becomes clearer and clearer that the most likely referrent here in v. 23 is Christians.</p> <p>Overall, it is perfectly reasonable grammatically and highly likely contextually that &ldquo;the heavenly __ themselves&rdquo; should be translated as &ldquo;the heavenly ones themselves&rdquo; in reference to Christians. Christ&rsquo;s atonement is the better sacrifice for Christians moreso than the blood of bulls and goats which could never take away sins. What beautiful news. This is seen clearly in the entire NT, the entire Chapter 9 of Hebrews, and is also the message of v. 23.</p> <p>Hebrews 9:24 brings light to what heavenly thing is cleansed. The argument flows as follows, getting rid of the interrupting phrases: &ldquo;23but the heavenly ones themselves with better sacrifices than these. For Christ (entered)&hellip; into heaven itself now to appear before the face of God on our behalf.&rdquo; He does not enter into heaven to sprinkle his own blood and purify the heavenly sanctuary, but rather he goes into heaven on our behalf! Read that again, according to v. 24 Jesus did not go into heaven to purify the sanctuary but on behalf of the Christian, he put away sin by the sacrifice of himself (Heb. 9:26).</p> <p>Ask Jerry, what is the metaphor refering to? If you want to say this is metaphorical, that is fine but what is it refering to?</p>'),
