(41, 1, 59, 3, 15, 2, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:52:33', '<p>It&rsquo;s not literally coming down from above, but rather it is heavenly, spiritual wisdom.</p>'),
(41, 1, 60, 1, 20, 2, null, 99, '2022-06-02 19:08:52', '<p>The fact that Peter uses &ldquo;foreknown&rdquo; here instead of &ldquo;known&rdquo; is huge. Jesus was not literally in existence yet, but he was in the mind of God. Therefore, it was known beforehand (foreknown) that there would be a Messiah to come.</p>'),
(41, 1, 60, 2, 7, 0, 'I have commentary to add', 99, '2022-07-01 15:33:32', '<p>&ldquo;<strong>cornerstone.</strong>&rdquo; The cornerstone reads literally in Greek &ldquo;the head of the corner&rdquo; and it can have two meanings. &ldquo;The phrase &lsquo;head of the corner&rsquo; can indicate one of the large stones near the foundations of a building which by their sheer size bind together two or more rows of stones,&rdquo; or it can &ldquo;refer to the final stone which completes an arch or is laid at the top corner of a building (so Jeremias)&rdquo; (J. B. Taylor, New Bible Dictionary, 228). Either way, this stone is an essential part to the building and thus the analogy is that Christ, who was rejected, has become of supreme value.</p> <p>J. B. Taylor, &ldquo;Cornerstone,&rdquo; ed. D. R. W. Wood et al., New Bible Dictionary (Leicester, England; Downers Grove, IL: InterVarsity Press, 1996), 228.</p> <p>LINK OTHER GOSPEL OCCURANCES</p>'),
(41, 1, 60, 3, 19, 4, null, 99, '2022-11-23 20:57:39', '<p>He didn&rsquo;t go preach to these souls in some disembodied state, it was after he was resurrected!!</p>'),
(41, 1, 60, 3, 22, 2, null, 99, '2022-10-07 15:13:04', '<p>Connect with Colossians 1</p>'),
(41, 1, 60, 4, 16, 1, null, 99, '2021-11-14 21:55:48', '<p>here are some additional scriptures that use the word Christian(s). Means &ndash; little anointed ones,we are anointed! co-heirs with Christ! little kings below the big king</p> <p>Acts 26:28</p> <p>I Peter 4:16</p>'),
(41, 1, 61, 1, 1, 2, null, 99, '2022-11-03 19:09:59', '<p>&ldquo;in the righteousness of our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ.&rdquo;</p> <p>It&rsquo;s really interesting that if you take Wallace&rsquo;s explanation that I have in John 20:28 to support the Granville Sharp rule, it discounts his argument in John 20:28. He can have either one or the other, but can&rsquo;t have both. However, ultimately, we believe that he has neither clearly calling Jesus God, because these are not hard and fast rules. The way the authors used the article depended on what they were referring to and if they were referring to something that would not be confused, there is no reason to use the second article. So, in other words if Wallace wants to take them as hard and fast rules he can only have one or the other, not both.</p> <p>Interestingly, originally Sharp allowed proper names to work in his rule because he wanted to get the 8 Christologically significant texts to teach that Jesus is God, 4 of which included proper names (Eph. 5:5; 2 Thess. 1:12; 1 Tim. 5:21; 2 Tim. 4:1), but he used a complete double standard because he ignored the TSKS constructions which use proper names in verses like Matt. 17:1 and Matt. 27:56. So, basically even Wallace himself concedes that the original Granville sharp rule does not work for the 8 Christological texts. So, the question is, does Wallace&rsquo;s revision of the rule work, especially concerning 2 Peter 1:1 and Titus 2:13?</p> <p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p> <p>2 Peter 1:11 and 2 Pet. 3:18 is same exact phrase!!! plus there is textual variant here.</p> <p>the passage makes more sense to understand it this way. plus &ldquo;righteousness of Jesus&rdquo; is a very common phrase in the NT.</p> <p>SUMMARY - Norton makes some great points and shows the irrelevance of the Granville Sharp Rule in &ldquo;proving&rdquo; the Trinity. The Granville Sharp rule does not apply if it is clear that the two things being discussed are different, for example, with gold and silver. We non-Trinitarians assert that there was no ambiguity in the minds of the first-century readers between God and Jesus. They were known to be different from each other. Because no ambiguity between Christ and God would arise in the minds of the readers if the second article was omitted, it can be (and was) omitted without a problem. Likewise, there was no need for a second article in Matthew 21:12 in the phrase, &ldquo;all the [ones] selling and buying,&rdquo; or in Ephesians 2:20 in the phrase, &ldquo;the apostles and prophets,&rdquo; because no one would ever think that &ldquo;sold&rdquo; and &ldquo;bought&rdquo; meant the same thing, or that &ldquo;apostles&rdquo; and &ldquo;prophets&rdquo; were somehow the same office. This sort of distinction is apparent in numerous passages throughout the Bible.</p> <p>The limitations and exceptions to the rule stated by him are as follows: In this case, then, it appears that the article is not repeated, because its repetition is not necessary to prevent ambiguity.</p> <p>2. No similar rule applies to proper names. &lsquo;The reason,&rsquo; says Middleton, &lsquo;is evident at once; for it is impossible that John and Thomas, the names of two distinct persons, should be predicated of an individual&rsquo; (p. 68).</p> <p>This remark is not to the purpose [i.e., &lsquo;is not correct&rsquo;], for the same individual may have two names. The true reason for this limitation is, that proper names, when those of the same individual, are not connected by a copulative or copulatives, and therefore that, when they are thus connected, no ambiguity arises from the omission of the article.</p> <p>5. Lastly, &lsquo;we find,&rsquo; he says, &lsquo;in very many instances, not only in the plural, but even in the singular number, that where attributives are in their nature absolutely incompatible, i.e., where the application of the rule would involve a contradiction in terms, there the first attributive only has the article, the perspicuity of the passage not requiring the rule to be accurately observed&rsquo; (p. 92).</p>'),
(41, 1, 61, 1, 21, 1, null, 99, '2022-09-07 19:47:29', '<p>In context, this &ldquo;prophecy&rdquo; is them just being eyewitnesses to Christ (v. 16-17), not necessarily, them prophesying something to come.</p>'),
(41, 1, 61, 3, 4, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-04 20:00:17', '<p>See v. 11, this is bigger than just AD 70. This is talking about the whole creation.</p>'),
(41, 1, 61, 3, 9, 3, null, 99, '2022-01-11 18:32:29', null),
(41, 1, 61, 3, 10, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:53:12', '<p>To apply this whole passage to 70 AD is a stretch. The only thing is the &ldquo;elements&rdquo;, and to base the whole interpretation off of a word like this is sketchy.</p> <p>However this lines up with Matt. 24 which speaks of no one knowing when the Second and final coming of Jesus will happen, and lines up with Revelation in talking of the New Heavens and Earth.</p>'),
(41, 1, 61, 3, 11, 5, null, 99, '2022-10-04 19:59:24', '<p>Second Coming! They already had the Holy Spirit, yet they are still waiting on New Heavens and Earth! Also, he uses same, thief in the night language.</p>'),
(41, 1, 62, 1, 1, 1, 'change translation', 99, '2023-01-09 22:10:17', '<p>Things we learn about John 1 from 1 John 1:</p> <ol type="1"> <li>&ldquo;The beginning&rdquo; is in the time frame of the new creation, because they &ldquo;heard&rdquo; it and &ldquo;saw&rdquo; it, yet they could not see the original creation of heaven and earth.</li> <li>&ldquo;That which&rdquo; should be &ldquo;He who&rdquo; or &ldquo;who&rdquo; it is clearly talking about a person (Jesus). The gospel is not what the ὃ is. One cannot physically see the gospel, or physically touch the gospel. Could the disciples have touched the Pre-existent Jesus? No! This is the Jesus on earth. I&rsquo;m not sure how much clearer John could be that this is not a metaphorical concept, but that he could touch the Word of Life.</li> <li>Since the Word of Life here refers to Jesus (something that can be touched), &ldquo;The Word&rdquo; of John 1 is also likely referring to Jesus. The parallels are uncanny. You can touch the Word of Life in 1 John 1. And in John 1 &ldquo;That which came to be through him (The Word) was life.&rdquo; &ldquo;Word&rdquo; and &ldquo;Life&rdquo; are strongly connected in both 1 John 1:1 and John 1:3-4. Word of Life seems like a pretty good title for Jesus in John 1 as well.</li> </ol> <p>The life in `1 John 1:2-3 is eternal life. But Jesus is the Word of Life, the logos, the expression of this life.</p> <p>The life was revealed IN JESUS (v. 2), we have seen it (the life) IN JESUS, etc. this lines up with John 1:3 &ldquo;That which came about in it (The Word) was life.&rdquo; That which came about in John 1 is that which was revealed in 1 John 1: life.</p> <p>The phrase &ldquo;which was with the Father&rdquo; in 1 John 1:2 parallels strongly with John 1:1 &ldquo;was with God&rdquo;. Yet the feminine relative pronoun makes it clear that the &ldquo;eternal life was with the Father&rdquo;, although throughout the gospel of John and 1 John, Eternal life is IN Jesus (John 1:3) Jesus IS the life (John 14:6), Jesus IS the bread of life (John 6:48) so I&rsquo;m not sure how much we can distinguish Jesus from eternal life here in 1 John 1.</p> <p><strong>In John 1 &ldquo;The word&rdquo; was with the Father, here in 1 John 1 &ldquo;the (eternal) life&rdquo; was with the father. I think they are both parallels to Jesus who is the Word (Rev. 19:16) and the Life (John 14:6).</strong></p>');
