(41, 1, 66, 1, 4, 2, null, 99, '2022-07-31 16:50:58', '<p>Clearly God the Father here, not Jesus</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 1, 8, 2, null, 99, '2022-07-31 17:06:09', '<p>God here again, not Jesus</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 2, 23, 0, null, 99, '2022-07-31 22:45:28', '<p><br /> <span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">The word used for &ldquo;search&rdquo; in Rev. 2:23 also means examine, so that kind of searching. It does not mean that Jesus knows every bit of knowledge. The context is in terms of judgement so Jesus is examining the heart and mind. Then it says he will give to each of us as our works deserve. In other words, he is a diligent judge. It also says that your &ldquo;works&rdquo; deserve. So our judgement is on our works. Not necessarily our innermost thoughts. Idk... I just think overall it&rsquo;s a leap to assume that this is saying Jesus knows all things, the word for searching is that one, doesn&rsquo;t already know!!!! Like the same word is used when the Pharisees &ldquo;searched&rdquo; the scriptures but the scriptures testified to Jesus! They searched for what they didn&rsquo;t already have....</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 7, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-09-09 17:18:48', '<p>Look especially at the summary statement of the promise to this Jewish first-century church composed of the 144,000 and other early believers. Verse 6 says,</p> <p>6 Those who come He shall cause to take root in Jacob; Israel shall blossom and bud, And fill the face of the world with fruit.</p> <p>That&#39;s the new Israel&#39;s destiny. So you can put AD 70-74 beside verses 2-6, and maybe the words believing remnant or 144,000. They re-start this process of world-wide conquest via the Great Commission.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 7, 4, 5, null, 99, '2022-09-24 05:05:17', '<p>And the &lsquo;gathering of the elect&rsquo; does not refer to an &lsquo;end times&rsquo; return of Jews to the geographical land of Israel; as Revelation 7 makes clear, the numbered members of the tribe of Israel (Rev 7.4) are in fact an unnumbered multitude from &lsquo;every tribe, language, people and nation&rsquo; (Rev 7.9), just as Dan 7.14 had predicted.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 12, 6, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-11 16:46:25', '<p>This was the same flight that Christ prophesied to John in Rev. 12:6 of the &ldquo;woman&rdquo; (the church of Christ) who fled the &ldquo;dragon&rdquo; (Rome) into the wilderness for 1260 days, or 3-1/2 years.</p> <p>Christians fleeing to Pella!</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 12, 9, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:53:19', '<p>This happens before the 1260 days of v. 6. This makes sense of the rest of the passage, plus v. 6 does not make it sound like the 1260 days have happened yet before v. 7.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 12, 17, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-27 05:08:50', '<p>Gen. 3:15</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 13, 3, 1, null, 99, '2022-01-27 05:09:18', '<p>Gen. 3:15</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 13, 8, 3, null, 99, '2022-08-05 17:24:21', '<p>&ldquo;<em>everyone whose</em> name has not been written in the book of life (belonging to the Lamb that has been slain) from the foundation of the world.&rdquo;</p> <p style="line-height:1.38; background-color:#ffffff"><span style="font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; white-space:pre-wrap"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="font-weight:400"><span style="font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration:none">Rev. 13:8 the translation should be the net bible translation because of rev. 17:8, which says, &ldquo;written in the book of life since the foundation of the world.&rdquo; With no ambiguity. So rev. 13:8 should read &ldquo;name has not been written since the foundation of the world in the book of life, belonging to the lamb who was slain.&rdquo;</span></span></span></span></span></span></p> <p>Consider adding &ldquo;to the present day&rdquo; or something to make it clear what &ldquo;from&rdquo; means, possibly even &ldquo;throughout the history of the world&rdquo; in all instances of &ldquo;apo&rdquo; to be clearer. Because that is what it means.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo;</strong> &ndash; There is great debate in this verse, Revelation 13:8, as to whether &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; should modify the verb &ldquo;written&rdquo; or the participle (the Lamb that has been slain), because grammatically it could modify either one. In other words, should it read, &ldquo;that has been slain from the foundation of the world,&rdquo; or &ldquo;written in the book of life from the foundation of the world?&rdquo;</p> <p>From our commentary on Revelation 17:8 we established that ἀπὸ καταβολῆς κόσμου &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo;, which is what occurs here in Revelation 13:8 means from Genesis to the present day, a range of time, and &ldquo;before the foundation of the world&rdquo; means before Genesis.</p> <p>The reason why understanding &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; here in verse 8 to be referring to Jesus&rsquo; death makes no sense is because the phrase &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; is used to speak of a range of time, a time period, not one specific instance or moment. So, to say that Jesus was slain &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo;, or over a period of time (the history of the world) is quite strange. Also, the exact parallel of Revelation 13:8 and Revelation 17:8 &ldquo;written in the book of life from the foundation of the world&rdquo; lends support to understanding the phrase &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; to refer to believer&rsquo;s being written in the book of life.</p> <p>Although there are certainly some things, like the Church and the Savior (Eph. 1:4; 1 Pet. 1:20) that were in the mind of God <em>before</em> the foundation of the world, each individual being written in the book of life did not occur &ldquo;before&rdquo; the foundation of the world because Revelation 17:8 along with Revelation 13:8 makes clear that these individuals being written in the book of Life occurs &ldquo;from&rdquo; the foundation of the world, in other words, from Genesis to the present day.</p> <p>This verse, Revelation 13:8, and Revelation 17:8 provide support for the doctrine of Open Theism, that God does not know the future exhaustively, thus, it makes sense why the scriptures would say that believers are written into the book of life progressively throughout history, instead of every person being written down in the book before Genesis, before they existed. We would say the reason why each individual is not written down before they existed is because God did not know exactly how each individual would live their life because our lives had not happened yet, and he gives us the free will to accept or reject him in this life. (For more information on God&rsquo;s foreknowledge see Appendix 8: On Calvinism and Predestination)</p> <p>Some theologians like the translation as the ESV, &ldquo;written before the foundation of the world in the book of life,&rdquo; because it is more clearly espousing the Calvinist doctrine that people&rsquo;s names are written in the book of life before the foundation of the world, i.e., God predestines them either to salvation or damnation long before they are born. After all, if people&rsquo;s names are written in the book of life before the foundation of the world, then God knows, and even determines, the fate of every person. This is not what Scripture teaches. God gives each person free will to make his or her own choices. God wants all people to be saved (1 Tim. 2:4), and we are the ones who decide whether we are saved or not.</p> <p>--------------------------------------------------------------------</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 16, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:53:22', '<p>In this Preterist commentary on Revelation 16 the reader will see that the seven plagues of Revelation 16 are a very accurate description of several notable events throughout the course of the Jewish War. The pouring out of the seven bowls of Revelation 16 is a reflection of the pouring out of drink offerings during Pentecost. During Pentecost in A.D. 66, Josephus and Tacitus record what appears to be the departure from the Temple of the seven angels with the seven bowls. Immediately thereafter, the Jewish War began. During this war the seas and rivers turned red with blood as predicted in the second and third bowls. A multitude of miraculous signs were witnessed in A.D. 69, one year before the climactic siege of Jerusalem in fulfillment of Revelation 16:14: &ldquo;They are spirits of demons performing miraculous signs, and they go out to the kings of the whole world, to gather them for the battle . . . .&rdquo; Amidst these miraculous signs, the kings of the east, Sohaemus and Antiochus, crossed the Euphrates to meet the other Roman forces near Mt. Megiddo (Armageddon)as indicated in Revelation 16:12 and 16. During this time a great thunderstorm and earthquake simultaneously rocked Jerusalem while both Rome and Jerusalem were divided by separate and concurrent three-way civil wars as predicted in the seventh bowl in Revelation 16:18-19: &ldquo;Then there came flashes of lightening, rumblings, peals of thunder and a severe earthquake. . . . [and; T]he great city split into three parts.&rdquo; When the Romans arrived in Jerusalem in A.D. 70, Roman catapults hurled boulders into the city. These stones were white and weighed about one hundred poundsas predicted in Revelation 16: 21: &ldquo;From the sky huge hailstones of about a hundred pounds each fell upon men.&rdquo; In the following preterist commentary on Revelation 16, the reader will be exposed to the evidence.</p> <p>FROM REVELATIONREVOLUTION.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 17, 8, 3, null, 99, '2022-06-07 20:42:12', '<p><strong>&ldquo;written in the book of life from the foundation of the world&rdquo;</strong> &ndash; Many scholars take this to mean that believer&rsquo;s names are written in the book of life before they are born in eternity past, and that this verse supports the idea of predestination. However, this is not the way that we should understand this phrase. As we attempt to figure out what this phrase means a distinction between the phrase &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; and &ldquo;before the foundation of the world&rdquo; is needed.</p> <p>Often interpreters will understand these two phrases to be synonomous, in other words, &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; and &ldquo;before the foundation of the world&rdquo; both mean before Genesis. However, when looking at occurances of these two phrases they clearly have different meanings. &ldquo;<strong>Before</strong> the foundation of the world indicates <strong>before</strong> Genesis, whereas <strong>from</strong> the foundation of the world indicates <strong>from</strong> Genesis to present&rdquo; (Soteriology101.com). Let us see some examples that show &ldquo;from the foundation of the the world&rdquo; does not mean &ldquo;before the foundation of the world.&rdquo;</p> <ul> <li>Luke 11:50 (ESV) &ndash; &ldquo;so that the blood of all the prophets, shed <strong>from the foundation of the world</strong>, may be charged against this generation, 51 from the blood of Abel to the blood of Zechariah, who perished between the altar and the sanctuary.&rdquo;</li> </ul> <p>This is ἀπὸ καταβολῆς κόσμου &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo;, clearly meaning from Genesis to the present day, no blood of the prophets was shed before Genesis 1.</p> <ul> <li> <p>Hebrews 9:25-26 (ESV) &ndash; &ldquo;Nor was it to offer himself repeatedly, as the high priest enter the holy places every year with blood not his own, 26 for then he would have had to suffer repeatedly since the foundation of the world.&rdquo;</p> </li> </ul> <p>This is ἀπὸ καταβολῆς κόσμου &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo;, in context this is talking about paying for sins, and since no humans sinned before Genesis 1, this is clearly talking about Genesis to the present.</p> <p>More examples could be given of this but it is clear that &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; means from Genesis to the present day. Here in Revelation 17:8 the phrase used is &ldquo;from the foundation of the world&rdquo; not &ldquo;before&rdquo;. Therefore, this verse does not teach predestination, instead it is saying that since the foundation of the world, more and more people have been written in the book of life (because they exercised faith) or they have not been written in the book of life (meaning they will not be saved).</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 17, 16, 5, null, 99, '2022-09-05 02:24:16', '<p>Ironically, God uses evil powers to destroy one another. The Beast and his cohorts turn against the Prostitute (vv. 16-17).</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 2, 5, null, 99, '2022-09-05 02:52:43', '<p>It is just Satan who is bound for 1,000 years, not all of the demons...</p> <p>the binding of Satan has already taken place through Christ&rsquo;s death and resurrection (John 12:31; cf. Col. 2:15; Rev. 12:9; Matt. 12:29).</p> <p>What is the binding of Satan?</p> <p>Well, prior to Jesus coming Satan had power over this world to kill and destroy! Nobody had defeated him, he was 100% at getting humans to sin, which brings death. But Jesus defeated Satan by living a perfect life and through his death, bringing forgiveness and life to a bunch of Sinners. Satan has been defeated. He has been bound (Mark 3:27).</p> <p>Here&rsquo;s the crux of the matter: Because Jesus is stronger than the strong man, he can offer those who trust him full and unfettered forgiveness for every sin.</p> <p>Jesus says in Mark 3 that once the strong man is bound, he can plunder all of his goods, well, what are his goods? Lost people! Now that the strong man has been bound, Jesus can save souls, and draw all men to himself (). Jesus says that the one who binds the strong man can plunder the strong man&rsquo;s house (3:27). Then he immediately says &ldquo;all sins&rdquo; and &ldquo;whatever blasphemies&rdquo; will be forgiven (except the blasphemy against the Holy Spirit) (3:28). In other words, the forgiveness explained in 3:28 is a result of Jesus&rsquo;s binding of the strong man recounted in 3:27.</p> <p>The battle with Satan isn&rsquo;t over in Mark 1 or Mark 3 (Jesus will end up sacrificing his life to establish the kingdom fully), but a decisive blow has already been dealt.</p> <p>Whereas Adam should&rsquo;ve cast out the serpent who called into question God&rsquo;s Word, Jesus overcame the Devil&mdash;and indeed bound him (cf. Rev. 20:2)&mdash;as part of his faithfulness to his messianic task.</p> <p>Adam should&rsquo;ve obeyed unto life; instead, Adam sinned and brought death. Jesus obeyed fully, even unto death, and his obedience brings everlasting life. Jesus bound the strong man through obedience to God&rsquo;s will. And only this fully obedient Savior has the authority to grant you life and forgive your sins.</p> <hr /> <p>John 12:31-32, another supporting text used by amillennialists states: &quot;NOW judgment is upon this world; now the ruler of this world shall be cast out. And I, if I be lifted up from the earth, will draw all men to Myself.&quot; this binding happened after Jesus&rsquo; resurrection!</p> <hr /> <p>Colossians 2:14&ndash;15 makes it clear what happened to the powers of evil through Christ&#39;s ministry &ndash; He disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him.&quot; This indicates that wicked powers were defeated in principle at the cross of Christ. When Jesus purged all of our sins on Calvary, something happened to Satan. The evil one lost his authority to keep people back from God. He was bound by what Jesus did.</p> <p>THEY USED TO HAVE THE POWER OF DEATH REIGNING OVER ALL MEN (ROM. 5) BUT JESUS CONQUERED THAT.</p> <p>I saw satan fall like lightning passage!! somehow his falling from heaven has to do with the preaching of the gospel by the apostles.</p> <hr /> <p>Revelation 12:11 testifies of the embattled saints that &quot;they have conquered him by the blood of the Lamb and by the word of their testimony.&quot; And Romans 8 we are more than conquerers. If we, humans can conquer Satan through faith, then he has been bound.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 4, 5, null, 99, '2022-11-10 02:17:05', '<p>Revelation 1:6, &ldquo;He has made us to be a kingdom and priests&rdquo;</p> <p>Revelation 5:10, &ldquo;You have made them to be a kingdom and priests to serve our God and they will reign over the earth&rdquo;</p> <p>Revelation 20:6, &ldquo;They will be priests of God and of Christ and will reign with him&rdquo;</p> <p>These verses give good evidence that the thousand years is now!!</p> <p>If I think it is Spiritual resurrection &ndash; life in Christ that starts with spiritual new birth (Rom. 6:8-11; Col. 3:1-4; Eph. 2:6).</p> <p>I think a very important point is that all of the verbs in Rev. 20:4 are in the aorist tense besides the substantival participle &ldquo;those who have been beheaded&rdquo;. Yet almost all bible scholars seem to conclude that the ἔζησαν lit. &ldquo;they lived&rdquo; occurs after the not &ldquo;worshipping&rdquo; προσεκύνησαν and not &ldquo;receiving&rdquo; ἔλαβον the beast&rsquo;s mark. There is seemingly no grammatical reason for this. What if, like the greek suggests, all four of these verbs that follow &ldquo;who&rdquo; οἵτινες are in the same time frame? So, instead of translating it &ldquo;who did not worship and did not receive the mark&hellip; came to life and reigned for 1000 years,&rdquo; we translate it, &ldquo;who did not worship the beast and did not receive the mark... and lived and reigned with Christ the 1000 years.&rdquo; What if the living and reigning happened before the non-worship and non-reception? When we translate it as they came to life and reigned for 1000 years, we end up translating the first two verbs as happening first, and then the second two happening after. Almost inherently adding a &ldquo;then&rdquo; they came to life. The first two verbs happen and then the second two, but grammatically there is no reason for this.</p> <p>Kik agrees with this^^ - Since they are all in the same tense they must refer to the same time. That is, the time of not worshipping the beast and not receiving his mark is the same time as that of sitting on thrones and living and reigning with Christ. J. Marcellus Kik, An Eschatology of VICTORY, (Phillipsburg, NJ: Presbyterian and Reformed Publishing CO., 1971), 228.</p> <p>Revelation 5:10 also gives more clarity to this passage. The exact same language is used. People from every nation HAVE BEEN made &ldquo;priests of God&rdquo; and they will &ldquo;reign upon the earth&rdquo;. One key insight is learned here as opposed to Rev. 20:4, is that they will reign upon the earth, not in heaven. So, to take Rev. 20:4 as souls departed from their bodies currently reigning with Christ in heaven would be a mistake. Another helpful point in Rev. 5:10 is that the priesthood is a present not a future reality. They have been made priests. This lines up very nicely with Rev. 1:6, which says that believers have been made priests, and 1 Pet. 2:5;9 which both call believers as a kingdom of Priests now.</p> <p>Problems with the Amillenial view that it is a resurrection of souls. The problem is that, that is not a resurrection at all. A physical resurrection is a resurrection of the body. If the body is still in the grave it is not a resurrection. Also the fact that Revelation 20 deals with a resurrection eliminates the interpretation that the Chapter is speaking of the intermediate state of the soul (An Eschatology of Victory, Presbyterian and Reformed, p. 230). And secondly, the Soul does not continue living after death. Souls are not immortal (See Spirit &amp; Truth Appendix).</p> <p>Problems with the Premillennial view:</p> <p>The most glaring problem with the Premillennial view is that they take this passage of visionary literature (Rev. 20:1; 4; I saw thrones&hellip; I saw the souls), and mistakenly interpret the visionary level to be the exact same as the referential level. This mistake is often made by Premillennialists in the book of Revelation.</p> <p>Let me explain this concept further. In prophetic and visionary literature the Visionary level is what John (in this case) sees in his vision. Such as an angel filling a censer with fire and throwing it on the earth (Rev. 8:5), a dragon with seven heads and ten horns sweeping down a third of the stars of heaven with his tail (Rev. 12:4) and saints who had been beheaded resurrecting and reigning with Christ for 1000 years (Rev. 20:4-5).</p> <p>Yet, what the vision depicts and what the elements represent are two very different things. John helps us understand that the visionary level and the referential level are two different things. He gives us the answer to what some of the symbols in Revelation mean, for example, the dragon represents the Adversary Satan (Rev. 12:9), the ten horns represent ten kings (Rev. 17:12), and seven heads are the seven mountains (Rev. 17:9). These clarifying statements also occur in Revelation 1:20; 4:5; and 5:6, how many times does John have to explain his visions for us to understand that they point to something else? Clearly John doesn&rsquo;t want his readers to interpret his visions &ldquo;literally&rdquo;. These symbols represent something other than the symbol itself, so if we find ourselves interpreting an entire vision &ldquo;literally&rdquo; we are in reality denying the presence of symbolism at all.</p> <p>This is where the Premillennial view falls short in interpreting Revelation 20:4-6. They fail to understand that it is a vision. The premillennialist tries to interpret Revelation as &ldquo;literally&rdquo; as possible until it is simply infeasible or John explicitly gives us what the vision is referring to (Rev. 12:9; 17:9-12). However, this is not how we should be reading prophetic literature! That is how we read the rest of the New Testament, that is not how we should read literature that is filled with visions and symbols. Sometimes Revelation itself even calls these visions &ldquo;signs&rdquo; (Rev. 12:1; 15:1) which are things that point to a greater reality. The mistake of the Premillennial is they read visions such as Revelation 12 in which a woman is clothed with the sun and understand that she could not literally be clothed with the sun, so they rightly see it as a metaphor. However, when it comes to visions which are theoretically possible (such as Rev. 20:4-6), they get lulled into thinking that it is not a vision anymore, but that we should be interpreting it literally. This is simply mis-diagnosing the genre, John clearly states that the section of Revelation 20:4-6 is a vision, so why would we read it with our &ldquo;literal&rdquo; glasses on instead of with our symbolic and prophetic glasses. I think the Premillennialist is wearing the wrong glasses when reading Revelation 20:4-6.</p> <p>What I propose is happening in these verses is a &ldquo;spiritual&rdquo; resurrection like is talked about in the gospels. Revelation 20:4-6 is a physical picture of spiritual resurrection. Just as the prostitute riding a dragon is a physical picture of a spiritual reality of unfaithful Israel following Satan instead of God. This passage is depicting a physical resurrection but it is referring to the spiritual resurrection (John 5:25), the coming to spiritual life by the Christian saints (Eph. 2:5), to live spiritually and reign with Christ for a very long time (Eph. 2:6; Rev. 5:10), a &ldquo;1000 years&rdquo;, which aligns nicely with other NT passages on the Spiritual life of the believer.</p> <p>It is also worth noting that the verb in v. 4 is came to life ζαο, not αναστασις which is usually the term for resurrection. So, physical resurrection is likely not in view here. Bodies are not being resurrected. More evidence for this is that John uses the term souls ψυχη, not σαρζ the flesh, or σομα typically translated body.</p> <p>BIG The view held by Augustine, who saw the reign spoken of in this passage as &ldquo;the spiritual reign of believers on earth in the present age, symbolizing the victory through which it is written that &ldquo;we are more than conquerors through Him who loved us (Romans 8:37).&rdquo;</p> <p>Who are the &ldquo;they&rdquo; who are seated on the thrones? The subject is Christ and his armies described in Rev. 19:11-21, as these are the only people remaining in the vision.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 5, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-08 02:16:46', '<p>Duncan Mckenzie has really interesting view on this. Basically, he thinks the phrase &ldquo;the rest of the dead did not come to life&hellip; shouldn&rsquo;t be in the text, which he has a point. But he understands the reason why the author calls it the first resurrection is that it is the first resurrection of all the dead, but as each person dies in this life, after he dies, he is resurrected and judged therefore, there are a lot of of subsequent resurrections.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 8, 5, 'still need to figure this out, not completely satisfied', 99, '2022-12-06 15:45:56', '<p>(Notice in 1 Thess. 2:18 the Devil is still active, but this is technically before the events of Rev. 19-20 take place.)</p> <p>Rev. 20:7-10 is still what he saw in his vision. But what are they referring to? He is literally seeing people from all over the earth surrounding the camp of the saints, but it is referring to people from all around the earth rising up against the church before they enter the new Jerusalem.</p> <p>This is because God is not done with Satan at 70 AD. The end of the thousand years is marked by the temporary release of Satan, so that he can attack New Jerusalem (Rev. 20:7-9). But notice the end of the millennium doesn&rsquo;t come with the arrival of New Jerusalem &ndash; but with Satan&rsquo;s attack on New Jerusalem. It is only then, a thousand years later, that the devil joins the beast and false prophet in punishment (Rev. 20:10).</p> <p><strong>Reasons for sequential</strong>:</p> <p>If John had wanted us to understand recapitulation rather than sequence in this passage [Revelation 20], John &ldquo;did us no favor&rdquo; by: (a) recasting the beast and false prophet (19:20) as Gog and Magog (20:8); (b) inserting a thousand year period between the two battles (20:2&ndash;5); (c) representing the period of Christian history from the first century to the end as &ldquo;a short time&rdquo; (12:12) and as &ldquo;a thousand years&rdquo; (20:2&ndash;6)&hellip; (d) offering no hint that Satan is bound before Rev 19:11ff while emphasizing his being bound before Rev 20:7ff; and (e) telling us that Satan will be thrown into the lake of fire where the beast and false prophet already are (20:10); (f) the false prophet had just deceived those who received the mark (19:20), and Satan worked through the false prophet and beast (2 Thess. 2:9), and then 20:3 says Satan was thrown into the abyss so that he would not deceive the nations, this sure seems chronological.</p> <p>THE FOLLOWING IS NOT CONVINCING, SOME SIMILARITITIES DO NOT MEAN SAME EVENT: <strong>Reasons Rev. 20:7-10 is a recapitulation of Rev. 16 and 19:18-21.</strong></p> <p>1.Christ&#39;s second coming is in both Rev. 19 and 20:7-10 not just 20:7:10. &quot;Postmillennialists, of course, readily affirm John&rsquo;s reference to Christ&rsquo;s second coming in 20:7&ndash;10 but vigorously deny it in 19:11&ndash;21 .&quot; TOUGH</p> <p>2. the use of Ezekiel 38&ndash;39 in 19:1721 and 20:7&ndash;10 , we should also notice John&rsquo;s use of Ezek 38:18&ndash;22 in 16:17&ndash;21.[14] The combination of earthquake, hailstorm, and God&rsquo;s judgment of the nations is apparently unique in the OT to Ezek 38:18&ndash;22and has evidently made its way into John&rsquo;s narration in 16:17&ndash;21 . The features of Ezek 38:18&ndash;22 can be seen in 16:17&ndash;21 as John links the earth-shattering quake (vv 18 , 20 ; Ezek 38:19&ndash;20 ) with the collapse of all the world&rsquo;s cities (v 19 ; cf. Ezek 38:20 ) and a plague of hailstones (v 21 ; Ezek 38:22 ). NOT MINE</p> <p>3. When we see the noun πόλεμος with the definite article in 20:8 , the article&rsquo;s presence makes it all but impossible to avoid the conclusion that the battle mentioned in 20:8 is the one previously described in 19:19 and in 16:14 . This observation is made all the more impressive when we notice that 16:14 ; 19:19 ; and 20:8 contain the last three uses of the noun πόλεμος in Revelation and, at that, the only uses accompanied by the article. Thus, we have firm ground on which to argue that in 20:8 John is repeating his previous accounts of the final battle in 19:19 and 16:14 .</p> <p>4. John uses precisely the same wording he uses in connection with the Armageddon revolt in 16:14 and virtually the same wording he uses in 19:19 (N.B. 16:14 , συναγαγειν ατος ες τν πόλεμον , &ldquo;to gather them for the battle&rdquo;; 19:19 , συνηγμένα ποιησαι τν πόλεμον , &ldquo;gathered to wage the battle&rdquo;; 20:8 , συναγαγειν ατος εις τν πόλεμον , &ldquo;to gather them for the battle&rdquo;).</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 9, 5, null, 99, '2022-03-28 21:43:09', '<p>Rev. 20:7-10 is still what he saw in his vision. But what are they referring to? He is literally seeing people from all over the earth surrounding the camp of the saints, but it is referring to people from all around the earth rising up against the church before they enter the new Jerusalem.</p> <p><strong>over the breadth of the earth</strong> &ndash; This isn&rsquo;t localized just in jerusalem, but is all over the earth, this is another hint that this is the Church being discussed here, not the physical Jerusalem.</p> <p><strong>camp of the saints</strong> &ndash; The camp of the saints &ndash; this brings in the idea of Israel&rsquo;s camp in the wilderness before entering into the promised land. In the same way, The camp that is surrounded in Revelation is the church, the camp of the saints, before they enter into the New Jerusalem.</p> <p>Look, overall, it would have been infinitely clearer for John to call this &ldquo;beloved city&rdquo; the New Jerusalem, and their would have been no confusion. Yet he didn&rsquo;t, so we cannot read that into this text. It is something different, it is before the New Jerusalem.</p> <p><strong>fire came down</strong> &ndash;</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 10, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:53:38', '<p>But in Rev. 20, Satan no longer has the beast, as God has already dealt with the beast. And rather than killing the saints, this time, Satan and his followers are burned up before they can even touch the saints. Instead of Jerusalem being burned up (Rev. 17:16), the ones who would besiege New Jerusalem are the ones who get burned and destroyed.</p> <p>It is impossible for Rev. 20:7-10 to happen literally, as New Jerusalem is a spiritual city on the earth. Therefore, New Jerusalem cannot literally be surrounded by a literal siege. But this scene does depict God&rsquo;s people gathered into one group, and all of the nations outside of Christ gathered into one group. This seems to fit Matt. 25:31-46 and 1 Thes. 4:13-18, which depict all peoples being gathered into two groups: all of God&rsquo;s people, and all nations/peoples that do not belong to God.</p> <p>For these reasons, I am inclined to think Rev. 20:7-10 is a figurative, stylized account of the final judgment, which is then retold in a different way in Rev. 20:11-15 (similar to how Rev. 17:15-18 describes the destruction of Jerusalem, and then retells it in a different way in chapter 18, to illustrate different points about the same event).</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 11, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:53:41', '<p>It is only at the end of the thousand years, the end of the reign of Christ that the resurrection occurs and death is defeated (1 Cor. 15:23-28). So it is no surprise that the final judgment and resurrection of the dead happens once the thousand year reign is complete (Rev. 20:11-15).</p> <p>The attack on old Jerusalem brought about the judgment of one nation in one generation, but the failed attack at New Jerusalem brings about the judgment of all nations and all generations.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 12, 5, null, 99, '2022-08-25 02:00:34', '<p>Notice how it is only the Dead who are at this judgement, there are no alive people at this great White throne Judgement, therefore, if it happened in AD 70 we would not expect us to take part in it, but we take part only after we die (1 Cor. 15, Rev. 14:6 Maybe).</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 20, 14, 4, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:53:47', '<p>cf. 1 Cor. 15 when death is the last enemy to be defeated.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 21, 1, 5, null, 99, '2022-12-28 01:43:03', '<p>Reasons why New Heavens and earth is still future to us:​</p> <ol> <li>The &ldquo;sea&rdquo; gives up the dead in it (Rev. 20; Great white throne judgment) and then here, the sea is no more, so this must be subsequent to the GWT judgment.</li> <li>The lake of fire which is also mentioned in Rev. 20:11-15 or so, is after the final judgement and the New Heavens and earth are dichotimized with the lake of fire, you are either in one or the other.</li> <li>Unbelievers are not currently in the lake of fire, so we are not currently in the New Heavens and earth.</li> <li>The most natural way to read the text is that Rev. 21 happens after Rev. 20.</li> </ol>'),
(41, 1, 66, 21, 3, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:53:58', '<p>This has to be future because Pentecost has already happened, so if it was just talking about God dwelling with us through the Holy Spirit, that has already happened. Therefore, this must be future.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 21, 7, 5, null, 99, '2022-01-06 22:54:00', '<p>&ldquo;These things&rdquo;, those who have faith/overcome will receive the New Heavens and earth, but those who don&rsquo;t will receive the lake of fire. The lake of fire which is also mentioned in Rev. 20:11-15 or so, is after the final judgement so I believe the New Heavens and earth are after the final judgement.</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 22, 4, 5, null, 99, '2022-12-28 01:39:18', '<p>See his face &ndash; this provides more evidence that this is not speaking of the church age</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 22, 5, 5, null, 99, '2022-12-28 01:38:51', '<p>They will reign forever and ever, this is different from the saints reigning for 1,000 years during the millenium, so this is after the millenium. It provides evidence that this is not speaking of the church age</p>'),
(41, 1, 66, 22, 15, 4, null, 99, '2022-01-09 16:20:00', '<p>How are there still people around outside the new Jerusalem if this is the final state of affairs? These are the same people listed in the Lake of fire in Rev. 21:8. The dogs are in the lake of fire!</p> <p>There will be only two places in eternity&mdash;1) the New Heaven and New Earth and 2) the Lake of Fire. Therefore, &ldquo;outside&rdquo; refers to the Lake of Fire.</p>'),
