(53, 0, 19, 90, 1, 0, null, 99, '2021-10-06 00:42:11', '<p>Psalms overview- Commentary on Psalm 90:1-f &amp; Book IV of Psalms by F. J. Licary 10-4-2021</p> <p>WHY SHOULD WE READ PSALMS? For more than 3000 years, God&rsquo;s people have turned to the Psalms in times of rejoicing and great trouble. The psalmists give us words to praise an awesome, wonderful God. When we are distracted or worried, the Psalms remind us of our mighty, loving God Who we serve. When our grief is so great we cannot pray, the cries of the psalmists put words to our pain.</p> <p>The Psalms are comforting because they focus our attention on Yahweh God, our loving Father and faithful Shepherd, and the truth that He is still on the throne&mdash; the One and Only True God, none is more powerful than Him. The Psalms reassure us that no matter what we are feeling or experiencing, God is with us, and God is good, all the time.</p> <p>WHO WROTE THE PSALMS? The Book of 150 Psalms is a collection of Hebrew poetry that was originally sung in worship to God with music instruments.</p> <p>Most Psalms identify the writer at the top of the page. These Psalm introductions on the Hebrew scrolls may be considered authoritative (according to John Schoenheit and other scholars). The writers had holy spirit upon them and God was the Author. The Psalms were not written by a single writer, but were written by at least 6 different men over about 5 centuries.</p> <p>Moses wrote one psalm, Psalm 90, &ldquo;A Prayer of Moses, the man of God.&rdquo; It is the oldest Psalm.</p> <p>About 450 years later King Solomon wrote two psalms: Psalm 72, &ldquo;Of Solomon&rdquo; and Psalm 127, &ldquo;A Song of Ascents Of Solomon.&rdquo;</p> <p>David is named the writer of 73 Psalms. 50 Psalms do not mention an author (Ps 90 for example) however, most scholars agree that David may have written some of these, also.</p> <p>Asaph wrote 12 Psalms (for example: Ps 73 &ldquo;Book III. A Psalm of Asaph.&rdquo; &amp; Ps 77 &ldquo;For the Musical Director. To Jeduthun. A Psalm of Asaph.&rdquo;)</p> <p>The Sons of Korah wrote 11 Psalms (for example: Ps 84 &ldquo;For the Musical Director. On an instrument of Gath. A Psalm of the sons of Korah.&rdquo;).</p> <p>Heman wrote Psalm 88 in concert with the Sons of Korah, &ldquo;A Song. A Psalm of the sons of Korah. For the Musical Director. To be sung in a depressed voice. A contemplation of Heman the Ezrahite.&rdquo;</p> <p>Ethan wrote Psalm 89, &ldquo;A contemplation of Ethan the Ezrahite.&rdquo;</p> <p>Commentary on Psalm 90:1-f &amp; Book IV of Psalms</p> <p>Ps 90:1 O Lord, you have been our refuge from generation to generation.</p> <p>Psalm 90 is entitled: &ldquo;A Prayer by Moses, the man of God.&rdquo; This is the only psalm attributed to Moses. Psalm 90 is the oldest psalm, written by Moses by the year 1440 BC. About 450 years later King Solomon wrote two psalms: Psalm 72 and Psalm 127.</p> <p>Psalm 90 marks the beginning of &ldquo;Book IV&rdquo; of Psalms (Psalms 90-106).. The arrangement of Psalms into five books goes back at least to when the Hebrew Scriptures were translated into Greek (the Septuagint) about 250-200 B.C.</p> <p>Psalm 90 is categorized as a community lament&ndash;&ndash;a psalm expressing the pain of the worshiping community and crying out for relief, forgiveness, restoration. It speaks of judgment imposed by Yahweh on the people. It refers to the experiences of the Israelites during the Exodus, when Yahweh punished them for their unfaithfulness.</p> <p>Commentary on &amp; Book IV of Psalms</p> <p>Book IV (Psalms 90-106) looks back to the time of Moses and the Exodus. Book IV has key words: &ldquo;our iniquities, afflicted us, we have seen evil, destructive pestilence, plague, terror by night, vengeance, wilderness&rdquo; and these following key verses:</p> <p>Ps 95:8-11 Do not harden your heart, as at Meribah, as in the day of Massah in the wilderness, when your fathers tested Me, they tried Me, though they had seen My work. For forty years I was disgusted at that generation and said, &ldquo;They are a people whose heart wanders astray. And they do not know My roads.&rdquo; Therefore I swore in My anger, &ldquo;They will never enter into My rest.&rdquo;</p> <p>Ps 96:5 For all the gods of the peoples are idols, but Yahweh made the heavens.</p> <p>Ps 98:1 Sing to Yahweh a new song, for He has done wonderful things! His right hand and His holy arm have worked salvation for Him.</p> <p>Ps 99:5-9 Exalt Yahweh our God and worship at His footstool! He is Holy!<br /> Moses and Aaron were among His priests, and Samuel was among those who called upon His name; they repeatedly called upon Yahweh and He answered them. He spoke to them in the pillar of cloud. They kept His testimonies and the statute He gave them.<br /> O Yahweh our God, You answered them; You are a forgiving God to them, but an avenger upon their deeds.<br /> Exalt Yahweh our God! Yes, worship at His holy hill, for Yahweh our God is holy.</p> <p>Selah. [Pause and consider]</p>'),
(53, 0, 19, 96, 5, 0, '<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/Psalms/chapter96/5" ondblclick="event.stopPropagation();event.preventDefault();" target="_self" title="Click for Commentary">For all the gods of the peoples are worthless ones [idols], but Yahweh made the heavens.</a>', 99, '2022-11-03 02:05:21', null);
