(53, 0, 32, 1, 9, 0, null, 99, '2022-01-07 19:07:23', '<p>Jonah 1:9 is the last use of &ldquo;Hebrew&rdquo; in the Old Testament Hebrew scriptures. Hebrew means &ldquo;one who crossed over&rdquo; a descendant of Abraham who crossed the Euprhates River, and descendant of the tribes that crossed over the Jordan River with Joshua.</p> <p>Josh 3:1 And Joshua rose up early in the morning, and they moved from Shittim and came to the Jordan, he and all the children of Israel. They camped there before they crossed over the Jordan.</p> <p>Josh 4:1Now when all the nation had completely crossed over the Jordan, Yahweh spoke to Joshua, saying,</p> <p>Josh 4:4Then Joshua called the 12 men whom he had appointed from the children of Israel, one man from each tribe.</p> <p>Josh 4:5And Joshua said to them, &ldquo;Cross over in front of the ark of Yahweh your God into the midst of the Jordan, and each of you take up a stone onto your shoulder, according to the number of the tribes of the children of Israel,</p> <p>Josh 4:8And the children of Israel did that, just as Joshua commanded; and they took up 12 stones from the midst of the Jordan just as Yahweh spoke to Joshua, according to the number of the tribes of the children of Israel; and they made them cross over with them to the camp and put them down there.</p> <p>Josh 4:9And Joshua also set up 12 stones in the midst of the Jordan, in the place where the feet of the priests who carried the ark of the covenant stood, and they are there to this day.</p> <p>Gen 14:13 is the first use of &ldquo;Hebrew&rdquo; in OT.</p>'),
