(53, 1, 42, 2, 8, 0, null, 99, '2021-12-13 18:13:26', '<p>I live in southern Wisconsin, Latitude 42 deg N with similar weather and crop-field conditions as Bethlehem, Israel, Latitude 32 deg N. After farmers harvest corn, in September and October I see many herds of deer in those fields grazing at night. After snow melts in March/April I never see deer grazing in those fields. There is only one time of year for Bethlehem shepherds to be night-watching their sheep in the fields.</p> <p>Where were the shepherds?</p> <p>Luke 2:8 And there were shepherds in the same region, living out in the [harvested crop] fields and keeping night-watch over their flock.</p> <p>The root of αγραυλουντες (agraulountes), the original Greek word translated &ldquo;living out in the fields&rdquo; (Luke 2:8), is αγρος (agros), which refers to a field cultivated for agriculture. So the shepherds were night-watching their flock while living in crop fields that were harvested.</p> <p>Why is that significant?<br /> Shepherds with flocks of sheep would not enter crop fields during Winter, Spring or Summer. Winter was too cold for sleeping outside at night. lest the sheep eat the crops, the Spring soil could be too muddy/moist for sheep. So the time of the year when shepherds and their sheep could enter and stay in these crop fields was the in the Fall, after the Summer harvest, when farmers invited the shepherds into their fields with their flocks so that the sheep can &ldquo;clean&rdquo; their fields by eating the straw and them fertilizing the field with manure.</p> <p>This means that Jesus was born in the Fall (September/October), not in Summer, not in Winter (December), and not in Spring (March/April).</p> <p>What month in the Fall?<br /> Mary&#39;s pregnancy began during the &ldquo;sixth month&rdquo; (Luke 1:36) of Elizabeth&#39;s pregnancy, which began just after her husband Zacharias, who was of the &ldquo;division of Abijah&rdquo; (Luke 1:5) had performed his duties of &ldquo;priesthood&rdquo; in the &ldquo;sanctuary of the Lord&rdquo; (Luke 1:9). The division of Abijah performed its priestly duties in the temple during the latter half of the fourth month in the Jewish calendar, which starts after Passover. Since Passover is in March/April of our Gregorian calendar, Elizabeth conceived in June/July (fourth month from March/April), and Mary conceived in December/January (sixth month from June/July). And since &ldquo;the days were fulfilled for her to give birth&rdquo; (Luke 2:6), Mary gave birth at full term, so Jesus was born about nine months thereafter in September/October.</p> <p>According to the book by Earnest L. Martin, The Star of Bethlehem: The Star That Astonished the World, Jesus was born on September 11 (Tishri 1), 3 B.C. about 7 pm.</p>'),
