(53, 1, 66, 2, 13, 0, 'Where the Adversary lives in 95 AD?', 99, '2022-11-08 18:53:34', '<p>Pergamum (Pergamon) an ancient Greek city in Mysia, 16 miles from the Aegean Sea coastline, northwest of modern city of Bergama, Turkey, became the center of a large kingdom in the 3rd century BC and retained its status as a political and cultural leader into the Byzantine period. Its acropolis rises 1,300 feet above the lower city located on the plain of the Caicus River. According to Eastern Orthodox tradition: Saint Antipas was killed in Pergamum, John the Apostle ordained Antipas bishop of Pergamon during the reign of the Roman emperor Nero (54-68 AD). Antipas was martyred by burning for casting out demons worshiped by the local population. Pergamos was said to be the City and Throne of Satan, where Satan dwells. Pergamum is one of the seven congregations in Revelation ch 2-3: Ephesis, Smyrna, Pergamum, Thyatira, Sardis, Philadelphia, Laodicea.</p>'),
