(117, 1, 43, 1, 1, 1, null, 99, null, '<p>The Word is as Elohim...It is as Theos. The Word of God expresses the invisible one True God who is the Father. The memra was used as a mentonym...a periphrastic expression for God and who God is. It is unlikely that John starts out to change the Hebrew Theological world view by now saying there is an additional God who is also with God and Like God. This would have been ludicrious to the Jews. It is nonsensical to state that the concept of the Trinity was in the Old Testament but not &quot;seen&quot; or understood by the Hebrews. To believe so is to make a mockery of the way in which God revealed himself to his people.</p> <p>The circumlutionary use of the Word enabled the Hebrews to avoid speaking &quot;Yahweh.&quot; Yahweh becomes the Word in the post exilic commentary and on into the targums. Of equal importance, The inspired Word of God describes the very nature of God who is otherwise largely &quot;unknown.&quot; While creation might declare the glory of God, his Word characterises his nature, purpose and intent in his relationship with man. God inspires man to record those things that express the mind of the One True God who is called the Word. Therefore the Word is with God and God is like his word.</p> <p>In the beginning reflects the link with creation. In the beginning can refer to any time reference point. In the beginning of the Gospel of Jesus Christ, at the beginning of the story, in the beginning of God&#39;s plan and purposes and revelation to man.</p>'),
