(123, 1, 51, 3, 13, 0, 'Forbear.Forgive. Forgive &amp; don&#39;t hold on to anger<br /> <br /> Sometimes, easier said than done. Nonetheless, God tells us to DO', 99, '2022-11-07 12:48:33', '<p><strong>bearing with one another and forgiving each other, if anyone has a complaint against another. Just as the Lord forgave you, so you also must forgive.</strong></p> <p>&ldquo;bearing with.&rdquo; The Greek word translated as &ldquo;bearing with&rdquo; is anechō (#430 ἀνέχω), and it means to &ldquo;bear with, forbear, put up with, endure, sustain yourself under, tolerate.&rdquo; Anyone trying to be unified with others knows that in order to do so there has to be some &ldquo;bearing with,&rdquo; &ldquo;putting up with,&rdquo; and &ldquo;tolerating.&rdquo; This is never an easy thing, but it is a Christian virtue that must be developed by any Christian who wants to be mature in the Faith. This same phrase occurs in Ephesians 4:2.</p> <p>&ldquo;one another.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;one another&rdquo; occurs in the context of the Christian community, and while we are to be good to everyone, in the context of the New Testament Epistles, the commands toward &ldquo;one another&rdquo; are specifically to other Christians. Christians are to be &ldquo;especially good to the household of faith&rdquo; (Gal. 6:10). It is very important for the richness of our lives together here on earth, for our personal growth here on earth, and for rewards in the next life, that each Christian needs to be &ldquo;other-focused;&rdquo; focused on others and how we can help them. The phrase &ldquo;one another&rdquo; occurs many times in the New Testament, stating and reinforcing that truth.</p> <p>[For more on the &ldquo;one another&rdquo; commands, see commentary on Galatians 5:13, &ldquo;one another.&rdquo; For more on &ldquo;love one another,&rdquo; see commentary on John 13:34.]</p> <p>&ldquo;Just as.&rdquo; The Greek also has a kai (and, also), but it is stylistic and appears in classical Greek writings also.a</p> <p>&ldquo;must forgive.&rdquo; The verb is not supplied, and although not completely necessary and therefore not necessarily an ellipsis, nevertheless, it seems logical to supply the verb, as many English versions do. Even those English versions which do not supply the verb &ldquo;forgive,&rdquo; often add words so the English reads easily. The Greek text is quite abbreviated, οὕτως καὶ ὑμεῖς; literally, &ldquo;so also you.&rdquo; Even the KJV adds the word &ldquo;do&rdquo; to help complete the sense: &ldquo;so also do ye.&rdquo;</p> <p>a)</p> <p>Markus Barth, Colossians [AB], 422.</p>'),
