(123, 1, 54, 3, 3, 0, 'Mercy', 99, '2022-11-21 12:26:28', '<p>&ldquo;reasonable.&rdquo; The Greek word is epieikēs (#1933 ἐπιεικής), which is an adjective, (occurs in Phil. 4:5; 1 Tim. 3:3; Titus 3:2; James 3:17; 1 Pet. 2:18). The noun is epieikeia (#1932 ἐπιείκεια; occurring in Acts 24:4; 2 Cor. 10:1). R. C. H. Lenski writes, &ldquo;[I wish] that we had a good English equivalent for this noble term!&rdquo;a</p> <p>The concepts of &ldquo;moderation, forbearance, gentleness, and sweet reasonableness&rdquo; all touch a side of the full meaning of this word. The meaning is yielding, not insisting on one&rsquo;s legal rights to the end that the legal rights become moral wrongs. Too strictly enforcing rules and not understanding that there are often legitimate exceptions turns &ldquo;right&rdquo; into &ldquo;wrong.&rdquo; Thus Ecclesiastes encourages people to not be excessively righteous (Ecc. 7:16).</p> <p>Richard Trench writes: &ldquo;Epieikeia refers to the sort of moderation that recognizes that it is impossible for formal laws to anticipate and provide for all possible cases and that the asserting of legal rights can be pushed into moral wrongs, so the highest right can in practice prove to be the greatest injustice.&rdquo;b As to the accusation that someone would be overly &ldquo;reasonable&rdquo; or yielding to evil, Lenski writes, &ldquo;Only perverted reason would think that &ldquo;yieldingness&rdquo; might include a yielding of truth to error, of right to wrong, of virtue to vice and crime&rdquo;c <strong>There are times when the &ldquo;rules&rdquo; obviously need to be bent to minister the grace of God effectively. This word covers exactly that situation&mdash;the true leader is &ldquo;reasonable,&rdquo; not rigid.</strong></p>'),
