(216, 0, 19, 19, 1, 0, null, 99, '2022-06-22 12:32:44', '<p>What stands out in this Psalm?</p> <p>God&rsquo;s overwhelming desire that we look to him for our soul to be restored, to become wise, heart rejoices, eyes enlightened, great reward that is better than gold and sweeter than honey.</p> <p>Importance of prayer to Bible reading?</p> <p>Asking God to show me my errors that I do not see,</p> <p>In what way does this psalm challenge my relationship with God?</p> <p>God is showing himself to me through nature and his word. Am I watching and listening to him? He knows me better than I know myself and can show me my sins.</p>'),
(216, 0, 19, 19, 14, 0, null, 99, '2022-06-22 12:43:15', '<p>What does it say?</p> <p>Let the words of my mouth and meditation of my heart be acceptable in God&rsquo;s eyes, who is my rock and redeemer.</p> <p>What is it saying to me?</p> <p>What I say and think matters to God and I desire to be accepted when God looks at me. He is my rock and redeemer; therefore, with His help I can do this.</p> <p>Short prayer.</p> <p>God, thank you that I please you through my words and my thoughts.</p>'),
(218, 1, 54, 1, 1, 0, null, 99, '2023-01-23 17:23:41', '<p><a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-study-guide-for-home-study-seminary-students/introduction-to-1-timothy?lang=eng">https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-study-guide-for-home-study-seminary-students/introduction-to-1-timothy?lang=eng</a></p> <p>In 1 Timothy we read that the Apostle Paul counseled Timothy, a Church leader in Ephesus, to ensure that sound doctrine was taught and not to allow popular falsehoods to distract from the teachings of the gospel. He taught Timothy about the offices of bishop and deacon and discussed the qualifications for those who served in these positions. Paul also recounted his deep gratitude for the mercy he had received from Jesus Christ when he was converted. Studying 1 Timothy can help increase your awareness of the importance of teaching sound doctrine in the Church. You can also deepen your appreciation for the Savior&rsquo;s mercy and for the important role of bishops and other Church leaders.</p> <p>Who Wrote This Book?</p> <p>Paul wrote 1 Timothy (see 1 Timothy 1:1).</p> <p>When and Where Was It Written?</p> <p>Paul&rsquo;s First Epistle to Timothy was likely written sometime between A.D. 64 and 65, possibly while Paul was in Macedonia (see Guide to the Scriptures, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles,&rdquo; scriptures.lds.org; 1 Timothy 1:3). Before writing this epistle, Paul had been released from his two-year imprisonment (house arrest) in Rome and was likely traveling widely, visiting regions where he had previously established branches of the Church (see Bible Dictionary, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles&rdquo;).</p> <p>To Whom Was It Written and Why?</p> <p>Paul wrote this epistle to Timothy, who had served with Paul during his second missionary journey (see Acts 16:1&ndash;3). Following their mission, Timothy continued to be a faithful missionary and Church leader (see Acts 19:22; Philippians 2:19) and one of Paul&rsquo;s most trusted associates (see 1 Corinthians 4:17). Paul referred to Timothy as his &ldquo;own son in the faith&rdquo; (1 Timothy 1:2). Timothy&rsquo;s father was a Greek Gentile, but he had a righteous Jewish mother and grandmother who had taught him and helped him learn the scriptures (see Acts 16:1; 2 Timothy 1:5; 3:15).</p> <p>At the time this epistle was written, Timothy was serving as a Church leader in Ephesus (see 1 Timothy 1:3). Paul hinted that some members doubted Timothy&rsquo;s leadership abilities because he was young (see 1 Timothy 4:12). Paul intended to visit Timothy in person, but he was unsure whether he would be able to do so (see 1 Timothy 3:14; 4:13). Paul wrote his epistle to Timothy to help the young Church leader better understand his duties.</p>'),
(218, 1, 55, 1, 1, 0, 'Paul also taught about the purposes of the scriptures. He ended his letter by encouraging Timothy to diligently fulfill his ministry.<br /> <span style="color:#e67e22;"><strong>Chronologically, 2 Timothy appears to be Paul&rsquo;s final letter in the New Testament (see 2 Timothy 4:6).</strong></span>', 99, '2023-01-23 17:22:00', '<p><a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-study-guide-for-home-study-seminary-students/introduction-to-2-timothy?lang=eng">https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-study-guide-for-home-study-seminary-students/introduction-to-2-timothy?lang=eng</a></p> <p>Paul&rsquo;s Second Epistle to Timothy emphasizes the power that comes from having a testimony of Jesus Christ (see 2 Timothy 1:7&ndash;8). It also contains a prophecy of the &ldquo;perilous times&rdquo; that would exist in the days of Paul and Timothy as well as in the last days (see 2 Timothy 3:1&ndash;7). To help Timothy with the challenges he faced, Paul encouraged him to trust in the scriptures and in Church leaders (see 2 Timothy 3:14&ndash;17) and to rely on true doctrine (see 2 Timothy 4:2).</p> <p>Paul&rsquo;s Second Epistle to Timothy was likely written sometime between A.D. 64 and 65 (see Guide to the Scriptures, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles,&rdquo; scriptures.lds.org). Paul wrote the epistle during his second imprisonment in Rome shortly before his martyrdom (see Bible Dictionary, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles&rdquo;).</p> <p>During his imprisonment Paul was in chains (see 2 Timothy 1:16; 2:9), he was likely in a cell or dungeon and exposed to the elements (see 2 Timothy 4:13, 21), and his friends struggled to locate him (see 2 Timothy 1:17). Luke was apparently his only regular visitor (see 2 Timothy 4:11), and Paul expected that his life was coming to an end (see 2 Timothy 4:6&ndash;8).</p> <p>In this letter Paul encouraged Timothy and offered strength to help him carry on after Paul&rsquo;s impending death. Paul was aware that his time was short, and he desired to see Timothy, whom Paul figuratively called &ldquo;my dearly beloved son&rdquo; (2 Timothy 1:2).</p> <p>At the end of his letter, Paul requested that Timothy and Mark visit him and bring him a few items that he had left behind (see 2 Timothy 4:9&ndash;13). Although Paul&rsquo;s letter was addressed specifically to Timothy, its counsel can be applied to those who live in &ldquo;the last days&rdquo; (2 Timothy 3:1) because Paul taught of challenges and solutions that are relevant to our day as well as his.</p> <p>This letter is one of the pastoral epistles, along with 1 Timothy and Titus, and &ldquo;contains the Apostle&rsquo;s last words and shows the wonderful courage and trust with which he faced death&rdquo; (see Bible Dictionary, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles&rdquo;). <span style="color:#e67e22;"><strong>Chronologically, 2 Timothy appears to be Paul&rsquo;s final letter in the New Testament (see 2 Timothy 4:6).</strong></span></p> <p>This letter contains some of Paul&rsquo;s reflections about the blessings and difficulties of serving as &ldquo;a preacher, and an apostle, and a teacher of the Gentiles&rdquo; (2 Timothy 1:11). Paul declared, &ldquo;I have fought a good fight, I have finished my course, I have kept the faith: Henceforth there is laid up for me a crown of righteousness&rdquo; (2 Timothy 4:7&ndash;8), indicating that he had a personal assurance that he would inherit eternal life. As one who had ministered for Jesus Christ for over 30 years, Paul was in an excellent position to instruct Timothy on how to serve effectively in strengthening the faith of others (see 2 Timothy 2:15&ndash;17, 22&ndash;26; 4:1&ndash;2, 5).</p>'),
(218, 1, 56, 1, 1, 0, 'This letter is one of the pastoral epistles (to a pastor, or leader, in the Church), along with 1 and 2 Timothy', 99, '2023-01-23 17:26:29', '<p><a href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-study-guide-for-home-study-seminary-students/introduction-to-titus?lang=eng">https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/new-testament-study-guide-for-home-study-seminary-students/introduction-to-titus?lang=eng</a></p> <p>Paul&rsquo;s letter to Titus, like his letters to Timothy, contains timeless counsel from the Apostle Paul to a local Church leader. Paul wrote that the <span style="font-size:110%;font-variant:small-caps;">&ldquo;hope of eternal life&rdquo; was first promised by God in the pre-earth life &ldquo;before the world began&rdquo; (Titus 1:2).</span> He taught that the Saints should look forward to &ldquo;that blessed hope&rdquo; of exaltation and to the Second Coming (Titus 2:13). Paul also wrote to Titus about &ldquo;the washing of regeneration&rdquo; and the &ldquo;renewing of the Holy Ghost&rdquo; (Titus 3:5), alluding to the ordinance of baptism and the purifying effect of receiving the gift of the Holy Ghost, both of which are preparatory to being &ldquo;made heirs according to the hope of eternal life&rdquo; (Titus 3:7). By studying Paul&rsquo;s inspired counsel to Titus, you can increase your <span style="font-size:110%;font-variant:small-caps;">faith that the doctrines and ordinances of the gospel bring hope for eternal life</span>.</p> <p>It is likely that Paul wrote the Epistle to Titus between his writing of 1 and 2 Timothy, around A.D. 64&ndash;65 (see Guide to the Scriptures, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles,&rdquo; scriptures.lds.org). Paul wrote the Epistle to Titus after his first imprisonment in Rome. <span style="color:#2ecc71;">He did not indicate where he was when he wrote this epistle.</span></p> <p>To Whom Was It Written and Why?</p> <p>This epistle was written by Paul to Titus, whom Paul referred to as &ldquo;mine own son after the common faith&rdquo; (Titus 1:4). Titus was a Greek (see Galatians 2:3) and had been converted to the gospel by Paul himself (see Bible Dictionary, &ldquo;Titus&rdquo;). After his conversion, Titus labored with Paul to spread the gospel and organize the Church (see Bible Dictionary, &ldquo;Titus&rdquo;). He helped gather donations for the poor in Jerusalem (see 2 Corinthians 8:6, 16&ndash;23) and also accompanied Paul to the Jerusalem council (see Galatians 2:1). Paul entrusted Titus to take his first epistle to the Saints living in Corinth (see 2 Corinthians 7:5&ndash;15). He wrote to Titus to strengthen him in his assignment to lead and care <span style="color:#f1c40f;">for the branch of the Church in Crete in spite of opposition</span> (see Titus 1:5, 10&ndash;11; 2:15; 3:10).</p> <p>This letter is one of the pastoral epistles (to a pastor, or leader, in the Church), along with 1 and 2 Timothy (see Bible Dictionary, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles&rdquo;). The Epistle of Titus provides the earliest evidence that the Church had been established on the Greek island of Crete in the Mediterranean Sea (see Titus 1:5). Titus had the responsibility of calling new bishops on the island. Paul listed <span style="color:#7f8c8d;">some</span> of the spiritual qualifications for bishops (see Titus 1:6&ndash;9). In addition, he gave specific advice to men, women, and servants on <span style="color:#4e5f70;">proper behavior for Saints</span> (see Titus 2:2&ndash;10).</p>'),
