(243, 1, 46, 12, 7, 0, '. . . for the common good &ndash; to build up the church and individuals in it.', 99, '2022-07-27 09:29:27', '<p>Some translations have &ldquo;for profit&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;for the common good&rdquo;. The use of &lsquo;common good&rsquo; <strong><em>symph&eacute;rō</em></strong> emphasises that the manifestations of God&rsquo;s spirit are not neccessarily for personal edification, but for edification or building up of the church of believers.</p> <p>Young has &lsquo;to bear together&rsquo; as the meaning of <strong><em>symph&eacute;rō</em></strong> as used in 1Cor 12:7.</p>'),
(243, 1, 46, 12, 10, 0, null, 99, '2022-07-23 10:20:53', '<p>Verses 8, 9 and 10 list the manifestations <strong><em>phanerosis</em></strong> of God&rsquo;s spirit to believers. These are imparted by God&rsquo;s grace <em><strong>charisma</strong></em> misleadingly descibed in most NT translations as &lsquo;gifts&rsquo;.</p> <p>The first gifts (or charisma&rsquo;s) are to do with edifying the assembly.</p> <p>Different kinds of tongues is not. (Unless interpreted).</p> <p>So, why is &lsquo;different kinds of tongues&rsquo; there?</p> <p>For that gift to be edifying (as the others are), it could apply to <span style="color:#2980b9;">individuals who know other languages</span> and are used to speak to the native speakers in their language in order to encourage them and share the gospel message. Also, as in Acts 2:4-13, when believers were filled with God&rsquo;s spirit and <span style="color:#2980b9;">the spirit gave them utterence</span>.</p> <p>A person who interprets the speaker of another language allows non-native speakers to also comprehend. Whether an interpreter knows the language spoken or does not know the language and the spirit interprets for him (or either) is not clear.</p> <p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="line-height:107%"><span new="" roman="" style="font-family:" times="">These manifestation <strong><em>phanerōsis</em></strong> of the spirit are given variously to each one for the common good. (See 1Cor 12:7)These manifestation <strong><em>phanerōsis</em></strong> of the spirit are given variously to each one for the common good. (See 1Cor 12:7)</span></span></span></p>'),
(243, 1, 46, 13, 1, 0, null, 99, '2022-07-23 09:44:47', '<p>The last verses of 1Cor 12 (verse 31): &ldquo;But earnestly desire the greater gifts. And yet I now show you a more excellent way&rdquo; leads to 1Cor 13:1. Paul goes on in chapter 13 discussing love as the greatest gift (or spiritual charisma &ndash; manifestation of God&rsquo;s grace).</p> <p>In chapter 12 Paul discusses the various charisma God provides for individuals and the church; including the gift of tongues and the interpretation of tongues. There is no reason to conclude from this chapter that these tongues are different from those mentioned in Acts 2. That they are languages of men.</p> <p>In 1Cor 13:1 Paul writes of the tongues of men (the languages of men), and also of the tongue or toungues of angels.<br /> Young states that&rsquo;angels&rsquo; in this verse mean &lsquo;messengers&rsquo; or &lsquo;agents&rsquo;. These messengers appear in the Hebrew scriptures as well as in the New Testament books. Invariably, when they talk to men or women, they converse in the language known to the recipient of the message or instruction.<br /> There is no indication anywhere in the scriptures that suggest the angels or messengers ever talk in any other fashion.<br /> What language (if any) is used in the heavenly realms is not known; and any suggestion of what it is can only be speculation.</p> <p>It is common in Christian teaching that the &ldquo;tongues of angels&rdquo; is glossolalia or intelligible utterings of people &lsquo;talking in tongues&rsquo;. But this is conjecture because, as has been seen, there are no scriptural indications that this should be so.</p> <p>Why does Paul use the expression &ldquo;tongues . . of angels&rdquo;?<br /> Some commentators say that Paul uses the phrase &lsquo;of angels&rsquo; to emphasise by hyperbole that speaking in any language to carry out God&rsquo;s work is empty unless love is behind what is said.</p> <p>Verses 2 and 3 use this pattern also.</p> <p>Here are verses 1 to 3 that show, using <span style="color:#d35400;">hyperbole</span>, that <span style="color:#16a085;">tongues, prophesy and giving</span> are all <span style="color:#2980b9;">nothing</span> without <span style="color:#8e44ad;">love</span>.</p> <blockquote> <p>If I speak with the <span style="color:#27ae60;">tongues of men</span> and <span style="color:#d35400;">of angels</span> but <span style="color:#8e44ad;">do not have love</span>, <span style="color:#2980b9;">I have become a sounding bronze, or a clanging cymbal.</span><br /> <br /> And if I <span style="color:#27ae60;">prophesy</span>, and <span style="color:#d35400;">know all the sacred secrets and all the knowledge</span>, and if <span style="color:#27ae60;">I have all trust</span> so that <span style="color:#d35400;">I can move mountains</span>, but I <span style="color:#8e44ad;">do not have love</span>, <span style="color:#2980b9;">I am nothing</span>.<br /> <br /> And if <span style="color:#27ae60;">I give</span> all <span style="color:#d35400;">my possessions to feed the poor</span>, and if <span style="color:#27ae60;">I give</span> <span style="color:#d35400;">my body to be burned</span>, but <span style="color:#8e44ad;">do not have love</span>, it <span style="color:#2980b9;">profits me nothing</span>.</p> </blockquote> <p><strong>In Summary:<br /> 1. It is unlikely that Paul is suggesting that some sort of non-human angelic language is included in his reference to &lsquo;tongues&rsquo;.<br /> 2. It is purely speculation by people that the &lsquo;tongues of angels&rsquo; imply a non-human angelic language.</strong></p> <p><strong>3. To use this verse to say that any of the occurences of the word &lsquo;tongues&rsquo; in 1Corinthians 14 means <em>glossolalia</em> has no validity.</strong></p>'),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 1, 0, 'Prophesy imparts information for building individuals or for building the church.', 99, '2022-07-26 09:58:57', '<p>Paul, in chapter 13 presents the case that love <strong><em>agape</em></strong> is the greatest manifestation of God&rsquo;s spirit &ndash; being the outworking of God&rsquo;s grace <strong><em>charisma</em></strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Paul writes in verse 8:<br /> Love never fails, but where there are prophecies, they will be done away; where there are tongues, they will cease; where there is a message of knowledge, it will be done away.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p>And in verse 13:<br /> But now remains trust, hope, love, these three, and the greatest of these is love.</p> </blockquote> <p>He contiues this theme in chapter 14 to not only desire love, but also other spiritual manifestations of God&rsquo;s <strong><em>charisma</em></strong> - especially to desire prophesy.</p> <p>Why especially &lsquo;prophesy&rsquo;?</p> <blockquote> <p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span new="" roman="" style="font-family:" times="">Note from <a href="https://www.ministrymagazine.org/archive/1973/12/what-is-prophesying">https://www.ministrymagazine.org/archive/1973/12/what-is-prophesying</a></span></span></span></span><br /> <span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="background:white"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">The root meaning of</span></span></span> <span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">προφητης</span></span> <span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">(prophet), &quot;one who speaks for&quot; another, is a natural basis for the classical meaning &quot;an interpreter of the will of a god.&quot; While it is by no means true that classical Greek always provides precise expression for Hebrew meanings, in this instance it is excellent.</span></span></span> <span style="color:black"><a href="https://biblia.com/bible/esv/Exod%207.1" target="_blank"><span style="border:none windowtext 1.0pt; font-size:12.0pt; padding:0cm"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:black"><span style="text-decoration:none"><span style="text-underline:none">Exodus 7:1</span></span></span></span></span></a></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">,</span></span></span> <span style="color:black"><a href="https://biblia.com/bible/esv/Exodus%207.2" target="_blank"><span style="border:none windowtext 1.0pt; font-size:12.0pt; padding:0cm"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:black"><span style="text-decoration:none"><span style="text-underline:none">2</span></span></span></span></span></a></span> <span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">illustrates this well: Aaron was Moses&#39; &quot;prophet&quot; in the same way as Moses was the prophet of Jehovah. And Jesus of Nazareth was that &quot;Prophet&quot; fore told by Moses (</span></span></span><span style="color:black"><a href="https://biblia.com/bible/esv/Deut.%2018.15" target="_blank"><span style="border:none windowtext 1.0pt; font-size:12.0pt; padding:0cm"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:black"><span style="text-decoration:none"><span style="text-underline:none">Deut. 18:15</span></span></span></span></span></a></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">;</span></span></span> <span style="color:black"><a href="https://biblia.com/bible/esv/John%207.40" target="_blank"><span style="border:none windowtext 1.0pt; font-size:12.0pt; padding:0cm"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:black"><span style="text-decoration:none"><span style="text-underline:none">John 7:40</span></span></span></span></span></a></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">) because like Moses He received instruction from God, which He relayed to the people and frequently repeated to them (</span></span></span><span style="color:black"><a href="https://biblia.com/bible/esv/Deut.%2018.16-19" target="_blank"><span style="border:none windowtext 1.0pt; font-size:12.0pt; padding:0cm"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:black"><span style="text-decoration:none"><span style="text-underline:none">Deut. 18:16-19</span></span></span></span></span></a></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">;</span></span></span> <span style="color:black"><a href="https://biblia.com/bible/esv/John%208.26-28" target="_blank"><span style="border:none windowtext 1.0pt; font-size:12.0pt; padding:0cm"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:black"><span style="text-decoration:none"><span style="text-underline:none">John 8:26-28</span></span></span></span></span></a></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span noto="" serif="" style="font-family:"><span style="color:#4a4a4a">).</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p> </blockquote> <p>In Corinthians 12,13,14, a &lsquo;prophesy&rsquo; is something &ndash; large or small &ndash; that a person recieves from God and imparts to another or others. Jesus said what the Father told him; Paul imparted what he had learned from God; others in the NT recieved shorter, but significant messages from God (or Jesus) that would edify individuals or a group of believers.<br /> All these prphesies built individuals and the church.</p> <p>Note that in the next verse (verse 2), Paul talks of &ldquo;whoever talks in tongues&rdquo; tongues. He does not mention in this instance interpretation of those tongues.</p>'),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 2, 0, '&lsquo;Whoever speaks in another language or dialect which no one understands, prays to God privately.&rsquo;', 99, '2022-08-19 05:53:46', '<p>The word &lsquo;<em>sacred</em>&rsquo; is added in the translation and is misleading. According to Young : . . . speaks &ldquo;what is known only to the initiated&rdquo; for &ldquo;speaks sacred secrets&rdquo;. That is, &lsquo;secrets&rsquo; =&gt; &lsquo;what is known only to the initiated&rsquo;.<br /> This implies that, because those in a particular group (the initiated) can understand what is being said, the language or dialect must be a human one.</p> <p>Note that no mention is made of an interpretation of what is said in the &lsquo;tongue&rsquo;.</p> <p>The &lsquo;tongue&rsquo; spoken of here could mean one of the Greek dialects which were spoken by the intelligensia, but which are not used by the common person.<br /> The &lsquo;tongue&rsquo; also could be Hebrew which only a few Jews &ndash; such as the priests and scribes &ndash; knew. Paul, being a learned &lsquo;pharisie of the pharisies&rsquo; probably could speak Hebrew.<br /> The &lsquo;tongue&rsquo; may have been Aramaic which was used by the Jews (along with Greek). The Corinthians likely wouldn&rsquo;t have known Aramaic.</p> <p>The tongue (or language) is unknown because no one (or not everyone) <em>present</em> understood it.<br /> But the person praying (by his own spirit or self) would of course.</p> <p>There is no reason to come to a conclusion that the tongue or language is not an existing human language or dialect.</p>'),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 4, 0, 'The one speaking in a language or dialect that others cannot understand, builds up only himself as no one else can partake. (Unless it is interpreted &ndash; see later)', 99, '2022-08-19 05:55:01', '<p>See also 1Cor 14:14 which says a similar thing.</p> <p>Regarding prophesies, these, as <em>charisma</em>, were received revelations which were edifying for the church or individuals.</p> <p>Young&rsquo;s for &lsquo;builds&rsquo; in 1Cor 14:4 &ndash; <strong><em>oikodomeō</em></strong>, to build up. Such as is used in 1Peter 2:5</p> <blockquote> <p>1Peter 2:5 &ndash; . . . you also, as living stones, are being built up <strong><em>oikodomeō</em></strong> a spiritual house, a holy priesthood, to offer up spiritual sacrifices acceptable to God through Jesus Christ.</p> </blockquote> <p>That is, for each person to be built up &ndash; to improve and enable one to be guided by the spirit of God.</p> <p>Similarly for &ldquo;builds up <strong><em>oikodomeō</em></strong> the chutch&rdquo;, the body of believers is strengthened, and grows to work with one accord</p> <p>For the &lsquo;tongue&rsquo; to improve a person, they must understand what is said; otherwise how can they be &lsquo;built up&rsquo;?</p> <p>Some may argue that a person talking <em>glossolalia</em> (without understanding) is built up by the presence of God&rsquo;s spirit; but there is no Biblical indication that that is so. Every believer is blessed and built up by God&rsquo;s spirit from time to time without talking <em>glossolalia</em>.</p>'),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 5, 0, 'Prophesies, as <em>charisma</em>, are received revelations for edification of the church or individuals.', 99, '2022-08-18 09:45:24', null),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 6, 0, 'This verse links to verse 14 &ndash; if one speaks in another language, let what is said be interpreted and edifying.', 99, '2022-08-19 05:58:47', null),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 14, 0, 'I pray with understanding; but that is unfruitful fot others (who don&rsquo;t understand the language or dialect).This links to vs 6', 99, '2022-08-19 04:26:15', '<p>I pray with my own understanding, but that is unhelpful to others (who don&rsquo;t understand the language or dialect I am using); so it is not useful or edifying for them</p>'),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 18, 0, 'Paul likely spoke Hebrew, Aramaic and Greek, and some Greek dialects used by scholars.<br /> At Mars Hill, he would have conversed amongst the intelligentsia using their language or dialect.', 99, '2022-08-19 06:02:20', null),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 21, 0, 'The &lsquo;people with other tongues &rsquo; were the Assyrians who took Israel captive to Assyria.<br /> They didn&rsquo;t repent (so never returned) despite the &lsquo;sign&rsquo; of a foreign language as spoken by Isaiah (Isaiah 28:11)', 99, '2022-08-19 05:23:43', null),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 22, 0, 'The Jews in Corinth (as in other places) did not believe the Gospel message.<br /> God rejected the Jews and the Gospel was acccepted and preached to and by Gentiles &ndash; of various languages &ndash; a sign to the contemporary Jews.', 99, '2022-08-19 06:03:28', null),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 23, 0, 'Other languages was a sign to the contemporary Jews; but languages spoken at meetings haphazardly and without order was madness to the gentiles', 99, '2022-08-19 05:36:02', null),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 26, 0, 'If anyone speaks in an unfamiliar language or dialect, it should be interpreted', 99, '2022-08-19 05:37:52', null),
(243, 1, 46, 14, 39, 0, 'Although the use of foriegn languages by some at Corinth was out of control; Paul does not discourage their use as long as they are used in an orderly fasion and interpretd if neccessary', 99, '2022-08-19 05:41:20', null),
