(342, 0, 1, 41, 40, 4, 'A type/ parallel with Christ', 99, '2022-12-25 13:40:57', '<p>&ldquo;I love the Old Testament story of how Joseph was taken after years of suffering and humiliation and exalted by Pharaoh to the first place in Egypt. The story suggests a beautiful type/ parallel with Christ being exalted by his God and Father to being His righthand man in His Kingdom. Pharaoh announces to Joseph: &ldquo;You shall be over my house, and according to your command all my people shall do homage; only in the throne I will be greater then you.&rdquo; And Pharaoh said to Joseph, &ldquo;See, I have set you over all the land of Egypt.&rdquo; Then Pharaoh took off his signet ring from his hand, and put it on Joseph&rsquo;s hand, and clothed him in garments of fine linen, and put the gold necklace around his neck. And he had him ride in his second chariot; and they proclaimed before him, &ldquo;Bow the knee!&rdquo; And he set him over all the land of Egypt. Moreover, Pharaoh said to Joseph, &ldquo;Though I am Pharaoh, yet without your permission no one shall raise his hand or foot in all the land of Egypt&rdquo; (Ex. 41:40-44). What a beautiful picture of the kind of prominence and place of honour God has exalted the Lord Jesus to. This was not a position Christ had by always being God from eternity. Jesus is &ldquo;the first-born from the dead; so that he himself might come to have first place in everything.&rdquo;&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; They Never Told Me This in Church! by Greg Deuble</p> <p>&ldquo;For &ldquo;God has put all things in subjection under his feet.&rdquo; But when it says, &ldquo;all things are put in subjection,&rdquo; it is plain that he is excepted who put all things in subjection under him (1Cor. 15:27). This means that God&rsquo;s purpose in Christ is to make man His vice-regent over all of creation, second only to God in the universe! All this is what God will accomplish in and through Christ&mdash;as man, for the words in Psalm 8 concern man and Yahweh&rsquo;s exalted purpose for him. This finds a good illustration in the well-known story of Joseph, whom Pharaoh appointed ruler over everything in Egypt&mdash;everything, that is, excluding Pharaoh himself (Gen. 45:26), thus making him second only to Pharaoh in the whole land. Such is God&rsquo;s glorious predestined plan for man in Christ. The exaltation of Christ in Philippians 2:9-11 can be illustrated by the exaltation of Joseph as ruler of Egypt in the following manner, &ldquo;Then Pharaoh took his signet ring from his hand and put it on Joseph&rsquo;s hand, and clothed him in garments of fine linen and put a gold chain about his neck&rdquo; (Genesis 41:42). These were not merely ceremonial acts, for by them Pharaoh conferred his own authority and glory upon Joseph, most notably by giving Joseph his signet ring which bore his personal seal, with which the king&rsquo;s official orders were sealed. That meant that Pharaoh entrusted the full weight of his personal authority to Joseph, thereby empowering him to act on Pharaoh&rsquo;s behalf. In the same way, in Philippians 2:9-11, Yahweh conferred on Jesus His own divine glory and authority. Just as the signet ring bore Pharaoh&rsquo;s name (the name above all names in Egypt) upon it, so, too, Yahweh conferred on Jesus the name above all names, and thereby fully empowered Jesus to act on His behalf. Yet the fact that the man Christ Jesus will be second only to Yahweh God in all of creation (and we in Christ) seems not good enough for trinitarians. Out of a misguided &ldquo;zeal for God, but not according to knowledge&rdquo; (Rom. 10:2; in which I also shared), they insist that Christ has to be absolutely equal with God in every way&mdash;something which Christ himself refused to grasp at (Phil. 2:6). For some strange (perhaps perverse?) reason they will not have it that Yahweh alone must be &ldquo;all in all&rdquo; (1Cor. 15:28), even though this is what the Son himself affirms by his own subjection to God, who subjected all things to him (v. 28). We do well to be careful lest we allow our misguided &ldquo;zeal&rdquo; to bring us into condemnation.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Only True God: A Study of Biblical Monotheism by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan</p> <p>I looked through a bunch of Trinitarian commentaries on this Joseph story and none of them seem to get the type here. Probably because it doesn&#39;t fit their narrative of God becoming man at the so called incarceration.</p>'),
