(342, 0, 12, 2, 11, 1, 'Elijah taken up into Heaven', 99, '2023-02-10 23:58:21', '<p>&ldquo;&ldquo;Those who insist that the whirlwind took Elijah to heaven, to immortality, into God&rsquo;s presence (despite Heb. 1:13, 39) have real difficulty with his letter to Jehoram. They have to suggest (a) that 2 Chronicles 21:12-15 is a corrupted text (though there&rsquo;s no evidence for this): or (b) that Elijah foresaw Jehoram&rsquo;s idolatry and, writing the letter before he is removed, left it with someone with instructions to send it ten years later; or (c) that he came back from heaven in order to write to Jehoram. But the straightforward explanation rings most true. And John was not opposing the Old Testament Scripture when he wrote John 3:13. Elijah and Enoch are not, as we say in Hebrews 11, exceptions. They too died (Hebrews 11:13), although they had previously experienced a miraculous &lsquo;transference&rsquo; by divine intervention. &ldquo;Josephus, the Jewish historian, says: &lsquo;As for Elijah and for Enoch (who was before the flood) it is written in the sacred books that they disappeared&rsquo; (Antiq. IX. 2.2). He gives no hint that he thought Enoch had ascended immortal to heaven but he does indicate mystery in his &lsquo;disappearance&rsquo; and links it with that of Elijah.&rdquo;&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
