(342, 0, 23, 6, 1, 0, null, 99, '2022-12-30 18:56:00', '<p>Follow-Up On Isaiah Seeing God&rsquo;s Glory - Not Jesus&rsquo;s Glory - At Isaiah 6:1&amp;5</p> <p>During a conversation following my original posting regarding the false Trinitarian argument that Isaiah saw Jesus&rsquo;s glory at Is.6:1,5 (https://www.facebook.com/.../17166.../posts/3436709956597266) it was argued that 1 Cor.10:1-4 - &ldquo;They [the Israelites in the wilderness] drank of that spiritual Rock that followed them: and that Rock was Christ&rdquo; - proves that Jesus is God because both are given the title &quot;rock&rdquo;.</p> <p>In answering this argument, I spent several hours doing research, and in the hope that it might prove valuable to some people in this group I am reposting my answer here:</p> <p>The Rock Is Not Jesus, It &ldquo;Represents&rdquo; Jesus</p> <p>Paul is using the metaphor of the rock that provided water for the Israelites in the wilderness (Ex.15:22-27) as a way of illustrating how Jesus is the source of spiritual nourishment for believers:</p> <p>&ldquo;This cannot be intended to be understood literally, for it was NOT LITERALLY TRUE&hellip; the gushing fountain of water might be regarded as A REPRESENTATION OF the Messiah, and of the blessings which result from him&hellip; the word &lsquo;was&rsquo; is often used to denote similarity or representation, and is NOT TO BE TAKEN LITERALLY. That rock was a striking REPRESENTATION of the fulness of the Messiah, of the abundant grace which he imparts to his people. The design of the apostle is apparent. It is to show&hellip; that which TYPIFIED the Messiah - Barnes&#39; Notes on the Bible</p> <p>To typify is: &ldquo;To serve as an EXAMPLE of&hellip;to REPRESENT, SYMBOLIZE, or PREFIGURE&hellip; BY MODEL OR RESEMBLENCE&rdquo; - The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language, 5th Edition</p> <p>&ldquo;That rock did&hellip; PREFIGURE Christ&hellip; in the same sense that the bread in the Lord&rsquo;s supper is the body of Christ, that is&hellip; SIGNIFIES Christ&rdquo;. - Matthew Poole&#39;s Commentary</p> <p>&lsquo;For they drank, of that spiritual rock that followed them&rsquo;; by which the apostle means NOT CHRIST HIMSELF, &hellip; BUT THE ROCK THAT TYPIFIED HIM&hellip; it SIGNIFIED Christ, it was A TYPE of him&hellip; Christ may be COMPARED TO the rock&hellip; as he is the foundation of his church&rdquo; - Gill&#39;s Exposition of the Entire Bible</p> <p>&ldquo;Did SIGNIFY Christ&rdquo; - Geneva Study Bible</p> <p>Shared Titles, Not Shared Identity</p> <p>The fact that Jesus and God share the title &ldquo;rock&rdquo; does not mean that they are the same being. Jesus also called Peter a rock, but Peter is neither Jesus nor God (Jesus said that only the Father is God - Jn.17:3). While God Himself is often called a &ldquo;rock&rdquo; (Dt.32:4, Ps.18:2, Is.26:4, etc.), Is.8:14 refers to the Messiah to come as a different rock - one which God would lay for a stumbling stone (to which Paul refers in Ro.9:33). This rock, laid by God, is not God Himself.</p> <p>Again, the &ldquo;living stone&rdquo; to which 1Pet.2:3 likens Jesus is not God Himself, but is &ldquo;chosen of God&rdquo;. And while Is.8:13-15 says that &ldquo;Jehovah of armies Himself&hellip; shall be&hellip; for a stone of stumbling&rdquo;, Scripture also states that He will lay a rock upon which unbelievers would stumble - from which we may properly conclude that:</p> <p>Jesus, as the rock God laid, TYPIFIES the Rock which is God, but is not himself God.</p> <p>Isaiah Distinguishes Between God And The Messiah</p> <p>Isaiah makes a continuous distinction between God and His Messiah-to-come, establishing that this Messiah is not God but His anointed representative and savior:</p> <p>&ldquo;Behold my servant, whom I uphold&hellip; I have put my spirit upon him&rdquo; - Is.42:1</p> <p>&ldquo;I, Jehovah&hellip; will&hellip; give thee for a covenant of the people, for a light of the Gentiles; To open the blind eyes&hellip;&rdquo; - Is.42:6,7</p> <p>&ldquo;Jehovah hath laid on him the iniquity of us all&hellip; it pleased Jehovah to bruise him; He hath put him to grief&rdquo; - Is.53:6,10</p> <p>&ldquo;Jehovah hath anointed me&hellip; he hath sent me&rdquo; - Is.61:1</p> <p>In light of Isaiah&rsquo;s continuous and clear distinction between God and Jesus, it would make no sense to interpret Isaiah 6:1,5 etc. as equating Jesus WITH God, nor does it, nor does John say that it does.</p>'),
(342, 0, 23, 6, 3, 0, null, 99, '2022-12-29 11:31:35', '<p>I can&#39;t believe Calvin thinks this is Jesus!</p> <p><br /> &ldquo;the God who appeared to Isaiah was the one true God, and yet John declares that he was Christ&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Institutes of the Christian Religion by John Calvin</p> <p><br /> &nbsp;</p>'),
