(342, 1, 40, 3, 17, 4, 'The son of God', 99, '2023-01-13 14:00:07', '<p>How did God the father introduced Jesus to the world? He called him his son.</p> <p>&ldquo;Brethren, I cannot fathom why my Trinitarian brethren totally disregard the straightforward and explicit words of Jesus. Apparently Jesus&rsquo; words to the disciples don&rsquo;t apply to them. Moses in the Old Testament claimed there would be a prophet like him who would come from among their brethren, and clearly stated, &ldquo;Listen to him!&rdquo; On the Mount of Transfiguration when God appeared in a cloud and stated that Jesus was His Son, the one whom He loved and approved, He added: &ldquo;Listen to him!&rdquo; James, John, and Peter were witnesses. How arrogant is a theologian, bible study teacher, author, or scholar to dare to call God a liar? I can&rsquo;t help but surmise that they must really have an eternal death wish.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
(342, 1, 40, 4, 10, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-18 15:29:50', null),
(342, 1, 40, 5, 5, 1, 'God owns the Earth', 99, '2023-01-12 23:32:21', '<p>Exod. 9:29; Ps. 24:1; 1 Cor. 10:26</p> <p>The reading of 1 Corinthians 15 at funerals reinforces the impression that this chapter is about the moment of death: in fact it revolves around two points, &lsquo;the third day&rsquo; and &lsquo;the last day.&rsquo;&rdquo;6<br /> Christians are challenged by Jesus to accept, believe and confess the biblical point of view and to expose erroneous tradition, however cherished and popular. The Bible, as professor Robinson and many others have told us, nowhere speaks of &ldquo;heaven at death&rdquo; as the Christian objective. Jesus and the Apostles constantly reinforced the Hebrew Bible&rsquo;s (our Old Testament&rsquo;s) promise that God is going to renew this planet earth and invite those who follow Him to &ldquo;inherit the earth.&rdquo; Jesus said it in words that ought not to be misunderstood: &ldquo;Blessed are the meek, for they are going to inherit the earth&rdquo; (Matt. 5:5). Could anything be clearer, as a statement of the point and purpose and goal of the Christian faith?<br /> Jesus, whose words are the words of life (John 6:63) and who must be believed by all who claim to &ldquo;believe in him,&rdquo; was citing Psalm 37:11. The meek are destined to have this renewed earth as their reward and inheritance.</p> <p>Popular tracts continue to make the biblical reward obscure. By avoiding the clear verses which spell out the Christian future, they leave the impression that &ldquo;heaven&rdquo; as a place far distant from this planet is where Christians are headed. This unbiblical teaching is reinforced in hymns, at funerals and by a deluge of literature. Christians constantly and habitually speak of heaven as their destination. With this they reinforce their misunderstanding. Our own habitual words teach us &mdash; not necessarily the truth! All this popular language about heaven blocks, jams and rejects the words of Scripture and of Jesus about the Christian&rsquo;s destiny and destination.</p> <p>Focus on the Kingdom, December 2007...its in my ebooks</p> <p>&ldquo;Behold, days are coming, declares the LORD, when I will raise up for David a righteous branch [the Messiah]; and he will reign as king and act wisely and do justice and righteousness in the land. In his days Judah will be saved, and Israel will dwell securely&rdquo; (Jer. 23:5-6).</p>'),
