(342, 1, 40, 25, 34, 1, 'The Kingdom of God', 99, '2022-12-27 11:47:31', '<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;From the foundation of the world&rsquo; is indicative that God purposed this very earth, when founded, for this Kingdom&rdquo; (The Theocratic Kingdom, Vol. 1, p. 35). The earth, as originally created, truly a crown jewel in the universe before it was cursed, was evidence of God&rsquo;s intention to carry out His plan for His Kingdom. As Christ&rsquo;s teachings show, this plan, though delayed through Adam&rsquo;s rebellion, is still being carried out. The earth still exists for the coming Kingdom.</p> <p>God pre- planned the kingdom, the Messiah, and the ones who share in populating the kingdom, its inhabitants. It is clear that the earth was designed and created as the location of the Kingdom of God.</p> <p>As human beings must change and be prepared to become citizens of the kingdom (Eph. 2:19), so the earth must be changed too. It is not the flawless sphere it was at creation, &ldquo;For the creation was subjected to futility, not of its own will, but because of Him who subjected it, in hope that the creation itself also will be set free from its slavery to corruption into the freedom of the glory of the children of God. For we know that the whole creation groans and suffers the pains of childbirth together until now&rdquo; (Rom 8:20-22, NASV). It has been cursed. It must be restored to be a suitable dwelling place for the glorious Kingdom and its inhabitants, &ldquo;For just as the new heavens and the new earth which I make will endure before Me, declares the Lord, so your offspring and your name will endure&rdquo; (Isa. 66:22, NASV).</p> <p>The present degenerate and decadent system will be forgotten and replaced with a new heavens and earth (Isa. 65:17-18). The apostle Peter says, &ldquo;even now we are looking for a new heavens and earth in which righteousness dwells&rdquo; (2Peter 3:13).<br /> Revelation 21:1 portrays the new heavens and earth. The former has passed away. The earth is restored to its original, beautiful, radiant, breathtaking glory, now suitable for its new inhabitants. God, Himself, in this opulent, royal setting, will dwell here in His full glory (v. 3). This is what the earth is for.</p> <p>Focus on the Kingdom<br /> Volume 2 No. 2 Anthony Buzzard, editor November, 1999</p>'),
(342, 1, 40, 25, 41, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-03 13:13:10', null),
(342, 1, 40, 25, 46, 1, 'Hell', 99, '2023-01-03 16:14:31', '<p>&ldquo;Eternal Conscious Torment (ECT). This is the view that is most commonly held by Protestant Christians, hence labelled the &ldquo;traditional&rdquo; view. Wayne Grudem defines hell as &ldquo;a place of eternal conscious punishment for the wicked.&rdquo; N.T. Wright states: &ldquo;The traditional view of hell is clear: human beings will be punished in an endless time.&rdquo; Biblical support for this view can be seen at least in ten texts in the Scripture that speak specifically about hell and the final state of the wicked: Isaiah 66:22-24; Daniel 12:2-3; Matthew 18:6-9; 25:31-46; Mark 9:42-48; 2 Thessalonians 1:6-10; Jude 7,13; Revelation 14:9-11; 20:10,14-15</p> <p>&ldquo;Just like capital punishment, &ldquo;eternal punishment&rdquo; is a punishment with an everlasting consequence. It is God&rsquo;s penal judgment on the wicked that is irreversible. The wicked will not return. This is &ldquo;the second death from which there is no resurrection or return forever.&rdquo;[ 43] In other words, &ldquo;eternal punishment&rdquo; does not refer to eternal punishing of the wicked, but once the punishment has been carried out the effect will last forever.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;Stott concluded that although fire in itself can inflict pain, the purpose of fire is to destroy. Stott argued that the outcome of fire is annihilation. Fire burns up what is put into it. The biblical imagery of fire implies that sin, evil, the devil, and the wicked will one day be no more. Stott added, &ldquo;It would be very odd if what is thrown into [the fire] proved indestructible.&rdquo;[&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;Stott concluded that although fire in itself can inflict pain, the purpose of fire is to destroy. Stott argued that the outcome of fire is annihilation. Fire burns up what is put into it. The biblical imagery of fire implies that sin, evil, the devil, and the wicked will one day be no more. Stott added, &ldquo;It would be very odd if what is thrown into [the fire] proved indestructible.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Conditional Immortality: The Case for Orthodoxy on the Doctrine of Annihilationism by Tanwin Tanoto<br /> &nbsp;</p> <p>&mdash; Conditional Immortality: The Case for Orthodoxy on the Doctrine of Annihilationism by Tanwin Tanoto</p> <p>&ldquo;Clearly something about hell is eternal. Exactly what that is, and what it means, is the subject of earnest conversation and sometimes heated debate among the scholars. The traditional majority view says that hell is eternal, that those who go to hell are eternal, and that they will live eternally in hell. In addition, this view says the torments of hell are eternal and will never end.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Hell A Final Word by Edward William Fudge</p>'),
