(342, 1, 42, 9, 26, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-15 13:14:06', '<p>&ldquo;All those Christians who disbelieve or are a bit suspect of the Trinity, but are sitting quietly in bible study classrooms, mouths closed tightly because they don&rsquo;t want to make waves for fear of rejection by the fellowship or family and friends by disavowing the human Son of God, consider what Jesus says regarding this stance: &ldquo;Everyone therefore who shall confess me before men, I will also confess him before my Father who is in heaven. But whoever shall deny me before men, I will also deny him before my Father who is in heaven&rdquo; (Matt. 10:32). &ldquo;Whoever is ashamed of me and my words, of him will the Son of Man [Jesus] be ashamed when he comes in his glory and the glory of [God] the Father and of the holy angels&rdquo; (Luke 9:26). (emphasis mine). According to Trinitarians Jesus IS God, so who is Jesus referring to as his Father in heaven in this verse? Where did Jesus say his Father was? In heaven! There goes the Nicene and Chalcedonian &ldquo;theory&rdquo; that God left heaven and became &ldquo;incarnate&rdquo; flesh and walked among humanity in old dusty shoe leather. According to my Trinitarian brethren and clergy, Jesus is obviously lying and/or doesn&rsquo;t know who he is. Well, not to worry, all Trinitarians know&mdash;it&rsquo;s a mystery, and it isn&rsquo;t Jesus speaking but God speaking in his human Jesus (dual nature) mode. Thus dictates the Chalcedon creed of 451 A.D. I personally believe that the Trinity is Satan&rsquo;s biggest and most convincing lie, and millions of Christians have made Satan, the father of lies, a very happy fat cat.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
