(342, 1, 43, 1, 1, 1, 'The word', 99, '2023-01-27 16:52:59', '<p>God&rsquo;s word in John 1 is simply the word of God, His creative wisdom and plan. That expressive activity of God was later embodied in the human Messiah who arose in due time, and by miraculous intervention, from a family in Israel just as Moses had predicted (Deut. 18:15-19).</p> <p>See the excellent article in &ldquo;Focus on the Kingdom&quot;, March, 2000</p> <p>It is entitled; &quot;Believing Impossible Things&quot;</p> <p>Most Trinitarians believe that the logos refers to Jesus Christ, so to them the translation &ldquo;him&rdquo; is proper. However, we assert that the logos is not a person, but the plan or purpose of God, and is, therefore, an &ldquo;it.&rdquo;</p> <p>The plan and purpose of God, that the earth and people would be restored to Him, was with Him in the beginning, and the plan and purpose became flesh in Jesus Christ as John 1:14 says, and so from John 1:14 until the end of John, the flesh and blood Christ is the focus, not the &ldquo;plan,&rdquo; the logos, of God.</p> <p>-from this commentary</p> <p>The Trinity is derived from Deductive reasoning, which is the mental process of drawing deductive inferences. It is a well known fact that the Bible does not contain any clear teaching on the Trinity doctrine. (Michael Todd)</p> <p>&ldquo;So shall My word be that goes from My mouth; it shall not return to Me void, but it shall accomplish what I please, and it shall prosper in the thing for which I sent it. (Isaiah 55:11) In this last example from Isaiah, we are to understand God&rsquo;s &ldquo;word&rdquo; as His plan or purpose or decree. So there is no good reason for the word logos to refer to a preexisting Son of God. In fact, nowhere in the entire Bible can you find any Hebrew or Greek word for &ldquo;word&rdquo; that implies another preexisting person in the Godhead. Also in John 1:2, 3, the words &ldquo;He&rdquo; and &ldquo;Him&rdquo; are impersonal pronouns in the Greek and therefore should be translated as &ldquo;it&rdquo; when referring to logos. Every English Bible before the King James Version of 1611 translated the pronouns this way. The following is an example. In the beginning was the word, and the word was with God: and the word was God. The same was in the beginning with God. All things were made by it, and without it nothing was made that was made. (Tyndale New Testament) [my emphasis]&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Twenty Biblical Reasons Why the Doctrine of the Trinity is Unbiblical by Chuck LaMattina</p> <p>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t help but wonder, what verse would they reference to the point of &ldquo;over-kill&rdquo; if John 1:1 wasn&rsquo;t in the Scriptures? Furthermore if John, who was exiled on the Island of Patmos and given a revelation of the Day of the Lord, had meant for the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; to mean Jesus was the one Almighty God, wouldn&rsquo;t he have been shocked to discover that Jesus and God were two completely separate entities in the heavenly realm? It was God&rsquo;s word (logos): His &ldquo;predetermined plan&rdquo; that became manifested in the man Jesus Christ, our lord and savior. John who was on the Mount of Transfiguration with Peter and James witnessed God&rsquo;s confirmation that Jesus was the one he loved and approved, and He charged them to &ldquo;listen to him!&rdquo; Was this a command from God or just a suggestion?&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p> <p>&ldquo;John wrote &lsquo;In the beginning was the word.&rsquo; The capital letter (&lsquo;Word&rsquo;) in your translation is very misleading, making you think that there are two persons there! The word was the word of God, not the Son of God. Only in verse 14 did that word or promise become a human person, when God brought about the generation of His unique Son by miracle in Mary.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;compatriots&hellip;John does not present Jesus as an eternal member of a Triune Godhead but as the fulfillment of God&rsquo;s eternal plan to bring into being the Messiah. Thus for John, as well as for Paul, Jesus preexisted in the mind and purpose of God, rather than literally as a timeless being.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 1, 14, 1, 'Became Flesh', 99, '2023-01-31 13:15:56', '<p>&ldquo;The word, the logos, God&rsquo;s plan, His purpose, His will, became flesh and dwelt among us. With the coming into existence of Jesus Christ at his conception and birth, the full plan and heart of God was expressed as a human being. Jesus Christ was full of divine grace and truth. What became flesh in John 1:14, was not a preexistent or eternally begotten Son of God. What became flesh was God&rsquo;s full plan of salvation revealed in the Man, Jesus Christ. A plan can take &ldquo;flesh&rdquo; when it is carried out or acted upon. When an architect&rsquo;s plan actually becomes a building it becomes &ldquo;flesh.&rdquo; In the same manner God&rsquo;s plan became literal flesh in Jesus Christ who fully revealed God&rsquo;s will.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Twenty Biblical Reasons Why the Doctrine of the Trinity is Unbiblical by Chuck LaMattina</p> <p>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t help but wonder, what verse would they reference to the point of &ldquo;over-kill&rdquo; if John 1:1 wasn&rsquo;t in the Scriptures? Furthermore if John, who was exiled on the Island of Patmos and given a revelation of the Day of the Lord, had meant for the &ldquo;Word&rdquo; to mean Jesus was the one Almighty God, wouldn&rsquo;t he have been shocked to discover that Jesus and God were two completely separate entities in the heavenly realm? It was God&rsquo;s word (logos): His &ldquo;predetermined plan&rdquo; that became manifested in the man Jesus Christ, our lord and savior. John who was on the Mount of Transfiguration with Peter and James witnessed God&rsquo;s confirmation that Jesus was the one he loved and approved, and He charged them to &ldquo;listen to him!&rdquo; Was this a command from God or just a suggestion?&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p> <p>&ldquo;The NET Bible Commentary remarks on the meaning of &ldquo;word&rdquo; in Ps. 33:6-11: &ldquo;The LORD&#39;s &lsquo;word&rsquo; refers to the decrees whereby He governs His dominion.&rdquo; Only when logos in John 1:1 is made into a second Person, the Son, do all the problems arise. Jesus defined God in Mark 12:29: &ldquo;The Lord our God is one Lord,&rdquo; not two or three! It would be a fatal contradiction to introduce a second &ldquo;God, Person&rdquo; in John 1. In John 17:3 Jesus was a strict monotheist declaring the Father to be &ldquo;the only one [monos] who is true God [theos].&rdquo; This is unitary not Trinitarian monotheism. Note Schonfield, Authentic New Testament: &ldquo;In the beginning was the expressed concept.&rdquo; If we read &ldquo;In the beginning was the SON&rdquo; we make two who are GOD, and this breaks the fundamental and easy, express monotheism of Jesus (Mk. 12:29; 1 Cor. 8:4-6) and the whole of the Bible. Sadly John 1: 1 has been used to contradict Jesus in John 17:3 and the detailed birth narratives of Matthew and Luke, and the more than 1300 NT references to GOD as the Father. There are thousands of references to God in Scripture as a single Person, defined by singular personal pronouns. The God of the Bible is a single divine &ldquo;someone,&rdquo; &ldquo;self.&rdquo; The moment someone else, the Son, is said to be God, two Gods are posited; the universe is &ldquo;tinkered with&rdquo; and idolatry is introduced (cp. 1John 5:20-21 for fair warning).&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The One God, the Father, One Man Messiah Translation: New Testament with Commentary by Anthony Buzzard</p>'),
