(342, 1, 43, 2, 19, 1, 'Did Jesus raise himself from the dead?', 99, '2022-12-20 17:55:18', '<p>&ldquo;DESTROY THIS TEMPLE, AND IN THREE DAYS I WILL RAISE IT UP&rdquo; - John 2:19.</p> <p>&ldquo;There is no contradiction between Christ&rsquo;s declaration and the ordinary N.T. theology, that the Son was raised by the Father. The expression is figurative&rdquo; - Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges</p> <p>Article Overview</p> <p>Trinitarianism would have us believe that Jesus claimed that he would raise himself from the dead - thus (in effect) declaring himself to be God because elsewhere the New Testament says that God raised him. In support of this idea Trinitarianism cites:</p> <p>&ldquo;Jesus&hellip; said unto them, Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up&rdquo; - John 2:19.</p> <p>But then, what are we to make of the following?</p> <p>&ldquo;The God of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father of glory&hellip; raised him from the dead, and set him at his own right hand in the heavenly places&rdquo; - Ephesians 1:17,20.</p> <p>Jesus is not the Father; nor is he his own God; nor does it make sense to say that he set himself at his own right hand.</p> <p>&bull; This article shall establish - by a preponderance of Scriptural evidence - that Jesus did not say that he would resurrect himself, and that he did not resurrect himself but that his God and Father (Jn. 20:17, Eph. 1:17, Rev. 3:12) resurrected him.</p> <p>&ldquo;Raise Himself&rdquo;, Or &ldquo;Be Raised&rdquo;?</p> <p>Those who heard Jesus&rsquo;s words reported that he said he would &ldquo;be raised&rdquo;, not that he would raise himself:</p> <p>&ldquo;Jesus began to shew&hellip; how that he must&hellip; be raised again the third day&rdquo;- Mt. 16:21</p> <p>&ldquo;Jesus said&hellip; the third day he shall be raised again&rdquo;- Mt. 17:22, 23</p> <p>&ldquo;The Son&hellip; must&hellip; be raised the third day&rdquo; - Luke 9:2</p> <p>(See also Romans 4:24, 25, 6:4, 9, 7:4, 8:11, 10:9, Acts 2:22, 24, 30, 32, 3:15, 26, 4:10, 13:33, 34, 37, 17:31, 1 Corinthians 6:14, 15:15, 2Corinthians 4:14, Galatians 1:1, Ephesians 1:20, Collosians 2:12, 1Thessalonians 1:10, 2Timothy 2:8, Hebrews 11:19, &amp; 1Peter 1:21).</p> <p>&bull; That&rsquo;s 31 times that the New Testament confirms that Jesus said he WOULD BE raised, and that he WAS raised - as opposed to 0 times that the New Testament says that Jesus raised himself.</p> <p>Questionable Witnesses</p> <p>The only report of Jesus claiming that he would &ldquo;rebuild the temple&rdquo; of his body is found twice; first at Mt.26:</p> <p>&ldquo;This fellow said, &lsquo;I am able to destroy the temple of God, and to build it in three days&rsquo; &ldquo; - Mt.26:61</p> <p>(Note that in Mt.27:40 they had said to Jesus: &ldquo;Save thyself if thou be the Son of God&rdquo; - indicating that they did not understand Jesus to be saying that he was God, but only God&rsquo;s son).</p> <p>And again at Mk.14:</p> <p>&ldquo;We heard him say, &lsquo;I will destroy this temple that is made with hands, and within three days I will build another made without hands&rsquo; &rdquo; - Mk 14:58</p> <p>But nowhere in Scripture did Jesus ever say that he would destroy the temple, he said that his enemies would destroy it; nor did he ever speak of a temple made with (or without) hands. So, then, how much credibility are we to give to this report (and especially in light of the fact that all other reports say that he said he would &ldquo;be raised&rdquo;, not &ldquo;raise himself&rdquo; )?</p> <p>&ldquo;Raised&rdquo; By Who?</p> <p>Many Scriptures clarify that it was God (i.e. the Father) who raised him:</p> <p>&ldquo;God the Father&hellip; raised him&rdquo; - Galatians 1:1</p> <p>&ldquo;Whom God hath raised up&rdquo; - Acts 2:24</p> <p>&ldquo;Knowing that God would raise up Christ&rdquo; - Acts 2:30</p> <p>&ldquo;This Jesus hath God raised up&rdquo; - Acts 2:32</p> <p>&ldquo;God, having raised up His Son&rdquo; - Acts 3:26</p> <p>&ldquo;Jesus Christ &hellip;whom God raised from the dead&rdquo; - Acts 4:10</p> <p>&ldquo;The God of our fathers raised up Jesus&rdquo; - Acts 5:30</p> <p>&ldquo;Him God raised up&rdquo; - Acts 10:40</p> <p>&ldquo;God&hellip; hath raised up Jesus&rdquo; - Acts 13:33</p> <p>&ldquo;He whom God raised&rdquo; - Acts 13:37</p> <p>&ldquo;God hath raised (Jesus) from the dead&rdquo; - Romans 10:9</p> <p>&ldquo;God was able to raise him&rdquo; - Hebrews 11:19</p> <p>&ldquo;God hath&hellip; raised up the Lord&rdquo; - 1 Corinthians 6:14</p> <p>&ldquo;God, who hath raised him from the dead&rdquo; - Collisions 2:12</p> <p>&ldquo;God was able to raise him up&rdquo; - Hebrews 11:19</p> <p>&ldquo;God&hellip; raised him up from the dead&rdquo; - 1 Peter 1:21</p> <p>&bull; Scripture says that God raised Jesus, but never says that Jesus raised himself.</p> <p>But Doesn&rsquo;t Jn.2:22 Say &ldquo;Was Risen&rdquo;, Not &ldquo;Was Raised&rdquo;?</p> <p>The KJV translates Jn.2:22 as:&ldquo;When therefore he was risen from the dead&rdquo;, but the Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges says: &ldquo;Better, &lsquo;was raised&rsquo; &rdquo;, and Vincent&#39;s Word Studies says: More correctly, &lsquo;was raised&rsquo; &rdquo; (&lsquo;was raised&rsquo; indicating that the action was that of someone other than Jesus).</p> <p>Accordingly, the verse is translated: &ldquo;When therefore he was raised from the dead&hellip;&rdquo; by the ASV, CSB, CEB, CJB, CEV, DARBY, ERV, EHV, ESV, EXB, GNT, HCSB, ICB, ISV, PHILLIPS, LEB, MSG, MEV, NABRE, NASB, NCV, NET, NIRV, NIV, NLV, NLT, NRSV, NTE, RSV, TLV, WEB, WE, YLT, etc.;</p> <p>Again, every New Testament report of the resurrection says that Jesus &ldquo;was raised&rdquo;, while none say that he &ldquo;raised himself&rdquo;.</p> <p>But Didn&rsquo;t Jesus Say That He Had The Power To Take Back His Own Life?</p> <p>Jesus&rsquo;s power to take back his life was given to him by the Father:</p> <p>&ldquo;No man taketh it [my life] from me, but I lay it down of myself. I have power to lay it down, and I have power to take it again. This commandment have I received of my Father&rdquo; - John 2:18</p> <p>&ldquo;The taking again was under the Father&rsquo;s authority&rdquo; - Ellicott&rsquo;s Commentary</p> <p>&ldquo;Take Back&rdquo;, Or &ldquo;Receive Back&rdquo;?</p> <p>Trinitarianism points to John 2:18 as evidence that Jesus brought himself back to life, but many English versions make clear that Jesus simply meant that he would receive back from God the life which he had first surrendered to Him:</p> <p>&ldquo;Receive it&rdquo; - CEV, NTE, OJB, EXB</p> <p>Also note that Jesus made clear that he did not intrinsically possess the power to take his life back, but that God (who is the Father) had authorized such power:</p> <p>&ldquo;Authorized&hellip; to give it up, and&hellip; authorized&hellip; to take it back&rdquo;. - AMP</p> <p>Maybe Both The Son And The Father Raised Him?</p> <p>Trinitarianism sometimes argues that since both Father and Son are God, they both raised Jesus - but such an idea is never presented in Scripture.</p> <p>The overwhelming weight of Scriptural evidence reveals that God (who is the Father) alone raised Jesus .</p> <p>But Doesn&rsquo;t The New Testament Say That Jesus Was Made Alive By The Spirit?</p> <p>&ldquo;Christ&hellip; being put to death in the flesh but made alive by the Spirit&rdquo; - 1 Peter 3:18 (NKJV, CSB, DLNT, etc.)</p> <p>This certainly sounds like &ldquo;the third person of the Trinity&rdquo; resurrected Christ. So why, then, would widely respected Trinitarian commentators make the following statements regarding the verse?</p> <p>&ldquo;This does not refer to the Holy Spirit, or the third person of the Trinity&hellip; for it may be doubted whether the work of raising the dead is anywhere ascribed to that spirit&rdquo; - Barnes&rsquo; Notes On the Bible</p> <p>&ldquo;We must be careful and not understand &lsquo;Spirit&rsquo; here (to be referring to) the Spirit of God&rdquo; - Vincent&#39;s Word Studies</p> <p>&ldquo;Not the Holy Ghost&rdquo; - Pulpit Commentary</p> <p>Not &ldquo;By The Spirit&rdquo;, But &ldquo;In Spirit&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;We cannot translate it: &ldquo;BY the spirit&rdquo;. It is literally: &lsquo;quickened IN spirit&rsquo; &ldquo;- Ellicott&#39;s Commentary for English Readers</p> <p>The ASV, LEB, MOUNCE, NASB, DARBY, DRA, EHV, ESV, JUB, etc. translations all translate it &ldquo;Being put to death in the flesh, but made alive IN the spirit&rdquo;.</p> <p>Simply stated, the idea expressed in 1Pet.3:18 is not that The Holy Spirit raised Jesus from death, but that Jesus&rsquo;s own spirit (&ldquo;into thy hands I commend MY spirit&rdquo; - Luke 23:46) was &ldquo;quickened&rdquo; (made alive) when his flesh was killed:</p> <p>&ldquo;In the very act of dying, his spirit was quickened&rdquo; - Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges</p> <p>&ldquo;His flesh put to death, but his spirit quickened&rdquo; - Pulpit Commentary</p> <p>&ldquo;His spirit&hellip; entered into fuller life&rdquo; - Bridgeway Bible Commentary</p> <p>Before He Was Resurrected</p> <p>Furthermore, this quickening of Jesus&rsquo;s spirit took place:</p> <p>&ldquo;PRIOR TO the resurrection of his body&rdquo; - Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges</p> <p>&ldquo;After being put to death in the fleshly realm but made alive IN THE SPIRITUAL REALM&rdquo; HCSB</p> <p>No, 1 Peter 3:18 does not say that Jesus was resurrected by the Holy Spirit, but that when his body died his spirit was enlivened, or quickened.</p> <p>Last Thoughts On John 2:19</p> <p>This article began by quoting John 2:19: &ldquo;Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up&rdquo;. It is well known among Biblical scholars that some of the wording of the NT was altered - and sometimes wholly counterfeited - by copyists with a trinitarian agenda. Nor is it likely that all such alterations have been identified. The earliest known copies of the Book of John date to the second century - plenty of time for tampering to have taken place. Again, these alleged words of Jesus stand at odds with the overwhelming weight of Scripture which says that it was his God and Father who raised him. But even if these words were uttered by Jesus, it is entirely conceivable that as God&rsquo;s prophet (Mk.6:4) it was God speaking through Jesus (John 14:10, 24, etc.). This is consistent with the rest of Scripture - which says that God would, and did, raise him.</p> <p>SUMMARY</p> <p>Thirty one New Testament verses agree that Jesus said he would BE raised, and that he WAS raised (the Greek &ldquo;passive voice&rdquo; form of the verb indicating that he was raised by someone other than himself), in contradistinction to two (questionable) reports that Jesus said he would raise himself, or that he himself would rebuild the temple of his body.</p> <p>Many of those thirty one verses explicitly state that it was &ldquo;God&rdquo;, or &ldquo;the Father&rdquo; who raised Jesus.</p> <p>Despite trinitarian arguments, Peter did not say that the Holy Spirit resurrected Jesus but that Jesus&rsquo;s own spirit was made alive when his body died (and prior to his resurrection).</p> <p>No after-the-fact report of Jesus&rsquo;s resurrection attributes it to any member of the Trinity other than the Father.</p> <p>CONCLUSION</p> <p>Neither Jesus nor the Holy Spirit had a role in his resurrection. It was the Father alone who raised him from the dead.</p> <p>Steven Blake</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 3, 16, 1, 'Perish vs Eternal Life', 99, '2022-12-18 12:37:23', '<p>&ldquo;In this verse, the final state of the wicked is contrasted with the final state of believers. While believers receive everlasting life, the wicked will perish. But if the wicked receive everlasting torment in hell, then they will not perish. To be tormented forever, the wicked need to be given everlasting life as well. If that is the case, the difference between the wicked and believers are not in their final state of being, but only in the nature of that life. Believers will get an everlasting life with the Lord, while the wicked will receive an everlasting life in torment. However, John 3:16 speaks about the different state of being between the wicked and believers: One will perish, and the other will receive everlasting life.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;Death is the opposite of life. The same dichotomy from John 3:16 can also be seen in Romans 6:23 (&ldquo; For the wages of sin is death, but the free gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord&rdquo;). In this verse, the contradiction is clear: God&rsquo;s gift is eternal life, while sin leads to death. Death is the opposite of life. Death does not mean eternal suffering because to suffer eternally would require life. Death means death.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;The one thing death does not mean is &lsquo;not dying&rsquo;&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;For conditionalists, three main biblical arguments contradict the above Platonic view: 1 Timothy 1:17, 6:16, and 2Timothy 1:10. Quoting these verses, Stott argues that only God possesses immortality in Himself and God reveals and gives immortality to humanity through the gospel. In other words, God only extends immortality as a gift for those who believe in Jesus Christ for salvation. The wicked will not be given eternal life&ndash;either in hell or elsewhere.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;For those who believe in Christ, the gift is everlasting life. This everlasting life is not given to all humanity but only gifted to those who believe.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;The first letter of John states this gift of life clearly by saying &ldquo;whoever has the Son has life; whoever does not have the Son of God does not have life.&rdquo; (1 John 5: 12). From this verse it is clear that life is conditional. Not everyone will have life. Only those who believe in Christ will have this eternal life that God inherently possesses.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;Conditionalism argues that eternal life is conditional. Eternal life is a gift only given to those who trust in Jesus. Therefore, conditionalists view God&rsquo;s gift of eternal life as more valuable than traditionalists&rsquo; view.&rdquo;</p> <p><span style="font-size: 1.2em;">&mdash; Conditional Immortality: The Case for Orthodoxy on the Doctrine of Annihilationism by Tanwin Tanoto</span></p>'),
