(342, 1, 43, 4, 22, 1, 'Who is this Trinitarian &ldquo;God&rdquo; that is being worshipped?', 99, '2023-01-15 13:58:57', '<p>&ldquo;In the skewed logic of trinitarianism, God the Son is really two incompatible opposites thrown together into a bipolar Jesus who is both mortal and immortal, both man and God, and therefore both mortal man and immortal God. Anyone who can believe this twisted and contradictory doctrine will not find it hard to believe any error that comes along his way. It must have taken an impressive power of persuasion to pull off this deception, not just on a few individuals but on great multitudes throughout church history. This causes one to wonder if the persuasiveness of the deception comes from some supernatural force. We are reminded of the words in Revelation: &ldquo;that ancient serpent, who is called the devil and Satan, the deceiver of the whole world&rdquo; (Rev. 12:9). What it means is that no one, no matter how intelligent or educated, can escape from the paralyzing grip of spiritual deception. Spiritual perception, on the other hand, involves &ldquo;having the eyes of your hearts enlightened&rdquo; by God (Eph. 1:18), enabling the heart to see the liberating light of His truth. The second person of the Trinity&mdash;the one who supposedly died on the cross&mdash;clearly cannot be God who in Scripture is most definitely immortal. That being the case, who exactly is this God called the second person of the Trinity? And who have trinitarians been worshipping ever since their dogma became the official doctrine of the church in the fourth century? This question is becoming ever more frightening.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Only Perfect Man: The Glory of God in the Face of Jesus Christ by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 4, 23, 1, 'True worshippers, worship the Father', 99, '2023-02-03 13:20:11', '<p>&ldquo;Who does Jesus declare are the &ldquo;true worshippers&rdquo;? He insists, &ldquo;The true worshippers shall worship the Father...&rdquo; If we would be amongst the true worshippers we must with Jesus worship his Father. Evidently, those who worship &ldquo;God the Father, God the Son and God the Holy Ghost, three Persons in one God,&rdquo; are not said by Jesus to be the true worshippers. Those who worship the Father as the &ldquo;only true God&rdquo; are. The worshipper of the One God, the Father, has Jesus&rsquo; own affirmation that he is the true worshipper.&rdquo;</p> <p>This is the Biblical pattern throughout. The so-called Lord&rsquo;s prayer, the model prayer, teaches us to &ldquo;pray in this way: Our Father who art in heaven...&rdquo; (Matt. 6:9). This pattern of prayer and worship prescribed by our Lord Jesus is followed and sanctioned by every example given in Scripture. See the following: &ldquo;Now may the God who gives perseverance and encouragement grant you to be of the same mind with one another according to Christ Jesus; that with one accord you may with one voice glorify the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ&rdquo; (Rom. 15:5-6). &ldquo;For this reason, I bow my knees before the Father&rdquo; (Eph. 3:14). &ldquo;Always giving thanks for all things in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ to God, even the Father&rdquo; (Eph. 5:20). &ldquo;Now to our God and Father be the glory forever and ever. Amen&rdquo; (Phil. 4:20). &ldquo;We give thanks to God, the Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, praying always for you&rdquo; (Col. 1:3). &ldquo;Giving thanks to the Father&rdquo; (Col. 1:12). &ldquo;And whatever you do in word or deed, do all in the name of the Lord Jesus [i.e. according to his teaching and authority], giving thanks through him to God the Father&rdquo; (Col. 3:17). This list is by no means exhaustive. But it is sufficient to show that we are, with our Lord Jesus, to worship and pray to the Father. This is the usual pattern of prayer and worship in the New Testament. They prayed to the One God through the name or authority of Jesus Christ.</p> <p>&mdash; They Never Told Me This in Church! by Greg Deuble</p> <p>&ldquo;This is one of the great confirmations of the non-Trinitarian faith of Jesus and the Bible. The idea that God is one Essence in three Persons is utterly foreign to Scripture. The God of the Hebrew Bible and thus of Jews, and the God of Jesus, is the one and only true God (Jn. 17: 3; Mk. 12: 29, etc).&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The One God, the Father, One Man Messiah Translation: New Testament with Commentary by Anthony Buzzard</p> <p>&ldquo;Trinitarianism speaks of three persons who are all equally God, and then goes on to claim a place in monotheism by changing the definition of God into a &ldquo;divine nature&rdquo;, &ldquo;substance&rdquo;, or &ldquo;Godhead&rdquo; in which the three persons all share; which means, of course, that this &ldquo;Godhead&rdquo; is not at all identical to the one and only personal God of the Bible. Where there is belief in more than one person who is God, that is polytheism by definition. What we need to realize is that trinitarianism is in essence, therefore, a different faith from Biblical monotheism. So we are not here dealing with the relatively simpler matter of Biblical interpretation, but with the far more profound matter of Biblical faith. In other words, what is at stake is true or false faith, not just true or false interpretations of the Bible. True or false faith, according to the Scriptures, is a matter of life or death.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Only True God: A Study of Biblical Monotheism by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan</p> <p><br /> Salvation is based on &ldquo;a love of the truth in order to be saved&rdquo; (2 Thess. 2:10).</p> <p>&ldquo;Dear brethren, I don&rsquo;t want riddles, abstract analogies, incomprehensible explanations, and double-talk to establish and cement the basis of my Christian beliefs and faith. For myself I need some degree of solidarity&mdash;a rock, if you will. And that Rock for me is the one Almighty God, and the Historical Jesus Christ, my Lord and Savior, the one the Father sent into the world to reveal Him (John 1:14). No one has ever seen God, but the only Son who is at the Father&rsquo;s side, has made him known. Not only did Jesus bring us the good news of the coming Kingdom of God, but he brought us a deeper understanding of God the Father. His message of mercy, forgiveness, love, compassion, hope and grace was so that we might know God better and live our lives in a manner pleasing to Him. It was &ldquo;in,&rdquo; &ldquo;through,&rdquo; and &ldquo;by&rdquo; Jesus, that God the Father was revealed to humanity. I refuse to build my spiritual beliefs upon the shifting sands of a man-made doctrine that is so esoteric and mythological that it must be accepted and embraced as a &ldquo;mystery.&rdquo; This line may work for my Trinitarian brethren, but it doesn&rsquo;t work for me. How can I worship God the Father in truth if, as Trinitarians proclaim, he is a mystery? Why would I even want to? Trying to figure life out is difficult enough, so why would I garner additional exasperation in the pursuit of a Creator God who is trying to mystify me? The primary reason the Trinity dogma has been propagated so successfully is that the clergy have convinced their flock they can&rsquo;t comprehend God without benefit of the blessed Trinity, but the truth is: The Trinity only precipitates confusion. The Trinity is merely the &ldquo;weeds&rdquo; of tradition, and it has choked out God&rsquo;s truth.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 4, 24, 1, 'Pneuma', 99, '2023-02-04 13:21:38', '<p>Look at my hands and my feet, and see that it is I myself. Touch me and see, because a spirit does not have flesh and bones as you can see that I have. Luke 9:24</p> <p><br /> Jesus later explained what a spirit is in Luke 24:36-39<br /> a good basic definition of pneuma, &ldquo;spirit,&rdquo; is something invisible that exerts a force.<br /> -from this commentary</p> <p>&ldquo;Trinitarianism also insists on making the Spirit of the LORD (Yahweh) a distinct person from Yahweh. For anyone somewhat familiar with the Old Testament, this is something strange. Jews must wonder whether Christians really have any understanding of the Bible at all. To argue that the Spirit of Yahweh, God&rsquo;s Spirit, is a person distinct from Him is like arguing that &ldquo;the spirit of man&rdquo; (1Cor. 2:11; Prov. 20:27; Eccl. 3:21; Zech. 12:1), man&rsquo;s spirit, is a distinct individual who lives in or with him as another person! This might be perceived as true by someone who suffers from schizophrenia, but to suggest that this is the case with God borders on lunacy if not something worse, like blasphemy. &ldquo;God is Spirit&rdquo; (Jn. 4:24) as Jesus said, yet we do not hesitate to declare that God&rsquo;s Spirit, the Spirit of the LORD, the Holy Spirit, is actually a different person from Him. The tragedy is that as trinitarians we have become so accustomed to this sort of teaching that we are no longer capable of seeing its absurdity. Surely, we assure ourselves, we are not that stupid. The problem is not stupidity but spiritual blindness&mdash;and we thought that it was only the Jews who were struck with blindness (Eph. 4:18; Rom. 11:25 KJV, esp. with regard to Jesus as Messiah)!&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Only True God: A Study of Biblical Monotheism by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan</p>'),
