(342, 1, 43, 5, 44, 1, 'The Only God', 99, '2023-01-10 00:11:35', '<p>&ldquo;Anthony Buzzard comments on creeds: &ldquo;Traditional creeds claim that not only the Father, but also the Son and Holy Spirit are the true God. They are in conflict with the belief system of Jesus. If it is reasonable to ask, how did the simple truth that the Father is the only true God disappear from Christianity? &ldquo;The churches replaced Jesus&rsquo; creed with a new creed of their own invention, and so it has remained until this day. Those who want to follow Jesus will return to his creed, which is simple and clear. There is only one true Christian creed: that the Father is &lsquo;the only true God&rsquo; and that Jesus is His Son, the Messiah (Christ). For confirmation of this see John 5:44, 1Timothy 2:5, Ephesians 4:6, and 1Corinthians 8:4-6. Never confuse the Father, who is the only true God, with Jesus, who is &lsquo;the Lord Messiah.&rsquo; Christ means Messiah, the anointed one.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey<br /> &nbsp;</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 7, 15, 1, null, 99, '2022-12-20 14:08:30', null),
(342, 1, 43, 7, 17, 1, 'God or me', 99, '2022-12-20 14:15:12', '<p>&ldquo;These words of Jesus are not easily misunderstood. By comparison, think about the phrase &ldquo;this or that&rdquo;. It is generally recognized that the words &ldquo;this&rdquo; and &ldquo;that&rdquo; refer to two different things. Likewise, in the phrase &ldquo;one or the other&rdquo;, we can be reasonably confident that the term &ldquo;one&rdquo; is speaking of something different than the term &ldquo;the other&rdquo;. The big giveaway in these phrases is the word &ldquo;or&rdquo;. It bespeaks a substantive distinction between the two things being referenced. In John 7: 17, Jesus presents a substantive distinction between himself and God-telling us that they are not the same person, but two different persons.&rdquo;</p> <p>In John 7:17, Jesus is talking about a doctrine. He tells his listeners that in doing God&rsquo;s will they will know &ldquo;whether it be of God, or whether I speak of myself &rdquo;, thereby confirming that he is not God (for that is what &ldquo;God or myself &rdquo; means.).<br /> &mdash; &quot;Sleight Of Mind&quot; - Volume One - The Myth Of The Christian Trinity by Steven Blake</p>'),
