(342, 1, 43, 10, 30, 1, null, 99, '2022-12-29 13:09:28', '<p>&ldquo;&ldquo;I and the Father are one&rdquo; (John 10:30) was clearly meant to describe the perfect unity of purpose and action possible between God and himself as the human Messiah. We know that this is the meaning Jesus intended, because only a few chapters later, in the same gospel of John, Jesus desires the same unity to be realized between God and Christians. &ldquo;Just as the Father and I are one, so you and God are to be one&rdquo; (see John 17:11, 22). Any argument, therefore, that forces &ldquo;I and the Father are one&rdquo; to mean &ldquo;I and the Father are both God&rdquo; collapses immediately on the patent evidence that Jesus describes the unity between disciples and God in exactly the same language as his own unity with God.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;If Jesus is God, not only is Jewish and Christian monotheism subverted and thousands of references to God as a single Person overthrown&mdash;worse still, Jesus&rsquo; amazing accomplishment on our behalf becomes an empty charade. If he is God he cannot be tempted, because God cannot be tempted with evil (James 1:13). And because God is immortal according to the plain statement of 1 Timothy 6:16, the Son of God, if he is God as orthodoxy holds, cannot by definition die. Yet Paul, unaware of any difficulty, writes that the Son of God died (Rom. 5:10). The best that Christian hymnology could do was to write nonsense: &ldquo;&rsquo; Tis mystery all: the immortal dies.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Jesus Was Not a Trinitarian by Anthony Buzzard</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 10, 33, 1, 'Make yourself out to be God', 99, '2022-12-10 14:57:47', '<p>Why do we place such weight on the fact that they said you make yourself out to be God (which Jesus seemed to deny), they also said he was Demon possessed and a sinner.</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 10, 34, 1, 'Ye are gods', 99, '2023-01-21 12:12:24', '<p>&ldquo;&ldquo;I said, &lsquo;You are gods, sons of the Most High, all of you; nevertheless, like men you shall die, and fall like any prince (sar, ruler).&rsquo;&rdquo; Jesus quoted this verse in John 10:34. The point is that the word &ldquo;god&rdquo; is sometimes used in the OT with reference to a person of authority such as a ruler or king and does not imply that that person is divine.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Only True God: A Study of Biblical Monotheism by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan</p> <p><br /> People familiar with the Semitic languages know that a man who is acting with God&rsquo;s authority can be called &ldquo;god.&rdquo;</p> <p>From the commentary at Isaiah 9:6</p> <p>The Jews took up stones again to stone him. Jesus answered them, &ldquo;Many good works have I showed you from the Father. For which of those works are you going to stone me?&rdquo; The Jews answered him, &ldquo;We are not going to stone you for a good work, but for defaming words, and because you, being a man, make yourself a god.&rdquo;</p> <p>&quot;...I said I am the Son of God&quot;</p> <p>&ldquo;If we stay within the bounds of Scripture, &ldquo;Son of God&rdquo; refers always to created persons, never to God. Jesus claimed the title for himself (John 10:36). He did so in an important passage in which he rebuffed the accusations of his opponents that he was claiming to be &ldquo;[ a] god&rdquo; (John 10:33). Jesus argued brilliantly that even the judges of Israel, as God&rsquo;s human representatives, had been entitled to the designation &ldquo;gods&rdquo; (John 10:34-36; Ps. 82:6; see also John 5:18-19).&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Jesus Was Not a Trinitarian by Anthony Buzzard</p> <p>In Exodus 22:28 &ldquo;gods&rdquo; refers to human judges and the judges were called &ldquo;gods&rdquo; in Psalm 82:6-7. Moses was designated as God in relationship to Aaron (Ex. 4:16) and also to Pharaoh (Ex. 7:1). Jesus answered the Jews who sought to stone him for blasphemy, &ldquo;Is it not written in your law, &lsquo;I said, You are gods?&rsquo; If he called them gods, to whom the word of God came, and the Scriptures cannot be broken do you say of him whom the Father sanctified and sent into the world, &lsquo;You blaspheme&rsquo; because I said, &lsquo;I am the Son of God&rsquo;&rdquo;? (John 10:34-36).</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey<br /> &nbsp;</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 10, 35, 4, null, 99, '2023-02-08 16:33:36', null),
(342, 1, 43, 10, 36, 1, 'Son of God', 99, '2022-12-27 18:46:07', '<p>&ldquo;Two thousand years later the precious biblical term &ldquo;Son of God&rdquo; has suffered severe confusion. This is because Jesus&rsquo; identity has been revised by the Church and its creeds to mean &ldquo;God the Son.&rdquo; Jesus&rsquo; biblical title &ldquo;Son of God&rdquo; has at the same time been retained, but given a new non-biblical meaning. Son of God in other words has been removed from its biblical context, severed from its Hebrew roots and made to express the idea of a second uncreated Person, &ldquo;God the Son.&rdquo;&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Jesus Was Not a Trinitarian by Anthony Buzzard<br /> &nbsp;</p>'),
