(342, 1, 43, 11, 24, 1, 'Lazarus brought back from the dead', 99, '2023-02-11 12:33:30', '<p>&ldquo;Brethren, please consider the following concerning the death of Lazarus. Jesus prayed to the Father before raising Lazarus: &ldquo;Father, I thank you that you have heard me. I know that you always hear me, but I said this for the benefit of the people standing here, that they may believe that you sent me&rdquo; (John 11:41-42). Jesus told Martha that Lazarus would be raised. She answered: &ldquo;I know he will rise again in the resurrection at the last day.&rdquo; Did Martha think Lazarus&rsquo; disembodied soul had gone to heaven? No! The immortality of the soul was not a belief among the early Christians. To take this a bit further and on a glib note, one might wonder why Lazarus didn&rsquo;t exit the tomb stating he had been at bliss in heaven, and immediately recognize Jesus as God bedecked in &ldquo;fleshly&rdquo; raiment, as many believe Thomas did! But Lazarus said absolutely nothing of his death experience because there was nothing to say! And there was no question that Lazarus was absolutely dead as Martha made reference to the odor of his decomposing body. Lazarus had been dead for four days, but Jesus took his time in getting to Bethany, which was less than two miles away. He did this for a specific reason. Prior to resurrecting Lazarus, Jesus had raised others from the dead, but they had only been dead a very short time. There was absolutely no doubt in anyone&rsquo;s mind that Lazarus was &ldquo;absolutely&rdquo; dead! Martha also said to Jesus: &ldquo;I believe that you are the Christ, the Son of God, who was to come into the world.&rdquo;&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 11, 27, 1, null, 99, '2023-02-12 13:57:02', null),
(342, 1, 43, 16, 13, 1, 'The spirit of truth', 99, '2023-02-03 13:45:29', '<p>&ldquo;&ldquo;Although we&rsquo;re sure God knows many things He has not told us, we believe that &lsquo;those things which are revealed belong to us and to our children forever&rsquo; (Deut. 29:29). We also believe Peter&rsquo;s exhortation in his second epistle, stating that God has given to us &lsquo;all things that pertain to life and godliness&rsquo; (2 Pet. 1:3). If the spirit has led us into all truth since Jesus ascended, we feel certain that he would not have forgotten or obscured something as basic as the nature of God. Especially since other items that are so important, like salvation in Christ, are so clearly repeated over and over again.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 17, 1, 1, 'The Father is the only true God', 99, '2023-01-01 14:09:11', '<p>For more on the Father in the Old Testament see:</p> <p>Deuteronomy 32:3-4, 6</p> <p>Psalms 89:26</p> <p>Isaiah 64:4,8</p> <p>Malachi 2:10</p> <p>Also check out the comments I put at those verses</p>');
INSERT INTO `myrevdata` (`myrevid`, `testament`, `book`, `chapter`, `verse`, `highlight`, `marginnote`, `sqn`, `lastupdate`, `myrevnotes`) VALUES
(342, 1, 43, 17, 3, 4, 'Jesus states there is only one God', 99, '2023-01-24 12:35:58', '<p>see also John 5:44</p> <p>Jesus says &ldquo;you&rdquo;, not us, not we or we three, or you, me and the Holy Spirit, he said you are the only true God.</p> <p>The Living Bible states it in this way.</p> <p>&quot;And this is the way to have eternal life&mdash;by knowing you, the only true God, and Jesus Christ, the one you sent to earth!&rdquo; verse 3</p> <p>When Jesus had finished saying all these things he looked up to heaven and said, &ldquo;Father, the time has come. Reveal the glory of your Son so that he can give the glory back to you. Verse 1</p> <p>Jesus Christ told us that the way to have eternal life is to know the Father as the only true God. Certainly then, knowing who the one true God is, is a matter of life and death and not a trivial matter as some would have us to believe</p> <p>This is the core and essence of the Life of the Age to Come, that they may know You, the only one who is true God, and the one You have commissioned&hellip;</p> <p>Jesus Messiah.Anthony Buzzard&rsquo;s Translation</p> <p>And this is life in the age to come, that they know you, the only true God, and Jesus Christ whom you have sent. Rev</p> <p>That is, this is how a human being may attain to immortality. Jesus&rsquo; unitarian definition of God is the most fundamental of all saving truths. Jesus&rsquo; words are a summary, concentrated on a single idea, expressed in the Greek as &ldquo;This is the life of the Age to Come&hellip;&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;Jesus expressed his unitarian confession of faith here by asserting that the &ldquo;Father is the only one who is true God.&rdquo; This text merely repeats the 1300 NT references to GOD as the equivalent of the Father. Jesus declares himself to be not GOD, which would make two Gods, but God&rsquo;s unique human agent. The simplicity of the confession in John 17:3 may be illustrated like this: &ldquo;You (singular), Father (singular), are (singular) the (singular) only (singular and exclusive) true (singular) God (singular).&rdquo;&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The One God, the Father, One Man Messiah Translation: New Testament with Commentary by Anthony Buzzard</p> <p>&ldquo;monotheism is what Jesus taught, it is at the foundation of his teaching. In fact the word &ldquo;monotheism&rdquo; is found in the Bible in Jesus&rsquo; own words, where in his prayer to God, the Father, he says, &ldquo;this is eternal life: that they know you the only true God, and Jesus Christ whom you have sent&rdquo; (John 17:3). &ldquo;Monotheism&rdquo; is made up of two Greek words: monos (&ldquo; only, alone,&rdquo; and as the BDAG Greek-English lexicon explains: &ldquo;with focus on being the only one&rdquo;) and theos (&ldquo; God&rdquo;). It is precisely these two words which are found in Jesus&rsquo; words which he addresses to the Father as &ldquo;the only (monos) true God (theos)&rdquo;. It is important also to notice carefully that Jesus&rsquo; words in John 17:3 have to do with eternal life, and that this involves two essential components: (1) &ldquo;that they know you the only true God&rdquo; and (2) &ldquo;Jesus Christ whom you have sent&rdquo;. Having eternal life is not merely a matter of &ldquo;believing in Jesus&rdquo; as some preachers would have people think. Jesus himself tells us that one must first come to know the one true God, and then also to know Jesus as the one sent by that one God.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;Jesus&rsquo; words are so clear that no complicated linguistic techniques are needed to explain them. What Jesus states with crystal clarity is that there is only one God, the One he calls &ldquo;Father,&rdquo; and he asks his disciples to call upon Him in the same way (&ldquo; Our Father in heaven&rdquo;). Jesus speaks of himself as the one sent by &ldquo;the only true God&rdquo;. It should, therefore, have been perfectly obvious to anyone truly listening to what Jesus said that if the Father is the one and only true God, then no one else can also be God alongside Him. It should be absolutely clear from Jesus&rsquo; words that he definitely excludes himself from any claim to deity by this absolute monos or &ldquo;only&rdquo; referring to the Father. Only the fact that we have been immersed in trinitarianism all our lives prevents us from hearing what Jesus says in these words. Christians have come to that spiritual state in which we address Jesus as &ldquo;Lord, Lord&rdquo; but do not hear or do what he says (Lk. 6:46; cf. Mt. 7:21,22). We have become accustomed to imposing our own doctrines upon his teaching, and when these doctrines are incompatible with his words, we simply ignore what he actually said. But whether we like it or not, monotheism is at the very root of Jesus&rsquo; life and teaching.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Only True God: A Study of Biblical Monotheism by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan<br /> &nbsp;</p> <p>See also</p> <p>Deuteronomy 32:3-4, 6</p> <p>Psalms 89:26</p> <p>Isaiah 64:4,8</p> <p>Malachi 2:10</p> <p>Have we not all one Father? Has not one God created us? Why then are we faithless to one another, profaning the covenant of our fathers?<br /> Malachi 2:10 -ESV</p> <p>&ldquo;It couldn&rsquo;t be any clearer. If the Father alone is God, then neither the Son nor the Spirit CAN be God. Hence, the 1,700 year-old teaching that God is a Trinity is demonstrated to be false, and those devoted to God, His son, and His book, are compelled to reject it.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; &quot;Sleight Of Mind&quot; - Volume One - The Myth Of The Christian Trinity by Steven Blake</p> <p>&ldquo;How could we have been so blind as to think that the Father is not the sole person in &ldquo;the only true God,&rdquo; or to think that Jesus is speaking to the three persons of the Trinity including Jesus himself? Does the &ldquo;you&rdquo; (singular in Greek) uttered by Jesus include &ldquo;me&rdquo;&mdash;Jesus himself? Is Jesus praying to himself? And what do we make of the words that follow, &ldquo;and Jesus Christ whom you have sent&rdquo;? Here Jesus makes a clear distinction between &ldquo;Jesus Christ&rdquo; and &ldquo;you&rdquo; by which he excludes himself from &ldquo;the only true God&rdquo;.&rdquo;</p> <p>The monotheism of John 17:3 is rock solid and defeats every attempt to give it a trinitarian interpretation. This explains why many commentaries avoid mentioning this verse altogether.</p> <p>&mdash; The Only Perfect Man: The Glory of God in the Face of Jesus Christ by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan</p> <p>See how A. W. Pink distorts this verse</p> <p>&ldquo;Appeal is made to this by Unitarians in their horrible efforts to disprove the Godhead of the second and third persons of the Trinity. That Christ cannot be here denying the Deity of Himself and of the Spirit we well know from many other passages, but what did He mean by affirming that the Father is &quot;the only true God&quot;? We believe the answer is twofold:&mdash;First, Christ was here excluding the idols of the Gentiles&mdash;false gods, el., 1 Thessalonians 1:9:&mdash;to denote that that Godhead is only true that is in the Father. The Son and the Spirit are not excluded because they are of the same essence with the Father. The Son and the Spirit are &quot;true God,&quot; not without, but in the Father. &quot;I and the Father are one&quot; (John 10:30); &quot;the Father is in me, and I in him&quot; (John 10:38): not divided in essence, but distinguished in personality. In 1 John 5:20 the Son Himself is called &quot;the only true God!&quot; Which no more excludes the Father than John 17:3 excludes the Son. Many such exclusive statements are to be found in Scripture, that must be expounded by the analogy of faith. For example: &quot;No one knoweth the Father, but the Son, and none knoweth the Son, but the Father&quot; (Matthew 11:27); but this excludes not the Spirit, for He &quot;searcheth the depths of God&quot; (1Cor. 2:10). One person of the Trinity does not exclude the others. When Scripture insists there is no God but one, it simply denies that all others who are&quot; called gods&quot; are such.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Gospel of John by Arthur W. Pink</p>'),
(342, 1, 43, 17, 5, 1, 'Did Jesus preexist?', 99, '2023-01-31 14:20:33', '<p>&ldquo;Trinitarians try to prove that Jesus literally preexisted by quoting John 17:5. What is missed is verse 22 where Jesus gives this &ldquo;same glory&rdquo; to future believers who are not yet alive (v. 20). Does this prove we literally pre-existed as Jesus supposedly did? I guess we can prove our pre-existence prior to our coming to this earth because all of us were given grace &ldquo;before the beginning of time&rdquo; (2 Tim. 1:9). None of this proves we pre-existed. Not to mention that to believe Jesus literally pre-existed would mean he was literally slain before the foundation of the world (Rev. 13:8), making him slain twice! The passage in John 17:5 does not prove Jesus pre-existed as a &ldquo;spirit being&rdquo; or the second member of the Trinity.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
