(342, 1, 44, 14, 11, 1, 'The gods have come down to us in human form!', 99, '2023-01-11 17:42:18', '<p>&ldquo;Gods&rdquo; coming down to the earth has some affinity with the &ldquo;orthodox&rdquo; doctrine of the Trinity and Incarnation. The Biblical view, however, is that God begat his Son, the Messiah in the womb of Mary (Lk. 1:35; Mt. 1:18, 20) and then commissioned him to reveal the true faith to us and also to die and be resurrected.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The One God, the Father, One Man Messiah Translation: New Testament with Commentary by Anthony Buzzard</p> <p>&ldquo;The widespread tendency for the citizens of the Empire to believe the gods came down for intercourse (both in its sexual and commercial meanings) made for a milieu where the deification of cultic figures was customary. After healing a cripple at Lystra Paul and Barnabas were confronted by a frenzied mob who shouted, &ldquo;The gods are come down to us in the likeness of men.&rdquo; They hailed Barnabas as Zeus and Paul as Hermes (Acts 14:11-12). And after a mighty oration the Greeks of Caesarea hailed King Agrippa I with the words, &ldquo;The voice of a god and not of a man!&rdquo; (Acts 12:22). The later deification of Jesus as God or as the Lord God is understandable within this cultural context.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;On one occasion Paul himself had to dissuade the adoring crowds who wanted to worship him and Barnabas. The crowd called out, &ldquo;The gods have become like men and have come down to us&rdquo; (Acts 14:11). Later in his life Paul was bitten by a poisonous snake. The locals expected Paul to swell up and die but when he showed no ill effects the same people changed their minds and began to say that Paul was &ldquo;a god&rdquo; (Acts 28:6). The translators know that the natives did not think that Paul was &ldquo;God&rdquo; so they wrote Paul was &ldquo;a god.&rdquo; Another instance: In Acts 12 King Herod gave a moving oration and the people cried out, &ldquo;The voice of a god, not of a man!&rdquo; (v. 22). The translators did not write &ldquo;The voice of God...&rdquo; because it is self-evident those pagans did not say that Herod was speaking with the very voice of God.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; They Never Told Me This in Church! by Greg Deuble</p> <p>&ldquo;Before Paul died, he warned that wolves were already coming in among the sheep. In Acts 14:11-12 Paul was called Hermes (Roman god Mercury) and Barnabas was called Zeus. The people shouted, &ldquo;The gods have come down to us in human form!&rdquo; Sound familiar!?&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p> <p>&ldquo;the biblical Jesus is a man, a real human being like every other human person in the world. He is not a &ldquo;divine man&rdquo; or a &ldquo;God-man&rdquo; as posited in trinitarianism. If there was ever such a person as a God-man, he would not be a real man. &ldquo;Divine men&rdquo; or &ldquo;gods&rdquo; (cf. &ldquo;gods many,&rdquo; 1Cor. 8: 5) abounded in Greek mythology and were familiar to the early Christians who lived in pagan societies. Barnabas and Paul, in their mission among the Gentiles, were mistaken for the gods Zeus and Hermes (Acts 14: 12) when the people of Lycaonia rushed out to worship them, even preparing sacrificial offerings to them. But Barnabas and Paul cried out, &ldquo;Men, why are you doing these things? We are also men of the same nature with you&rdquo; (v. 15). Jesus, as we see him in the New Testament, is a man with the same nature as all human beings, just as Elijah was a man with the &ldquo;same nature&rdquo; as us (James 5: 17). Because Jesus shared the same nature as humans, he was &ldquo;in every respect tempted as we are, yet without sin&rdquo; (Heb. 4: 15).&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Only Perfect Man: The Glory of God in the Face of Jesus Christ by Eric H.H. Chang, Bentley C.F. Chan</p>'),
