INSERT INTO `myrevdata` (`myrevid`, `testament`, `book`, `chapter`, `verse`, `highlight`, `marginnote`, `sqn`, `lastupdate`, `myrevnotes`) VALUES
(342, 1, 44, 20, 26, 1, 'This day', 99, '2023-01-12 23:46:53', '<p>The thief was assured that very day that he and Jesus would be together in that Eden to be restored on this planet. (For a similar strong promise, see Acts 20:26: &ldquo;I testify to you this day...&rdquo;)</p>'),
(342, 1, 44, 20, 30, 4, null, 99, '2022-12-31 04:13:36', null),
(342, 1, 44, 24, 14, 1, 'Heresy', 99, '2022-12-29 13:33:50', '<p>Gotta love this. I didn&#39;t know that the Greek word translated by most English translations as &quot;sect&quot; in Acts 24:14 is actually in Greek αἵρεσιν &quot;heresy&quot;!</p> <p>Note KJV: &quot;But this I confess unto thee, that after the way which THEY CALL HERESY, so I worship the God of my fathers...&quot;</p> <p>We are in good company!<br /> a Facebook post by Bill Schlegel</p> <p>&ldquo;Paul is from start to finish a unitary monotheist, just as Jesus was. God is &ldquo;the God of our fathers&rdquo; (Acts 24:14), and the same God of the Jews is the God of the Gentiles (Rom. 3:29).&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Jesus Was Not a Trinitarian by Anthony Buzzard</p>'),
(342, 1, 44, 28, 6, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-18 11:47:15', null),
(342, 1, 45, 1, 4, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-27 16:20:28', '<p>&ldquo;&ldquo;It is interesting to observe in this connection how regularly in the New Testament Jesus is referred to as having been &lsquo;raised from the dead&rsquo; (rather than being spoken of as &lsquo;delivered from death&rsquo; or in some similar way), as, for example, in Rom. 1 &lsquo;...designated Son of God by his resurrection from the dead.&rsquo; This expression, with the plural &lsquo;dead,&rsquo; is not to be taken as merely a linguistic idiom; it says something distinctive and important. Jesus was raised not merely from his own death (in some possibly unique or esoteric sense of the word), but from the death which he suffered in common with all other men. He was raised from among the dead of whom he was one.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
(342, 1, 45, 1, 22, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-25 20:49:23', null),
(342, 1, 45, 1, 23, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-25 20:49:18', null),
(342, 1, 45, 1, 25, 4, 'Worshipping God the Son?', 99, '2022-12-27 18:24:39', '<p>&ldquo;The peril of adding &ldquo;Gods&rdquo; to the One God of Jesus&rsquo; and Israel&rsquo;s creed is extreme. The addition of &ldquo;gods&rdquo; of any description to the One God of the Bible is in fact the ultimate crime against God. Readers should inspect their own thinking on this point with urgency and care. Did not Paul warn that amongst the follies committed by humankind was that of worshipping the created being in place of the Creator? (Rom. 1:25). Two thousand years later the precious biblical term &ldquo;Son of God&rdquo; has suffered severe confusion. This is because Jesus&rsquo; identity has been revised by the Church and its creeds to mean &ldquo;God the Son.&rdquo; Jesus&rsquo; biblical title &ldquo;Son of God&rdquo; has at the same time been retained, but given a new non-biblical meaning. Son of God in other words has been removed from its biblical context, severed from its Hebrew roots and made to express the idea of a second uncreated Person, &ldquo;God the Son.&rdquo;&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; Jesus Was Not a Trinitarian by Anthony Buzzard</p>'),
(342, 1, 45, 4, 24, 1, null, 99, '2022-11-29 16:05:26', null),
(342, 1, 45, 6, 23, 4, null, 99, '2022-12-14 11:31:27', null),
(342, 1, 45, 8, 29, 1, 'Firstborn', 99, '2022-11-22 14:06:52', '<p>&ldquo;when Jesus Christ has completely accomplished the restoration of Paradise and produced a new race for a new age, he will report to God, his Father, and say, in essence, &ldquo;Last Adam reporting; mission accomplished; Paradise regained.&rdquo; Then he will take his place as the Head and Firstborn of a great company of redeemed brothers and sisters in an everlasting family reunion in Paradise with his Father and his spiritual siblings.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; One God &amp; One Lord: Reconsidering the Cornerstone of the Christian Faith by John W. Schoenheit, Mark H. Graeser, et al.<br /> &nbsp;</p>'),
(342, 1, 45, 10, 2, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-08 03:28:11', null),
(342, 1, 45, 10, 9, 1, 'Lord means God?', 99, '2022-12-24 15:45:19', '<p>Generally speaking, a lord is someone with authority, control, or power over others; to say that someone is &ldquo;lord&rdquo; is to consider that person a master or ruler of some kind. In Jesus&rsquo; day the word lord was often used as a title of respect toward earthly authorities; when the leper called Jesus &ldquo;Lord&rdquo; in Matthew 8:2, he was showing Jesus respect as a healer and teacher (see also Matthew 8:25 and 15:25).<br /> <br /> However, after the resurrection, the title &ldquo;Lord,&rdquo; as applied to Jesus, became much more than a title of honor or respect. Saying, &ldquo;Jesus is Lord,&rdquo; became a way of declaring Jesus&rsquo; deity. It began with Thomas&rsquo; exclamation when Jesus appeared to the disciples after His resurrection: &ldquo;Thomas said to him, &lsquo;My Lord and my God!&rsquo;&rdquo; (John 20:28). From then on, the apostles&rsquo; message was that Jesus is Lord, meaning &ldquo;Jesus is God.&rdquo; Peter&rsquo;s sermon on the Day of Pentecost contained that theme: &ldquo;Let all Israel be assured of this: God has made this Jesus, whom you crucified, both Lord and Messiah&rdquo; (Acts 2:36). Later, in Cornelius&rsquo;s house, Peter declared that Jesus is &ldquo;Lord of all&rdquo; (Acts 10:36). Note how in Romans 10:9 Jesus&rsquo; lordship is linked to His resurrection: &ldquo;If you declare with your mouth, &lsquo;Jesus is Lord,&rsquo; and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.&rdquo;<br /> <br /> The statement &ldquo;Jesus is Lord&rdquo; means that Jesus is God. Jesus has &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth&rdquo; (Matthew 28:18). He is Lord of the Sabbath (Luke 6:5). He is &ldquo;our only Sovereign and Lord&rdquo; (Jude 1:4). He is, in fact, the Lord of lords(Revelation 17:14).</p> <p><a href="https://www.gotquestions.org/Jesus-is-Lord.html">https://www.gotquestions.org/Jesus-is-Lord.html</a></p> <p>That is a Trinitarian lie!</p> <p>If that was true than Mary called someone she thought was a gardener God when she called him lord.</p> <p>Jesus said to her, &ldquo;Woman, why are you crying? Who are you looking for?&rdquo; She, supposing him to be the gardener, said to him, &ldquo;Lord, if you have carried him from here, tell me where you have laid him, and I will take him away.&rdquo;</p> <p>John 20:15</p> <p>Κύριον (Kyrion)<br /> Noun - Accusative Masculine Singular<br /> Strong&#39;s 2962: Lord, master, sir; the Lord. From kuros; supreme in authority, i.e. controller; by implication, Master.</p> <p>&ldquo;what are we to make of the traditional claim that unless we believe that Jesus is the Lord God of the Old Testament we cannot be saved? Speaking on Romans 10: 9, &ldquo;that if you confess with your mouth Jesus as Lord, and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you shall be saved,&rdquo; Martyn Lloyd-Jones asserts that the text teaches two essentials. The first is that Jesus is Lord, and the second is that God raised him from the dead. Those are the two absolute essentials of the Christian faith. There is no salvation unless we are clear about them. But right here Lloyd-Jones makes a fundamental and classic mistake. He claims: the word translated &ldquo;Lord&rdquo; is used in the Greek translation of the Old Testament to stand for the Hebrew word &ldquo;YHWH&rdquo; (Jehovah)&mdash;the name by which God wished to be personally known... so this statement, &ldquo;that if you confess with your mouth Jesus as Lord,&rdquo; means, &ldquo;If you confess with your mouth that Jesus is Jehovah (YHWH)!&rdquo; Jesus is the Lord God Jehovah!... You say, &ldquo;My faith rests upon Jesus, Jesus of Nazareth, but I say that He is God, He is Jehovah.&rdquo; This is the Christian confession.[ 179] It is a sad thing for me to read such erudite scholars making such baseless, misleading claims. If they are to be consistent, what do they make of the confessions of the early New Testament Christians who called Jesus &ldquo;Lord&rdquo; but had no idea they were calling him Jehovah? An example or two will suffice. When Mary Magdalene found Jesus&rsquo; grave empty, she wept with deep emotion, because she thought somebody had stolen the body. She did not recognize that the risen Jesus was standing right in front of her. Jesus said to her, &ldquo;Woman, why are you weeping? Whom are you seeking?&rdquo; Mary supposed Jesus was the gardener and said to him, &ldquo;Sir [Greek kurios, &ldquo;Lord&rdquo;], if you have carried him away, tell me where you have laid him, and I will take him away&rdquo; (John 20: 15). Here Mary, thinking Jesus is no higher a dignitary than the gardener, calls him &ldquo;Lord.&rdquo; No one in their right mind would believe for a moment that Mary thought the gardener was Jehovah, the Lord God! The translators rightly render the word Lord here as &ldquo;Sir.&rdquo; The same appellation is given by the Philippian jailer to Paul and Silas, the prisoners under his charge. The jailer falls at their feet and calls them Lords, that is, sirs. In John 4 the woman at the well has just met Jesus. Jesus has not yet even told her he is the Messiah. But she addresses him as Lord: &ldquo;Sir [kurios, &ldquo;Lord&rdquo;], you have nothing to draw with and the well is deep&rdquo; (v. 11). Martyn Lloyd-Jones is evidently unaware that the one Greek word for Lord may be applied to either God or man.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; They Never Told Me This in Church! by Greg Deuble</p>'),
