(342, 1, 53, 1, 6, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-12 11:32:33', null),
(342, 1, 53, 2, 3, 1, 'The falling away', 99, '2023-02-04 12:21:17', '<p>&ldquo;The original word Paul used for &ldquo;the falling away,&rdquo; is apostasia, which literally means an apostasy or departure from Jesus Christ inside the Christian Church.&rdquo;</p> <p>As we are about to see, this &ldquo;falling away&rdquo; unquestionably takes place inside the church.</p> <p>&ldquo;A brief survey of the following Bible passages shows plainly that an apostasy, departure, or &ldquo;falling away&rdquo; from Jesus Christ was predicted to occur inside of Christianity. I call this, &ldquo;The Big Detour.&rdquo; 1. Acts 20: Paul told &ldquo;the elders of the church&rdquo; of Ephesus (vs. 17) that soon many false Christian leaders would rise up from among themselves to &ldquo;draw away the disciples&rdquo; after them (vs. 30). He was so burdened about this coming apostasy that he warned the church &ldquo;night and day with tears&rdquo; (vs. 31). 2. 1 Timothy 4: The Holy Spirit clearly warned that &ldquo;some will depart from the faith, giving heed to deceiving spirits and doctrines of demons&rdquo; (vs. 1). Here again is a predicted departure from the faith inside the church. 3. 2 Timothy 4: Paul predicted a time would come when many in the church would no longer &ldquo;endure sound doctrine, but according to their own desires, because they have itching ears, they will heap up for themselves teachers; and they will turn their ears away from the truth, and be turned aside to fables&rdquo; (verses 3-4). Friend, there is no doubt about it. These words point toward an apostasy in the church that will lead professed Christians to turn from Bible truth to fictitious fables. 4. 2 Peter 2: Peter told the early believers that soon &ldquo;there will be false teachers among you&rdquo; (vs. 1). &ldquo;Among you&rdquo; means inside the church. 5. Jude: After urging believers to contend earnestly for the original faith, Jude warned that &ldquo;certain men&rdquo; had already &ldquo;crept in unnoticed&rdquo; among them (vs. 4). 6. Revelation 2: Jesus Christ Himself sadly told His followers in the church of Ephesus, &ldquo;Nevertheless, I have this against you, that you have left your first love. Remember therefore from where you have fallen; repent and do the first works&hellip;&rdquo; (verses 4 and 5). These words are so clear! Many Christians in the early church of Ephesus were Falling Away From the Truth falling away from their initial love for Jesus Christ, who died for them. Thus we see Paul, Peter, Jude, and Jesus Christ all passionately con cerned about a &ldquo;falling away,&rdquo; which means an apostasy, occurring inside the Christian Church. We might compare this apostasy to a disease entering a portion of a human body. As a result, a malignant cancer finally develops. The shocking reality is that God&rsquo;s Word has predicted a similar disease-like condition would eventually overtake a large portion of Christianity. According to 2 Thessalonians 2, as a direct result of this unhappy condition, a diabolical spiritual cancer would rise up. Paul called this cancer, &ldquo;the mystery of lawlessness&rdquo; (2 Thessalonians 2: 7).&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; End Time Delusions by Steve Wohlberg</p> <p>Is it too much of a stretch to wonder if the Trinity isn&rsquo;t more of a Greek myth than biblical truth? God said He would permit a great lie. The fact that Satan in all his evil plotting and ingenuity could convince millions that Jesus Christ is God in the flesh, thus demeaning and annulling the sacrifice our Lord and Savior made for us all &mdash; what greater lie could there be? Our churches teach us that Jesus is God in the flesh, yet the Holy Scriptures clearly tell us that God sent His only begotten Son. If you place your faith in the Trinity doctrine and dismiss the clear and explicit words of God, be not deceived; you have bought into what I honestly believe is the great lie &mdash; the apostasy.</p> <p>&ldquo;The participant in opposition to the Trinity stated that he thought the Trinity was the apostasy referred to in 2 Thessalonians. In my research material, I noted another author echoing the same conclusion. I also believe it to be true. Jesus and Paul forewarned that there would be an apostasy, a falling away from the true Gospel of Christ until he returns, when true worship will be restored. Paul stated, &ldquo;For the time will come when they will not endure sound doctrine; but wanting to have their ears tickled, they will accumulate for themselves teachers in accordance to their own desires; and will turn away their ears from the truth, and will turn aside to myths&rdquo; (2 Timothy 4:3-4). Do I think we Unitarians will win this battle in this age? Probably not! Why? Because the prince of this age rules and has many followers in high places. But be assured, dear brethren; he won&rsquo;t rule in the next age. And make no mistake: it&rsquo;s the next world I need to be concerned about, not a Trinitarian&rsquo;s opinion and judgment of me on Satan&rsquo;s stage. Dear readers, doesn&rsquo;t the following sound like a myth: One-in-three, distinct but one, 100 percent man, 100 percent deity, the God-man?&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey<br /> Page 294</p>'),
(342, 1, 53, 2, 10, 4, 'They refused to love the truth', 99, '2023-02-04 17:54:27', '<p>When one knows the truth and refuses to obey it, he is subject to any lie, any deception, any untruth that humanity can conjure up. &ldquo;For although they knew God, they neither glorified Him nor gave thanks to Him, but their thinking became futile and their foolish hearts were darkened. Although they claimed to be wise, they became fools&rdquo; (Romans 1:21-22). Paul goes on in the next few verses to describe the mindset and behaviors of those who disbelieve (see Romans 1:29-31). As a result of human foolishness and arrogant disdain of the things of God, &ldquo;God gave them over to a depraved mind, to do what ought not to be done&rdquo; (Romans 1:28). And correspondingly, &ldquo;Although they know God&rsquo;s righteous decree that those who do such things deserve death, they not only continue to do these very things, but also approve of those who practice them&rdquo; (Romans 1:32).</p> <p>&ldquo;Salvation in the NT is defined by the important text in 2 Thessalonians 2:10. It was because people failed to have &lsquo;a love for the truth in order to be saved&rsquo; that they were in jeopardy, risking spiritual shipwreck. A careless indifference to the issue of truth and error is dangerous.&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;The Fact that Christians have bought into this &ldquo;comedy of errors&rdquo; should be an embarrassment, and a testament to just how indifferent most Christians are when it comes to seeking and searching out the truth of God&rsquo;s Word for themselves. Those who have not questioned the absurdity of the Trinity but have accepted it totally at face value because they were expected to, and have ignored the explicit words of God, giving more credence to the precepts of man; perhaps they should re-evaluate where they stand with God. I humbly make this suggestion because if a Christian doesn&rsquo;t believe the explicit words of God, then what good is their faith? I mentioned earlier regarding a classmate affirming that she didn&rsquo;t care to delve into the matter of the Trinity, while another stated that she just believed what she was told&mdash;unfortunately this is pretty much the norm among the &ldquo;flock.&rdquo; I perceived their nonchalant attitudes as Christians inexcusable.&rdquo;</p> <p>&mdash; The Tyranny of the Trinity: The Orthodox Cover-Up by P.R. Lackey</p>'),
