(342, 1, 56, 2, 1, 1, 'Sound Doctrine', 99, '2023-02-01 13:03:32', '<p>&quot;teaching.&rdquo;</p> <p>The Greek word is didaskalia (#1319 διδασκαλία), a noun, and it has two primary meanings: It is used of the act of teaching or instruction (as if it was a verb), and it is also used for what is taught, i.e., the doctrine or material that was presented. Interestingly, we use &ldquo;teaching&rdquo; in English in the same way. If, in the middle of the day, someone calls a friend who is a schoolteacher, she may hear, &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t talk now, I&rsquo;m teaching.&rdquo; In that context, &ldquo;teaching&rdquo; is being used as a verb&rdquo; the teacher is in the act of teaching. If, on the other hand, the two are walking out of church, one might say to the other, &ldquo;What did you think of the teaching?&rdquo; In that context, she is using &ldquo;teaching&rdquo; as a noun, and what she means is, &ldquo;What did you think about what we were taught?&rdquo; It is the context that determines whether didaskaliais the act of teaching or the subject matter that was taught.</p> <p>Didaskalia is used 21 times in the NT. One of the problems we have in translating from the Greek to the English is that in almost every use of didaskalia, we have to separate the act of teaching from what is taught (the doctrine). Most English versions use &ldquo;teaching&rdquo; for the act of teaching, and &ldquo;doctrine&rdquo; or &ldquo;what is taught&rdquo; for the subject matter that is taught. But in Greek there are times when the Scripture verse can easily refer to both the teaching and what is taught, (this is a kind of amphibologia.)a A good example is Titus 1:9, where we encourage with &ldquo;sound didaskalia.&rdquo; In that verse, both &ldquo;teaching&rdquo; and &ldquo;doctrine&rdquo; fit perfectly, because we encourage with sound teaching (not all teaching is &ldquo;doctrine&rdquo;), and we encourage with sound &ldquo;doctrine.&rdquo; The Greek reader instinctively sees both meanings in the word, but that is not true of English, where we usually have to make a distinction.</p>'),
