(374, 1, 45, 4, 25, 3, 'Jesus died for our transgressions and raised for our righteousness &ndash; I just can&rsquo;t fathom and it&rsquo;s always been the most important thing to me', 99, '2023-01-07 20:15:51', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 1, 1, '<span style="font-size:12pt"><span sans-serif="" style="font-family:Calibri,">Peace with God appears to mean that we&rsquo;re no longer ruled by fear / also, I think of peace in the sense of a treaty (reading further below it talks about not being an enemy of God and enemies are likened to that of those who your at war with) so we&rsquo;re no loner enemies. There&rsquo;s a spiritual war waged and once we become right with God, it&rsquo;s like there&rsquo;s a treaty or peace ', 99, '2023-01-15 18:51:16', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 2, 1, 'God gives grace freely but we can stand in His grace through the faith we have in Christ / The Hope is the fulfillment to restore His creation (read that somewhere) so through grace we&rsquo;re restored by faith and that is what we boast in.', 99, '2023-01-15 18:32:40', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 3, 2, '<span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">Be thankful for God&rsquo;s grace through the rough times as it&rsquo;s produce endurance and produce character (Christ&rsquo;s character includes love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, meekness, and self-control (in Galatians))</span></span><br /> &nbsp;', 99, '2023-01-15 18:42:01', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 4, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-15 18:35:00', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 5, 1, 'Having true hope (not false hope) &ndash; it will not &ldquo;put us to shame&rdquo; (notes re disappoint)', 99, '2023-01-15 18:34:28', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 6, 3, 'Helpless meaning we were weak (dead in our sins) so there was no way we could save ourselves, we needed a savior...', 99, '2023-01-15 18:42:49', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 7, 3, null, 99, '2023-01-15 18:37:29', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 8, 3, 'What I find interesting about this is it talks about someone dying for another person which means they would be making the choice to sacrifice themselves and while Christ did makes the same choice (although he asked to take the cup from him) God did not/could not make the sacrifice of Himself ...why? Because God is not a man, He is spirit, He is immortal, He cannot die so in His place He sent his son and sacrificed His son to save us', 99, '2023-01-15 18:45:30', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 9, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-15 18:53:02', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 10, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-15 18:53:04', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 11, 4, '<span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">We&rsquo;ve been declared &ldquo;right with God&rdquo; that is righteous by the blood of Christ so we&rsquo;ll be saved from the wrath (bible says &ldquo;the wages of sin are death&rdquo;) &ndash; commentary shows although we&rsquo;re made right with God through the blood of Christ we are still sinners (think of someone in Court being let off for their offenses, they still commited them but', 99, '2023-01-15 18:58:54', null),
(374, 1, 45, 5, 17, 5, '<span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:13.0pt"><span style="background:white"><span style="color:black">No sinful person can pay for the sins of another sinful person and thus absolve him of the consequence of death</span></span></span></span></span><br /> &nbsp;', 99, '2023-01-15 19:17:00', null),
(374, 1, 45, 6, 8, 0, 'The AMP version states we were &ldquo;nailed to the cross&rdquo; with Jesus, &ldquo;buried with him&rdquo; &ndash; these are figurative statements. When reading this I think about the process of water baptism and how we&rsquo;ve learned it&rsquo;s symbolic in terms of death and resurrection but these verses seem to agree that our salvation isn&rsquo;t in a water baptism but in a spiritual baptism. SEE NOTES', 99, '2023-01-15 19:32:57', '<p>Because we weren&rsquo;t physically on the cross or buried with him but metaphorically (The AMP bible states: &ldquo;Baptize&rdquo; is a transliteration of the Greek word baptizo, which means to submerge an object into liquid. In this passage Christ becomes the liquid, metaphorically, and those who are baptized into Him remain in Him forever and benefit from His experiences, including His death.)</p>'),
(374, 1, 45, 6, 12, 4, 'WE NEED TO FIGHT AGAINST LETTING SIN RULE OVER US. To do that, I believe we should put our focus on what the Word says we need to do to live godly (like the fruits of the spirit). Practice the positive rather than Not Doing the Negative. I have a feeling that&rsquo;s the difference between being kindom minded rather than sin conscious.', 99, '2023-01-15 19:37:36', null),
(374, 1, 45, 6, 13, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-15 19:37:37', null),
(374, 1, 45, 6, 14, 4, null, 99, '2023-01-15 19:37:39', null),
(374, 1, 45, 6, 19, 0, 'See AMP verse and commentary on practical sanctification', 99, '2023-01-15 19:43:17', null),
(374, 1, 45, 6, 23, 2, '<strong>&ldquo;For the wages of sin is death.&rdquo;</strong> is a general statement about sin causing death. Sin causes our first death, and if a person is not saved, it will cause his second death. The statement, &ldquo;the wages &lsquo;of&rsquo; sin,&rdquo; is a subjective genitive and means &ldquo;the wages paid by sin.', 99, '2023-01-15 19:45:12', null),
(374, 1, 45, 8, 1, 2, '&ldquo;Condemnation&rdquo; is the Greek word <em>katakrima</em> (<a href="https://www.blueletterbible.org/lexicon/G2631/kjv" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Click to see BlueLetterBible.org''s notes for #2631 (new window)">#2631</a> &kappa;&alpha;&tau;ά&kappa;&rho;&iota;&mu;&alpha;), and in this context it refers to both the pronouncement of guilt and also ultimately the infliction of punishment.', 99, '2023-01-15 19:54:42', null),
(374, 1, 45, 8, 18, 2, null, 99, '2023-01-15 19:58:27', null),
(374, 1, 45, 8, 26, 1, null, 99, '2023-01-15 19:59:16', null),
